<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN FINANCE PROPOSAL IS SACRIFICED FOR BIGGER PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In another vote on campaign finance, the House on
Wednesday night resoundingly rejected a measure that was widely
considered one of the main threats to a bipartisan bill to ban
unregulated campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The defeated measure, the first of 11 the House will debate,
would have created a 12-member commission, split evenly between
Republicans and Democrats, to study how best to overhaul the
campaign finance system. Many Democrats and Republicans said that
in principle they supported the proposal, sponsored by Rep. Rick
White, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill was voted down 156 to 201 by House members who
viewed it as an effort by the Republican leadership to doom two
major pieces of legislation to overhaul the system of campaign
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering supporters of the overhaul effort, 64 Republicans
voted with 136 Democrats and 1 independent to reject the commission
proposal. Another 68 members, mostly Democrats, voted ``present,''
indicating that they agreed with the measure but did not want to
hurt the chances of one of the main overhaul proposals sponsored by
Reps. Chris Shays, R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Under procedures set by Republican leaders, the House will
debate 11 versions of the legislation and the one that receives the
most votes will become the House bill. Wednesday night's vote made
it unlikely that the commission proposal would survive to become
the primary legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason they will vote `present' or `no' is because they
know that this is simply an attempt at the moment to undercut
Shays-Meehan,'' said Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., during a
sometimes shrill debate over which side wanted genuine change.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner was the vote completed than the debate on campaign
finance stalled again when the House put off a procedural vote to
allow members to offer nearly 280 amendments. Republican leaders
maintain they are simply paving the way for a ``free and open''
debate. But Democrats and supporters of the overhaul effort called
it an attempt to kill off the legislation, slowly and deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear on Wednesday night whether Republicans had
enough votes to permit the many amendments or whether Democrats
would be able to defeat the move.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said Wednesday night's vote and the
squabble over the amendments indicated that pressure was mounting
on Republican leaders to act on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders in Congress oppose the effort to tighten the
law on unregulated campaign contributions, known as ``soft money,''
a major provision of the Shays-Meehan proposal, seeing it as an
effort to erode their party's traditional fund-raising advantage.
Republican leaders also oppose efforts to regulate issue
advertising, another component of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece of legislation in the campaign finance debate,
sponsored by a group of House freshman, would restrict soft-money
donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
