</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY CONCLUDES IN BRAWLEY DEFAMATION SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to clarify identity of Steven Pagones in 5th graf)  (ja) 
 By CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ After seven months, more than two dozen
witnesses and the last-minute appearance of a television celebrity,
testimony concluded Wednesday in the Tawana Brawley defamation
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The case has been marked by outrageous antics and, in keeping
with its history, it ended with a threat of further dramatics. But
breaking with history, the judge put a stop to that.
</P>
<P>
   Justice S. Barrett Hickman of State Supreme Court left the
courtroom Wednesday afternoon with a box of papers in his arms,
prepared to work on the complicated charge to the jury. Closing
arguments are expected to begin some time next week and the jury
could begin deliberations before the end of month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court is very happy to have reached this point,'' said
Hickman. ``There may have been some doubts as to whether we would
or not.'' The judge has endured bruising attacks from all four
lawyers involved in the case, and criticism from outside observers
about the the length of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. are
being sued by Steven Pagones, a former Dutchess County assistant
district attorney, because they publicly accused him of
participating in the abduction and rape of Miss Brawley in 1987. A
grand jury that investigated the allegations in 1988 determined
there was no evidence that Miss Brawley had ever been assaulted,
and specifically exonerated Pagones. He has charged that the
defendants acted recklessly and maliciously and is now seeking
about $400 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hardy, the lawyer representing Sharpton, attempted to
wrap up his case by asking Geraldo Rivera, the television
personality, to testify about the ``crucial issue'' of Sharpton's
character. Rivera, arriving at the Dutchess County Courthouse an
hour late, said he had known Sharpton for 15 years and was prepared
to testify that his character was excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe that Al Sharpton is capable of malice,''
Rivera said outside the courthouse. ``I believe history will
ultimately recognize Rev. Sharpton as one of the great civil rights
leaders in America.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rivera had taken the stand, Stanton said he was prepared to
call any number of witnesses to rebut whatever Rivera might have
said. This could have pushed testimony into the trial's fourth
season.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hickman has frequently been criticized for losing
control of the proceedings, he had previously ruled that Rivera
would not be allowed to testify. Wednesday, he held firm. In
stopping Rivera's testimony, the judge said the issue of character
was at most only ``remotely relevant,'' and that it would cloud
other more important issues, unnecessarily prolonging the trial.
</P>
<P>
   At that, Hardy rested his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, fine,'' said the judge. ``That's cause for some
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no cheers, however, and observers exited quietly, as
they would on any other day. Sharpton, who was making a rare
appearance in court, embraced Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   But some people were smiling: the jurors. One court officer said
that the jurors were so happy they were almost singing as they left
the building. And he hazarded a guess as to why: ``They won't have
to listen to witnesses drone on, although I have a feeling their
ears will be bleeding by the time summations are over.''
</P>
<P>
   For some of the jurors, the trial that began last Nov. 18, has
had bitter consequences. One juror had to draw heavily on her
savings to support herself while sitting on the lengthy trial.
Another, an alternate, was hit by a car and critically injured as
she returned to court from a lunch break. Both women were
eventually excused. Now six jurors and two alternates remain.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it marked the end of testimony at the trial, there
were those who were disappointed by the decision that prevented
Rivera from taking the stand. Sharpton said later: ``I can be
called a buffoon, but a guy comes in to testify that I have an
excellent character, and he's not allowed to. We call this
justice?''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Maddox said he would not appeal the jury's
decision, whatever it might be.``I don't think there's a court in
this land that will give Maddox, Mason and Sharpton justice,'' he
said. ``It would be an exercise in futility to take this case any
further.''
</P>
<P>
   Pagones needed to prove that Sharpton and the other defendants
disregarded facts and willfully avoided learning the truth when
they accused him of attacking Miss Brawley. To do so, Pagones'
lawyer, William Stanton, called 24 witnesses to the stand _
including hospital nurses who said there had never been any
evidence of rape, and a neighbor who said she had seen the
15-year-old Miss Brawley crawl into the garbage bag in which she
was later discovered, covered in excrement and racial epithets.
</P>
<P>
   Maddox, who is representing himself, called four witnesses and
sought to show that Pagones had been protected from justice by a
corrupt legal establishment. Stephen Jackson, representing Mason,
called only one witness. Hardy asked his client, Sharpton, and
Pagones to return briefly to the stand to clarify several points.
In total, there were 29 trial witnesses and 303 exhibits and
supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pagones said he was relieved to be done with this portion
of the case, he couldn't resist a final jab at the defense:
``Mason, Maddox and Sharpton tried to call everybody except for the
relevant people _ Tawana, Glenda Brawley and Ralph King,'' he said,
referring to Miss Brawley, her mother and stepfather. ``You didn't
hear from any of them and you've got to ask why.''
</P>
</TEXT>
