A4650 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-LADN     06-18 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-GRIFFEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD'S PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Griffey Jr. nearly popped a lung late
Tuesday afternoon when he saw David Segui's newly bleached swath of
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you singing the anthem tonight?'' Griffey yelled.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey continued his ribbing, comparing Segui to the Spice
Girls, sending Seattle Mariners teammates Rob Ducey and Jay Buhner
into roars of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Later during batting practice, the 28-year-old Griffey displayed
the enthusiasm of an 11 year old when he played safety against a
wave of teammates trying to catch baseballs as a receiver would
catch a football.
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult to tell that these players, many of whom have
been mentioned in trade rumors, had lost 18 of their previous 26
games. Griffey's playful demeanor and carefree attitude must be as
contagious as the flu.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle outfielder Glenallen Hill paused about 20 seconds when
asked about Griffey's most valuable characteristic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he interacts with his teammates during adversity,''
Hill said. ``He's like a cornerstone. It's hard to explain the
energy he gives off. It's pretty amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the clubhouse, Griffey neatly folded a bundle of
form-fitting Nike garments, placing each in a steel footlocker. A
lengthy discussion ensued between Griffey and someone about the
uniqueness and costliness of such clothing.
</P>
<P>
   In a routine Abbott and Costello would have enjoyed, Griffey was
asked why Nike treats him so well. He quickly flashed his right
index finger. Then the four fingers of his right hand hit the air.
Then those four with three fingers from his left were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Five Griffey fingers soon appeared, then six. He slowly
continued to mark his American League MVP numbers from last season
_ 147 RBI, 56 home runs, .304 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Unspoken point made, loud and clear. The Mariners will pay
Griffey $8.5 million a season through 2000 to continue putting up
MVP-like numbers.
</P>
<P>
   He entered Wednesday's game against the Anaheim Angels with a
league-high 26 home runs, and he'll battle Mark McGwire in pursuit
of Roger Maris' record 61 homers for a second consecutive season.
Griffey is on pace for 63.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers and his place in history, however, have scant bearing on
Griffey, the cornerstone of a franchise who is difficult to corner.
He said the game is in good hands, that he just tries to play hard
and he has no time to chat.
</P>
<P>
   A clubhouse attendant stops by with three baseballs, and Griffey
says the price of a signature has jumped to $40. ``College fund for
the kids,'' he said of his young son Trey and daughter Taryn. Then
he smiles and signs. No money is exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   He joins his teammates, who are watching an Eddie Murphy movie
on the clubhouse TV set. ``This is the funny part,'' he said,
stepping up to a couch. The room explodes. He steps back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about most things,'' he said. ``I just want to
be the best person I can be, the best player I can be. If that's
not good enough for somebody, I couldn't care less. As long as it's
good for my family and myself, those are the people I have to worry
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have to be truthful to myself, and that's it. All I
have to do is go out there and play, and when I wake up the next
morning I look in the mirror and ask myself if I did the best job
that I could yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said he has never played the game to prove something to
others or himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make a mistake,'' he said, ``I'm human like everyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Angels reliever Mike Holtz's thought on Tuesday. Holtz
faced Griffey in the top of the eighth inning with the Angels
leading 3-2. Although he's struggled this season, he didn't this
time, retiring Griffey on a pop-up to first baseman Cecil Fielder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you have to be perfect,'' Holtz said. ``You
don't have time to think. He's one of the greatest hitters in the
game and it's a very stressful situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Four pitches _ no fastballs over the middle of the plate, just
three breaking balls and a key second-strike forkball down and away
_ and Holtz was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll set some great records,'' Holtz said of Griffey. ``For
me, it's a real privilege to have the honor to actually be able to
go out there and pitch to him. You sit there and say to yourself,
`I'm pitching to Ken Griffey.' At the same time, it's your job to
get him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the real highlights in baseball. He has a certain
energy about him and he just has fun playing the game. It seems the
game comes so easy to him. You like to see guys who really enjoy
going out there, who have fun and smile at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what has impressed Angels center fielder Jim Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has fun and it shows,'' Edmonds said. ``I've always admired
his demeanor. He never seems to get frustrated. I watch him and he
never loses his cool. That's pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, though, were a depressed group after Tuesday's
game. Patches of players sat before their cubicles, unemotional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans take vacations to see Ken Griffey Jr. play, and my heart
goes out to them when he comes up in a big situation and he doesn't
come through,'' said Hill. ``My heart goes out to them those few
times.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the laughter, the smiles and Griffey were long gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
