A4652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     06-18 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP ORIOLES, 5-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Darryl Strawberry strikes out about every third
at-bat, and his batting average is about 30 points lower than the
Yankees' team average. Weeks can pass between his home runs.
</P>
<P>
   But that occasional jolt of power is why the Yankees signed him,
why his manager started him on Wednesday night. Strawberry smacked
a three-run homer in the first inning of the Yankees' 5-3 victory
against Baltimore, refreshing the first-place team, which had lost
three of its last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's 465-foot shot _ the longest home run ever hit in
the seven-year history of Camden Yards _ helped Andy Pettitte
improve his record to 8-5 as he pitched seven and one-third
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gene Budig, the American League president,
suspended the Yankees' Mike Stanton for hitting Baltimore's Eric
Davis with a pitch on Monday night. The bad blood continues to
simmer: the Orioles' Norm Charlton knocked down Strawberry with a
fastball in the seventh inning on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre has used Strawberry intermittently, in
situations tailored to Strawberry's strengths. He almost never
plays against left-handed pitchers, and sometimes he doesn't start
against right-handed pitchers who throw particularly hard. Whereas
Tim Raines never seems to lose his swing, Strawberry is often left
searching for his, after a couple of days off, hacking wildly.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, however, Strawberry felt all right. In batting
practice, he hammered a ball halfway up the scoreboard in Camden
Yards. Imagine a space shuttle launching: 480 feet, the first ball
ever hit to that spot in the ball park. A portent of good things to
come for Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of days, I took some extra b.p.,'' Strawberry
said. ``It really kind of got me going. I had a good rhythm
going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way he's swinging the bat,'' Torre said. ``I like
the life in his bat.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone said: ``Straw had a little fire in his eye. He wasn't
happy about missing the game on Wednesday night and being out of
the lineup. It was almost as if he had something to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the Yankees' offense this year has been the
patience of its hitters. Even when they haven't generated hits,
they have forced the opposing pitcher to work hard and throw an
inordinate number of pitches. Boston's Pedro Martinez once needed
130 pitches to get through five and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   Without the injured stars Bernie Williams and Derek Jeter,
however, the quality of the Yankees' at-bats has eroded. The young
left fielder Ricky Ledee has replaced Williams, often going down on
one or two pitches; the free-swinging Luis Sojo has taken over for
Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, they reversed this trend against the
Orioles' Mike Mussina. Sojo walked with one out in the first
inning, the culmination of a seven-pitch at-bat and only Sojo's
second walk this season in 62 plate appearances. Paul O'Neill then
hit a bouncer through the third-base hole; Sojo stopped at second.
Mussina blew a 92-mile-an-hour fastball past Tino Martinez for a
strikeout and the second out of the inning. (Martinez was batting
.326 when Armando Benitez threw a fastball into his back May 19.
His average has subsequently dropped more than 35 points.)
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who had been 0 for 6 in his career against Mussina,
strolled to the plate, booed lustily, for being himself and for
taking a punch at Benitez last month. Mussina missed with a
curveball to run the count to 2-1. Mussina threw a tailing
fastball, his 20th pitch of the inning. Strawberry swung, and in
center field, Brady Anderson took one step back and stopped, slowly
turning around and looking skyward. A high wall looms beyond the
center-field wall, and Strawberry's home run skipped off that.
</P>
<P>
   Three innings later, Joe Girardi smacked a hanging curveball
into the left-field stands. Baltimore home runs by Rafael Palmeiro
and Joe Carter cut into the lead against Pettitte, but he was in
control after seven innings with a 5-2 advantage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
