A4659 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-ALBRIGHT-1STLD-W     06-18 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-ALBRIGHT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETARY OF STATE RESPONDS TO OVERTURES FROM IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to   report on actual speech instead of prepared version;
rewriting throughout)  (See also IRAN-U.S.) 
(mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called on Iran
Wednesday night to join the United States in drawing up ``a road
map leading to normal relations.'' She made the remark as part of
the Clinton administration's first comprehensive reply to cautious
overtures from Iran's moderate president.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years after the 1979 Iranian Revolution ruptured
relations with Washington and installed a fundamentalist Islamic
government in Tehran, Albright said it was time to find ways to
bridge the gap between the two nations and the civilizations they
represent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to do so would be irresponsible,'' she said, insisting
that the United States had no quarrel with Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who is regarded as one of the administration's
harshest critics of Iran, changed course Wednesday night in a
speech in New York to the Asia Society, and focused on promising
aspects of the new Iranian government. In her remarks, she hailed
President Mohammad Khatami, who took office last summer, as a man
who ``deserves respect because he is the choice of the Iranian
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Khatami was elected with the strong support of women and others
who hope for a relaxation of Islamic rule, but conservatives want
to reverse the trend. Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's supreme
leader, is a conservative.
</P>
<P>
   While praising Iran for taking several steps to redress
longstanding conflicts, Albright also demanded progress on human
rights, a turning aside from terrorism, and evidence that Iran was
not trying to develop weapons of mass destruction. She offered no
specific incentives or promises of additional American actions, but
said the United States was ``ready to explore further ways to build
mutual confidence and avoid misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright noted that the United States had relaxed rules on
travel to and from Iran and supported cultural and academic
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Islamic Republic should consider parallel steps,'' she
said. ``If such a process can be initiated and sustained in a way
that addresses the concerns of both sides, then we in the United
States can see a very different relationship. As the wall of
mistrust comes down, we can develop with the Islamic republic, when
it is ready, a road map leading to normal relations.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of state listed steps Iran has taken in recent
months that have been viewed favorably in Washington, including
giving public support to Yasser Arafat _ and not more radical
leaders or groups _ as the voice of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Khatami had denounced terrorism and condemned the
killing of civilians in Israel in January. She also mentioned the
record of Iran in fighting drugs and its efforts to help bring
peace to Afghanistan in talks that involve both American and
Iranian officials. Administration officials also say that other
channels of communication have been opened with Iran, but would not
give details about what they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view these developments with interest, both with regard to
the possibility of Iran assuming its rightful place in the world
community, and the chance for better bilateral ties,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright said that progress where it existed ``must be
balanced against the reality'' of serious obstacles in such areas
as terrorism and Iran's attempts to acquire weapons of mass
destruction, including chemical and nuclear arms. Without progress
on such issues, economic sanctions will remain in place, as will
American opposition to the development of Iranian oil and gas
pipelines, American officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Albright also lamented ``inflammatory and unacceptable'' Iranian
denunciations of Israel, which Tehran does not recognize. And she
asked for more progress in ending serious abuses of human rights.
She did not cite the case of Salman Rushdie, the Indian-born
British writer on whom the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
pronounced a death sentence for blasphemy in 1989 because of his
novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' in which Muslims found derogatory
references to their faith and its founder. A senior official said
Wednesday night that this issue has always been part of the
administration's human rights agenda on Iran, and it was not
necessary to mention it on every occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Albright spoke against a backdrop of deep and unsettling changes
in Asia that administration officials said played a part in her
opening to Iran. Nuclear tests in India and Pakistan have abruptly
changed the atmosphere across the region, provoking concerns that
Iran as well as Iraq could renew hopes of developing nuclear arms.
At the moment the United States has no leverage in Iran and is
losing support for its policy of continued sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Asian economic crisis is beginning to have
ripple effects around the world, adding to the problems India and
Pakistan will face because of the loss of World Bank loans and
other financial aid as a result of the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Asian economic crisis figured in Albright's speech. On the
day that President Clinton stepped in to support the faltering
Japanese currency, she told the Japanese that ``more needs to be
done'' to contain the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   On Indonesia, which she described as ``a country of critical
strategic importance'' to the United States, Albright stopped short
of endorsing President B.J. Habibie's proposals for the gradual
establishment of a genuinely democratic electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   But in a gesture of confidence, she announced that all American
diplomats evacuated from the country in May during the unrest that
led to the fall of President Suharto would now return and that the
United States would step up aid in food and support for democratic
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Albright also touched on Korea, India, Pakistan and
China, reiterating administration policies, the largest part of her
address was devoted to Iran and the administration's long-delayed
response to overtures made to the United States by Khatami in an
interview with CNN in January. In that interview, Khatami, who was
elected a year ago despite the opposition of the country's
conservative religious leadership, spoke of his respect for the
American government because it reflected ``the great American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright went out of her way in her speech to demonstrate that
the United States was not ``anti-Islamic'' and that Americans would
do well to learn to understand ``Eastern civilization and Islamic
civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Islam is the fastest-growing religious faith in the United
States,'' she said. ``We respect deeply its moral teachings and its
role as a source of inspiration and instruction for hundreds of
millions of people around the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
