<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENNETT'S BALLAD TO A `GOOD LIFE'  
 A FAVOR FROM THE BOSS  
 GOOD DEEDS  
 LUCKY DAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can learn a lot about yourself by reading your own
autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Wait a minute, this is a good read,''' declared Tony
Bennett, who left the writing to Will Friedwald, the author of
``Sinatra! The Song Is You: A Singer's Art'' (Da Capo, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   And that was only the opening of ``The Good Life,'' which Pocket
Books is scheduled to publish in the fall. Friedwald is still
working on the manuscript. ``He's now in the 1970s,'' Bennett said.
``He interviews almost everybody I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   And dredges up things that Bennett was too busy living his life
to pay attention to; for example, that he received a presidential
citation in the 1950s. ``I was the GI who went the farthest with my
education under the GI Bill of Rights,'' Bennett said. ``That just
knocked me out.'' (He attended the American Theater Wing, later
known as the Actors Studio. ``The best bel canto teacher, the best
coach for teaching popular singing and jazz, and Stanislavsky's
secretary, who performed with Stanislavsky, as an acting coach,''
Bennett said.)
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that becoming a co-author was not his own idea.
``They called me,'' he said of the editors at Pocket Books. ``I'm
at the right age. I'm going on 72. It's just naturally a time when
you start reflecting, even though you don't like to retrogress.
It's a time when you can see a story in all the different things
that have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Boss, Always the Boss
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner saw five teen-agers spray-painting graffiti
on Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the one with the can,'' Ray Negron recalled Wednesday.
``He's telling me he's going to have me arrested, damaging Yankee
Stadium, sacred ground, etc. They had a holding cell downstairs.
He's telling me he's taking me there, a little police station. I'm
begging him to give me a chance. He asks me, why should I give me a
chance? I said, `Because my mother's going to kill me.' He makes a
quick about-face. He takes me to the Yankee clubhouse. The door
opens up, he pushes me in and says, `Give this guy a uniform. He's
got damage he's got to work for.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was 25 years ago. Negron was a batboy for a couple of
seasons, then played with the Pittsburgh Pirates organization.
Later, he returned to the Yankees, working with Reggie Jackson and,
more recently, Dwight Gooden. He left the Yankees in January to
work for the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   But he still has the boss' telephone number, which is how
Negron's 13-year-old son, Jon-Erik, came to be a batboy for a day
at Yankee Stadium last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did great,'' Negron said. ``People love to trash George.
But think about it: That was a million-to-one shot that George
Steinbrenner was going to catch me. I hope this doesn't start a
whole flurry of kids doing graffiti at Yankee Stadium. Look out.
People don't realize George was a track star in school.''
</P>
<P>
   `Seinfeld' and Ford Benefit Charities
</P>
<P>
   Old ``Seinfeld'' scripts keep surfacing. The Urban Justice
Center, a nonprofit advocacy organization for the homeless, said it
would auction a script for the last episode of the long-running
sitcom at a benefit next week. The center got the script from one
of its directors, Phyllis Louis-Dreyfus, the stepmother of Julia
Louis-Dreyfus, who played Elaine on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a silver cover, very fancy,'' said Ann Vermes, the
center's director of development. ``I'm guarding it with my life.''
A script from the final episode of the show about nothing is worth
something: Ms. Vermes said she had read on the Internet that a
similar script sold for $9,100 on the night the final episode was
broadcast last month ... Anne Ford, a daughter of Henry Ford II and
a great-granddaughter of the founder of Ford Motor Co., is pledging
$1 million to the National Center for Learning Disabilities, a
Manhattan group of which she is chairwoman. Her commitment is
personal: her daughter, Allegra Ford, was diagnosed with severe
learning disabilities 20 years ago. ``I determined, back when my
daughter was very young,'' she said, ``that I must help all those
parents like me, who feel helpless in a world where
misunderstandings about learning disabilities can devastate you.
Parents still feel uncomfortable about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Randall at Center Stage &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tony Randall got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, his public relations agency sent out faxes saying
that Randall, 78, was ``pacing with anxiety.'' His wife, Heather,
28, was pregnant, and Randall hoped the baby would be born on a
Monday, ``because in his 60 years onstage, Tony Randall has never
missed a performance.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Jefferson Salvini Randall was born at Beth-Israel
Hospital on Monday, Randall's day off from ``The Sunshine Boys''
with Jack Klugman at the Lyceum Theater. The 7-pound, 2-ounce boy
is the second child for the Randalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could write such a story?'' Randall said Wednesday. ``I
always thought my father was too old to have children. I guess it's
repeating family history. I think my father was in his 60s when we
were born.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby was named for two 19th-century performers. ``One was a
comedian, one was a tragedian,'' Randall said. ``He'll be the
master of them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
