r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX     06-18 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSE TO ATHLETICS, 3-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ This time don't blame the starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   That was the only part of the Rangers' game that stood up last
night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   But John Burkett's strong seven innings weren't enough to
overcome defensive lapses or the offensive futility against Oakland
starter Kenny Rogers, and the Rangers' slide continued with a 3-2
loss. The Rangers have lost six of seven games and are 9-14 since
May 24 after a 31-16 start. They've lost nine of their past 12
games at The Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're losing it's tough,'' Burkett said. ``But I haven't
played with a team yet that went through a whole season playing
well. In '93, I was with the Giants and we won 103 games, but we
lost eight in a row at home in August. We're in a low point right
now, but we've got a team that's going to keep going out there and
firing away and taking our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' defensive mistakes came from two of their more
reliable defenders. First baseman Will Clark committed two errors
that led to two unearned runs, and shortstop Kevin Elster's bobble
on a possible rally-killing double-play ball in the second led to
another run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about the rest of the team, but I didn't help
John tonight,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave three runs away,'' manager Johnny Oates said. ``Our
defense was not been very sharp tonight to say the least.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been lately. Starting pitching has been the focal
point of the Rangers' troubles, but their defense has fallen off as
well. The Rangers, who won a division title two years ago by
leading the league in defense, have committed 17 errors in their
past 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   The offense was missing last night as well, even though a
left-hander was on the mound. The Rangers were hitting a
league-best .345 against left-handers before last night's game but
managed just four hits through seven scoreless innings against
Rogers. Roberto Kelly's two-run homer in the eighth made it a 3-2
game, but the Rangers could do no more against Oakland relievers
Mike Fetters and Bill Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's troubles started in the first inning when he couldn't
handle Ben Grieve's sharply hit two-out grounder. The Athletics
followed that with a single from Matt Stairs and a double by Mike
Blowers to take a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada started the second inning with a single, and
Elster could only get a force after bobbling Ryan Christenson's
grounder. A.J. Hinch's single put runners on first and third, and
Christenson scored when Clark threw too late to home on Rickey
Henderson's chopper.
</P>
<P>
   The final defensive mistake came in the eighth, and it proved
even more painful after Kelly's home run. With two outs and runners
at first and third, Tejada broke for second base. Catcher Ivan
Rodriguez's throw had him beaten so badly that Tejada stopped and
was caught in a rundown. But Clark, trailing on the play, failed to
catch a short toss from second baseman Luis Alicea and Blowers
raced home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I booted one, and on the other I got too close to the
runner,'' Clark said. ``We had a collision, and that's when the
ball popped out. I'm not going to make excuses. When things are
going well, you can get away with mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the Rangers aren't going well. The frustration is
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks ago, it seemed no matter how many runs the other
team scored, we would score more,'' Burkett said. ``No matter what
the situation, we would win the ballgame. Now it's the other way.
But I'm sure we'll get it turned around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
