<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-18 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros
</P>
<P>
   Four-run ninth &QL; 
against Brantley &QL; 
sinks Cardinals
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Add Jeff Brantley to the list of high-profile closers the Astros
have beaten and battered this season, particularly in the past nine
days.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros hijacked Brantley for four runs in the bottom of the
ninth en route to a 6-5 come-from-behind victory over the St. Louis
Cardinals on Wednesday at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Astros' 20th come-from-behind victory of the season,
and the 11th time they have won in their last at-bat. If Brantley
needs a support group, he might get some sympathy from Detroit's
Todd Jones or Cincinnati's Jeff Shaw. Both fell prey to the Astros'
ninth-inning magic in the past nine days, Jones being victimized
twice.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 37,417 was in place at the beginning of the game, but
about 10,000 of them headed for the exits after Mark McGwire's
final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have one (thing to say) for those people who left after
(McGwire's) last at-bat,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``They must not have been following this club very closely in the
last couple of weeks. We do have a habit of pulling off some
miraculous finishes.''
</P>
<P>
   This one was a heart-stopper. The Astros entered the ninth
trailing by four runs but showed the confidence of Michael Jordan
on a layup. Derek Bell drove home a run with a sacrifice fly, Jeff
Bagwell hit a tying two-run homer, and Brad Ausmus provided the
slam dunk with a game-winning single off Curtis King, who was
unsuccessful in his attempt to rescue Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for something over the plate,'' said
Ausmus, who was 3-for-4. ``That's probably the most fun I've had on
a hit this year. It's great when the guys come out and hit you on
the top of the head and you get to walk off the field a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good offensive club, and you know we're going to
score runs, so you can never count us out. Four runs in the ninth
inning is a possibility for us. On the scoreboard, it looks worse
than it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros increased their lead over the Chicago Cubs to three
games in the National League Central Division. They also pushed the
Cardinals 9{ games off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' rally spoiled a strong outing by Cardinals starter
Todd Stottlemyre and took Astros starter Jose Lima off the hook for
what was shaping up to be a hard-luck loss. Stottlemyre, the
Cardinals' only healthy front-line starter, held the Astros to two
runs in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Lima matched Stottlemyre's effectiveness on the mound, but a
crucial eighth-inning throwing error cost the Astros starter a
chance at his eighth victory and would have cost his team the game
if not for another exhibition of late-inning magic.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 2 and runners on first and second, Lima
pounced off the mound to field Tom Pagnozzi's sacrifice-bunt
attempt. Lima had a play at third base on pinch runner David
Howard, but the pitcher's throw to third baseman Bill Spiers ended
up in the Cardinals' bullpen down the left-field line. Willie McGee
scored all the way from first, and the Cardinals added one more run
in the inning to take a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Another large crowd came out to watch McGwire, and this time he
lived up to the hype. After going 0-for-3 on Tuesday, McGwire was
3-for-5 with two singles and his 32nd homer Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I was very happy about (the crowd leaving so
early),'' Bagwell said. ``I understand people want to see Mark, but
I'd like to think they'd also be coming to see the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing some pretty good baseball. We're a
resilient club, and that's a good feeling to have this early in the
season. A win like this was a big lift for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre struggled with his control in the first inning,
walking the bases loaded and giving Carl Everett a chance to do
some damage. Everett, who is hitting .400 with the bases loaded
this season, grounded out to second to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were more efficient in the second inning, turning two
singles and a sacrifice bunt into a 1-0 lead. Craig Biggio singled
home Ausmus, who hit a one-out single and moved into scoring
position on Lima's perfectly placed bunt.
</P>
<P>
   To say the Cardinals tied the score in a hurry would be an
understatement. One swing of McGwire's bat resulted in one of the
quickest home runs you'll ever see. Lima got ahead 1-2 in the count
and tried to blow an inside fastball by McGwire, whose line-drive
home run exited the confines of the playing field with warp speed.
</P>
<P>
   Everett reclaimed the Astros' lead on Stottlemyre's first pitch
of the sixth inning. The center fielder crushed Stottlemyre's
offering for his sixth homer of the season and his first at the
Astrodome in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Cardinals had an immediate response for the
Astros. Left fielder Brian Hunter led off the seventh with his
third home run. It was the 14th homer surrendered by Lima this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' eighth-inning rally started with a heady play by
veteran third baseman Gary Gaetti, who surprised the Astros with a
line-hugging bunt down the third-base line. Howard entered the game
as a pinch runner for Gaetti and moved to second on McGee's sharp
single to right.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it appeared things were going to fall apart for the
Astros, but they've gotten to be pretty good at working miracles in
the final inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
