<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT BORING, YES, BUT WESTPHAL HAS MOXIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The most recent photograph of George Karl published in
the P-I showed the former Sonic coach standing in shorts atop a bar
in a local bistro, baseball hat backwards and beer in hand,
exhorting his fans at a self-thrown farewell bash.
</P>
<P>
   In the dozens _ maybe hundreds, if things go as Wally Walker
hopes _ of photographs the P-I will publish of Karl's successor,
Paul Westphal will never be captured in so earthy a repose.
</P>
<P>
   Pity.
</P>
<P>
   In the personality portion of the Sonics' little comparison
contest, Karl dunks all over Westphal _ just a crotch-grab away
from a full Kemp. Karl's engaging volatility was appealing as the
class clown.
</P>
<P>
   Until, of course, it's time to pass a hard test. Hearing funny
mouth noises from the back of the room is not a help.
</P>
<P>
   In the basketball portion of the comparison, Westphal matches up
a whole lot better.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal didn't make the NBA's list of top 50 players, but if
the list were expanded to 100, he would have. The Phoenix Suns'
leading scorer was voted to the NBA's first team three times in the
late 1970s, when he was perhaps the chief nemesis of the Sonics'
powerhouse teams. Karl as a player was a gritty sub who blew out
his body taking too many charging fouls from George McGinnis.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, Westphal prepped for his current duties with three
years at teensy colleges in Arizona before spending four years as a
Suns assistant. Karl banged around the CBA and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As an NBA coach, Karl has been fired three times, Westphal once,
but he had a later start. They have each lost to the Bulls in an
NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   And they have both had top-seeded playoff teams on the precipice
against eighth-seeded teams.
</P>
<P>
   Difference was, Karl lost and Westphal won.
</P>
<P>
   The year before the Sonics' suffered their ignominious
first-round loss to the Denver Nuggets _ the first and only time a
No. 1 seed has lost in the opening round _ Westphal, in his rookie
year as Suns head coach with a team that won 62 regular-season
games, lost the first two games at home to the eighth-seeded
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, Westphal pulled off one of the more stunning coaching
stunts of the '90s _ he flat-out predicted his team would sweep the
Lakers and win the best-of-five series.
</P>
<P>
   Durned if he wasn't right. They went on to the Finals, going
through San Antonio and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else was I going to do?'' Westphal said Wednesday,
grinning at the recollection. ``I heard later (his Suns' bosses)
wondered, `What is he doing?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really felt we were a better team than L.A., and I
wanted my team to know it. If faced with the same situation again,
I don't think I'd do it. But it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   One good move does not a coach make. But in the thin line
between success and firing in the NBA, imagine what would have
happened had Karl finagled one more win over the Nuggets in a year
that Michael Jordan played baseball and the Houston Rockets became
champions.
</P>
<P>
   The guess here is the Sonics would have won the 1994 title, Karl
would still be employed as Sonic coach and Westphal would still be
helping coach his local high school team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many ironies in coaching,'' Westphal said. ``It's
not an exact science. You do what you think is best at the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is as good a reason as any to think the Sonics are in
quality hands with Westphal. The NBA remains a player's game, which
Westphal knows and is happy about. He doesn't have an unusual
defensive system, nor was his offense as Suns coach known for its
triple-post majesty.
</P>
<P>
   He's a proven manager of egos and game strategy, and is secure
in himself. That's all Walker needed, all the players want, and all
Sonic fans should worry about in qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think you'll miss Karl's passion borne of his
ultra-competitiveness, well, Westphal has been brought to agonized
tears, too.
</P>
<P>
   When they were Sonic teammates in the 1980-81 season, Walker
remembers going to dinner on the road at a Mexican restaurant with
Westphal. For no reason other than he couldn't help making a
competition out of a meal, Westphal asked Walker to buy him dinner
if he ate all the jalapeno peppers in a bowl on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Walker sampled one, felt his tongue dissolve, and said, ``You're
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Westphal knew he was in trouble, his face
turning Soviet red and sweat coming in rivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he wouldn't back down,'' Walker said. ``He said he was
going to do it, and he got them all in his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a pitcher of margaritas, a tubful of sour cream and most
of the evening before the fire was put out, but not before his
tablemates exhausted themselves in laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best $6 worth of entertainment I've ever had,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   You know, catching Westphal in a bar might not be so boring
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
