u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-WEST-SPI &LR;      06-18 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITIVE, CREATIVE, WESTPHAL HAS ADMIRERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Westphal is formal yet casual. From his appearance, you
think you are being shown the living room _ only to discover it's
the family room after all.
</P>
<P>
   He is conservative yet liberal. One of his best friends is Rush
Limbaugh, the right-wing political commentator. Then you turn
around and notice that Westphal likes to draw up unconventional
plays, make boastful comments and rule his troops with leniency.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think the Sonics hired a total opposite to George
Karl, take another look. Westphal is known for being a bench coach,
a player's coach, a creative coach.
</P>
<P>
   Like one of the moves he made as an All-Star, Westphal can be
deceiving. Perhaps he wears a white collar. But he is a
button-down, suck-it-up kind of coach, expecting the most from his
players and himself. The new Sonics leader is a highly competitive
person who does not seem that way because of the smile that usually
accompanies the wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be a beard or an anguished expression on the
sidelines this season. The same energy that Karl bared from every
pore is secluded in Westphal, but raging nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul appears relaxed like Larry Bird,'' said Suns coach Danny
Ainge, who played under Westphal for three seasons in Phoenix.
``You don't know if the fire is burning. I can assure you, the fire
is burning.''
</P>
<P>
   You would know that if you have ever tried to beat Westphal at
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate losing more than I love winning,'' he said. ``If my
image is that I'm so laid-back that I don't care what happens, then
that's so far away from who I am, it's like coming out of the
Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   So this is what that feeling drives him to do. One night in the
early 1980s, after Westphal was traded to Seattle for Dennis
Johnson, Westphal engaged in endless games of H-O-R-S-E with
then-Bellevue Community College basketball coach Ernie Woods at the
BCC gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played all night long and by the time we left, it was
daylight,'' Woods said. ``Nobody wanted to go home a loser.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's wife, Cindy, won't play Monopoly with him anymore
because of how he acts when he loses.
</P>
<P>
   But Westphal loves games and challenges. He used to invite
friends over to his house for a Superstars-like competition, a
decathlon of events featuring basketball and volleyball in his
swimming pool, backgammon, tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, it was his own international Olympics,'' said
Keith Erickson, a former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't beat you straight-up, he will invent ways to win,
not by cheating but by innovation. This type of originality must
have been attractive to Sonics president Wally Walker. When Phoenix
and Boston met in the 1975 NBA Finals, Garfield Heard hit the
turnaround shot to force a third overtime at Boston Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal made it possible. Phoenix trailed by one. A second
remained. The Suns had the ball under the Celtics' basket. The Suns
did not have a timeout but Westphal called one anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the penalty was a technical foul, but the offending
team kept the ball. Boston made the free throw, but Phoenix got the
ball at midcourt, resulting in a higher-percentage inbounds pass to
Heard.
</P>
<P>
   While coaching at Phoenix, Westphal's Suns were in a similar
situation. Phoenix trailed by one. Everyone knew that Charles
Barkley would get the ball, including the opponent, which swarmed
him. Westphal instructed Oliver Miller to throw the ball from
midcourt and bounce it off the glass, hoping the ricochet would end
up in the cutting Barkley's hands. The play did not work, but
Westphal scored anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul always had a feel for the game,'' said former Suns coach
Cotton Fitzsimmons. ``He thinks ahead. He's imaginative. He's like
Columbus _ he'll take chances on new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes up with things nobody else would dream of,'' Erickson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But then came a few nightmares. Expectations grew like Miller,
engulfing the Valley of the Sun. After Westphal guided the Suns to
the NBA Finals in his first season in 1992-93, they were eliminated
two years in a row by Houston in the Western Conference semifinals
_ in Game 7 both times.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of injuries and apparent player unhappiness,
Westphal was fired the next season on Jan. 16, 1996, with the Suns
languishing at 14-19.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unfair what happened to him,'' Charles Barkley said
Wednesday from the clubhouse at Gainey Ranch in Scottsdale, Ariz.
``He didn't deserve to be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal had a different set of rules for Barkley and that
disturbed at least one player, A.C. Green. But Westphal figured it
was necessary to cater to his star player, in the same way Phil
Jackson tolerated Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul either had to alienate Charles or work with him,''
Erickson said. ``Everybody has to realize you're going to make
concessions for a superstar. Players on the team held grudges
against Charles and Paul, which was absolutely asinine.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ainge: ``Nobody can coach Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   How Westphal plans to deal with the cantankerous Gary Payton
will be critical to the Sonics' success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't have to handle Gary, Gary should just do his damn
job. He's making $10 million to play,'' Barkley said. ``He should
enjoy playing for Westphal.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley did. ``Y'all got a very good coach and a great person,''
he said. ``His character is beyond reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Karl once had a non-drinking clause in his contract,
Westphal is a teetotaler. When the Suns played the Bulls in the
Finals, Ainge recalled a revealing story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us he wanted to win the championship and celebrate
with soda pop instead of champagne,'' Ainge said. ``He wanted to
set a good example.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal is a religious man, but Ainge knows him better as one
who possesses patience. Undoubtedly, Barkley was his instructor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be so easy to yell and scream, but he would deal with
things the right way because he has his life in the right
perspective,'' Ainge said. ``He never made it seem like it was
panic. He got great performances as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   You might see him smiling, even joking at the strangest times,
times when Karl would be the tormented soul on TV screens
everywhere. Westphal once mockingly gave Barkley the ``choke'' sign
after Sir Charles missed a big shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches look like death on the sidelines,'' Ainge said.
``It gets to you as a player. Paul has a tendency to laugh at a
mistake you just made. It's his way of loosening a player up. He
builds confidence in people.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some players grew to disdain the treatment he gave
Barkley, Westphal originally had their support. He has a long
rotation, doling out minutes to many players.
</P>
<P>
   As with Karl, Westphal plays hunches. During the '93 Western
Conference finals against the Sonics, he started Tom Chambers, then
Cedric Ceballos, then Richard Dumas at small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Paul gets up in the morning, if his dog licks his left
hand, he goes with Richard,'' Ceballos said at the time. ``If his
dog licks his right hand, he starts me.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dumas: ``I'm gonna go shoot that dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal drills his teams in training camp and practices more
leisurely during the season, sparing the ailing veterans. He will
only criticize in private and crack down when vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy needs it, I'll flex my muscles or hit him with the
hammer,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   He won Barkley over with a proclamation at an astounding time.
After the Lakers took the first two games _ in Phoenix _ of their
playoff series, Westphal publicly stated that the Suns would storm
back to win the first-round series in '93.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a defining moment,'' Barkley said. ``That let me know
he had great confidence in all of us. He treated everybody like a
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal has not returned to coaching mainly for two reasons _
he has been waiting for the right opportunity and his son, Michael,
to graduate from high school. They both occurred this month.
</P>
<P>
   Now he heads to Seattle for his next game of chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
