<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-USOPEN-SPI &LR;      06-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CLUB HAS TOUGH REPUTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The hearts that have been left here in past U.S.
Opens include those belonging to some of the greatest names in the
history of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer and Tom Watson all succumbed to the
siren song that whispers from the Cyprus-lined fairways and tangled
rough of The Olympic Club Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan called this the ``longest short course in the world''
after losing the Open to unknown Jack Fleck in 1955. The course
crushed Palmer in the 1966 Open during a playoff loss to Billy
Casper, after Palmer led the final round by five strokes with five
holes to play.
</P>
<P>
   And Watson was humbled by Scott Simpson in 1987 when Simpson
played the last six holes with three birdies and three pars to
erase Watson's one-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   In those three previous Opens here, only four players have
managed to break par over the duration of the tournament. All this
from a 6,826-yard course that has no water that comes into play and
only one lonely fairway bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the next victims left looking in frustration at the
stunning views of the Golden Gate and Baghdad by the Bay? Odds are
that long hitters like Tiger Woods and Fred Couples will have
difficulty avoiding the inevitable disasters that lurk around every
twist and turn. This is not a course where corners can be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, you won't see many birdies,'' Couples said. ``A guy
who plays well may have three birdies, two bogeys and all pars. If
you do that for two days, and hang in there for two more, you can
win. But I don't think 5- or 6-under is going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even par could even be a score to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about the history of the course and the great
players it has devoured, Woods responded that a win at Olympic
would be as memorable as his 1997 Masters victory for that very
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if I could (win),'' Woods said. ``One,
because we have had some great moments that have happened here, but
I think for me more importantly is that this is near where I used
to live. I used to live 20 minutes down the road at Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   But local course knowledge isn't much of a guarantee for success
at Olympic, as witnessed by Watson, another Stanford product.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there are bittersweet memories,'' said Watson, whose
loss to Simpson represented the closest he would ever get to
winning the coveted Open.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, the course is likely to be even more difficult
than in 1987. The toughest hole that year, the par four, 468-yard
17th, is 40 yards longer. It normally plays as a 522-yard par five
for members.
</P>
<P>
   What's worse, according to Watson, is that the poa annua rough
is longer, deeper and more sinister than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rough is the worst rough, most difficult rough that I
have seen in the U.S. Open _ ever,'' Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success will be out-thinking the course and avoiding
the temptation to try for heroics, said one of golf's greatest
shotmakers, Jack Nicklaus, playing in his 42nd Open. He won four of
them, but finished tied for 46th at Olympic in 1987 and third
behind Casper and Palmer in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course certainly is a formidable test,'' Nicklaus
said. ``And the ability to score on the course is going to largely
involve manipulation of the golf ball and patience.''
</P>
<P>
   To Nicklaus, experience will be the key, which means that
players like Watson could be considered among the favorites,
especially with Watson coming off of a win May 31 at the Mastercard
Colonial Country Club in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certainly a golf course that most of the young kids
today will not have experienced,'' Nicklaus said. ``Certainly, some
of the more experienced guys will probably have a little bit of an
edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples agreed: ``I'm not saying you can't have a fluke winner,
because everyone is talented. But I think it's going to take
someone with a lot of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson, 48, laughed when told that he was considered one of
those who could possibly win the event because of his experience at
Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, `possible winner' from `not a chance' is a big upgrade
for me, isn't it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Watson wouldn't rule out Woods' chances of another major
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tiger is a threat any time he tees it up,'' he said.
``He can play this course. He is going to have to lay up with on a
lot of holes here, but he can lay up with a 2-iron and still hit it
out as far as me with my driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Another one of the young players who might do well here is 1997
British Open champion Justin Leonard, who has the solid, all-around
game that Olympic requires. Leonard overcomes his inexperience with
measured precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to come in here overconfident,'' Leonard said.
``I'm a very patient player, which I really think pays off in this
kind of event.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson offered this assessment after comparing the course
conditions now with 1987: ``This year the rough is definitely
longer. I think it is as long and tough as anywhere we have played.
... Overall, the course looks pretty much like I remember. Yeah, it
is tough. It is just a tough, real fair golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how he plays this week, the course will forever be
there embedded in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has changed my life in that I always will be known as a
U.S. Open champion,'' Simpson said. ``... At least that one week, I
accomplished something incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
