<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIGH STYMIES YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Eric Young says he won't need to go on the disabled
list, but his strained right thigh is not getting better. He was
scratched from Wednesday's Los Angeles Dodgers lineup with
continued soreness even though he stole a base and scored in
Tuesday's 10-6 loss to the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The thigh, first injured May 21 in Chicago, forced him out of
the next three games. He came out in the third inning of the June 9
game against Oakland and did not play the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it is chronic, but it doesn't seem to be
getting better,'' Dodgers manager Bill Russell said. ``It's a
strange injury. He stole a base last night, but he has trouble
running from first to third or second to home. We hope the night
off will help.''
</P>
<P>
   Young says his condition is day-to-day, ``and I don't think I
will have to go on the D.L. But it's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Young is expected to play tonight against the Rockies, his
former team. His day off against Oakland preceded the
Dodgers-Colorado series at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   __ Martinez diagnosed: Wednesday, right-hander Ramon Martinez
saw Angels orthopedist Lewis Yocum, who confirmed the cartilage
damage and torn rotator cuff in the right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Martinez will be seen by noted orthopedist William
Andrews in Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has three options: He can have surgery and miss the
rest of the season; undergo therapy and rehabilitation and attempt
to come back as he did last season when he missed two months with a
torn rotator cuff; or he can skip a start and try to pitch during
the Dodgers' next homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez underwent an MRI exam by Dodgers orthopedist Frank Jobe
after coming out of Sunday's game. Yocum examined the MRI and said
Martinez has the same cartilage tear that forced Todd Hollandsworth
to undergo season-ending shoulder surgery last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot tell the severity of an injury unless you go in
(surgically),'' head trainer Charlie Strasser said. ``Not everybody
sees the same things on an MRI. Ramon wanted to get as many
opinions as possible to decide what he wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Johnson leaving: Catcher Charles Johnson will leave the club
after tonight's game to attend the funeral of his maternal
grandmother Ethel Watkins, who died of cancer at the age of 59.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was reared by Watkins after the age of 8 in Ft. Pierce,
Fla., an hour south of the Dodgers' spring-training base in Vero
Beach. He will rejoin the club Sunday in Colorado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
