<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FINDS ITSELF ON SHAKY GROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There is some debate on whether the United States' loss
to Germany in its World Cup opener on Monday has left it in
precarious circumstances heading into Sunday's game with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to gain anything from the match with the Germans has
left the Americans desperate for a victory _ but is that a new
development? Their progression to the second round of the
tournament has always seemed to hinge on triumph in their second
Group F game, a fact that's been amplified by a poor performance in
Monday's 2-0 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a must-win game for us,'' said winger Frankie Hejduk, who
figures to move into the U.S. lineup after providing a spark off
the bench in the second half against Germany. ``There are no more
(playing for) ties for us. We can't afford to play for a tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win these next two games. That's it; that's the
bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not unexpected. The U.S., after analyzing its chances
before the tournament began, knew the Iran game would be important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put ourselves in the position that we pretty much
realized we were going to be in,'' goalkeeper Kasey Keller said.
``We knew going against Germany we probably weren't going to pick
up any points and we needed to accept that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that, really, for us the Iran game would be the first
game we truly needed to get some points in if we wanted to get to
the next round, and that's what we're going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll also need something, perhaps just a draw, from their
first-round finale against Yugoslavia next Thursday. What will be
required to earn a second-round assignment in Montpellier or, more
likely, Toulouse, won't be known until Sunday, after the U.S.-Iran
and Germany-Yugoslavia results are in. A best-case scenario would
be a one-sided win by the U.S. coupled with a decisive German
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, we have to beat (Iran) by two goals,'' Hejduk
said. ``We have to attack from the start ... pressure Iran right
from the kickoff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans didn't do that on Monday, and once Andy Moeller's
header gave Germany an eighth-minute lead, they panicked, falling
into a conservative game plan that cost them any chance of fighting
back. Worse, it led them to second guess their strategy and
personnel in the aftermath of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Sampson questioned the performance of several of his
starters, most notably forward Eric Wynalda, who might be benched
in favor of Roy Wegerle.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, who made no impact on the match and managed no shots,
claimed he suffered from a lack of service, but Sampson wanted no
part of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was in place for Eric to grasp the opportunity,''
Sampson said Wednesday. ``When Frankie got in, he got off a shot,
didn't he? Can you imagine how much work it took to get to the near
post? Tab Ramos got off a shot. Brian Maisonneuve created
situations for himself. I think it's all a matter of how badly you
want it.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's spirits were still sagging two days after the game _
``Just about everybody was down,'' said Ramos, who will move into
the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were into their whining mode and veteran Alexi
Lalas had to snap them out of it with some strong words.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, from the time the players first walked into the
locker room, Alexi lifted their spirits and got them refocused on
the task at hand, which was playing better in the second half,''
Sampson said Wednesday. ``Today in training, he did the same kind
of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran is widely seen as the weakest team in the World Cup, but it
stunned observers with a narrow 1-0 loss to Yugoslavia on Sunday.
With a roster that includes three German-based players _ forwards
Ali Daei and Khodadad Azizi and midfielder Karim Bagheri _ and
several solid youngsters, the Iranians are capable of an upset, and
there is no doubt they will be up for the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to match their aggressiveness, but we're not concerned
with politics,'' Claudio Reyna said. ``Our motivation may be
different than theirs, but we both need three points (from a
victory).''
</P>
<P>
   Much, Sampson suggests, will depend on ``how we respond to
(Monday's) loss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be much more demanding physically, much more
offensive-minded, much more precise in front of the goal,'' he
said. ``These are things we must do to be among the elite
soccer-playing nations. It's very important to show a good response
against Iran.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wynalda: ``We know how to play, we just have to do it. It's
not too late; that's the good news. We have two more games to put
it right and I really believe there are better days ahead of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
