 !dlim! His home run off Seattle pitcher Jeff Fassero powered the
Angels to their 15th win in the past 17 
games. !dlim!!jump1! ANGELS !jump2!!dlim!!jfrom1! ANGELS !jfrom2!!dl
im!!head!Fassero can' t  
pull fast one 
past Erstad!dlim!!head!Angels increase AL West lead!dlim! !by1! By
 Joe Haakenson  
!by2! San Gabriel Valley Tribune !dlim!
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !text! &LR; ANAHEIM _ Seattle Mariners pitcher Jeff Fassero made the
Angels' Darin Erstad look foolish with two breaking balls out of
the strikezone in the seventh inning Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad swung at and missed both, falling behind in the count
1-2, when Fassero got foolish.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero tried to sneak a fastball past Erstad, and when the
baseball finally landed in the right-field seats, the Angels had
taken a 3-2 lead on their way to a 4-2 win before 24,800 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' 15th win in their last 17 games and increased
their lead over the Texas Rangers in the AL West to 1{ games. The
Mariners, meanwhile, fell deeper into last place, 13 games behind
the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's team-leading 16th home run of the season woke up the
crowd and an Angels offense that appeared to be lulled into a
trance against Fassero.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero (5-4) gave up a first-inning run on Tim Salmon's RBI
single, but allowed only three hits during the next five innings as
the Mariners took a 2-1 lead. But in the seventh, after Justin
Baughman singled and took second on Gary DiSarcina's sacrifice
bunt, Erstad turned the game upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback was made possible because Angels starter Omar
Olivares managed to get through some tough innings and keep the
Mariners from running away with it. Olivares (5-2) went eight
innings, allowing two runs and four hits. He has now pitched into
the seventh inning in seven consecutive starts.
</P>
<P>
   The key for Olivares is his sinker, which he needs to keep down
in the strikezone in order to get groundball outs. Wednesday, he
got 17 groundball outs.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Pervical pitched the ninth and earned his league-leading
22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels jumped on Fassero early before he settled down. In
the first inning, Dave Hollins walked, went to third on a single by
Jim Edmonds and scored on a single by Salmon. The Angels, however,
got only two more hits during the next four innings. During one
stretch from the third inning to the sixth, Fassero retired nine
consecutive batters.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Mariners took a 2-1 lead after Alex Rodriguez's
RBI single in the third inning and Dan Wilson's solo home run in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares got help from the defense, which turned three double
plays in the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have risen to the top of the AL West despite a rash
of injuries, particularly to their starting rotation. Sixty percent
of their rotation coming out of spring training is on the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   Starters Jack McDowell, Ken Hill and Allen Watson are trying to
come back from elbow injuries, with only Watson close to returning.
And Watson is still probably two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels have been able to do better than simply hang
tough in their absence, thanks to the three pitchers they now have
in the rotation. Olivares, Jarrod Washburn and Steve Sparks went
into Tuesday's game having combined for 13 starts, and the Angels
won nine of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jarrod Washburn said `I belong here,' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``Steve Sparks said `This is my chance.' And Omar
Olivares always wanted to start. That's why I like competition in
spring training _ there's one job open and two guys are contending
for it. A guy sees a spot and sees the challenge. He says `I'm the
guy.' These guys have accepted the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   All three entered the rotation coming from different situations.
Sparks, 32, is coming off elbow surgery and did not pitch in 1997.
Washburn is a 23-year-old rookie, and Olivares is a journeyman with
a career record under .500 and started this season in the Angels'
bullpen. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
