<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTPHAL: `THIS IS A GREAT JOB' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to identify Walker in eighth graph.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Calm. Clean-cut. Collected.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westphal was every bit as what the Sonics prescribed the
day they decided to change their coaching situation.
</P>
<P>
   As Westphal was ushered in Wednesday as the Sonics' new head
coach, he sat with one leg folded across his knee. When quizzed
about the future of Sonic basketball, his dashing retorts were
accompanied by light satire and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, 47, exuded confidence in himself. He certainly wore no
signs of being intimidated by the success of his predecessor,
George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the majority of my time here won't be talking about
what George did,'' Westphal said. ``I respect the job that George
did ... but I wasn't here.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal filled one job requirement like a waterfall would a
sand pail. Indeed, he is no George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   He will play center Jim McIlvaine more. He is looking forward to
developing young talent. It does not hurt that Westphal will never
be named to the NBA's All-Interview team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further we got into the process, the more evident it
became that Paul was the right man,'' said Sonics president Wally
Walker, who satisfied his self-imposed deadline of hiring a coach
by the June 24 NBA draft. ``His leadership, his people skills, his
knowledge of the game, the fact that he is one of the most
competitive people alive, and you combine that with the fact he's
been a successful competitor at every level, led us to this
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal signed a four-year deal, with the Sonics having an
option on the fourth year. Financial terms were not disclosed, but
the contract is loaded with incentives. Sources said Westphal will
earn between $1 and $1.5 million in base salary each season.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's record as head coach of the Phoenix Suns was 191-88
(.685) in three-plus seasons. Westphal, who coached the Suns to the
1993 NBA Finals in his rookie year as coach, also has a reputation
of handling veteran and star players well.
</P>
<P>
   He was a five-time All-Star guard who has become a player's
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to coach the way that I would have liked to have been
coached,'' Westphal said. ``It's a player's game. You have to
create an environment where they can play up to their potential. As
a player, I would like a coach to listen to me, then he has to have
the last say.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal is believed to have been Walker's choice all along.
Walker also interviewed Bob Hill, Paul Silas and former Karl
assistant Bob Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Walker acknowledged the Sonics waited until after the NBA Finals
were completed to make the hire. But once it became apparent the
indecisiveness of Chicago coach Phil Jackson would hold up the
process, Walker moved forward.
</P>
<P>
   He offered Westphal the job the same night the Bulls clinched
their sixth championship. Westphal, who was in San Francisco at the
time, then met with Sonic point guard Gary Payton Monday in
Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal's agent, Lonnie Cooper, worked out the contract details
with Walker on Tuesday. Westphal said his meeting with Payton was
purely a get-to-know-you gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded like, unfairly, that it was some kind of final
judgment _ to pass Gary Payton's test or something. That wasn't it
at all,'' Westphal said of his lunch with Payton. ``... It was just
a nice time to get together and get to know the new coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal met only with Payton. He plans to talk with the rest of
the team in the coming days. Westphal will also interview assistant
coaches, including the Sonics' staff under Karl: Dwane Casey, Tim
Grgurich and Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Stotts, who was Karl's No. 1 assistant, said he would like
to follow Karl wherever he lands. Walker emphasized his desire to
retain Grgurich, who has a special relationship with Payton and was
instrumental in helping Payton become a superstar player.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Westphal is faced with two important questions: Can he keep
the Sonics as formidable as they have been?
</P>
<P>
   Westphal is known for being an offensive-minded coach. He is
taking over a team that relied heavily on defense during Karl's 6{
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that there is any one way to play basketball
in that we'll play slow ball or fast-break basketball. ... You have
to mold the system to fit the players that you have, offensively
and defensively,'' Westphal said. ``And the idea is to be ahead at
the end of the game. My style, if anything, is to figure out how to
do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't write some book saying this is the Paul Westphal
system on how to play basketball. ... All I'll try to do is get
this team playing as best as it can play, and see how far we can
get in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, though, did plot his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   He did not interview for many coaching jobs during his 18-month
hiatus. Westphal explored the Denver vacancy last year, didn't like
the situation and removed himself from consideration. Westphal was
up for the Dallas job after he was fired in 1996. He lost that
position to former Bulls assistant Jim Cleamons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for a great job and this is a great job. I
couldn't be happier,'' said Westphal, who seemed content living in
Phoenix and coaching a high school basketball team led by his
18-year-old son, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   That aside, there is no wonder Westphal has surfaced again on
the NBA coaching scene. Only his well-known friendship with
ultra-conservative and controversial talk-show host, Rush Limbaugh,
raises eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rush is a nice guy. He's a good friend. I don't apologize for
that,'' Westphal said. ``A person's politics doesn't have anything
to do with whether I can be their friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker downplayed the fact that he and Westphal played for the
1980-81 Sonics. They have spoken at least once a year over the past
decade. Walker and Westphal spoke at least twice this past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and I have been friends,'' said Walker, who is entering
the final year of his five-year contract. ``... I just wanted to
make sure we got the best person for the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
