<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT KEEPS ON WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this before, but Helen Knight has won
another women's championship at El Caballero Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   That makes 36 El Cab titles for the sweet-swinging grandmother,
who learned the game from major champions Tommy Armour and Johnny
Ravolta more than a half-century ago as a University of Michigan
coed.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, who moved to California after World War II, won the
first 32 women's championships played at the Tarzana course and the
last four to make it 36 of 41 overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a surprise,'' Knight said Tuesday, after winning by
20 strokes and averaging 12{ strokes over par during her four
rounds on one of the most difficult courses in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, they're all getting younger, and I'm getting older.
How long can I this keep up?''
</P>
<P>
   She kept it going this year with solid ball-striking that kept
her out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't putt that well, but I kept it in play,'' said Knight,
whose 334 total earned her yet another reprinting of her name on
the club-championship trophy that is already overcrowded with Helen
Knights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll use a little Scotch tape if we have to,'' Knight said.
``We'll paste it on there somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Technology prevails: The big sigh of relief _ $2.5 billion
worth _ at this week's U.S. Open came from equipment makers
Wednesday, following the U.S. Golf Association's announcement that
``probably all'' of the hot new titanium clubs on the market would
pass a proposed new standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not uncomfortable with what we see in the market
today,'' said USGA executive director David Fay in dispelling much
anxiety by clubmakers who feared Wednesday's news conference at
Olympic Club had been called to announce technology-curbing
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fay announced that the USGA has developed a test to
measure the springboard effect from golf clubs and would be sending
it to manufacturers for comment before it is implemented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that clubs submitted at this point have
lessened the skill to play the game at championships such as the
U.S. Open or at a recreational level,'' Fay said.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the equipment makers. Technology-fanned
repeat business helped produce $2.5 billion in wholesale sales of
clubs and balls in 1997, and future sales could increase with the
leading edge of the baby-boomer generation approaching an age of
diminished distance.
</P>
<P>
   The industry had lobbied against anticipated technology-curbing
regulations with recent full-page advertisements protesting any
changes in standards. On Wednesday, Big Bertha and her titanium
brothers prevailed, with an endorsement from a man who is sponsored
by Callaway but doesn't need much help from technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free country,'' said six-time PGA Tour driving champion
John Daly, whose 302-yard average of 1997 exceeded the tour driving
average (269) by more than 30 yards. ``I don't believe in slowing
down technology. That's what America's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Junior rates reduced: Los Angeles City courses will lower the
cost of junior green fees on July 1, from $9 to $5 on a walk-up
basis or $7 on a reservation system. The City reduction follows a
reduction at L.A. County courses, which cut junior fees from $9.50
to $4.75 this year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Stephanie Martin of Camarillo has earned a
berth in the July 2-5 U.S. Women's Open by virtue of her medalist
performance in a sectional qualifier at Timarron Country Club in
Dallas. She shot 74.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur Nicole Dalkas, who just completed her freshman year at
USC, also qualified with a 74 at Mission Viejo Country Club. The
Women's Open will be played at Blackwolf Run Golf Course in Kohler,
Wis....
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kinsell of Glendale, Dan Pouliot and Desi Patao of Burbank
and Victor Keesey of Palmdale have qualified for the SCGA
Championship scheduled for July 10-12 at SCGA Members Club in
Murietta, where defending champion Craig Steinberg of Van Nuys is
bidding for a record fifth title.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsell qualified with a 2-under-par round of 70 at the PGA West
Weiskopf course. Pouliot was medalist at 2-under 70 at Crystalaire,
where Patao shot 74 and Keesey 75. Don Baker, many times the club
champion at Braemar, is an alternate, as are Steve Dougherty of
Burbank, Spike Silver of Woodland Hills and state amateur qualifier
Rick Pratt of Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   __ Only three more shopping days: What do golfing dads want most
for Father's Day? According to a national telephone poll of 500
golfers, what dads really want is to play a round at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   What they have received instead in the past, according to the
survey by Golfsmith International, included exploding golf balls, a
wig, beer-holding golf clubs and clown shoes with spikes. The same
poll asked participants to name their favorite golfer and Freddie
Couples was the overwhelming winner, drawing three times as many
votes as runner-up Tiger Woods.
</P>
</TEXT>
