<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-18 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVARES BEATS OLD TEAMMATES AS ANGELS EDGE MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Omar Olivares pitched so poorly for the
Mariners last season, he didn't even get invited to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He got even Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares said he has no hard feelings toward the Mariners. He
simply is taking advantage of a new start in a new place. He is
pitching for a first-place team again, but instead of being along
for the ride, he's right in the middle of the Anaheim Angels'
surge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the guy we traded for,'' Seattle manager Lou Piniella
said after Olivares stymied the Mariners on four hits over eight
innings in a 4-2 victory at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares looked nothing like the pitcher who had a 1-4 record
and 5.49 earned run average in 13 games with the Mariners after
being acquired from the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't go away mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the move they made (keeping him off the
postseason roster) and it didn't bother me,'' he said. ``I knew the
way I was pitching and so did they.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliveras said the biggest difference between this year and last
is being in a rotation that allows him to pitch ``every fifth day
instead of every ninth day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he could give us innings as a spot starter,''
Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said. ``Then, after we signed
Jack (McDowell), we decided to put (Olivares) in the bullpen. We
liked his versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Bavasi didn't expect Oliveras to have a 5-2 record and 2.70
ERA in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like this,'' Bavasi said, ``but sometimes you get
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares moved into the rotation when McDowell got injured and
the Angels have surged, winning 14 of their past 16 games to build
a 1{-game lead in the American League West over the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The way Mariner starter Jeff Fassero pitched Wednesday night,
even Olivares' best didn't seem good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wilson's fifth-inning home run, his fourth of the season and
first since May 5, presented Fassero with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   It lasted one-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Baughman led off the seventh inning with a single and
shortstop Gary DiSarcina sacrificed the runner into scoring
position. The Angels were playing for the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero fell behind Darin Erstad 2-and-0, threw two wicked
sliders that Erstad swung on and missed badly. Wilson called for
another slider, hoping it would be in the same place with the same
swing-and-miss result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Midway through my delivery I had second thoughts about
throwing another slider,'' Fassero said, ``but it was impossible to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   This slider hung over the middle of the plate and Erstad
deposited it into the right field bleachers for his 15th homer of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mad at myself for throwing that pitch,'' Fassero said.
``It's difficult throwing three good sliders like that in a row. I
hung it. He hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added another run in the inning and the Mariners went
quietly in the eighth inning against Olivares and Angel closer Troy
Percival, who collected his league-leading 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team is going good, they play for a tie by bunting and
then get a two-run homer,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are going real good.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are heading in the opposite direction, losing their
fourth straight and 24th of their past 34 games to fall a
season-high 13 games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're struggling right now and we can't get anything going,''
said Fassero, now 5-4 after a 5-1 start. ``It's a battle. Nothing
is going right for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels jumped out to a 1-0 lead in the first inning, scoring
when Fassero walked Dave Hollins with out and yielded back-to-back
singles to Jim Edmonds and Tim Salmon. The Mariner left-hander
eluded further damage, striking out Cecil Fielder and retiring
Garret Anderson on a comebacker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 0240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
