<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 04:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4768 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BBN-SFCHRON-GIANT     06-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BBN-SFCHRON-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS WIN 2ND STRAIGHT AS KILE, ROCKIES CRUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY SCHULMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be hard to over-hype the importance of the Giants'
four-game series against the first-place San Diego Padres this
weekend, but as reliever Steve Reed sees it, their just-completed
series against the Colorado Rockies might have been more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overlook series like these,'' Reed said after
contributing a scoreless inning to Wednesday's 6-3 victory over
Colorado in the rubber game. ``You have to win series against the
teams you're supposed to beat, the teams that are behind you,
before you go into a series like San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it gives you a chance to bounce back,'' he said. ``If
we dropped two of three in this series, everybody would have been
kind of demoralized.''
</P>
<P>
   After following their 11-game winning streak with five straight
losses, the Giants will take two straight wins into tonight's
series opener with San Diego. With Barry Bonds back in the lineup
Wednesday despite lingering neck pain, the Giants peppered Rockies
starter Darryl Kile and reliever Mike DeJean with 12 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Every Giants starter had a hit, and when was the last time you
read that? Following a familiar pattern for the team, Kirk Rueter
(8-3) spotted Colorado three runs in the first inning, but the
Giants tied it by the second inning and went ahead on Rich
Aurilia's two-run, opposite-field homer in the sixth to deal Kile
(5-10) his seventh straight loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what the score is, we feel if we just pluck, pluck,
pluck, pluck, we can get back in the game,'' said Charlie Hayes,
whose first-inning single with two out brought Bill Mueller home
with the first Giants run.
</P>
<P>
   (Hayes played first base because J.T. Snow's mother, Merry
Carole, died Wednesday at age 54 after a lengthy battle with
cancer. Manager Dusty Baker said Snow would rejoin the team for
tonight's game and play until he leaves for his mother's funeral in
Southern California, on a date to be announced.)
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton contributed a two-out, two-run double in the
second inning to tie the game 3-3, a gift Rueter did not waste as
he blanked Colorado for the rest of his six-inning start.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of gives you a boost back after the top of the first
when you're down 3-0,'' Rueter said. ``I felt I let the team down.
But Charlie's big hit made it 3-1, and Ham- &LR; ju  &LR; bone had a big
double to tie it. That gave us new life. As a starter you say, `All
right, let's start over and see what happens.'''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was Stan Javier leading off the sixth with a
single for his 1,000th career hit and Aurilia driving a 1-1 Kile
fastball over the wall in right to give the Giants a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Mayne added a two-out RBI hit in the seventh, and Rich
Rodriguez, Reed and Robb Nen finished the game. Nen got his 21st
save despite a wearisome ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   One key to nailing Kile might have been a tremendous at-bat by
Hayes in the third inning. After Bonds led off with a single, Hayes
built the count to 3-2. He then fouled off seven straight
fastballs, with Bonds running on every one (a little slower each
time), before finally grounding out on the 13th pitch. On a warm
afternoon, that must have taken a toll on Kile. It certainly did on
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing I was running on a treadmill yesterday, or
I'd be dead,'' Bonds said.
</P>
<P>
   With their 43rd win in hand, the Giants left for a team party
and a night to prepare for the Padres, who smoked them in three
straight last weekend in San Diego. The Giants feel things will be
different this time, at 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got our momentum back,'' Aurilia said. ``We
still miss Jeff (Kent), but I think we've shown in the last couple
of days that we have guys who can contribute to the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hayes, ``When we went down there we didn't play very well.
What we relied on all year, pitching and defense, we only got half
of, the pitching. Our defense was bad. Anytime you give a team like
San Diego more than three outs an inning, you're going to lose.
Hopefully we're back on the right track.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
