 NEWS &AMP; FEATURES SUMMARY No 2456 - JUNE 18, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE MONSTERS OF FATHER'S DAY Just in time to mark Father's
Day, Tim Herrera provides a warm, funny and personal recollection
of two generations of fathers and sons at the movies, and explains
how his family traditions of a Father's Day trip to see a monster
movie ties his sons to their now-deceased grandfather. 900 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
SMOKING DOUBLES RISK OF ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE Smokers may be more
than twice as likely to develop Alzheimer's disease than are people
who have never smoked, according to a new study. The findings
contradict earlier studies that suggested smoking might reduce the
risk of Alzheimer's. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet News Service.
1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
THE JOY OF FRUIT The biggest trouble with maintaining a healthy
diet is that to most of us, the things that are good for us taste
bad, and the things that are bad for us taste good. That's why
fruit is so prized - packed with essential nutrients, it's also
delicious, either fresh and whole or as part of salads, juices or
more elaborate dishes. Ken McAlpine talks to the experts about what
fruit can and can't do for you, why adding fruit to your diet is a
good first step, but not a solution, why athletes need a lot more
fruit than non-athletes and which fruits contain which key
nutrients. From Spirit magazine. 1,400 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
``I WANT MY FEELINGS PURE'' : THE BIRTH-CONTROL PILL'S
</P>
<P>
   INVENTOR IS A VIAGRA SCEPTIC The chemist Carl Djerassi changed
the world when he developed the birth-control pill in the '60s.
Will Viagra, the impotency cure, have a similar impact on sex in
the '90s? Djerassi doubts it. He believes that when the excitement
wears off, it will simply remind women that too many men view
coitus as a mechanical act and women as sex objects. It could also
lead to the further spread of AIDS as older people have more sex.
From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation available.) Q&AMP;A
format.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
SETTING LIMITS FOR YOUR TODDLER Testing their limits comes as
naturally to toddlers as breathing - which can be infuriating for
parents who must again and again deal with the same misbehaviour.
Margery D. Rosen explains why toddlers try your patience, what kind
of limits will be most effective and how you can make it through
the ``terrible twos'' and stay sane. From Child magazine. 1,400
words. 6. TO AVERT DISASTER, THE WEST MUST HEED WARNING
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS IN RUSSIA James H. Billington, the librarian of Congress
and author of ``The Face of Russia,'' writes of turmoil, unrest and
danger in Russia which, if not addressed by the West, could evolve
into the most serious threat to global stability since the end of
the Cold War. New York Times Op-Ed. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
THE GREAT GENE ESCAPE In the future, you might be consuming foods
that include high-yield, insect-resistant breeds of corn and
herbicide-resistant soybeans. They're called ``transgenic'' crops,
and some people claim they may hold the power to increase food
production around the world. Seed companies say the plants they
have created are safe. But who's to know what will come from a romp
in the field with an untamed weed? By Josie Glausiusz. From
Discover magazine. 1,600 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
A TOUCH OF SCIENCE A growing number of scientists are discovering
that a picture just won't do for their purposes. Objects large and
small can now be represented with physical models. From a
laboratory in San Diego comes a mix of science and sculpture that
lets even microbiologists lay hands on their subjects. By Kathy A.
Svitil. From Discover magazine. 1,300 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
EUROPE'S LEADERS ARE PASSING THE BUCK TO BRUSSELS Europe is all set
for a giant new step to integration, the abandonment of national
currencies by 11 of the Union's 15 members and adoption of a
single, common legal tender. But there is little public enthusiasm
for this historic move. Much more effort is needed to sustain
public support for this great enterprise which is transforming the
history of nations. By Flora Lewis. 1,000 words. 
____________________________________________________________________
____ 10. From NEW SCIENTIST magazine (N/A Australia, Brazil, New
Zealand) A. PASTORAL SYMPHONY : Can the natural sounds of birds,
bees and waterfalls help beat the airport blues and soothe stressed
travellers? By Kevin Hilton. B. CATCHING THE TIDE : Giant
underwater turbines will soon start generating electricity from the
sea's ebb and flow. Has tidal power's time come at last? By Fred
Pearce. C. GUT REACTION - IS FOOD TO BLAME FOR AUTISM ? When his
son was diagnosed with autism, biochemist Paul Shattock devoted his
efforts to tracking down the cause. By John McCrone.
</P>
