<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-FE-ART-CENTRAL-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN SANTA FE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JUDITH ANDERSON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Santa Fe, the city of Holy Faith, this year celebrates the 400th
anniversary of Spanish settlement in New Mexico. But Santa Fe was
already old when the Spaniards arrived, and central to nearly
100,000 native people living in 70 nearby adobe pueblos.
 &HT;    This summer, the activities of the Hispanic Cuatro Centenario
blend with the calendar of Native American feast days and the flux
of all-American tourism that characterizes the City Different.
 &HT;    The streets may be crammed with trendy boutiques in faux-pueblo
architecture, but there is usually a balancing glimpse of history
nearby or a salutary view of the surrounding Jemez or Sangre de
Cristo mountains. The clear air at 7,000 feet is permeated with
sage and pinon.
 &HT;    But what really sets this city apart, besides its tripartite
Hispanic-Indian-Anglo world view, is art. All the arts.
 &HT;    Santa Fe isn't a big town _ just 67,000 residents _ yet with the
help of some 1.4 million tourists a year it supports 7 art museums,
about 250 galleries, an eight-week opera season and 10 performance
stages.
 &HT;    Within a single square mile, centered on downtown and Canyon
Road, more than a million pieces of art are concentrated, and that
doesn't include 400 years of sacred images in the churches and
missions.
 &HT;    Summer is high season, marked by abundant music, dance and
theater, by art festivals, wine festivals, mountain-men festivals,
by dozens of feast days in the pueblos, and by the annual markets
in the Plaza.
 &HT;    At Spanish Market, July 25 and 26, more than 100 vendors sell
santos and retablos, weavings and carvings _ the folk art of their
ancestors.
 &HT;    Indian Market, Aug. 22 and 23, a juried competition of more than
500 artists and craftspersons, is one of Santa Fe's most famous
events.
 &HT;    It has often been noted that in a city so steeped in history and
culture, what one most indelibly remembers is the shopping.
Certainly there are stupefying opportunities for buying, in shops
and souvenir stands and directly from the artist who made the
piece.
 &HT;    And yet, holding its own under that commercial veneer, the core
of Santa Fe is still esthetic.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    The 20th annual Santa Fe Arts and Crafts Festival will fill the
Plaza with more than 200 vendors on June 20 and 21. Open 9 a.m. to
6 p.m. each day. Call (505) 988-7621.
 &HT;    On June 23 and 24, San Juan Pueblo, site of the first capital of
New Mexico in 1598, will celebrate the feast of St. John the
Baptist. Foot races and Comanche and Buffalo dances will last from
late morning to midafternoon. About 45 minutes north of town off
Route 68; (505) 852-4400. Check at the Governor's office at the
pueblo to see if photography is permitted.
 &HT;    When the Santa Fe Opera opens its 1998 season on July 3,
audiences will see major improvements to the opera house, including
a roof over all the seats, but it will keep its open-air
atmosphere.
 &HT;    ``Madame Butterfly,'' which opened the first season in 1957,
will inaugurate the renovated house, then alternate with Mozart's
``Magic Flute'' and three other operas. Tickets for the grand
opening are $50 to $200; for the rest of the season, $20 to $118.
Performances begin at 9 p.m., 8:30 starting Aug. 16.
 &HT;    The opera is about seven miles north of town on Highway 84-285;
(800) 280-4654, fax (505) 995-3030; on the Web:
www.santafeopera.org.
 &HT;    The 49th annual Rodeo de Santa Fe, July 8 to 11, will be held at
the rodeo grounds on Rodeo Road, about four miles south of town.
Some events have an admission fee. Information: (505) 471-4300.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    The heart of Santa Fe is the Plaza, built in 1610 by Don Pedro
de Peralta. One side is formed by the Palace of the Governors, 105
West Palace Avenue. Built in 1610, it is the oldest public building
in the United States.
 &HT;    For decades, the portal, or front porch, has been reserved for
the Indians of New Mexico, who set out blankets and sell their
wares (pottery, jewelry and golf ball markers are in this year).
 &HT;    The Georgia O'Keeffe Museum, 217 Johnson St., (505) 995-0785,
boasts a self-consciously hip gift shop and about 100 works by the
artist, who moved to New Mexico permanently in the 1940's. Open 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Sunday, until 8 on Friday.
Admission: $5 for one day, $10 for four-day pass to all branches of
the Museum of New Mexico. Free Friday 5 to 8.
 &HT;    At the Museum of International Folk Art, Aug. 29 will mark the
inauguration of the much-anticipated Neutrogena Wing of textiles
and folk art, with displays from a 3,000-piece collection ranging
from Peruvian leather to Indonesian silks.
 &HT;    One of the most delightfully unexpected museums anywhere, it has
a vast and exuberant collection, ingeniously displayed. Part of the
museum plaza at 706 Camino Lejo, (505) 827-6350. Open 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. Tuesday through Sunday. Admission: $5 or Museum of New Mexico
pass.
 &HT;    Open just a year, the Institute of American Indian Arts Museum,
108 Cathedral Place, (505) 988-6212, houses a national collection
of contemporary Native American art. A sculpture garden and
welcoming circle (a meditation chamber with piped-in music) invite
contemplation. Open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily. Admission: $4.
 &HT;    Canyon Road is two winding miles of galleries, cafes and private
homes in lovely adobes and haciendas. If you walk up it early, you
can catch the opening of most galleries, around 10 a.m., on your
way down. Or drive to a parking lot near the top of the road, just
past Camino del Monte Sol.
 &HT;    In the dust at the roadside beyond the opera house, Trader
Jack's Flea Market is an event every Friday, Saturday and Sunday
from spring through fall. Squash-blossom necklaces may be sold
right next to pickled pig's feet.
 &HT;    It's good entertainment, especially combined with lunch at the
Tesuque Village Market, (505) 988-8848, a few miles up the road.
The flea market usually runs 9 a.m. to dusk. Turn left off Highway
84 just past the opera house.
 &HT;    One way to learn about the regional cuisine _ then eat it _ is
to take a three-hour class ($35 to $57) at the Santa Fe School of
Cooking, 116 West San Francisco Street, on the upper level of the
Plaza Mercado, (505) 983-4511.
 &HT;    At a recent class on Mexican cuisine, Maurice Zeck, executive
chef at La Fonda Hotel, whipped up four courses including pork loin
with peanut mole.
 &HT;    On a mountain less than four miles north of town, Ten Thousand
Waves offers relaxation according to ancient Japanese tradition.
Spa treatments range from a half-hour massage ($35) to a Half-Day
Indulgence: an hour in a private hot tub, an herbal wrap, 90-minute
massage, facial, and a salt-glow treatment _ five hours for $296.
Open from 4:30 p.m. on Tuesday, 10 a.m. other days; closes at
midnight Friday and Saturday, 10:30 p.m. otherwise. Appointments
and directions: (505) 982-9304.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Accommodations in Santa Fe are subject to 10.25 percent tax.
 &HT;    Owned in partnership with the Picuris Pueblo, the Hotel Santa
Fe, 1501 Paseo de Peralta, (800) 825-9876, fax (505) 984-2211,
incorporates microwaves and mini-bars with Native American
storytelling at the kiva fireplace or bread-baking in the outdoor
horno. A 10-minute walk from the Plaza, the hotel runs a free
shuttle all day.
 &HT;    The 129 units, which are mostly suites, are decorated in low-key
Santa Fe style, and many have balconies and mountain views. There
is a heated outdoor pool and hot tub. Doubles, $129 to $149; the 90
suites are $159 to $209.
 &HT;    The Grant Corner Inn Bed and Breakfast, 122 Grant Ave., (505)
983-6678, fax (505) 983-1526, owes much of its popularity to its
location, two blocks from the Plaza, and its Sunday brunch. The
Colonial manor house has 10 guest rooms, some furnished with brass
bedsteads and vintage quilts; all have cable TV. Two rooms share a
bath. Doubles, $95 to $155. Children over 8 are welcome.
 &HT;    Budget: Bare-bones bed and breakfast accommodations are
available right in the heart of downtown at Plaza Resolana en Santa
Fe, 401 Old Taos Highway, (800) 821-5145, fax (505) 986-1917. A
retreat house affiliated with Ghost Ranch Conference Center in
Abiquiu, it lets seven of its 30 rooms. Simple, comfortable rooms
with full private bath have one double bed and one twin bed but no
phone or TV. Doubles, $80 with full breakfast. No smoking.
 &HT;    Two miles north of the Plaza, El Rey Inn, 1862 Cerrillos Road,
(800) 521-1349, fax (505) 989-9249, is surrounded by five acres of
gardens with courtyards, fountains, a heated pool and sunken
whirlpool next to an outdoor fireplace. There are 86 units, some
with fireplaces and kitchenettes. Doubles, $60 to $75, including
Continental breakfast.
 &HT;    Luxury: The Inn of the Anasazi, steps from the Plaza at 113
Washington Avenue, (800) 688-8100, fax (505) 988-3277, refers to
the Ancient Ones with its massive hand-carved doors and sculptured
stairways, but the 59 rooms, all with fireplaces and four-poster
beds, acknowledge every modern creature comfort. Doubles, $239 to
$419.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    For visitors who are out late, casual Il Vicino, off the Plaza
at 321 West San Francisco St., (505) 986-8700, offers a selection
of crispy individual pizzas ($4.75 to about $7) and select ales,
including Pig Tail Blonde and Slow Down Brown Ale, on draft for
about $3 a pint. Open Sunday through Thursday from 11:30 a.m. until
11 p.m., Friday and Saturday 11:30 a.m. to midnight. No
reservations.
 &HT;    In the charming dining room of the Inn of the Anasazi, 113
Washington Ave., (505) 988-3236, regional cuisine tends to rely on
meat and chilies in such dishes as red deer tenderloin stuffed with
apple and spinach and served with chili-peach coulis. A
three-course dinner for two, with wine, runs about $90. Dinner
nightly; breakfast and lunch Monday through Saturday, brunch
Sunday.
 &HT;    One of the newer places in town is Jack's, 135 West Palace Ave.,
(505) 983-7220, which affects a stainless-steel swank. Grilled
salmon with citrus vinaigrette, asparagus and new potatoes can be
preceded by a more inventive appetizer such as a sweet onion tart
with arugula, goat cheese and red pears. A three-course dinner for
two with wine starts at about $70. Lunch and dinner daily.
 &HT;    The six romantic dining rooms at La Tertulia, 416 Agua Fria,
(505) 988-2769, graced by Colonial art, once were part of the
Dominican convent at the Guadalupe Mission. A steak dinner for two,
either straight up or smothered in green chilies, accompanied by
the house sangria, costs around $55. Open for lunch and dinner
every day but Monday.
 &HT;    Tia Sophia's, 210 West San Francisco St., (505) 983-9880, is the
little cafe credited with the invention in 1975 of the breakfast
burrito: bacon and potatoes rolled in a tortilla with chili and
cheese ($5.50). Lunch specialties such as blue corn enchiladas
($5.75) are equally popular today. No alcohol. Open 7 a.m. to 2
p.m., closed Sunday.
 &HT;    Afternoon tea is a treat on the verandah or in the lobby of the
Hotel St. Francis, 210 Don Gaspar Ave., (505) 983-5700. The $10 tea
consists of finger sandwiches, a scone with clotted cream and jam,
and a pastry, accompanied by a pot of tea or glass of sherry, port
or champagne. Daily from 3 to 5:30 p.m.
 &HT;     (Judith Anderson, who writes frequently about the Southwest,
lives in Tucson, Ariz.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Judith Anderson  
