<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-AMERICAN-WEST-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GLIMPSE OF THE REAL AMERICAN WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The Montana Daylight excursion train rambles across the
mountainous portion of Montana and upper Idaho, giving passengers
what may be their only look at the present-day American West.
 &HT;    What they see is rarely observed from the interstate: deep
gorges where autos can't go, punctuated with scenic tunnels dug by
railroad workers before the turn of the century; children returning
from school on horses waving at the train _ even some real cowboys;
cattle grazing lazily on ranges; and a network of rivers, fed by
the Bitterroots, Cabinets and other nearby mountain ranges, many of
which capped by snow, even in midsummer.
 &HT;    In fact, the view from the Montana Daylight is not that
different from printed scenes of the old American West.
 &HT;    Passengers on this rail jaunt see little-known towns defined by
white churches on one end and saloons on the other _ like bookends.
A feed store might be stuck in the middle, where ranchers sit on
rockers and debate the issues of the day.
 &HT;    This part of the country is so remote that during our train ride
a mechanic, totally unaware of the our prying eyes, tried to combat
the midday heat by working in the nude in his garage, which is
alongside the train's tracks. We and our fellow passengers laughed
and cheered as we rolled by.
 &HT;    Indeed, the Montana Daylight is touted as the only overnight
excursion train that shows off the American West, the rugged
country where Lewis and Clark _ and later the Nez Perce and Teddy
Roosevelt _ came through.
 OLD-TIME JOURNEYS  
 &HT;    Our 455-mile journey on the Daylight began at the historic depot
in Livingston, Mont., with an overnight in Missoula, and ended in
Sandpoint, Idaho, on the edge of breathtaking Lake Pend Oreille.
The ride was part of a six-day tour that took us from Salt Lake
City to Spokane.
 &HT;    Aboard the Montana Daylight, a railfan can relive many an
old-time rail journey across America. Diesel engines pull three to
five coaches, much like Santa Fe's El Capitan and the Chiefs; dome
cars like those that once served passengers on the North Coast
Limited and Great Northern's Empire Builder; a rear-end observation
car like the one from the Chesapeake &AMP; Ohio; a rebuilt diner car
from the Nickel Plate Railroad; and private cars from the Chicago &AMP;
Northwestern, outfitted for sleeping and separate dining for
high-paying passengers.
 &HT;    There are three classes of service. Most passengers choose the
``Explore'' class, which features comfortable coaches, continental
breakfasts and box lunches. Those in the ``Big Sky'' class ride in
dome cars and have sit-down lunches in the dining car.
 &HT;    A handful of ``Gold Nugget''-class passengers ride like rail
barons of old, in their wood-paneled private cars with gourmet
meals prepared in separate galleys. At night, Gold Nuggets have
their own elegant sleeping compartments aboard the train.
 &HT;    On the first day, the train crosses the Bozeman Pass (on the
return route of Lewis and Clark), enters the Missouri River
headwaters (the confluence of the Gallatin, the Jefferson and the
Madison rivers) and crosses the Continental Divide at 5,500 feet
through the Mullan Tunnel. This is tunnel-and-trestle railroading,
with steep grades and sharp curves _ great for photography buffs
riding in the open vestibules.
 &HT;    While on the observation deck, we overheard other passengers'
conversations, which were filled with typical railfan questions:
What are the origin of the cars? Why don't most trains go
``clickety-clack'' anymore?
 &HT;    The on-board narrator graciously answered peoples' queries and
talked about the gorges and wildlife we had sighted.
 CAROUSEL AT TWILIGHT  
 &HT;    We arrived in Missoula for our overnight hotel stay just as the
sun was setting and the town's famous carousel was about to close.
It's a new, full-size carousel, which was created by local
volunteers, and we had looked forward to taking a spin on it all
day.
 &HT;    About 30 of us trouped to the ride, explaining our plight _ and
stretching the truth just a bit: We had come all the way from
places like Chicago and Texas just to ride their famous
merry-go-round.
 &HT;    Fortunately, the understanding Missoulans kept it open a little
longer and charged us all the senior-discounted rate of 50 cents a
ride.
 &HT;    For the next half-hour we whirled around like kids on the 38
hand-painted horses, amid bright, blinking lights and loud
pipe-organ tunes.
 &HT;    The next day the Montana Daylight meandered along the Flathead
and Clark Fork rivers, in the rolling valley between the Cabinets
and Bitterroots, leaving the original Lewis and Clark route far to
the south.
 &HT;    Our last night was in Sandpoint, Idaho, and then we traveled by
motorcoach to Spokane, Wash.
 PACKAGED TRIPS  
 &HT;    The two-day train ride is just one part of this Montana Rockies
Rail Tour.
 &HT;    The most popular package among mature travelers begins in Salt
Lake City and includes the Tetons, Yellowstone National Park and _
new this year _ an additional few days in Glacier National Park.
 &HT;    The westbound trip begins every Thursday in Salt Lake City, so
tour-goers can visit Mormon Square and other sites by daylight and
enjoy the free Thursday-evening rehearsals of the Mormon Tabernacle
Choir.
 &HT;    The next two days are spent in a motorcoach, traveling to
Jackson Hole, Wyo., through the Tetons. Tour-goers then spend a
night in Yellowstone Park.
 &HT;    We visited the park's steamy geyser basins and watched the
beautiful wildlife _ bison, elk, moose and mule deer _ leaving the
park at Mammoth Hot Springs.
 &HT;    Those who can't handle Yellowstone's 8,500 altitude or who
choose not to walk the long, wooden pathways to the geysers or take
the mile-long walk down Mammoth's steep terraces are given other
options.
 &HT;    The itinerary is reversed for eastbound tour-goers.
 &HT;    The cost ranges from $799 in Explorer class (double occupancy)
to $1,399 in Gold Nugget. A four-day, train-only tour from Spokane
to Livingston and back costs $629 to $1,799 a person, and a two-day
sampler rail tour from Livingston to Sandpoint is $399 to $999.
 &HT;    A great add-on is the four-day extension to Glacier National
Park for an additional $540 a person.
 &HT;    This year, journeys of the Montana Daylight and its accompanying
tours run from July 9 to the end of August. Get more information
from your travel agent or Montana Rockies Rail Tours, 2660 W.
Ontario, Sandpoint, Idaho 83864; (800) 519-7245.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
