<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4933 &Cx1f; tad-z
s k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV2     06-18 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: WHERE DOES GATES WANT TO GO TODAY?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 21
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Nowadays, towering construction cranes and huge
earth-moving machines loom above the sprawling Microsoft corporate
campus. The world's leading software company is rapidly running out
of office space at its Pacific northwest headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innovate or die,'' is the Microsoft's corporate slogan, coined
by co-founder Bill Gates, who dreams of putting a Microsoft-fed
personal computer in every home and on every desk.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing innovative about Microsoft's architecture.
There's no corporate program to wow visitors. Nor are there any
Disneyesque public tours _ save virtual ones on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft ``museum,'' closed to the public, houses the Altair
computer that stirred Gates so greatly when it appeared in 1975
that, at age 19, he dropped out of Harvard to write an operating
system for the machine.
</P>
<P>
   In their first year, Gates and his then-partner, Paul Allen,
earned $16,005. In 1997, Microsoft earned $11.4 billion. The value
of Gates's stock in the company exceeded $45 billion, making him
the richest man in America.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, when he bought a jet, Gates flew economy class.
Gates's office in Redmond is modest, basically no different from
thousands of others on this 296-acre campus.
</P>
<P>
   Some corporate visitors are known in the trade as ``original
equipment manufacturers,'' or OEMs, but there's nothing original
about the basic software they put on their PCs. Nearly all of it
comes from Microsoft. These hardware ``partners'' from Compaq, Dell
and the like usually meet with Microsoft managers in hotel suites
on Lake Washington, a half-hour down the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   There they sign non-disclosure agreements that make them privy
to the innards of the next big Microsoft software release. Windows
2000 will come in separate home and business flavors that will rest
for the first time on a common digital kernel.
</P>
<P>
   With Windows 98 about to reach customers, the (mostly) young men
who come to work in cutoff jeans and hiking boots to write the
millions of lines of code that make up this new release have
departed as a group on vacation. As they rest up, the spotlight
falls on hundreds of (mostly) lower-paid technical support workers
who will field questions posed by phone, fax and on the Internet
from users who find themselves in a jam.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gates may be in a bit of a jam himself with the
trust-busters back in the other Washington, he shows no signs of
caving in to pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is very striking is the animosity toward Gates among his
rivals,'' Ron Chernow, the biographer of John D. Rockefeller, notes
in Fortune. It's much the same, Chernow says, as what Rockefeller
generated a century ago and ``seems to be spreading to other
businesses that are not at this moment rivals but see themselves as
potential rivals.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, the U.S. Supreme Court broke up Standard Oil, an act
that did nothing to change Rockefeller's status as the richest man
of his day. Nearly nine decades later, Gates fervently believes
that the same antitrust law was not designed to let government
regulators design his software.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
