<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4953 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN18-COX     06-18 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President Clinton wisely dumped candidate Clinton's China policy
 &HT;    (ATTN: Editorial, opinion page editors)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By TOM TEEPEN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton's visit to China will be awkward for him, for
reasons he has pretty much created himself. There's poetic justice
in that, but the poetry shouldn't be allowed to cancel out the very
important prose of this visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton set himself up first when he was running for the
presidency in 1992, blasting President Bush for not reacting
strongly enough to China's brutish suppression in Tiananmen Square
of the rising democracy movement three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   It was true that Bush too quickly made up with Beijing, verged
on obsequiousness in doing it and was secretive about it when
openness might have kept his administration from the excesses of
its Chinese embrace. But, realpolitik being, well, real, it was
never in the cards that U.S. policy toward China could be mainly
based on the moral high dudgeon candidate Clinton seemed to
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Now the president finds himself pleading Bush precedent for
endorsing technology sales to China that congressional Republicans
denounce. Can you say ``petard''?
</P>
<P>
   And the president belly-flopped into more hot water in a
re-election panic that was studiedly incurious despite day-glo
signs that some campaign funds were perhaps being bootlegged into
play from Chinese shadows. As a result, Clinton's mercantilist
policy toward China _ though it is of a piece with his general
mercantilism _ is vulnerable to suspicions, often politically
prodded, of taint.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, at least U.S.-Sino relations have rebounded from
their 1994 low when China was flinging missiles around the Taiwan
Strait _ supposedly testing but actually saber-rattling _ and the
United States rushed two carrier battle groups from the 7th Fleet
to the troubled waters.
</P>
<P>
   China is not the lost cause some would have us, dangerously,
treat it as. Beijing has more often than not supported U.N.
peacekeeping operations. It played a key role in corking North
Korea's nuclear-weapons program. There have been human-rights
improvements at least at the margins. The beginnings of business
law, essential as China moves into market economics, might lead to
a general rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center in Atlanta _ whose experience in such matters
gives the effort credibility _ is working with Chinese officials to
regularize China's system of village elections. There's an opening
in that for democracy to bubble up slowly into the larger political
system.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly is the key. Chinese policy does not whip around like a
kite's tail in the wind, as ours often does. Chinese fundamentals
change with geologic leisure, if at all. U.S. policy has to be
nuanced and steady, quietly _ usually quietly anyway _ pressing for
human-rights advances, crediting Beijing when it plays well with
others but firmly opposing irresponsibility, as in its recklessness
retailing of nuclear and missile knowhow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continues to put too much faith in trade's political
payoffs. (Indeed, in trade's payoff, period. China's seductive mass
market is so far mostly tease.) But he is right that the
compromises that are necessary for engaging with China are
preferable to the dangers that would grow in a self-righteous
estrangement. President Clinton was smart to ditch candidate
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail:teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
