<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Didn't Atlanta pitcher Tony Cloninger hit four grand
slams in a game in the late '60s or early '70s?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do we know how the number 911 was chosen for a universal
emergency phone call, as compared to any other random three digits?
</P>
<P>
   A: In November 1967, officials of AT&AMP;T and the Federal
Communications Commission met to find a means of establishing a
universal emergency number that could be implemented quickly,
something done as early as 1937 in Britain, the first country to
establish such a number. The next year, AT&AMP;T announced that it
would establish the three digits 9-1-1 as the U.S. emergency code.
It was selected because it was brief, easily remembered and had
never been authorized as an official code, area code or service
code. It also met the long-range numbering plans and switching
configurations of the telephone industry. On Feb. 16, 1968, the
first 911call in the United States was successfuly placed in
Alabama. The serving company was Alabama Telephone Co., which later
became Contel Corp. That 911 system is still in use.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can just anybody have their ashes scattered over the Grand
Canyon, or is it restricted to dignitaries? It was reported
recently that the late former Sen. Barry Goldwater (R-Ariz.) wanted
that done for himself. If anyone can do it, what is the procedure
for requesting permission?
</P>
<P>
   A: The spreading of ashes at the canyon is not restricted to
dignitaries. But a permit is required, according to park
spokeswoman Maureen Oltrogge. Some 20-30 permits are requested and
issued each year. A person wanting to spread ashes there must apply
in writing for a permit, stating whose ashes are involved, who will
be at the canyon to spread them and the date. Permits normally are
granted so long as the location requested is not by a water source,
sacred or archaeological site or a public use area. The address:
Grand Canyon National Park, Special Use Permits Office, P.O. Box
129, Grand Canyon, AZ 86023. Information: 520-638-7841.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Canyon isn't the only national park that permits the
spreading of ashes. It was done recently in the Everglades for
environmentalist and writer Marjory Stoneman Douglas. Anyone
contemplating such a request should contact the individual park's
superintendent's office.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you settle a bet? Was the late Rep. Sonny Bono
(R-Calif.) ever the mayor of Carmel, Calif.? If so, was that his
first public office? Also, was Clint Eastwood ever elected to any
office?
</P>
<P>
   A: Q&AMP;A hopes you bet that Dirty Harry . . . er, Eastwood, and
not Bono, was Carmel's mayor. Eastwood was elected to a two-year
term April 8, 1986; he declined to run for re-election in 1988.
Bono also was a mayor, but of Palm Springs, Calif. He was elected
to a four-year term in 1988, his first public office. In 1992, when
that stint ended, he ran for the U.S. Senate, but finished a weak
third in the Republican primary. Two years later, however, he was
elected to represent California's 44th District in Congress, and he
won re-election in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A said young men still are required to register with the
Selective Service. My son will turn 18 later this month. Where,
how, and within what time frame must he register?
</P>
<P>
   A: Men can register by completing a form available at any post
office. Some high schools also have a faculty or staff member who
serves as a Selective Service registrar. Registration is required
within 30 days of the person's 18th birthday. Failing to register
makes a person subject to prosecution and fine up to $250,000,
and/or imprisonment for up to five years. Registration also is
required to qualify for federal student aid and most federal
employment. Information: 1-847-688-6888; or, on the Internet,
www.sss.gov/ (registration also is possible on-line).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
