<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE3-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: My son will turn 18 later this month. Where, how, and
within what time frame must he register for Selective Services?
</P>
<P>
   Q: In what year did our young men no longer have to register for
the draft?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. government stopped drafting males in 1973, but
registration with the Selective Service System continues for almost
all male U.S. citizens, and male non-citizens living in the United
States, who are 18 through 25. Something called the ``stand-by
draft'' was created by the government in 1973, but discontinued in
1975. In 1980, Congress passed legislation resuming registration
requirements for the draft. Men who would be classified as
conscientious objectors if they were drafted also must also
register. Registration provides the government with a list of men
who could be inducted into the armed services in the event of a
national emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At one time, hurricanes were named after women only. When
were men's names included?
</P>
<P>
   A: The practice of naming hurricanes solely after women came to
an end in 1978 when men's names were included in the eastern North
Pacific storm lists. In 1979, male names were included in lists for
the Atlantic and Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know hurricanes are given names, and sometimes some of
those names, such as Andrew, are retired. Why is that done? What
others have been retired?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hurricane names typically are retired, says the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, and replaced with new ones
when a storm associated with a particular name causes great loss of
life or property damage. The countries most affected by such a
storm can make a recommendation to the World Meteorological
Organization that a name be retired, Frank Lepore of the National
Hurricane Center in Miami told Q&AMP;A. In Andrew's case, it was the
United States that recommended scrapping it, with Alex taking its
place, starting in 1998. NOAA said such retirement isn't
necessarily permanent; the name just can't be used again for at
least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   These Atlantic Ocean storm names have been retired: Agnes,
Alicia, Allen, Andrew, Anita, Audrey, Betsy, Beulah, Bob, Camille,
Carla, Carmen, Carol, Celia, Cleo, Connie, David, Diana, Diane,
Donna, Dora, Elena, Eloise, Flora, Frederic, Gilbert, Gloria,
Hattie, Hazel, Hilda, Hugo, Ione, Inez, Janet, Joan, Klaus, Luis,
Marilyn, Opal and Roxanne.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard recently that formaldehyde is used in the process to
decaffeinate coffee. I've also heard that it is used in processing
milk. Is that true? It sounds very bad to me.
</P>
<P>
   A: Formaldehyde is not used in the decaffeination process of
coffee, nor is it used in milk processing for human consumption,
said Chris Rosenbloom, spokeswoman for the American Dietetic
Association. It's sometimes used as a preservative on farms when
testing milk samples for various components in the milk, she said,
but not for processing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If formaldehyde is not used in processing decaffeinated
coffee, what is?
</P>
<P>
   A: Decaffeination agents include carbon dioxide; ethyl acetate,
a substance that occurs naturally in many fruits; methylene
chloride, a solvent; fats and oils; and water, said Chris
Rosenbloom, spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association. The
Food and Drug Administration has determined that methylene chloride
is safe for use in coffee decaffeination in up to 10 parts per
million, but the coffee industry's practice results in levels 100
times lower than this amount, she said. The decaffeination process
starts with softening the green, unroasted beans in the agents,
after which they're ``agitated'' to draw the caffeine away. Then
the beans are heated and blown with steam, followed by roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
