<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: If formaldehyde is not used in processing
decaffeinated coffee, what is?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Monica Lewinsky has hired a new team of defense attorneys who
have been described in news reports as ``top notch, well-connected
and experienced.'' Since she is an unemployed former White House
intern, who is paying her legal bills?
</P>
<P>
   A: Reports published when the new legal team was brought on
board said Washington attorneys Jacob Stein and Plato Cacheris were
recruited and hired by the Lewinsky family. Lewinsky's parents are
divorced. Her father, Dr. Bernard Lewinsky, is a radiation
oncologist in Beverly Hills, Calif. He has said that he paid the
legal bills of his daughter's former lawyer, William Ginsburg.
Monica Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis, is a New York writer. Well
before the change in attorneys, Dr. Lewinsky mounted a defense fund
to help defray his daughter's legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Newspaper articles have reported that about 20 states have
high school graduation tests or ``exit exams.'' Will you list them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Education Commission of the States lists these: Alabama,
Alaska (effective Jan. 1, 2002), Arkansas, Arizona, Florida,
Georgia, Hawaii, Indiana (unless principal certifies student has
met ``Core 40'' requirements), Louisiana, Maryland, Massachusetts
(must pass proficiencies, but not a single exit exam), Mississippi,
Nevada, New Jersey, New Mexico (to graduate with a diploma), New
York, North and South Carolina, Ohio, Tennessee, Texas, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Minnesota students graduating in 2000 must pass tests in
reading, math and writing to meet the requirements of the Minnesota
Graduation Rule. And Pennsylvania students must achieve 52 state
academic performance ``outcomes'' (assessments) plus locally
developed outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Exactly what is required for a baseball pitcher to be awarded
a win, besides, obviously, the team winning? Why do some relief
pitchers get the win?
</P>
<P>
   A: The winning pitcher _ the one given official credit for his
team's victory _ can be the starting pitcher or a reliever who
comes in with his team tied or behind and wins the game. A starting
pitcher must complete at least five full innings to be so credited.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Jerry Lewis has been honored many times over the years for
his work with muscular dystrophy. Do you know why he became
involved with that cause?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many people speculate that the actor and comedian must have
known someone, perhaps a family member, who was stricken with a
neuromuscular disease, but Lewis has never disclosed a specific
reason for his interest and involvement, Jim Brown of the Muscular
Dystrophy Association in Phoenix told Q&AMP;A. ``We're just very
thankful he has been involved for more than four decades now,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lewis has been volunteer national chairman of the
health agency for more than 40 years, it's his fund-raising
telethons each Labor Day that have kept him _ and muscular
dystrophy _ most in the public eye. These efforts have raised more
than $900 million for the search for treatments and cures for some
40 neuromuscular diseases. Lewis also makes personal appearances on
behalf of MDA that are never publicized. ``There probably has not
been a single day in the last 45 years on which Jerry has not met,
worked for, phoned or just talked about youngsters and adults
living with neuromuscular diseases, and MDA's effort in their
behalf,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
