<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4989 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-QUINCY19-COX     06-18 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-QUINCY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOBACCO AND COKE STOCK MADE THIS LITTLE TOWN RICH
 &HT;    By CHERYL BLACKERBY
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUINCY, Fla. _ Political skirmishes notwithstanding, Tallahassee
just isn't that interesting. Go to a football game in the fall,
take a quick tour of the old Capitol building, and, suddenly, home
is looking pretty fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Not so quick.
</P>
<P>
   Just drive 20 minutes west of Tallahassee to Quincy, one of
Florida's oldest towns. Hit the brakes, park the car and hoof it.
</P>
<P>
   Quincy is the town that tobacco and Coca-Cola built. After the
turn of the century, tobacco growers invested profits in a new
company called Coca-Cola on the advice of the president of the
Quincy State Bank, and the wealthy little town got rich, rich,
rich.
</P>
<P>
   More than 36 blocks of Quincy have been designated as a
Nationally Registered Historic District. Many of the 100-plus
houses were built in the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   You can easily spend a day strolling past an astounding array of
architecture _ Victorian, antebellum, Classic Revival, Creole,
Georgian _ with gardens of magnolias, camellias, daffodils and
gardenias.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 years ago, planters came here from Virginia, the
Carolinas and Georgia. They crossed Virginia tobacco with Cuban,
and then started growing the connoisseur's ``shade tobacco''
(fields were shaded with cheesecloth).
</P>
<P>
   They built lavish mansions, monuments to their success.
</P>
<P>
   The McFarlin House inn gives a close-up view of how the wealthy
lived. The magnificent Queen Anne-style mansion, built in 1895 by
tobacco planter John McFarlin, has seven fireplaces, a three-story
turret and a 42-pillar wraparound porch.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed in the third-floor octagonal room in the turret. From
the antique brass and iron bed, I had a bird's-eye view of oak
trees and the ornate J.E.A. Davidson House (built in 1859) with its
six Corinthian columns across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The McFarlin House was vacant for 20 years before Richard and
Tina Fauble bought it in 1994 and restored it with the help of his
parents. The house was in such bad shape that raccoons lived in it.
</P>
<P>
   The McFarlin House guests used to be those interested in history
and architecture, but now the owners host corporate and political
groups with business in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out they don't think Tallahassee is very interesting
either.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: Carrying the little guide book as you walk will be
your only exertion. There is lots of shade and many benches.
</P>
<P>
   Historic inn: The McFarlin House, 305 E. King St., (850)
875-2526. Weekend rates range from $75 ($65 weekdays) to $175.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hike to get there: Take I-10 west past Tallahassee to
Exit 27, which is U.S. 90. Drive 10 miles to Quincy. Turn right on
Love Street. The inn is on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Contact the Quincy Chamber of Commerce, (850)
627-9231, or drop by the office on the corner of Madison and King
streets, and pick up a walking map. Groups can arrange tours.
Photos by BOB SHANLEY/Staff Photographer
</P>
<P>
   A huge Coca-Cola sign downtown displays Quincy's ties with the
soft-drink company. Tobacco growers at the turn of the century
invested in Coca-Cola stock and got rich.
</P>
<P>
   The 1895 McFarlin House inn, owned by Richard Fauble and his
wife, is one of the town's opulent mansions. Quincy's historic
district covers 36 blocks and includes more than 100 homes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
