<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAV-PLENTY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    3 PRETTY WOMEN AND A GUY WHO DOESN'T SEEM TO CARE
 &HT;    By HAP ERSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were a guy planning to write, direct, produce, edit and
star in your own movie, you'd make it about three gorgeous women
throwing themselves at you, right?
</P>
<P>
   Rookie filmmaker Christopher Scott Cherot does exactly that with
``Hav Plenty,'' demonstrating that Mrs. Cherot didn't raise a
dummy. His amiable, low-key movie about relationships introduces us
to a talent who deserves a future in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   It brings to mind Spike Lee's ``She's Gotta Have It'' and early
Woody Allen, though such comparisons may be too much of a burden.
If you're looking for a breezy romp about an intriguing circle of
twentysomethings, ``Hav Plenty'' has plenty to recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   Cherot wears the character of novelist wannabe Lee Plenty with
casual, endearing indifference. Attracted to high-powered,
successful Havilland Savage, who is way above him on the economic
ladder, Lee is taken aback to be invited to share New Year's Eve
with her at her family home. He nonchalantly introduces himself to
her upwardly mobile friends as broke and homeless, which turns him
into an object of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Havilland, her French-spouting friend Caroline and married
sister Leigh each are drawn to Lee, and are each startled by his
unexpected indifference. In particular, Lee and Hav have an
attraction/repulsion relationship like two magnets, and they dance
around their feelings for each other for the movie's brief
hour-and-a-half. Cherot includes the audience in his character's
puzzlement over the opposite sex, addressing us directly and
winking at us over his bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Such a screwball souffle is hard to keep floating, but Cherot's
easygoing, improvisational manner proves very ingratiating, just
like his character. It works because of ``Hav Plenty's'' laid-back
style, though it requires some patience on the audience's part.
Just approach it as a shaggy dog story on contemporary love, with a
clever coda in which art reflects life reflecting art.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cherot, most of the cast is making its feature film debut,
which gives the release a documentary-like feeling with so many
unknown faces. If, as the movie insists, it is based on a true
story _ a claim we have learned to doubt ever since ``Fargo'' _ it
has surely been warped into a fiction to suit Cherot's purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Chenoa Maxwell is all poise, assurance and foul mouth as
privileged Havilland, and it is enjoyable to watch her lose her
cool in Lee's presence. Tammi Katherine Jones is similarly all
attitude, but she decides on a whim to bed Lee and is crestfallen
to find herself rejected. Convinced that he must be gay, he becomes
a project for her to crack and Jones' comic verve becomes a
highlight of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   An attention-getter at this year's Sundance Film Festival, ``Hav
Plenty'' earned a distribution deal from Miramax and, reportedly,
Cherot got a deal for future movies. If he can retain the
spontaneity and light touch he shows here, Cherot is an emerging
hyphenate well worth hearing from again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
