<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-MULAN19-COX     06-18 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MULAN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `MULAN' DESIGNED TO CHARM YOUNG, OLD
 &HT;    By HAP ERSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the first delicate, dancing swirls of Asian watercolor and
ink, Disney's latest animated feature ``Mulan'' proclaims itself a
cartoon willing to be different.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Chinese legend, it ventures into new geographic and
cultural territory, even as it clings to much of the time-tested
Disney genre formula. Featuring a cast of vicious Hun warriors as
well as adorable, scene-stealing sidekick creatures, ``Mulan''
looks calculated to satisfy all tastes. If not quite on par with
the studio's classic best, it is nevertheless its most enjoyable
animated effort since ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Written by committee with enough messages about female
empowerment to warm the hearts of Ms. magazine's editorial board,
``Mulan'' is the fable of a young girl who joins the Chinese
imperial army to save the life of her hobbled father. Disguised as
a man, she has to learn macho soldiering ways, but it is her wily
battle tactics that prove victorious and allow her to rescue her
homeland from certain defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, Joan of Arc and G.I. Jane. Make way for Mulan.
</P>
<P>
   From our first introduction to the title lass, in a tinkly
``Flower Drum Song'' number by Matthew Wilder and David Zippel
called ``Honor To Us All,'' it is clear that Mulan _ voiced with
spunk by Ming-Na Wen (``One Night Stand'') _ is not cut out for
traditional subservience. With her mute pet cricket Cri-Kee (hardly
as parental or wise as Jiminy) and a street-smart, scrawny dragon
named Mushu (Eddie Murphy, as the funniest, most irreverent Disney
creation since Robin Williams' ``Aladdin'' genie), she joins the
rag-tag troops led by a jut-jawed hunk captain, Shang (B.D. Wong).
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has something at stake, from Mulan's family honor to
Cri-Kee's reputation for bringing good luck. Curiously, in its zeal
to focus on the heroine, the movie forgets to give Shang an
opportunity to show his bravery and military acumen.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the story plays out well, matched nicely early on by
a handful of clever Wilder-Zippel tunes. In the movie's second
half, though, the songs disappear, giving ``Mulan'' an unbalanced
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Still, such quibbles are more than offset by the striking
visuals contributed by Disney's Florida animation unit in its first
full feature effort. Asian art style is evoked beautifully with
elegant, spare suggestions of background landscapes. In contrast,
yet subtly complementary, are the awesome uses of
computer-generated imaging, represented by the crowd in a climactic
Imperial City sequence and a thundering battle charge down
snow-covered slopes by the Hun cavalry. (The Huns, by the way, are
depicted as bloodthirsty land-grabbers. Presumably, there is no Hun
Anti-Defamation League for Disney to fret over.)
</P>
<P>
   For the most part ``Mulan'' is a dramatic tale of a girl's
heroic war exploits. More than just fulfilling their baby-sitting
obligations, adults may enjoy the movie more than their kids do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
