</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-XFILES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXPLOSIVE `FILES': SCI-FI SERIES BECOMES TOP-NOTCH SUMMER FLICK
 &HT;    By KEVIN D. THOMPSON
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so you want to know the truth about The ``X-Files: Fight the
Future''?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, we can't tell you. Well, we can, but then we'd
have to kill you. Then ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter would kill
us.
</P>
<P>
   But we can tell you this: ``Fight the Future'' does reveal more
juicy details about the cloak-and-dagger government/alien
conspiracy (it dates back to a frigid North Texas in 35,000 B.C.).
You do get a good look at those nasty, up-to-no-good aliens
(they're in the movie's best scenes), and it will take a few
moments getting comfortable gawking at Mulder's humongous schnoz on
the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, ``Fight the Future'' is also a pretty darn good film.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, The X-Files have been shut down. Instead of chasing
extraterrestrials, FBI agents Scully (Gillian Anderson) and Mulder
(David Duchovny) are investigating a mysterious bombing of a Dallas
office building and the secrets buried inside. Like most
``X-Files'' episodes, ``Fight the Future'' raises more questions
than it actually answers. That's always been the show's shrewd
selling point, however. Like a veteran best-selling novelist,
Carter always leaves viewers wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   Making the film was a tough challenge since ``Fight the Future''
had to please die-hard fans and non-X-Philes.
</P>
<P>
   Did Carter succeed?
</P>
<P>
   He did on most levels. Actually, non-fans will probably enjoy
the movie more. Screenwriter Carter and director Rob Bowman dumbed
down, if you will, the often confusing mythology. The film doesn't
explore the whereabouts of Mulder's sister, whom he believes was
abducted by aliens; it fails to address whether the evil Cigarette
Smoking Man (William B. Davis) is Mulder's father; and we never see
the shape-shifting aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Carter wisely chooses to focus on the planned alien
takeover and The Syndicate's role in it. It's really ``Independence
Day'' and ``All The President's Men'' rolled into one. And Carter
gives audiences enough background on Scully and Mulder and their
paranormal world so non-X-Files viewers can follow the plot.
</P>
<P>
   In a clever bar scene, a cursing, drunk Mulder gives five years'
worth of dossier information while explaining to a barmaid what he
does for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fight the Future'' does excel as a top-notch, brainy
sci-fi/conspiracy thriller and translates well to the big screen.
That's no surprise, though, since watching the eerily filmed TV
series is like watching a weekly one-hour movie. ``Fight the
Future'' doesn't skimp on all the ingredients that made ``The
X-Files'' one of TV's most popular shows.
</P>
<P>
   There's Mark Snow's sinister score, Ward Russell's ominous
cinematography and a hulking Cigarette Smoking Man puffing in the
dark. As Dr. Alvin Kurtzeil, a shadowy, Deep Throat-type character,
a wide-eyed Martin Landau is pleasingly effective while babbling
about ``silent wars'' and ``planned armageddons.''
</P>
<P>
   With a reported $60 million to spend, Carter and Bowman were
also able to create more elaborate special effects. Without giving
away anything, let's just say what we see of those ornery aliens is
pretty convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny and Anderson also had no trouble making their
characters bigger-than-life. Both actors know these characters so
well, they can speak to each other without uttering a word. For
Mulder and Scully, TV's most sexually frustrated couple, it's all
in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
