<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OSPREY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THIS PARK IS FOR THE BIRDS (SCRUB JAYS, THAT IS)
 &HT;    By JOHN J. LOPINOT
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSPREY, Fla. _ Wildlife encounters.
</P>
<P>
   We've all heard the hype and seen the billboards advertising
wildlife adventures at theme parks scattered across Florida.
</P>
<P>
   You pay big bucks and are herded through man-made attractions
where you see captive animals.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a quiet place near Venice where you can encounter
wild animals including a threatened species of bird _ the scrub jay
_ so close, one might even land on your head.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small preserve called Oscar Scherer State Park.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful scrub jay is easily distinguished from much more
common blue jays: It has no crest on its head, and its feathers are
a lighter, sky-blue color. These curious animals live only in the
scrub habitat in Florida. Spreading development and agriculture
have greatly reduced their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Scherer State Park is in the midst of a large urban area,
but careful planning and preservation has made it a fantastic place
to view wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Bald eagles, bobcats, river otters, alligators, warblers and
woodpeckers are often seen year-round.
</P>
<P>
   The park covers more than 1,000 acres of pine flatwoods and
scrubby flatwoods on the banks of a tidal creek. Both flatwood
habitats are important for a number of declining species in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The park was established in 1955 when Elsa Scherer Burrows
donated 462 acres to the state in memory of her father, Oscar
Scherer, an inventor who developed a process for dyeing leather for
shoes in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   There are 98 campsites.
</P>
<P>
   And how to find those popular scrub jays? Park at the north side
of Lake Osprey and walk into the scrubby flatwoods to the
northeast. Family groups of curious scrub jays often come close to
visitors. DO NOT FEED THE BIRDS. (They lose their fear of humans
and they don't eat their natural diet, which leads to malnutrition
and death.)
</P>
<P>
   But if you hold an open hand out, often the birds will land on
your head, looking for a treat.
</P>
<P>
   Get out the binoculars for this park
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: With a choice of hiking trails, canoeing and
swimming, the exertion level is up to you. Bird-watching takes
patience.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Scherer State Park: Oscar Scherer State Park, 1843 S.
Tamiami Trail, Osprey, FL 33559; or call (941) 483-5956
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Sunrise to Sunset, sunrise to sunset, 7 days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $3.25 per vehicle; camping is extra.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
