<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-STEINHATCHEE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DON'T LET THIS REMOTE FISHING VILLAGE GET AWAY
 &HT;    By CHERYL BLACKERBY
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEINHATCHEE, Fla. _ The vehicles on County Road 51, the main
street of this tiny town, are mostly long-bed trucks pulling
fishing boats.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial fishing boats dock next to the banks of the
Steinhatchee River before it empties 2 miles downstream into
Deadman Bay on the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Marinas offer sport fishing boats, fishing guides, fishing
equipment, ``anglers sunglasses'' and ``anglers hats.''
</P>
<P>
   There's freshwater fishing and saltwater fishing. You like to
fish? Welcome to Steinhatchee.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of weathered houses strung along the river,
Steinhatchee (pronounced STEEN-hat-chee) is in the bend of the
state _ south of Tallahassee, due west of Gainesville and squarely
in the middle of nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to do here. Just fish,'' said a waitress.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity didn't come to Steinhatchee until 1945; telephone
service in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   There are no high-rise hotels, just a half-dozen low-rise,
low-rent motels _ the kind of places where no one minds if you
store bait in the fridge and track mud across the linoleum.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one upscale resort that attracts discerning
anglers, including former President Jimmy Carter in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhatchee Landing, a group of 20 new Victorian-style and
cracker cottages built next to the river, has the amenities of a
Marriott and the low-key ambience of a cabin in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Even the tiny two-room, two-story cottages have two TVs, VCR,
modern bath, kitchen with dishwasher, telephone, and washer and
dryer.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to imagine that the resort is a small town in the last
century as you sit on the screen porch in a big country rocker and
look at the surrounding forest and towering moss-draped oaks.
Horses trot by the cabins taking riders from the stable to trails
along the river.
</P>
<P>
   But the pool, a small fitness center, a big restaurant, nature
trails, a fleet of bikes, games including archery and volleyball,
plus free use of bright red canoes give the feeling of being at a
luxurious summer camp for grown-ups. (Steinhatchee is only a couple
of miles from the gulf, but it's a 17-mile drive to a beach.)
</P>
<P>
   During my recent stay, the resort was filled with families, some
with three generations in attendance. A grandfather took two
teenage granddaughters on a bird-watching trip up the black,
slow-moving water of the Steinhatchee.
</P>
<P>
   It is here, on this wild river, that they can appreciate the
life of the Indians who once lived, hunted and fished here. If
guests are lucky they might see manatee and alligator in the river,
or deer, wild boar and fox venturing from the woods to the muddy
banks.
</P>
<P>
   But if they're really lucky, they'll catch a big tarpon. FISHING
FOR INFO ON STEINHATCHEE
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: Steinhatchee is a no-sweat kind of vacation except
for the gulf sun burning your skin like hamburger in a frying pan.
</P>
<P>
   Steinhatchee Landing: Rates range from $110 ($660 per week) per
night for the one-bedroom, two-story cottages to $225 ($1,350 per
week) for the three-bedroom Presidential Retreat where President
Carter stayed in 1994. Call (352) 498-3513., The Steinhatchee River
Inn, a modern motel, is the Landing's sister hotel a couple of
miles down the river. Rates start at about $60.
</P>
<P>
   Horse rentals are $35 per hour for one horse, $25 each for two
or more horses per hour. The trips are led by the resort's
wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   Where is it? From West Palm Beach, take Florida's Turnpike until
it ends at Interstate 75. Go north to Ocala. Exit onto U.S. 27, and
drive north, then go north on U.S. Alternate 27. Take S.R. 351 to
Steinhatchee, about 2 miles from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
