<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4995 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX     06-18 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Books are the best part about moving
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I like to move. Some people dread it. My running buddy gets
downright stressed out about moving. That's probably because she's
only done it about three times, and the furthest she's ever moved
is about seven miles -- from one end of town to the other.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I have moved a ridiculous number of times.
I've moved in the neighborhood of two dozen times in 25 years to
seven different towns. Luckily, this latest move is just across
town. Don't get your hopes up. I'm not going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I don't much enjoy the physical act of moving, since it means
either sweating or freezing, this being East Texas where the
weather is rarely described as moderate except in chamber
brochures. What I like is re-ordering the things we own, putting
pictures in different places, getting rid of stuff we don't need,
and listening to different sounds when I step outside early in the
morning to get the paper.
</P>
<P>
   The best part is moving the books. It's also one of the most
cumbersome parts, since my collection of books seems to grow in
inverse relation to the time available to read them. I am
particular about moving the books. In a cross-town move, I don't
want any help. I don't box them up. I move them by loading them in
the back of my Explorer one armload at a time until the back of the
truck is filled. I go to the new house and put them on the shelves
so they stay in the right order.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds goofy, but it works. When you box 1,500 books or so,
you end up with about 75 boxes of books. You can't put many books
in a box and still pick it up. Then you have to lug all the boxes
to the new location, unbox them and put them up. I have eliminated
the middle step.
</P>
<P>
   I reacquaint myself with my books when moving. Titles that have
stood on the shelf since the last move jump out at me. There's the
three-volume narrative of the Civil War by Shelby Foote. I still
need to read the last volume. Here's that biography of Harry Truman
I got halfway through before moving on to a piece of light fiction
with the vow to return to the weightier work soon. I need to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my books have smoke-tinged spines, a reminder of a house
fire 14 years ago that destroyed much of what we own, including
about half my books. I never have replaced the set of Harvard
Classics that burned. Some day I'll find a set in a garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   There are even a few tattered remainders from the book store I
once owned in Nacogdoches in the mid-1970s, my first venture into
small-business ownership. It wasn't successful, but I still have a
copy of ``Does it Matter'' by Alan Watts and nearly all of Herman
Hesse's novels.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the few hundred or so books of Texana, much of
which comes free and unsolicited in the mail from book publishers
looking for reviews. These include some strange little books, such
as the ``History of Texas Baptist Journalism,'' ``What's Right With
Football,'' and ``Gone With the Kudzu.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm often asked, especially by kids, if I've read all these
books. No, I haven't, I answer truthfully. I don't ever want to be
in the position of having read all my books, because then I'd have
to go out and buy a bunch more. Nothing beats the delight and
anticipation of running your fingers down a shelf of books, looking
for something to read while a thunderstorm pounds outside.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's summer and presumably you have more time to read,
here are a few new titles I came across while lugging books across
town:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cold New World,'' by William Finnegan, a writer for The New
Yorker. Recently published with a glowing review in Time, this is a
social history of four communities, including San Augustine across
the river. The other towns include New Haven, Connecticut, a small
town in Washington state, and South Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   This is a fine social history, disturbing in many ways as it
describes a common thread of lost youth in cities of all sizes.
Finnegan is an excellent reporter, meticulous and patient. He spent
more than six months living in San Augustine and then returned
several times. This is a great read.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Underworld,'' by Don Delilo. This is a strange novel that
centers on Bobby Thompson's home run to give the Giants the pennant
in 1951 and what happened to the baseball he hit out of the park.
It meanders through 40-plus years of American cultural changes in a
journey that is sometimes hard to keep up with, but is well worth
the trip.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``In the Beauty of the Lilies,'' by John Updike. Updike is
one of America's most durable novelists, and his latest effort is a
radical departure from previous work. It's set in Massachusetts in
2020 after an atomic war has destroyed much of the country. It has
Updike's typical suburban pathos and humor.
</P>
<P>
   Pick one of these books up if you're looking for a way to while
away the hours while on the beach. And think of me lugging those
boxes around while you're sunning.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborderscoxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
