<SLUG> BC-FENG-SHUI19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TOO MUCH PRESSURE AT THE OFFICE?
 &HT;    By CAROLYN SUSMAN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do you feel pressured at work?
</P>
<P>
   Are you sure everyone is talking about you behind your back?
</P>
<P>
   In short, does paranoia descend when you're at your desk?
</P>
<P>
   Don't dial the nearest therapist. Rearrange your chair.
</P>
<P>
   Relief can be as quick and convenient as changing your seating
arrangement, according to ``Feng Shui at Work'' (Villard Books,
$13.95). Author Kirsten M. Lagatree has researched this ancient
Chinese art of placement that puts surroundings in harmony with
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``With proper feng shui (pronounced fung shway),'' she writes,
``you can tilt the balance in your life toward financial success,
improved relationships, enhanced creativity _ whatever goals you
may have.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, your goal at work is to feel productive.
</P>
<P>
   This begins at the desk: ``The golden rule in determining
optimal desk placement is simple: When seated behind your desk, you
must always be able to see the door.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens when you can't?
</P>
<P>
   _ You'll always be surprised by people entering your office and
(worse) by things they tell you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Because your back is exposed, you may be the victim of
backstabbing and office politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Even the most easygoing person can become paranoid in this
situation and colleagues will notice.
</P>
<P>
   But don't panic. There is a solution, even if you can't move
your chair so you greet visitors. Put a mirror over your desk so
you can see who's approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to empower yourself at the office is to place your
desk with enough space to view as much of your workspace as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   And third, feng shui adherents advise, avoid an L-shaped desk.
</P>
<P>
   The ``L'' suggests an incompleteness that can undermine your
authority, cut you off from your colleagues, or cause chronic
physical maladies. But there's also a solution here. Fill in the
missing corner with a plant or floor lamp.
</P>
<P>
   If you're going to create a hazard by doing this, put a fan on
your desk to keep your good energy - your ``chi'' - circulating
around you.
</P>
<P>
   Sound silly? That's OK. But don't dismiss it. Feng shui might be
the key to another worker's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's not disturbing to other coworkers or the
administration and it provides the employee with a measure of
comfort, a sense of ritual or tradition, it can be enhancing to
their ability to organize their work and concentrate,'' says Palm
Beach Gardens psychologist Janet Hibel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can decrease workplace stress, then it's positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
