<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4997 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULAN-CREATION19-COX     06-18 1316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-CREATION19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW DISNEY'S ORLANDO STUDIOS CREATED A CARTOON SPECTACLE
 &HT;    By HAP ERSTEIN
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Tom Bancroft remembers with a wince his days in
the fishbowl.
</P>
<P>
   One of the supervising animators on Disney's new cartoon feature
``Mulan,'' Bancroft started his career as a stop on the Disney-MGM
Studios tour here. Walking through a mock-up of artists' offices,
tourists could see him and other animators sketching and doodling.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Bancroft's favorite part of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we weren't drawing, people would go like, `Get back to
work,' '' he recalls. ``They wanted a better tour.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry never took the studio's Florida animation unit
seriously. Neither, for that matter, did Disney's top executive
Michael Eisner, who initiated the group for the sake of tours. As
he is reported to have said, ``What it actually does, I don't care
about.''
</P>
<P>
   That was nine years ago. Tomorrow, the unit's first feature, the
Chinese fable ``Mulan,'' opens nationwide. The group that the
industry once scoffed at unveils what is probably the studio's best
release in years.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives try to put a positive spin on it, but their
recent animated features, ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame'' and
``Hercules,'' were box office disappointments. Long before they
failed to meet expectations, Disney animation executives started
searching for material that would let them move into a new realm of
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter (Schneider, president of Disney Feature Animation) and I
were talking about the idea that we needed to get out of what we
thought was a pretty conventional circle of movies,'' recalls
executive vice president Tom Schumacher. ``We referred to them as
castle and wimple movies, movies that were very Western and
European-based.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they looked to the East, sifting through Asian folk
tales for material to apply the Disney touch to. After rejecting
stories from Korea and Japan that lacked a universal, uplifting
appeal, they embraced the age-old ``Legend of Mulan,'' the saga of
a young Chinese woman who goes off to war disguised as a man. A
little bit ``Yentl,'' a little bit ``G.I. Jane,'' it had a strong
theme of female empowerment and an attractive parent-child bonding
message.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the core animation and production team left from
Florida for China to soak up atmosphere and immerse themselves in
the culture. The visit is typical of the care and expense lavished
on the project. Although Disney executives refuse to discuss the
cost, Variety estimates ``Mulan's'' budget at $90 million, as much
as 25 percent higher than the average animated feature.
</P>
<P>
   For the Orlando team, that's a long way from a tour exhibit. The
change came in the late 1980s, when the Florida animators produced
some cartoon shorts. By 1990, they were assigned a 10-minute
segment of ``The Rescuers Down Under.'' They delivered so well that
these support jobs continued, including the creation of 25 minutes
of ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, animation president Schneider, feeling confident of the
unit, started thinking about giving them a complete movie.
``Artistically, they had proved that they could produce at a
quality far beyond what was ever intended,'' he says. ``It made
sense to challenge them further and give them a crack at a project
that was truly their own.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of ``Mulan's'' premiere, the staff is feeling bullish
about its work. ``I think we've proven ourselves already,'' says
supervising animator Mark Henn, who studied under the old guard
Disney animators and oversaw the character of Mulan. ``A lot of
people outside the studio didn't think we had it in us here to make
this kind of a movie at this quality. No matter what happens with
this film, we've already proven to them that we can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the 1,400-employee Burbank animation unit, the
400-member Florida team is smaller, younger and greener, which the
group turned to its advantage. They dubbed themselves ``the little
studio that could.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it was a fairly young group, fairly inexperienced, but
they were passionate about it,'' says ``Mulan's'' co-director, Tony
Bancroft. ``They wanted to prove what they could do as artists.''
</P>
<P>
   For starters, ``Mulan'' looks different from other Disney
animated movies, adopting a flat, simple Asian watercolor style for
its backgrounds. It is cast _ carefully, but appropriately _ with a
host of Asian-American voices, from Min-Na Wen and B.D. Wong in the
leading roles, to George Takei, Pat Morita and James Shigeta in
supporting cameos. (But it also has Donny Osmond singing and Harvey
Fierstein as a gruff, macho soldier.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the California animators, who are currently working on a
handful of different features such as ``Tarzan,'' the new
``Fantasia'' and an original Inca story called ``Kingdom of the
Sun,'' the Florida unit concentrated all its efforts on ``Mulan.''
</P>
<P>
   Those with experience working on both coasts noted a different
atmosphere in Orlando. ``We tend to have a more easygoing approach,
maybe less competitive, less stressed feeling here,'' says Tom
Bancroft, brother of Tony, who supervised the animation of the
dragon character Mushu. ``In California, it's a bit more of a rat
race.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood could be attributed to the top Disney brass being 3,000
miles away. ``It's always fun to just be off by yourself,'' says
``Mulan'' producer Pam Coats. ``It's that old saying, `It's easier
to beg forgiveness than to get permission.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, Disney's fascination with emerging technology
and zeal for micro-management meant that the Burbank Mouse Factory
kept close tabs on Orlando. They reviewed all storyboards and
animation sequences, often tossing them away or sending them back
for revision.
</P>
<P>
   The geographic distance was minimized by a 24-hour television
link. That link has since been expanded to Disney's newest
animation unit, established in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Why so many decentralized operations? With the current boom in
animation that has Disney Studios committed to two major releases a
year, the need for trained animators has grown. And Disney
recognizes that not everyone is willing to move to Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the top European artists quite frankly want to live
in Europe,'' says Coats. ``And a lot of people who are really good
at what they do really love Florida. They love the climate for
raising families, and they're happy here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tangible evidence of Disney's commitment to the Florida unit is
its new 200,000-square-foot animation center, a state-of-the-art
office complex opened in April to replace the makeshift facilities
_ ``glorified trailers,'' as Coats describes them _ where ``Mulan''
was made. And yes, as a further reminder of the unit's roots, you
can still tour a mock-up of an animation studio at the Disney-MGM
theme park and watch artists sketching and doodling.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Florida animators are waiting for critical and
public reaction to ``Mulan,'' they haven't put down their pencils.
Some of the staff is working on a new short based on the John Henry
legend, others are toiling on a sequence for ``Kingdom of the
Sun,'' due for release in 2000. A third group is brainstorming
story concepts for the unit's next full feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, we were always dependent on California to find
something for us,'' says Henn. ``They finally gave us the support,
encouraging us to come up with our own ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of some post-production work, such as color
correction and print duplication, the Orlando animation unit
insists it can do anything that the California studio can.
</P>
<P>
   As Coats puts it, ``Working in Florida is the feel of working in
a mom-and-pop store, with the money of Bloomingdale's.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
