r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEES-BANNED19-COX     06-18 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEES-BANNED19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beekeeping banned in Florida town
 &HT;    By Lisa Ocker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ With more than 3 million bees in 68 hives,
Jack Rollins used to be among a few hundred state-registered
beekeepers in South Florida. Now, the semi-retired barber, who
learned beekeeping from his uncle in his native Kentucky coal
country, is one of a few dozen in the region. And he's the only bee
man in Boca.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he almost became the last.
</P>
<P>
   City codes don't allow beekeeping, Code Compliance Administrator
Ruby Childers said.
</P>
<P>
   When the city received some anonymous complaints _ bee droppings
on a neighbor's lawn, an allergic woman's fears about being stung _
the city slapped Rollins with a code violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't bother you unless you bother them,'' said Rollins,
73. ``I can't say the same for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   With a petition in support signed by most of his neighbors and
about 20 supporters in the audience, Rollins persuaded the code
enforcement board Monday to let him keep his three-banded Italian
honey bees. The vote was 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   A past code violation forced Rollins to move most of his 68
hives in 1996, but finding new homes wasn't hard.
</P>
<P>
   People who appreciate nature appreciate the little pollinators,
he says. ``Not everybody is a city slicker from Fifth and Broadway
who's never seen a tree grow in Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins used to hunt quail on vacant fields just yards from his
house on Northwest 14th Avenue. His hives, each containing some
50,000-60,000 bees, produced 750 pounds of honey per hive a year.
</P>
<P>
   There are houses on those fields now and Rollins' hives have
dwindled to four, but each still draws some 50,000 bees and 750
pounds of honey per year. He keeps them on a nearby lot on
Northwest 15th Avenue, with grapefruit, orange, lime, tangelo,
papaya, banana and mulberry trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just changing. When you get people, people, people,
there's no room for anything else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Joyner, urban horticulturalist for the county's
agricultural extension service, agrees that increased development
has hurt the bee population.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the time, people complain about their fruit trees blooming
year after year, but they never see any fruit developing,'' Joyner
said. ``That's why we encourage people, whenever they can, to keep
bees.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins gives away most of his honey and pollen. He also gives
away bees to people who sting themselves to relieve symptoms of
rheumatoid arthritis and multiple sclerosis, he said.library
checking for legitimacy of medical treatment.. And whenever there's
a wayward swarm of bees, Rollins is the bee man; 911 operators call
him for help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
