<HEADER>
A5002 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAILED-FOURTHGRADE19-     06-18 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAILED-FOURTHGRADE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-thirds of Ohio fourth graders face repeated term
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If the state's new ``fourth grade guarantee''
were in effect today, two-thirds of the area's school districts
would be faced with retaining 40 percent or more of their
fourth-graders.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which takes effect in July 2001, requires that students
pass the reading portion of the Ohio Fourth Grade Proficiency Test
before advancing to the fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   But school district report cards issued this month by the state
show a wide disparity between the number of fourth graders
currently promoted to fifth grade and the number of those students
passing the reading test. Just over half of the 60 districts in
Montgomery, Miami, Warren, Greene, Shelby, Preble and Darke
counties, Ohio, send all fourth graders to the fifth grade,
according to statistics gathered by the Ohio Department of
Education. No local district promotes less than 96 percent of
fourth graders.
</P>
<P>
   But reading passage rates range from a low of 23.8 percent for
Dayton schools to a high of 84.1 percent in Oakwood, with the bulk
of schools having passage rates of less than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although state and local school officials remain optimistic that
the gap will be narrowed by the time the law takes effect, it is
clear that educators soon will need to address the thorny issues
around forcing students to repeat a grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preponderance of research shows that retention has adverse
effects on the social, emotional and intellectual development of
children,'' said Sam Sava, executive director of the National
Association of Elementary School Principals. ``Retention is an
absolute last resort in order to help a youngster achieve in his or
her areas of skills.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2.6 million children are retained annually, Sava
said.
</P>
<P>
   Studies show that children who are retained perform more poorly
on average when they go on to the next grade than if they had not
been retained, according to a summary of research data provided by
Monica Zarichny, Ohio Department of Education spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dropouts are five times more likely to have repeated a grade
than are high school graduates. Students who repeat two grades have
a probability of dropping out of nearly 100 percent,'' the research
summary stated.
</P>
<P>
   The state's law does provide some flexibility. Students are
given three chances to pass the test, rather than the current
single opportunity. And those who have failed the test may be
promoted if the school principal and reading teacher agree that the
child is academically ready for the fifth grade. Disabled children
may be exempted from the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires districts to offer intense help to
struggling students after the third grade and the state is
developing a program for schools to improve reading curriculum. The
question of who will pay for those programs has not been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Connolly, director of policy and communications for the Ohio
Senate Republican Caucus, said, ``The whole purpose is to be sure
that kids know how to read because if they can't read, they can't
do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, will retaining students achieve that goal?
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Johnson, a Dayton schools lead principal, said a
student's ability to gain from retention depends on many factors,
including the child's attendance history, age, communication
skills, physical size, previous retentions and intelligence level.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude of the child and the parent toward retention also
is critical.
</P>
<P>
   Fairborn parent Yvette Sales, 28, protested her son's promotion
to the sixth grade this year despite a report card dotted with Fs.
The school district has now offered her a range of help, including
financial aid for summer school, and given her the final choice on
whether or not he will move up a grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before my son goes on to sixth grade I want to know he can
grasp on sixth grade material,'' said Sales, who will delay her
decision until after the 11-year-old boy completes summer school.
``I don't want him to struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Retention tends not to hurt children who have good self-esteem
and social skills and those who are able to catch up easily,
according to the National Association of School Psychologists. It
also may help children who have missed school due to illness or
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Educators were unanimous in saying that each child should be
considered on an individual basis and that elementary school
retention doesn't do any good if nothing changes in the way the
child is being taught the second time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't identify what skills are missing in Johnny's
foundation and if holding him back in the fourth grade doesn't
directly address them and target those skills, what good is that
going to do?'' asked Debbie Slavens, executive director of Sylvan
Learning Centers of Vandalia, Piqua and Richmond, a local company
offering remedial and enrichment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
