<HEADER>
A5049 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILNER-BOOKS19-COX     06-18 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-BOOKS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOKREVIEW: Greene's back with another 50 best
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1981, in Texas Monthly magazine, A.C. Greene published a
daring piece called ``The 50 Best Texas Books.'' The piece was
swiftly followed by reactions from several Texas writers, including
Texas most widely read novelist, Larry McMurtry, who has since won
a Pulitzer Prize for literature.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't talked with Mr. Greene directly about this, but I
would assume that this reaction was his aim when he wrote the
article. McMurtry's response, in effect, was that there really
weren't 50 best books by Texans. His essay was entitled, ``Ever a
Bridegroom: Reflections on the Failure of Texas Literature.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to that quote ``was immediate and sometimes
explosive,'' which no doubt was part of the aim of Mr. McMurtry's
reply.
</P>
<P>
   Before Texas can produce a notable share of best literature, the
thinking goes, it first must passionately discuss what's already on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   So, that was 15 years ago and the furor has since died down. Now
along comes A.C. Greene with a book entitled ``The 50 Plus Best
Books on Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction to his new book, and it's mostly new, Greene
says: ``In the 16 years that ``The 50 Best Books on Texas'' has
been around it has become a kind of guidebook to Texas literature,
which embarrasses me. It was not conceived as that...the listings
are my picks... Some books have been dropped from that '50 Best'
list...Texas writing is changing. Many more Hispanic and black
writers will explore their Texas roots or relationships as
individuals. More Texas writers will pursue the peculiar puzzles of
life in the larger Texas cities, and perhaps the day will come when
there will be no need, other than for historical reasons, for lists
of best books about Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene's new list includes J. Frank Dobie's ``Coronado's
Children,'' and Larry L. King's ``And Other Dirty Stories,'' a wide
range at first glimpse but not so wide after I thought about it for
a while.
</P>
<P>
   I won't attempt to put the entire list here, but some of my
special favorites include ``Horse Tradin''' by Ben K. Green and
``Blessed McGill'' by Bud Shrake. There's also John Graves
wonderful ``Goodbye to a River .''
</P>
<P>
   Greene left out one of my favorites -- Cormac McCarthy's ``All
the Pretty Horses'' -- because, he says in his introduction, ``...
while it skips across the Texas-Mexico border, it is basically a
novel of Mexico.'' I might could argue about that some, but I won't
do so here.
</P>
<P>
   This is a very interesting book, particularly for Texana
collectors by a man who knows what he's talking about, even if you
disagree with him along the way, which, as previously mentioned, is
at least partly the reason for the list in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been riding in MIR the past few decades you may not
know who A.C. Greene is. For those readers I repeat the following.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green was the book editor, editorial page editor and
columnist for the Dallas Times-Herald before being awarded the
Dobie-Paisano fellowship which resulted in his classic book, ``A
Personal Country,'' now available in trade paperback. He has
published more than 22 books, including his first novel just this
year, ``They are Ruining Ibiza,'' which was reviewed here recently.
He currently writes a column for the Dallas Morning News.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
