<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-CO     06-18 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: AMA throws up petty puff of smoke
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 21, 1998.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Medical Association, on the very day that Trent
Lott and his troops were killing a politically mutated anti-tobacco
bill, chose not to condemn the U.S. Senate but to flay the Chicago
Bulls instead.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was not the $40 million the tobacco industry spent to
fight the bill but the fact that Michael Jordan, Scotty Pippen and
others of the three-in-a-row National Basketball Association
champion team lit up cigars following their victory.
</P>
<P>
   (Inasmuch as hockey is not as popular, the AMA apparently chose
to ignore the fact that Detroit Red Wings star Vladimir
Kostantinov, critically injured in an auto accident, wheelchair
bound and with severe short-term memory problems, also displayed a
cigar while celebrating his teammates' second consecutive Stanley
Cup victory Tuesday night.)
</P>
<P>
   At convention _ in Chicago, no less _ the delegates voted 474-1
(the dissenter thought it should be handled privately) to tell the
Bulls they were appalled by the cigars and to urge sports teams and
the TV industry not to show tobacco products after sports events.
</P>
<P>
   It sends a dangerous message to kids, the AMA contended. (No
mention was made of champagne, an enduring celebratory item and
speed-path to inebriety.)
</P>
<P>
   I no longer am a smoker, haven't been for some time, abhor
cigarette and cigar smoke, won't take a table in a restaurant near
a smoker, but I've got to tell you that this is what I believe is
the message sent by the Chicago Bulls:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win three straight NBA championships, when you win
six in eight years, when you come to the realization it's the
Bulls' ``last dance,'' you are entitled to light up a stogie _ no
matter how bad it may look.''
</P>
<P>
   I have the same feeling for first-time daddies, as long as it
remains a unique experience: ``It's twins! Have a cigar!''
</P>
<P>
   While I do not believe I have had a cigar in my mouth since
Fidel Castro rode into power 38 years ago, I promise I will light
one (just one) the day he leaves _ and damn the consequences,
medical or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Don't necessarily light up, but lighten up, docs.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much more on TV every day and night that can damage
kids (and adults) that a vote against a celebratory cigar just
comes across as petty piffle.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the AMA has waged a good war against tobacco, one I
certainly support. But to seize upon this moment of celebration,
this singular instant, is to devalue the legitimate struggle
against tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   I recall no such reaction toward that voyeuristic moment when
Bill Clinton, a strong supporter of the failed anti-tobacco
legislation, was caught by a long lens in his African hotel room,
ostensibly celebrating the Paula Jones case dismissal, with a cigar
in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   I also wonder how many of the 474 delegates who voted against
the Bulls' public use of cigars are closet smokers, living a deceit
and supporting the tobacco industry directly.
</P>
<P>
   The AMA has very important work on its agenda, and the war
against tobacco is high on that list, as it also is a war against
cancer and heart disease. To take the time and energy to get into
an uproar over Michael Jordan with a cigar between his lips seems a
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, everyone wants to be like Michael, but I don't think his
celebrating what may be his last great victory with a cigar is the
image his admirers will try to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more to Michael Jordan than just a puff a smoke.
And the kids all know it.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
