<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-POWER-COX- &UR; -$AD     06-18 1955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POWER-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV21-1500&AMP;ADD 
 &HT;     SOUTHERN COMPANY'S ASIAN DREAMS STILL DRUM LOUD
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     With CHINA-POWER-SIDE-$ADV21.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG, China _ The company that has called itself the ``900
pound gorilla'' of American electric utilities is finding Asia a
cruel and trackless jungle.
</P>
<P>
   Thorns in the form of generator glitches continue to torment the
reliability of Southern Co.'s giant Shajiao C power plant here in
China's booming southern industrial strip.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere throughout the continent, nettles from the Asian
financial crisis have stung the prospects of four of the five
largest future power projects that Southern took on when it bought
control of its Asian subsidiary two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been out here in times of turmoil, and if you're
sitting back in the United States, you would probably look out here
and say, `Asia is not the place where you would like to be,''' said
F.D. ``Rick'' Kuester, who was sent out from Mississippi Power to
become a top executive in Southern's Hong Kong-based Asian
subsidiary, Consolidated Electric Power Asia (CEPA).
</P>
<P>
   Yet dreams about electrifying the Orient still drum loud in
Southern's psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the per-capita consumption of electricity
compared to anywhere else in the world,'' Kuester said, ``you can
see tremendous opportunities for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Southern's fire-breathing optimism about Asia is
not without reason.
</P>
<P>
   Its shareholders have just tasted their first Asian profits,
less than two years after Southern invested $2.1 billion to buy
into a Hong Kong billionaire's Asian power enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The initial payback on one of the biggest investments in
Southern's 75-year history was something short of gargantuan. An
earnings report for January through March showed Southern collected
$15 million in Asian profits, or about one-twentieth of Southern's
worldwide earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Southern says this is a felicitous omen because its
Asian venture wasn't expected to turn profitable until the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the happiest tidings have come from the Philippines.
CEPA's mid-sized Philippines plant, the 735 megawatt coal-fired
Pagbilao Power Station, has been churning out virtually all of the
Asian profits that Southern has reported.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Shajiao C plant in China that is still hampered by
startup glitches, the Philippines' Pagbilao plant ran smoothly
enough to generate 100 percent of its contracted electrical
generating capacity from January through March.
</P>
<P>
   And Southern's much bigger 1,200 megawatt Sual coal-fired power
station in the Philippines, now under construction, is on schedule
and nearing completion on Luzon Island. Its first unit will enter
commercial operation in June 1999, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   For Southern, the most painful aspect of its journey to Asia has
been its inability to expand beyond the footprint of power plant
investments that it bought from Hong Kong entrepreneur Gordon Wu in
October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Especially frustrating has been China, which Southern viewed as
its most promising patch for building new power plants because of
the country's explosive growth and its 1.2 billion potential
electricity-users.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's Hong Kong office now acknowledges that the
five-year-old joint venture it inherited from Wu to build a
coal-fired plant in China's Jiangsu Province ``has been shelved for
the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   And in nearly two years, no new Southern Co. power plant deals
in China have been concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``China obviously needs power _ a lot of it,'' mused Kuester.
``Why then is the China market so difficult to crack?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kuester and the rest of Southern's 16-member Asian
executive corps may be nearing an answer. After rattling the bamboo
in China for more than a year, Southern is reportedly close to
announcing one or two breakthrough deals _ perhaps as early as
during the June 25-July 3 visit to China by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One deal close to blossoming is for a Southern Co. investment in
a mid-sized Chinese 600-megawatt coal-fired power plant near the
mouth of a coal mine in the northern province of Shanxi, 150 miles
west of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   For about six months Southern has been pursuing this Shanxi
contract in partnership with former U.S. Senator J. Bennett
Johnston's Washington-based energy company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are basically in a joint venture with him on that one,''
said Kuester, referring to the former chairman of the U.S. Senate
Energy Committee who went into the energy business after retiring
from the Senate last year.
</P>
<P>
   Kuester declined to predict when the Shanxi negotiations might
conclude, saying ``it is premature to announce anything now.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Southern's Hong Kong-based go-getters have been
rushing to complete a significantly larger deal in China, this time
apparently without Johnston's participation and clout.
</P>
<P>
   This spring Southern dispatched a technical team to investigate
a possible investment in two existing 1200-megawatt Chinese
coal-fired power plants in coastal Shandong province, a fast-growth
region between Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, a report on China's official Xinhua news agency
appeared to boost Southern's chances. It disclosed that Shanxi
Province has budgeted $8.4 billion to expand 10 coal-fired power
plants and make the province a major electricity exporter over the
next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coal is expected to continue to provide 70 percent of the
country's energy needs well into the next century as China has few
alternatives to satisfy fast-expanding demand for power,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   That is the kind of cheery intelligence that first attracted
Southern to open a small business development office in Hong Kong
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The first three years of Southern's Asia business prospecting
yielded meager results. So in October 1996, Southern chairman A.W.
Dalhberg decided to risk a quantum leap by concluding a $2.7
billion contract to buy 80 percent of Wu's CEPA.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year Southern's profits were so robust that
Dahlberg could tell shareholders that Southern was the ``900-pound
gorilla'' of the American power business, and was intent on
becoming a global ``1,800-pound gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu, who needed cash to pare down debts from other heavily
leveraged ventures, received $2.1 billion from Southern, plus a
$600 million one-time cash dividend from CEPA's treasury.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Southern expected to operate CEPA indefinitely in
partnership with Wu, who was counted on to add his vision and his
Rolodex of power industry contacts to Southern's base of technical
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   But the Asian financial crisis, starting with a tsunami wave of
Asian currency devaluations last summer, pressured Southern and Wu
to part ways.
</P>
<P>
   Though the full story of their breakup remains tightly held, one
seed of tension was their diverging appraisals about the future
profitability of CEPA'S Tanjung Jati B power project in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Wu _ contending that Tanjung Jati B would ultimately yield $20
billion in income _ had pressed Southern to deliver a $138 million
contingency payment that had been part of the original $2.7 billion
CEPA price tag.
</P>
<P>
   But Southern said no, on grounds that the Indonesians had not
made a binding commitment on how much they would pay for Tanjung
Jati B's electricity once the plant was built.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the Asian currency crisis was starting to explode last
July, Southern bought out Wu's remaining 20 percent of CEPA for
$115 million in cash, plus Southern's share of the CEPA rights to
develop the disputed Indonesian Tanjung Jati plant.
</P>
<P>
   For Southern, this second deal with Wu came in the nick of time.
Within weeks, Indonesia's economy was sucked into a whirlpool that
would squeeze out three-quarters of the value of the Indonesian
currency and help cause this spring's ouster of President Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanjung Jati B plant, now back in Wu's portfolio, is on
indefinite hold, and Southern is one of the few international
electric power companies that emerged from the Indonesia debacle
unscathed. Indonesia's state-owned electricity distributor declared
this month that it ``has no money'' to pay foreign-based power
companies for contracted generating plants in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Rightly or wrongly, Wu has congratulated himself on getting the
better of the deal in the two-stage takeover by Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we sold CEPA, it was based on this principle: we already
had completed contracts and there was a whole bag of receivables on
hand,'' Wu told the South China Morning Post last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comment at the time was that I had sold the family jewels.
At $18.50 (the price per share Southern paid for CEPA), I was a
happy seller. I'd be lucky to get half that price today.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern's Hong Kong executives prefer not to publicly dispute
Wu's judgment about what CEPA was really worth.
</P>
<P>
   However, a footnote in Southern's 1997 annual report informs
stockholders that Southern's $2.1 billion net cost for acquiring
100 percent of CEPA ``exceeded the fair market value of net assets
by approximately $1.6 billion.'' The annual report explained that
the excess over market value in buying the Asian subsidiary _
$1.649 billion _ was entered onto Southern Co. books as an
``increase in goodwill.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia's changing economic fortunes accounted for much of the gap
in valuations. Chances have increased that Southern may never
receive a payback on four out of the five biggest future Asian
power plant projects that were on Wu's drawing boards when he sold
his company to Southern.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the shelved plant in China's Jiangsu Province and
Indonesia's Tanjung Jati B that Wu reclaimed, the potential
non-performers are:
</P>
<P>
   -- A proposed $1.6 billion Keti Bandar coal-fired power plant in
Pakistan. This Wu-initiated plant ``is basically at a standstill,''
Kuester acknowledged in an interview. ``They (the Pakistanis) don't
need any more power, they don't want any more power, and we are not
pushing ahead on that because it doesn't make sense for the country
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   -- A proposed $5.5 billion electricity mega-plant in India.
Kuester said the new Indian government has signaled a willingness
to proceed with some electricity mega-plants. But the India
``memorandum of agreement'' that Southern inherited from Wu was not
a fully negotiated deal. ``We still have to stand back and assess
the situation _ is that a project that makes sense for us,
economically?'' said Kuester.
</P>
<P>
   When Southern bought CEPA, it also acquired a billion tons of
coal reserves in a remote mine in Austria. Southern is weighing
construction of a coal-fired power station near the mine, which
would convert the coal into revenue-producing electricity without
today's high transportation costs.
</P>
<P>
   Prickly though Southern's path has been, Kuester believes the
American utility giant is gradually becoming more comfortable in
its new Asian habitat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so different in Alabama or Mississippi or Georgia,''
Kuester said. ``You don't walk into somebody's office and all of a
sudden do a business deal and make friends. It takes a while to
develop a relationship ... The fact that they didn't know who we
were and didn't trust us when we walked in the door, and that it
took some time, that didn't surprise me.''
</P>
<P>
