<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-POIROT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DRUG BATTLES LOSS OF MEMORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of us have difficulty finding the right word sometimes, but
a person with Alzheimer's disease may forget simple words or
substitute inappropriate words, making sentences incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can temporarily misplace a wallet or keys. A person with
Alzheimer's may put the wallet in the freezer and forget that the
keys are needed to start the car or to open a door.
</P>
<P>
   It's normal to forget the day of the week or a destination
momentarily, but with Alzheimer's you can forget what year it is or
become lost on your own street.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine not remembering your own daughter's name.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of people each year, it's becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 4 million Americans are afflicted with Alzheimer's
disease, and that number is expected to triple as the baby boomers
age, says Dr. Susan Blue, a Fort Worth neurologist.
</P>
<P>
   Women are disproportionately affected because we live longer,
and the risk increases dramatically with advancing age.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2050, the number of Americans with Alzheimer's is
expected to hit 14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Alzheimer's is a disease of the brain that causes a steady
decline in memory that results in dementia _ a loss of intellectual
functions (including thinking, remembering and reasoning) severe
enough to interfere with everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Blue lists some of the early warning signs as:
</P>
<P>
   _ Persistent and increasing problems with short-term memory.
</P>
<P>
   _ A tendency to forget the date, including the month and year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recurring disorientation, such as repeatedly getting lost on
familiar routes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Difficulty with language skills or performing simple
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier the disease is diagnosed and treated, the better
the chances of being able to slow the progress of the disease,''
Blue says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alzheimer's is the fourth leading cause of death in the United
States. Each year we are spending $100 billion treating the
disease. What's exciting is that now we have a treatment option
that allows us to offer the patients some hope of stabilizing their
condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceutical companies Pfizer and Eisai are collaborating
on development and distribution of Aricept, a new drug to slow the
memory loss associated with Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Aricept and Cognex, the only other drug approved
for the treatment of Alzheimer's, studies show estrogen replacement
therapy, ibuprofen and other nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs
and vitamin E may offer some protection to nerve cells in the brain
that are destroyed by the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Alzheimer's Association has launched a new campaign aimed at
educating women about the disease. For a free copy of the brochure
``Women and Alzheimer's Disease,'' with information including
warning signs, treatment options and caregiver tips, call (800)
272-3900.
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
