<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMOCRACY-NOT-PERFECT     06-18 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRACY-NOT-PERFECT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY: IS IT FOR EVERYONE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (The Council on Foreign Relations is offering this commentary
on late 20th-century democracy as part of our monthly World Leaders
Forum. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. )
 &HT;    
 By SAMUEL P. HUNTINGTON  
 c.1998 Council on Foreign Relations  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Is democracy for everyone? No _ not yet, but it certainly is for
more people now than it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the single-most important political phenomenon of
the late 20th century has been the expansion of democracy in
country after country around the world.
</P>
<P>
   And by democracy I refer to electoral democracies _ which I
define as a political system whose most powerful decision makers
are selected through relatively fair, honest, periodic elections,
in which candidates can freely compete and in which virtually all
the adult population is eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   By that definition, the number of democracies in the world has
gone up very substantially in the past few decades, from about 40
back in 1970, to 66, according to Freedom House, in 1988, to 117
now. This expansion has, in considerable measure, been worldwide;
it has affected every part of the globe.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest concentration of democracies, obviously, is among
wealthy countries and among those who were part of, shall we say,
Western civilization. But at least one democratic regime exists in
every major civilization or culture in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy, I believe, is desirable for two reasons: One, it
provides order and a mechanism for incremental change, and it
provides a way of removing from office political leaders who have
turned out to be total flops.
</P>
<P>
   Two, it is also one way _ not the only way _ of protecting
liberty in a society. And I agree that violations of liberty are
less likely if you have a democratic system of elected officials
who must face voters again to run for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening to democracy as it spreads around the world?
First, I think it is becoming more variegated; it is taking on
different forms and acquiring different characteristics in
different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Second, democracy, as I've defined it, is simply a way of
constituting, limiting and changing governments. There is often a
tendency, however, to see it as much more _ as, for example, to
suppose that the introduction of democracy will bring about peace,
equality, prosperity and harmony among nations, classes and so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think that is the case. Governments produced by
elections can be inefficient, corrupt, shortsighted or
discriminatory. They can pursue aggressive nationalistic policies
and ruinous economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy is no guarantee that other good things will happen,
although they may. People around the world may want to believe that
democracy won't have unhappy consequences. But I think we have to
confront the fact that, in this world, elections can produce
results that don't necessarily make us happy.
</P>
<P>
   Elections may produce anti-Western governments, illiberal
governments, ones that we find very difficult to deal with _
including (when they are weak and resting on fragile coalitions),
even governments that go off, as India has, and explode nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to standard rhetoric, if other countries will simply
democratize _ if we can encourage them to move in that direction _
they will not always be friendly and cooperate with us.
</P>
<P>
   For example, this assumption underlies the thinking of virtually
everybody on every side of the China debate. If only we could make
China democratic, the thinking goes, it would be so much more easy
to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps it would be, but, on the other hand, it is not
difficult to conceive of a democratic China simultaneously being a
China that is highly nationalistic, in which politicians competing
for office find it worth their while, in terms of votes, to
denounce the United States.
</P>
<P>
   So while I am all in favor of promoting more democracies, I
think we ought to do it in a realistic way, with our eyes open.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think instituting a democratic system of government is
necessarily going to guarantee greater prosperity, equality,
elimination of ethnic conflict or the solution of other social
problems and ills. I do not mean that it will be impossible for
democratic governments to do that; only that there is no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 Council on Foreign Relations &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This commentary is adapted from a panel discussion entitled
``Democracy: Is It for Everyone,'' held at the Council on Foreign
Relations, in New York, on May 19, 1998.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Professor Samuel P. Huntington is the Albert J. Weatherhead
III university professor at Harvard University, the director of the
John M. Olin Institute for Strategic Studies, chairman of the
Harvard Academy for International and Area Studies and chairman of
the Harvard Center for International Affairs. He is the author of
numerous books and articles, most recently, ``The Clash of
Civilizations and the Remaking of World Order.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
