<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5137 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-GIRL-VIOLENCE-NY     06-18 2525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-GIRL-VIOLENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAZOR'S EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By ROYAL FORD  
 FROM: The Boston Globe Magazine  
 &HT;    Watch Quania's eyes.
 &HT;    Dark beneath her broad forehead and furrows of braid, they
reveal nothing. She keeps them distant.
 &HT;    As the bus called ``the 28'' rumbles along Blue Hill Avenue
toward Grove Hall, Quania looks straight ahead. She does not watch
the chattering groups of other teen-age girls, doesn't look at
anyone's clothes or face, certainly doesn't cast a glance at any
boy sitting with a girl.
 &HT;    Later at Grove Hall, where a building of squat shops curves
around a corner, two girls face each other in a darkened doorway,
their backs to the doorposts. Quania's glance in their direction is
too stealthy to be seen: ``I almost looked over at them, but I
looked right back away,'' she says, her tone almost apologetic.
 &HT;    At 15, Quania Daniel, a sophomore at Boston English High School,
already has learned the danger of a misinterpreted glance _ a
glance mistaken for superiority or haughtiness, for a sneer at
another girl's appearance or for flirting with someone's boyfriend.
 &HT;    Here in Grove Hall, behind the Beulah Holmes Holiness Center, a
girl pulled a knife on Quania one night a few months back. It was a
confrontation sparked by a glance Quania might have cast _ though
she doesn't remember it _ at the Chez Vous roller rink up the
avenue.
 &HT;    When the knife came out, she walked away. Chicken, some girls
called her. Smart, she calls herself.
 &HT;    But the next night, she happened to run into the girl again at
Grove Hall, and this time they did fight, fist-to-fist _ ``up and
up,'' as Quania says, distinguishing it from fights with weapons or
fights where a group of girls jumps a lone victim. ``I didn't lose
that fight'' is all she will say about it.
 &HT;    She was lucky to have a fight end so cleanly. One of her
friends, tied by rumor to another girl's boyfriend, had her face
slashed with a box cutter just a block down from Doyle's, the
Jamaica Plain tavern where warm friendships and conviviality
abound.
 &HT;    Until about 10 years ago, teen-age girls seldom fought each
other _ even with fists. They did not carry knives and razors and
box cutters. They did not form roaming packs and attack other
girls. They did not fight with sticks, bats, bricks.
 &HT;    Today they do. And that has made the world of many girls like
Quania a terrain of fear, a place where caution is essential. The
threat is not just in the cores of cities. It exists in
Massachusetts at the Quincy Center MBTA stop; at a trailer park in
Concord, N.H.; at a school in York, Maine.
 &HT;    Violence by teen-age girls is not yet a deluge, but its steady
escalation, even as overall crime rates in the nation are falling,
is troubling.
 &HT;    Consider these recent crimes by girls:
 &HT;    In Roxbury, Mass., two 15-year-olds use razors to slice the arms
and forehead of a 16-year-old girl.
 &HT;    In Concord, N.H., four girls surround a 14-year-old girl as she
gets off a school bus at the mobile-home park where she lives and
beat her with baseball bats.
 &HT;    In Revere, Mass., a state trooper is brought down by a
15-year-old girl who jumps him from behind after he stops her
father for a minor traffic violation.
 &HT;    In Cromwell, Conn., two 18-year-olds are charged with using box
cutters to slash the necks of two other teen-age girls.
 &HT;    In Rhode Island, a girl who was 13 at the time of the killing is
sentenced to 45 years in prison for the murder of a 23-year-old
single mother she shot in the head in a fight over a man.
 &HT;    And in Springfield, Mass., a teen-age girl holds up a young
mother at gunpoint, then beats her victim's 18-month-old child with
the pistol.
 &HT;    Kathleen M. O'Toole, the state's secretary of public safety,
recalls that when she was a Boston street cop in the 1970s and
'80s, girls were arrested rarely, and then only for nonviolent
crimes such as shoplifting. In the mid-1980s, however, that began
to change, and the rise in violence has been steady.
 &HT;    Since 1987, according to the FBI, the number of violent crimes
committed annually by boys under 18 has risen from 51,653 to 78,853
_ a 53 percent increase. But that is less than half the percentage
increase among girls during the same period: Violent crime by girls
under 18 climbed 118 percent, from 6,418 incidents to 13,995.
Aggravated assaults were up 124 percent; robberies, 117 percent.
 &HT;    Guns are rarely the weapon of choice for girls _ at least for
now. They opt for less deadly weapons, such as razors, box- and
carpet-cutting knives, sticks, bats, fists. Before teen-age boys
turned to guns, sometime in the mid-1980s, they too used knives and
razors, and that leaves open the question of whether girls will
also turn to guns as the taboo on violent female behavior fades.
 &HT;    Still, the total number of girls committing violent crimes is
small compared with boys. Meda Chesney-Lind, professor of women's
studies at the University of Hawaii at Manoa and co-author of the
recent book ``Girls, Delinquency, and Juvenile Justice,'' cautions
that the perceived increase in teen-age female violence may be
partly a result of greater attention to the problem by police and
the news media.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, the shift has been perceptible enough that
educators, social workers, judges and police are worried that if
the trend continues, girls might achieve a perverse equality in
crime, an achievement nobody would cheer.
 &HT;    Now Quania is in a program trying to stay out of violence and
help other kids do the same. But she knows it's not easy.
 &HT;    Time was, a teen-age girl living in bad circumstances did one of
two things: She either retreated into herself, becoming the
hollow-eyed waif who said little in school and maybe even quit
altogether, walking through the days full of pain and
submissiveness; or she got pregnant, because pregnancy meant escape
and, with another life dependent on her, a vestige of power.
 &HT;    Today, girls have a third way to go wrong: by striking out in
violence.
 &HT;    The triggers can seem trivial. A girl might attack someone she
thinks looks down on her clothes, her hair, her family. Somebody
sizes up her boyfriend, maybe. Or somebody looks as if she wants to
rise above their shared lot, by dressing well, studying hard,
refusing to hang in the neighborhood or joyride on the streets or
country roads.
 &HT;    Most girls who turn to violence are reacting to the same
circumstances that have long been blamed for breeding violence
among boys. They come from dysfunctional families, learning at home
about abuse: of their bodies, of drugs and alcohol, of their own
esteem. What they don't learn there they pick up on the streets.
They form cliques that a decade ago might have been merely vocally
abusive but today are assault squads.
 &HT;    This generation of girls spends many hours after school without
parental supervision. But what is new is that they do it in the
company of boys, and as the equals of those boys. Just as some boys
and girls hang together today in positive ways, as groups of
friends, not couples, so others hang together in destructive
pursuits.
 &HT;    ``They're acting like they do because of the way the boys
behave. They don't want the boys to have one up on them,'' says Joe
Mascaritolo, the assistant director at Madison Park
Vocational-Technical High School, in Boston. ``You see it more in
groups of boys and girls all being together, all trying to be
equals.''
 &HT;    But there is irony in this, says Sibylle Artz, a professor of
children and youth care at the University of Victoria, in British
Columbia. The girls who become violent and so feel they are
achieving power do it not by becoming powerful young girls but by
stepping out of gender, by acting like violent young men.
 &HT;    Part of the influence on girls is the music that many listen to,
as well as the movies, television shows, fashion ads and news
programs that emphasize power and violence. Artz points
specifically to music videos, which entered the culture shortly
before the first increase in violence among girls was noted.
Perhaps significantly, many videos portray women as powerful by
virtue of their potential violence.
 &HT;    Complaints about the effects of pop culture are not new, but the
level of violence among girls is rising just as girls are tuning in
to this culture in record numbers. In 1997, for the first time,
more girls bought CDs, records and tapes than boys. Li'l Kim, the
rap singer, calls herself the Queen Bitch and sings of sex and
excess _ to the sound of a gun being cocked.
 &HT;    Quania recalls a number with the refrain ``slice you up'' and
marvels that one song she loved by Master P turned out, once she
got past the beat and heard the lyrics, to be a recipe for
producing crack cocaine.
 &HT;    ``These girls are not becoming violent out of thin air,'' says
Martha P. Grace, chief justice for the Massachusetts juvenile-court
system. They emerge from ``a constellation of parental neglect,'' a
world where they have ``either witnessed violence endlessly on TV,
in their home, or they have been violated by a parent or someone
else.''
 &HT;    ``Women judges may sometimes be the first women they encounter
who are not powerless,'' Grace notes. This is so even though women
today are more powerful than ever in business, medicine, the law,
the trades, sports and many other realms. Women in these roles
often exist beyond the ken of troubled teen-age girls. But a shadow
of that social shift has fallen across their world: Girls now see
they can rise in the world of violent crime.
 &HT;    Frenia learned most of her bad ways on the street, or in classes
where she wasn't always paying attention. Like Quania, she is
working hard to keep her own life in order and help others at the
same time.
 &HT;    To that end, eight teen-age girls are at ease, sitting around a
make-believe living room. Bone-Net, played by Charlene Johnson, has
invited her girlfriends in to watch TV, and they're finger-flicking
through the channels. The flashing images trigger memory and
reaction in each of the girls.
 &HT;    One by one, they rise on the makeshift stage in the cafeteria of
the Clarence R. Edwards Middle School, in Charlestown, Mass. Each
has a lesson in danger to present to an audience of her peers.
 &HT;    A young woman named Precious stands to tell of her dilemma: Her
friends Trisha and Toya are at each other, she says, and she is
worried that their vocal dispute will turn violently physical. Toya
has already threatened Trisha: ``You're that girl who was talking
bad trash about me,'' and ``I'm going to beat your behind,'' with
eight other girls to help.
 &HT;    Caught in the middle of impending violence between two friends,
Precious asks the audience what she should do. ``I don't want to
get cut up over nobody.''
 &HT;    Several hands shoot up immediately. Talk to your friends, one
student suggests. Tell them violence is no way to go, remind them
that they are friends. Get them to sit down and talk this out.
 &HT;    Precious's real name is La 'Toshia Leathers; she's a member of a
traveling troupe of high school students. The group puts on skits
illustrating some of the dangers teen-age girls face, then invites
the audience to talk about avoiding such pitfalls. Called teen-age
Girls InFormed, the troupe was put together by the Massachusetts
Prevention Center, at the Medical Foundation in Boston, and is
supported by the public school system.
 &HT;    A discussion such as this is one of several ways in which
schools and public officials are beginning to confront the problem
of escalating violence among adolescent girls. Some programs are
aimed specifically at them, while others that once targeted boys
have been expanded to include girls.
 &HT;    In some communities, teen-agers are recruited as peer leaders in
their schools; in others, officials have set up downtown drop-in
centers for troubled youths. Still other programs, such as teen-age
Girls InFormed, hope their cautionary tales will reach young people
before violence happens.
 &HT;    The audience on this afternoon, at least, appears to be engaged
in Precious' story. Later, other characters rise: Blue, whose real
name is Marilyn Jean, acts the part of a drunk, telling how she
forced a girl who didn't drink to slug down some liquor. ``It's not
my fault she choked on her vomit,'' she says. ``It's not my fault
she died.'' The audience groans in disapproval.
 &HT;    As the session continues, actors come forward to talk of date
rape, of more drinking, of more violence. They ask the audience to
respond: Who was at fault in the date rape? Should a drunken mother
be reported to the social service department? How do you stop
drinking? How do you stop fighting?
 &HT;    Today, Frenia is a peer leader for Teen Empowerment, a South
End-based outreach program with offices in three Boston high
schools: Madison Park, English and Dorchester. Peer leaders try to
help steer troubled youngsters away from violence by teaching them
to express their anger and frustrations in ways that are vocal, not
violent.
 &HT;    ``They learn violence at home,'' Frenia says. ``They aren't
respected and they end up not respecting themselves. And how are
you going to respect anybody else if you can't respect yourself?''
 &HT;    Teen Empowerment tries to teach self-respect by encouraging kids
to talk about what is troubling them, in casual gatherings after
school, without dictating solutions. Instead, a peer leader, such
as Frenia or Quania, uses her own experience to help peers work out
answers for themselves.
 &HT;    While programs such as these seem promising, no one is sure yet
what will work best. Yet the studies that Artz and others have
done, in both Canada and the United States, offer some clues to
what might work. It seems the skits presented by teen-age Girls
InFormed are useful because they present tangible problems, inspire
discussion and propose nonviolent options.
 &HT;    The issue is critical, because the question that logically
follows the surge in violence among girls is frightening: Will the
trend continue, mimicking the level of mayhem among boys?
 &HT;    Hopefully not. Moreover, girls appear to learn from one another
in ways that boys, long ingrained with the notion that
aggressiveness is natural, do not. Many are hoping this will be a
key to the battle.
 &HT;     c.1998 The Boston Globe Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Royal Ford is a staff reporter for The Boston Globe.) &LR;
</P>
