r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-CELL-HNS &LR;      06-18 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-CELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY PLANS FUEL CELLS FOR THE HOME BY 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LATHAN, N.Y. _ Plug Power LLC says it has developed a cleaner,
cheaper and more reliable way of getting electricity into the
average home.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power announced it expects to bring a $3,000
dishwasher-sized power source that can supply all the electricity
needed to run the average home by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and government energy-policy architects
attending Wednesday's announcement agreed the fuel-cell technology
is a good idea. They like the way fuel cells can produce
electricity in a clean, contained process that doesn't generate air
pollution the way coal-fired plants do, and that is also more
efficient in generating power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very interested in promoting this technology not only
to consumers, but to municipalities around the state,'' said Daniel
R. Mackay, representative of the New York Conservation Education
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind fuel-cell technology is to take a common fuel,
such as natural gas or propane and convert that into hydrogen gas.
Early models are starting with hydrogen gas.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrogen molecules are actually split into electrons and
protons, with the electrons providing the power that can be
converted into electricity for the home. The protons left over
react with oxygen in the air and create water, which is emitted
from the fuel cell as exhaust. Thin membranes are used as a sort of
staging for the whole process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never stops to boggle my mind that a little Saran Wrap-type
material can give you 300 to 400 amps of power, and your average
toaster uses 15 amps of power,'' said William Ernst, vice president
and technical director of the Latham, N.Y.-based Plug Power.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cells are manufactured to match the specific energy needs
of different categories of consumers. Plug Power's first product
will produce 7,000 watts of power, more than enough to handle the
energy demands of a 2,000 square-foot home, according to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a modest brick-faced ranch belonging to a company
employee is using a demonstration model fuel cell now.
</P>
<P>
   Company employees admitted visitors to the home Wednesday to
show how computers, televisions, kitchen appliances, lights and air
conditioners can all be powered at the same time from the fuel
cell.
</P>
<P>
   Because the electricity is actually produced right on the home
site with a delivered fuel such as natural gas or propane from a
home tank, it doesn't have to be transmitted through power lines
and poles that can be felled in storms.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power said the power produced by a fuel cell could be 20
percent cheaper than that provided by major utility companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, heat expended by the fuel cell can be used to heat
water in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power President Gary Mittleman said he expected utility
companies to distribute the systems to residential customers when
the first product, the Plug Power 7000, comes onto the market in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Utility companies may own the product, install it on customer
premises and charge for the electricity produced, he said. As the
market evolves, customers might buy their own models, perhaps even
from appliance dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies also are trying to produce this technology and
to get into related markets. Some companies, for instance, are
focused solely on fuel cells for cars.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut-based Onsi Corp. produces fuel cells for commercial
buildings that require more power.
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems distributes power-generation units for small
industrial units, and so goes after a different segment of the
power market, according to a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Plug Power is well-positioned to be the leader in the
U.S. residential market, said Jean M. Redfield, president of DTE
Edison Electric, which is one of Plug Power's two corporate
parents.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power also has its eye on markets in China, Latin America
and other countries where some regions lack extensive power-grid
systems, executives said, as well as industrialized nations that
are grappling with air-pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power is a joint venture between DTE and Mechanical
Technology Inc. of Latham, an early developer of fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power was formed a year ago, and soon after one of its fuel
cells was used to convert electricity to gasoline for cars. The New
York State Energy Research and Development Authority helped the
company with a $1.2 million grant for early research.
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to increase payroll from 125 to 300 when
it gets to the manufacturing phase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
