<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-PROFIT-BOS &LR;      06-18 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-PROFIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS PONDER CONVICTED AU PAIR'S RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Louise Woodward, convicted in the killing of
eight-month-old Matthew Eappen, likely is free to cash in on her
notoriety, but the Eappen family also has a good legal basis to
seize any money their former au pair might get for telling her
story, attorneys said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Woodward traveled home to England Wednesday, US District
Court Judge William G. Young issued a temporary order requiring
her, and those who represent her, to notify the court and Eappen
family attorneys if she signs a contract to earn money from her
story. Young also ordered Woodward not to spend any money she might
get under any such arrangement with a United States firm for at
least 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Young said he would review First Amendment law and also the
only case in Massachusetts where the issue of a criminal profiting
from a crime was addressed by the Supreme Judicial Court. The SJC
ruled that Katherine A. Power, who admitted participating in a bank
robbery and the murder of a Boston police officer in 1970, was
properly banned by a judge from making money from her crime. The
judge made the ban a condition of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Most people interviewed in downtown Boston Wednesday said they
wouldn't support a book on the trial, and that Woodward shouldn't
make money from one. But Eliza N. Coady of Allston said she thinks
it would receive wide support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tabloid story,'' the 18-year-old office assistant said.
``It's like slowing down to see a car accident ... It's one of
those things where a lot of people will say that they won't read
it, but when it comes out, it's a best-seller.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys who specialize in First Amendment law split on whether
Woodward can successfully argue that Young's order is a violation
of her constitutional rights, which are protected in American
courts.
</P>
<P>
   John ``Ike'' Williams, of Palmer&AMP;Dodge, said that the last time
the US Supreme Court looked at the issue, it ruled that a New York
State law, known as the ``Son of Sam'' law, was unconstitutional.
The 1991 decision made it clear that a criminal cannot
automatically be barred from profiting by telling his or her story,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Power case, the SJC ruled that she could be kept from
profiting as a condition of her probation after she pleaded guilty
to manslaughter in the death of Officer Walter Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Young's order ``tiptoed'' between those two legal standards,
said Williams, who added that he believed the First Amendment could
derail any legal limitation on Woodward's financial benefit from
her notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has a real chilling effect on speech,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jon Albano, a First Amendment lawyer with Bingham,
Dana&AMP;Gould who also represents the Globe, said that his reading of
the same cases leads him to a different conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Eappens are only seeking money Woodward would earn
from signing a contract, they are not blocking her from exercising
her First Amendment right to free speech, he said. Moreover, since
the Eappens have filed a wrongful-death lawsuit, courts routinely
put financial strings on defendants to ensure any judgment is
eventually paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you happen to be an author, and they happen to want to
collect a debt from money you've made from your writing, then I
really don't see that raising any First Amendment concern,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Son of Sam'' law was dangerously overbroad and banned all
criminals from profiting, Albano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say that anybody convicted of a crime can't write books
and make money from their experiences, then people like Martin
Luther King, who gets convicted of civil disobedience, is subject
to that statute,'' Albano said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Woodward flew back to England Wednesday, attorneys said
the wrongful-death suit could follow in her wake. They also said
that while she does not have to be in federal court on Oct. 1, when
the trial is now scheduled to begin, from a legal strategy
standpoint, it would wise for her to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys say jurors in the civil case might look upon her
absence negatively, as if she doesn't care about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Michael S. Greco, a Boston attorney with Hill and Barlow, said
nations extend ``comity'' to each other under which a judgment from
one country can be enforced in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are vast differences among foreign countries,'' Greco
said, ``but England is pretty much easier because of the same
Anglo-American legal tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ``it's not a slam dunk'' that the Eappens
would be able to convince an English court to back up any judgment
if a jury concludes they deserve money in their wrongful-death
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court there could again look at the facts leading up to
the entry of a judgment and could find ways to refuse to honor the
judgment on some basis,'' Greco said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
