<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5176 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERKINS-HOUSE-2TAKES-     06-18 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKINS-HOUSE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAINE, THE PERKINS HOUSE SMILES AT RESTORATION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   YORK, Maine _ Elizabeth Perkins knew her own mind, and because
she had ample funds, she could have her own way. By the time she
died &UR;  &LR; in 1952 at the age of 83, she was a certifiable grande dame
and all-around local character. She thought nothing of driving her
old Buick &UR;  &LR; across your field if that was the shortest way home.
Mention her name in York and people would collapse in anger or
glee.
</P>
<P>
   Without Perkins, &UR;  &LR; the village called Old York would look
considerably different. She and her family had become summer people
here in 1898, just as the historic preservation movement was
getting under way. Anybody could save a lovely old house or church
and many did; and coastal Maine is famous for its stately homes.
But the always contrary Elizabeth Bishop Perkins (together with her
mother, Mary Sowles Perkins) chose to befriend sad old buildings
that were destined for certain demolition in the name of progress.
They saved the schoolhouse and a tavern. On a hunch, they saved a
shed, its origins all but lost to history. This proved to be the
village jail, and this Old Gaol is, moreover, the oldest surviving
British Colonial public building in America. Thanks to the
Perkinses, Old York is rich in aspects of village life that go
beyond the beautiful and the good.
</P>
<P>
   So it should come as no surprise that the certifiably ancient
and historic Perkins residence is not all that it appears. True, it
sits on land settled in 1631 and the oldest part of the house may
date from 1686. But enter the house and it's pure 1952. Room after
room is decorated in the oft-despised ``American Colonial Revival''
style. Even if she had lived to know historically correct
restoration, it's by no means certain Elizabeth Perkins would have
wanted to live with it. This was a woman who so loved dotted Swiss
curtains with ball fringe that every window had them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sleuthing out curtains
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty pairs of curtains!'' says an amused Tom Johnson. As
curator of collections for the Old York Historical Society, it was
his job to help with the restoration of Elizabeth Perkins's old
home. Like everybody else, he just assumed he could buy dotted
Swiss at the local Joanne Fabrics. Not so. After many a phone call
to fabric shops, he happened on the William Ginsberg Co., a
manufacturer of fabric trim in New York City. ``They sleuthed it
out for us and located absolutely the last dotted Swiss of that
type in upstate New York and we bought the lot.'' Stashed away in a
Long Island warehouse was the last of the small elegant ball fringe
of Perkins's day. Historic restoration is like that, says Johnson.
``What you think are the easiest things are complicated, and the
complicated things are a snap.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to restore the Perkins house was not easily made.
Other properties maintained by the society are considered more
important historically, among them the John Hancock Warehouse and
Jefferds' Tavern. With more than 30 period rooms and galleries,
some contents dating from 1719, the society did not lack for
outstanding examples of regional furniture, ceramics, glassware,
and paintings. Not just students of Colonial upholstery seek out
the Bulman bed hangings made in York in the 1740s.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colonial restoration
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That the Elizabeth Perkins House was something of an
embarrassment can be inferred from the society's decision to
restore it in 1954, two years after her death. Scholars were
beginning to revisit so-called period rooms and toss out all those
inventive ``decorator touches'' that made house museums look
livable _ and worth emulating at home. You can't blame Old York.
Based on what was then known, the 1954 restoration intended to make
the Elizabeth Perkins house more authentically Colonial. And so in
the name of history, the Perkins interiors got a new paint job,
with colors of the Williamsburg persuasion. The rich deep-chocolate
woodwork in her maple sitting room disappeared under a corn yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Williamsburg wasn't the real Elizabeth Perkins and it wasn't
what her house represents in the history of American decorative
art. ``American Colonial Revival'' has its own pedigree. Some
people think of Colonial revival as a village within the Arts &AMP;
Crafts movement and, like it, a reaction to Industrial Age mass
production. Maybe so, but Perkins was not a purist. Funky could be
her middle name. Take the centerpiece on the dining-room table.
Antiques lovers will recognize the big dish as a Chinese Export
blue and white charger. But the four white china swans guarding it?
``Irish Beleek,'' says curator Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
