<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL REBALANCING GOOD FOR SOME, BAD FOR OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of smaller companies riding the dizzying ups and downs
of this year's stock market are about the run into another
complication.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small and midsize stocks is about to
go through its annual ``reconstitution,'' throwing out some
companies and adding others to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for Massachusetts companies like investment
firm Affiliated Managers Group in Boston and upholstry fabric
manufacturer Quaker Fabric Corp. of Fall River that are probably
joining. It's a headache for companies like software company Inso
Corp. of Boston or sneaker-maker Converse Inc. of North Reading
that are likely to fall off the list.
</P>
<P>
   Money managers invest tens of billions of dollars in small
stocks, indexed to the Russell benchmark, just as others invest in
larger stocks to match the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index. They will
buy or sell thousands of small-company shares based on changes in
the index.
</P>
<P>
   The same annual reconstitution is also taking place in the
Russell 1000 index, a grouping of the market's 1,000 largest
companies. The Russell 2000 tracks the next 2,000 companies by
size, and the two lists combined make up a third index known as the
Russell 3000.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Russell Co., the company that manages the indexes,
announced the preliminary list of stocks that would be added or
subtracted from the combined Russell 3000. That list of
adjustments, revealed last Friday, is subject to modest change and
doesn't provide information about the smaller Russell 1000 or
Russell 2000 indexes.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts estimate nearly 500 stocks will be added to
the Russell 2000 and more than 300 will be deleted in this year's
rebalancing. There are more additions than deletions because some
stocks disappear from the index in the course of a year due to
mergers and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Investment managers are much more interested in those stocks
than changes in the big-stock Russell 1000. The smaller stocks tend
to be much less liquid, and big swings in investor interest will
have more dramatic effects on prices, moving up or down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more money following the Russell 2000 in proportion to
their market capitalization,'' said Arlene Rockefeller, a principal
at State Street Global Advisors, which manages more than $15
billion in various Russell indexes.
</P>
<P>
   A study by ITG Research found that stocks added to the Russell
2000 outperformed those eliminated from the index by 18 percent
during a two-month period around the time of last year's index
rebalancing. It was the fourth straight year ITG Reserach had
measured the effect, which has become more pronounced each year.
The studies give all the stocks equal weighting and the performance
gap usually evens out over time.
</P>
<P>
   But money managers following the index can't wait for
small-stock prices to settle down over a period of months, so they
begin to buy and sell now based on Russell's list of preliminary
changes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Rockefeller and others said, prices of those stocks
will move up or down between now and June 30, when final Russell
index lists will be decided.
</P>
<P>
   A warning to investors looking to make a quick score buying
expected Russell additions now or shorting stocks to be elminated:
it's a dangerous game.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price advances and declines are uneven and don't
happen in every instance, said Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to look at the entire group of stocks and it
continues all the way through June,'' she said. ``You wouldn't see
the full impact yet, but prices have already started to move.''
</P>
<P>
   We sampled a handful of local stocks and could not find any
clear pattern. Brookline Bancorp., which is expected to be added to
the Russell 2000, finished at 15 1/2 Wednesday, slightly lower than
its price before the preliminary good news was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Videoserver Inc. of Burlington, a tentative deletion
from the Russell list, has actually gained a sliver of value since
the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Maybe research scientist Changnian Liu should have stayed in the
lab.
</P>
<P>
   The US Securities and Exchange Commission charged Liu with
insider trading Wednesday, allegations stemming from the 1996
purchase of stock in his former employer, Immunogen Inc. of
Norwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Liu was a lead author of a paper documenting a new Immunogen
drug's ability to eradicate human colon tumors grown in mice, work
that was published in The Proceedings of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Liu bought 30,000 shares of Immunogen a week before the
scheduled appearance of the article. Publication sent Immunogen
stock soaring by 65 percent
</P>
<P>
   Liu has agreed to disgorge $41,700 of trading profits, a civil
penalty of $41,700, and interest payments of $6,653, the SEC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
