<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LILY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTANY PROFESSOR, DAY LILY AN ITEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A funny thing happened to James Brennan on his career path: A
passing research acquaintance blossomed into full romance.
</P>
<P>
   Not his wife, with whom he raised seven children, leading to 17
grandchildren, but day lilies.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, a professor of botany at Bridgewater (Mass.) State
College, over the course of a long career has gone from looking at
day lilies as a convenient research subject to serving as president
of the American Hemerocallis Society. His seduction by the
ubiquitous plant _ I grow it, you grow it, we all grow it _
redefined his career and his life, and next, with Brennan
contemplating retiring in December 1999, day lilies may light his
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, four years out of graduate school at Virginia Tech and
the University of Maryland, from which he received a doctorate in
plant morphology, Brennan was looking for a research interest. He
had chosen to teach at Bridgewater State College because it was
about to construct a new science building and intended to stock it
with research equipment.
</P>
<P>
   At an institute in Tennessee that summer, Brennan found that
interest on a side trip to a botanic garden that was holding a day
lily exhibition. ``I was intrigued by the form and color of these
members of the lily family, and I knew at first glance that there
was great potential for this plant as the subject of a research
program,'' he wrote in the Bridgewater Review last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are easily propagated, Hemerocallis species would
be perfect for research. Brennan bought his first three plants that
summer; he still has them, somewhere. But his research plans did
not work out. Budget cuts meant Bridgewater State would not get the
X-ray unit he counted on, and he switched to research with members
of the genus Tradescantia. (Many of these are houseplants, and
outdoors, spiderwort, T. virginiana, is a wonderful plant; my rubra
cultivar is now in bloom under an ornamental plum.)
</P>
<P>
   Brennan explored the development of plant cell shapes, aided
largely by the college's purchase of an electron microscope,
treating tiny hairs on Tradescantia with various chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years passed. Then his wife introduced him to Tranquil
Lake Nursery in Rehoboth. This is an outstanding source of day
lilies. ``My wife started going over there, and I went a few times
and got bitten by the day lily bug,'' he told me recently.
</P>
<P>
   He switched his research to day lily structures, particularly
those involving color. Chloroplasts inside interior cells were
loaded with fat-soluble anthocyanins providing yellow and orange
colors. Cells nearer the surface contained water-soluble red,
lavender, and purple pigments.
</P>
<P>
   He also began breeding.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan was captivated by the shapes and colors and forms of
these plants (each flower really does bloom for but a day). ``Man,
there's everything out there except blue, but I gave up trying to
hybridize for blue,'' he said. He doubts there will ever be a blue
day lily.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's been breeding for browns. He is intrigued by
chocolate brown flowers. His love of research and love of day
lilies combined, and in the pursuit of brown flowers, he discovered
something unexpected: brown, crystalline globs inside the surface
cells of brown petals. Holding concentrated purple pigments, these
have been the subject of much research by Brennan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Brennan received membership in the American
Hemerocallis Society as a birthday present. His involvement has
grown steadily. Now, as president, he finds himself strapped for
time, between research, teaching, growing and breeding day lilies,
and the demands of the society.
</P>
<P>
   He recently returned from the group's annual convention in
Louisiana. He was enthused, which seems to be Brennan's normal
state, about the plants he saw down South. ``We grow what are
called dormants here, and they grow evergreens, and here they lose
their leaves.'' Brennan has a microclimate in his yard that allows
him to grow some semi-evergreen day lilies.
</P>
<P>
   The society, which functions as the international naming
authority for day lilies, has 11,000 members. ``There's everyone
from little old lady gardeners to big hybridizers to PhDs,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps Brennan occupied. There are 15 regions. In July, he
goes to the regional meeting on Long Island. Aug. 29 brings the
annual plant sale at the University of Massachusetts field station
in Waltham, ``and it's a biggie.''
</P>
<P>
   In 2001, the national convention will be held in Newton, and
that will showcase local day lily breeders and marketers. One of
those is Brennan. ``I've registered five or six,'' he said, adding
that ``there's some 40,000 registered cultivars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bee Gee,'' ``Carnival Lady,'' ``Grandma Jean,'' ``Hee Hee''
and ``Sturdy Son'' are Brennan developments being sold by Greene
Acre Sales, a small nursery at owner Steve Green's Sudbury home.
``He's a schoolteacher up there,'' Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan loves the variety and growth in popularity of day
lilies, though he is bothered that some cultivars cost $150. His go
for $7.50 to $25. He jokes about how they are not selling, but they
are beautiful. ``Sturdy Son'' stands 34 inches tall and has dark
ruby red flowers 6 inches in diameter. ``Bee Gee'' is 32 inches
tall with 6-inch flowers in soft pink and light vein lines running
through delicately pinched petals.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan talks dreamily of journeying to Sakhalin Island, a
Russian property near Japan, to view some rare day lilies. He
refers to being at the close of his career, but he brims with
energy for continued research and grows excited at the prospect of
the 2001 convention.
</P>
<P>
   And will that convention show off the culinary delights of day
lilies (they are tasty raw and sautee well)?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Brennan cried. ``That's cannibalism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
