<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-PROFIT-BOS &LR;      06-18 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-PROFIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS PONDER CONVICTED AU PAIR'S RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Louise Woodward, convicted in the killing of
eight-month-old Matthew Eappen, likely is free to cash in on her
notoriety, but the Eappen family also has a good legal basis to
seize any money their former au pair might get for telling her
story, attorneys said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Woodward traveled home to England Wednesday, US District
Court Judge William G. Young issued a temporary order requiring
her, and those who represent her, to notify the court and Eappen
family attorneys if she signs a contract to earn money from her
story. Young also ordered Woodward not to spend any money she might
get under any such arrangement with a United States firm for at
least 12 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Young said he would review First Amendment law and also the
only case in Massachusetts where the issue of a criminal profiting
from a crime was addressed by the Supreme Judicial Court. The SJC
ruled that Katherine A. Power, who admitted participating in a bank
robbery and the murder of a Boston police officer in 1970, was
properly banned by a judge from making money from her crime. The
judge made the ban a condition of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Most people interviewed in downtown Boston Wednesday said they
wouldn't support a book on the trial, and that Woodward shouldn't
make money from one. But Eliza N. Coady of Allston said she thinks
it would receive wide support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tabloid story,'' the 18-year-old office assistant said.
``It's like slowing down to see a car accident ... It's one of
those things where a lot of people will say that they won't read
it, but when it comes out, it's a best-seller.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys who specialize in First Amendment law split on whether
Woodward can successfully argue that Young's order is a violation
of her constitutional rights, which are protected in American
courts.
</P>
<P>
   John ``Ike'' Williams, of Palmer&AMP;Dodge, said that the last time
the US Supreme Court looked at the issue, it ruled that a New York
State law, known as the ``Son of Sam'' law, was unconstitutional.
The 1991 decision made it clear that a criminal cannot
automatically be barred from profiting by telling his or her story,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Power case, the SJC ruled that she could be kept from
profiting as a condition of her probation after she pleaded guilty
to manslaughter in the death of Officer Walter Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Young's order ``tiptoed'' between those two legal standards,
said Williams, who added that he believed the First Amendment could
derail any legal limitation on Woodward's financial benefit from
her notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has a real chilling effect on speech,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jon Albano, a First Amendment lawyer with Bingham,
Dana&AMP;Gould who also represents the Globe, said that his reading of
the same cases leads him to a different conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Eappens are only seeking money Woodward would earn
from signing a contract, they are not blocking her from exercising
her First Amendment right to free speech, he said. Moreover, since
the Eappens have filed a wrongful-death lawsuit, courts routinely
put financial strings on defendants to ensure any judgment is
eventually paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you happen to be an author, and they happen to want to
collect a debt from money you've made from your writing, then I
really don't see that raising any First Amendment concern,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Son of Sam'' law was dangerously overbroad and banned all
criminals from profiting, Albano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you say that anybody convicted of a crime can't write books
and make money from their experiences, then people like Martin
Luther King, who gets convicted of civil disobedience, is subject
to that statute,'' Albano said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Woodward flew back to England Wednesday, attorneys said
the wrongful-death suit could follow in her wake. They also said
that while she does not have to be in federal court on Oct. 1, when
the trial is now scheduled to begin, from a legal strategy
standpoint, it would wise for her to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys say jurors in the civil case might look upon her
absence negatively, as if she doesn't care about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Michael S. Greco, a Boston attorney with Hill and Barlow, said
nations extend ``comity'' to each other under which a judgment from
one country can be enforced in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are vast differences among foreign countries,'' Greco
said, ``but England is pretty much easier because of the same
Anglo-American legal tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ``it's not a slam dunk'' that the Eappens
would be able to convince an English court to back up any judgment
if a jury concludes they deserve money in their wrongful-death
suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court there could again look at the facts leading up to
the entry of a judgment and could find ways to refuse to honor the
judgment on some basis,'' Greco said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SACCO-LOTHROP-BOS &LR;      06-18 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACCO-LOTHROP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACCO, VANZETTI ORDEAL HAUNTS LONGTIME ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Rev. Donald G. Lothrop looked back on a life of 92
years Wednesday, one regret stands out. On Aug. 29, 1927, six days
after Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were electrocuted, a
funeral honoring the pair and decrying the trial that had convicted
them passed through the North End of Boston. And Lothrop was not
among the thousands of mourners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a college kid, I suppose I didn't know any better. But
it would have been right to be there,'' recalled Lothrop, who would
later become the pastor of the Community Church of Boston and an
ardent player in the effort after the fact to find out whether
justice played fair in the trial of the Italian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The procession was to Forest Hills and the cemetery that had
agreed to cremate the remains of controversy, but wasn't bold
enough to bury the ashes. A young man from Lexington wasn't there,
and he has held the grudge against himself for the past 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the passion Donald G. Lothrop still holds, indeed
nurtures, for what many consider the mistrial of Sacco and
Vanzetti, convicted in 1923 for a pair of murders during an armed
robbery. To this day, many defenders claim that the only ``crimes''
committed by Sacco and Vanzetti, whose alibis placed them far from
the robbery, were being immigrants and avowed anarchists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Wednesday, Lothrop drove down from his farm in Alna, Maine,
(``got passed by just about everything except the toll booths'') to
participate in a symposium about the Sacco-Vanzetti trial. Held at
the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, the
symposium was slated to follow a sceening of Court TV's newest
documentary on Sacco and Vanzetti. Other scheduled participants
included former governor Michael S. Dukakis and Judge Peter Agnes,
First Justice of Charlestown District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Sacco and Vanzetti were convicted and executed for the 1920
murders of a paymaster and his guard in Braintree. Citizens from
all walks of life joined in a protest about the way the trial was
handled for the men, who were politically controversial because of
their anarchistic views and support of labor.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help when Judge Webster Thayer was quoted outside the
Dedham courtroom saying, ``Did you see what I did with those
anarchistic bastards the other day?''
</P>
<P>
   Lothrop vaguely recalls the arrests, but as the trial got under
way in the spring of 1923, the young Lothrop, son of a florist, was
preparing to begin college at Tufts, paying his tuition with
earnings from road construction jobs. At Tufts he studied under the
late Clarence Skinner, a theologian and 1920 founder of the
Community Church of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The church, based in Copley Square, still exists, but in its
formative days decades ago it would fill such places as Symphony
Hall with speeches calling for tolerance _ often tolerance for
political causes veering sharply left of center.
</P>
<P>
   When Lothrop served as minister from 1936 to 1973, for example,
he made Globe headlines for opposing the Spanish regime of General
Francisco Franco, and much later, for getting punched by Cuban
exiles for allowing an advocate of Fidel Castro to speak at his
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sometimes isn't easy standing firm for what you believe,''
Lothrop explained Wednesday, seated in a Holiday Inn room which he
almost couldn't enter because of the ``new-fangled entry cards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happened to keys?'' he asked, unpacking belongings
from a battered leather suitcase that had traveled to Poland a
half-century ago with his late wife, Helena.
</P>
<P>
   It was at college under Skinner's tutelage that Lothrop became
aware of a nation polarized by the Sacco and Vanzetti trial. After
the executions, when Lothrop took over the Community Church, he met
one Aldino Felicani, a printer in the North End whom Lothrop paid
to produce weekly church bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   Felicani, he would learn, had led the fund-raising efforts to
defend Sacco and Vanzetti, and would become a frequent speaker at
the weekly Wednesday night church dinners hosted by Lothrop.
</P>
<P>
   Another church member was one Sara Ehrmann, whose husband,
Herbert, attempted, but failed, to get Sacco and Vanzetti a new
trial. Herbert Ehrmann dug up a sales receipt that placed one of
the defendants in Plymouth buying eels at the time of the murders,
Lothrop said. Another member was Tom O'Connor, a reporter who
unearthed evidence indicating that some eyewitness testimony was
withheld from the trial by the prosecution, Lothrop said.
</P>
<P>
   These men would all be frequent speakers at Lothrop's church _
and when they died, the last in the late 1970s, Lothrop gave their
eulogies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, following the electrocutions, Gutzon Borglum, a
sculptor best known for his carvings on Mount Rushmore, created a
bas relief of Sacco and Vanzetti that took 50 years for Boston to
accept. But last August, Mayor Thomas M. Menino announced that the
piece will be installed in a yet-to-be announced location in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture will be cast from an aluminum copy that sits in
the Boston Community Church, according to Carol Adams, a church
spokeswoman. And the fact that the church has a copy of the Borglum
sculpture suitable for reproduction, she added, is thanks to the
Rev. Donald G. Lothrop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; sci-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEED-SURGERY-NYTSF &LR;      06-18 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEED-SURGERY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT GENE ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -------------------- FREE ART! --------------------
 &HT;    FOUR COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at no extra charge to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' national news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JOSIE GLAUSIUSZ  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contemplating world hunger from the vantage point of a
well-laden breakfast table is certainly comfortable, if odd.
</P>
<P>
   One morning last January, executives of Iowa-based Pioneer
Hi-Bred International, the ``world's largest developer, producer
and marketer of genetically improved seed,'' gathered at a cafe in
downtown Manhattan for a discussion about global food security.
</P>
<P>
   The three officials and a group of journalists ate pancakes and
muffins as Pioneer's chairman and CEO, Chuck Johnson, outlined his
vision of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business we're in is ensuring that the world has the
capacity to have the food it needs to survive,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   That future capacity, he is convinced, can come only from the
crops that companies such as Pioneer are producing: high-yield,
insect-resistant breeds of corn, soybeans, sorghum and sunflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer makes some of its seeds conventionally, by creating
hybrids. Back in the 1920s, though, the conventional was radical,
and the typical farmer looked upon the newfangled seeds, in
Johnson's words, as ``witchcraft and Satanism _ until he got his
first taste of the yield.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, however, Pioneer has been offering
genetically engineered seeds, which have genes spliced into their
chromosomes that make them more resistant to insects and weed
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson told the journalists about herbicide-resistant soybeans
and a variety of corn that produces a toxin normally made by a
bacterium known as Bacillus thuringiensis, or Bt.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he said, a million acres of the Bt corn were planted
in the Midwest, with an increased yield of 10 percent to 15
percent, thanks to the way the Bt toxin discourages corn-eating
insects.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer's vice president for marketing, Mary McBride, then
chimed in, claiming that these ``transgenic'' crops have the power
to increase food production in the developing world with minimal
environmental impact.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer, as McBride put it, is creating ``virtual acres.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of transgenic crops claim that ecological and
evolutionary forces could turn these crops into disasters. Perhaps
the plants will prove so robust that they will grow aggressively,
like weeds, and invade other environments _ including a neighboring
farmer's fields.
</P>
<P>
   Virus-resistance genes could escape into weeds and make them so
hardy they'd outcompete endangered plants in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Antibiotic-resistance genes (which botanists insert into
transgenic crops as supposedly harmless markers) might escape into
soil bacteria and from there into those that infect humans.
</P>
<P>
   Crops engineered to carry Bt-toxin genes might trigger the
evolution of ever adaptive Bt-resistant bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Is all this worry just more witchcraft and Satanism? The only
way to know how seriously to take such doomsday scenarios is to run
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have only begun to do this work, setting up
experiments to see how readily transgenic genes and proteins can
escape the crops they were meant to help. The results thus far are
proving that the doomsday scenarios are not pure fiction.
</P>
<P>
   But the researchers are split over whether the results should be
cause for anxiety. Much of the concern over transgenic crops stems
from the promiscuous sexual habits of plants.
</P>
<P>
   Not only can pollen from one breed of plant fertilize another,
but different species can sometimes mate and produce hybrids that
can reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   Genes in one population of plants (crops, for example) can thus
seep into another population (neighboring weeds).
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s geneticist Norman Ellstrand at the University
of California at Riverside began warning of the dangers of this
genetic escape.
</P>
<P>
   One could, for example, imagine an herbicide-resistance gene
getting into weeds and making superweeds that could take over a
field.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this possibility hinged on how likely it was for crops and
weeds to hybridize, and for the transgenic genes to establish
themselves in the wild population.
</P>
<P>
   Ellstrand decided therefore to measure the likelihood, and in
1996 he reported that domesticated sorghum, Sorghum bicolor, could
readily form hybrids with a weed called Johnsongrass, Sorghum
halepense.
</P>
<P>
   (Domesticated crops are often surrounded by their close weedy
relatives, since both flourish under the same conditions.)
</P>
<P>
   Using harmless gene markers rather than actual transgenes,
Ellstrand found that wind-carried pollen could create hybrid seeds
over 300 feet away from the original crop.
</P>
<P>
   These hybrids produced pollen and seeds as viable as the
johnsongrass, meaning that they could spread just as aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   More recent experiments with actual transgenic crops also show
that inserted genes can move between species.
</P>
<P>
   Plant geneticist Rikke Bagger Jorgensen of Denmark's Riso
National Laboratory in Roskilde studied the yellow-flowered crop
called oilseed rape, known in the United States as canola and in
Latin as Brassica napus. Oilseed rape is a cultivated cross between
a weed called wild mustard, or Brassica campestris, and Brassica
oleracea, the cabbage plant.
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen planted a version of oilseed rape engineered to
survive a weed killer called Basta alongside its wild ancestor (and
weedy neighbor) B. campestris.
</P>
<P>
   Fertile hybrids easily formed, and when jorgensen sowed the
hybrids together with the original weed, a second generation of
seeds was produced. These seeds grew to adulthood and turned out to
be impervious to Basta as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jorgensen returned to her fields the following spring and
discovered that this second generation had produced offspring of
their own, which continued to be herbicide resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite these results, Jorgensen and others remain sanguine
about the prospects of transgenic crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can put in genes that give the plant itself a better
resistance, for instance, to fungal pathogens or to insect pests,
then you can minimize your use of pesticides, and that would be
beneficial to the environment,'' Jorgensen says. And she believes
that as long as transgenic oilseed rape is carefully managed, it
can be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spray very early, before the campestris flowers, you
minimize its potential to hybridize,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be unwise to grow Basta-resistant oilseed rape
alongside a crop resistant to a different herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then what you'll have is Brassica campestris plants with
multiresistance in very few generations,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   A weed with only one herbicide-resistance gene would, however,
still be manageable. As one researcher said, you can always destroy
the plants with another herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of herbicide-resistant crops creating the need for
spraying still more herbicides doesn't fit well with the
environmentally friendly image offered by companies like Pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some critics think that biotech corporations are actually
comfortable with that prospect because they can make transgenic
crops as well as herbicides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biotech companies, since they make the herbicides, don't
see it as a big problem, because it forces them to make a new
herbicide,'' says botanist Hugh Wilson of Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has been studying transgenic gene flow and its possible
effects not on the struggle between weeds and crops but between
weeds and rare or fragile wild plant species.
</P>
<P>
   Herbicide resistance isn't so much of a problem in this regard,
since weed killers are found only on farms. Of far more pressing
concern to him is the possibility that genes for resistance to
insects, viruses and fungi can be just as important in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   It's conceivable that a spread of genes from transgenic crops
into wild plants could allow them to outcompete other species.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   One possible way to contain the threat of transgene escape might
be to bar certain genetically engineered crops when weedy relatives
already exist in a given place.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no weeds related to maize in Europe,'' says French
cytogeneticist Anne-Marie Chevre of the national Institute of
Agronomic Research at Le Rheu. ``But we have a lot of wild species
more or less related to oilseed rape in the field everywhere.''
Therefore France has permitted transgenic corn to be grown on its
soil.
</P>
<P>
   The United States could similarly allow transgenic maize
soybeans, and potatoes to be farmed, since they have no wild
relatives with which they are sexually compatible here. On the
other hand, squashes and sunflowers do.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways that this policy might go wrong, however. A
desperate farmer might ignore the law and plant a transgenic crop
that can breed with local weeds.
</P>
<P>
   And crop-to-weed gene exchanges are only one kind of change that
transgenic crops can bring. Researchers have been developing a
transgenic potato, for example, that can fight off the aphids that
feed on it. The new potato produces a protein called lectin that
ruins the aphids' digestion.
</P>
<P>
   Greenhouse tests have shown that this transgenic potato can
reduce populations of the peach-potato aphid by half. That's
impressive but not quite good enough to allow the potatoes to
survive on their own. To fully protect their crop, farmers would
need to introduce aphid-devouring ladybugs.
</P>
<P>
   But as entomologist Nick Birch of the Scottish Crop Research
Institute in Dundee has shown, the lectin in the potato makes
ladybugs ill: After eating transgenic potato-glutted aphids,
ladybugs produce far fewer offspring and live much shorter lives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even though he has shown how transgenic crops can have
harmful effects that spread through a food chain, Birch doesn't
think his results are cause for alarm. If ladybugs can also find
aphids in the wild that are unaffected by transgenic potatoes, the
plant's harmful effects will be diluted.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Birch thinks that with careful tests of their
potential effects, transgenic crops can prove safe and useful in
reducing our dependence on pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows _ maybe those witchcraft and Satanism theories are
indeed wrong ...
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Josie Glausiusz is an associate editor at Discover
magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEED-SURGERY-NYTSF &LR;      06-18 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEED-SURGERY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT GENE ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine _ the rate is not prohibitive _ contact one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
