<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEEKH-KABOBS-HNS &LR;      06-18 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEEKH-KABOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY SEEKH KABOBS FOR A SOUTH ASIAN TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Seekh kabobs, made with a mix of ground beef and
spices, and nan, a flat bread, are common Pakistani dishes. The
spices are available at Indian and Pakistani stores.
</P>
<P>
   Here are recipes, courtesy of Suraiya and Sabir Siddiqui's
Siddiqui Kitchen, which caters mainly to the Pakistani and Indian
communities in the Albany area:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEEKH KABOBS
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 12 to 15 kabobs, serves six to eight)
</P>
<P>
   Two pounds lean ground beef
</P>
<P>
   Two tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   One medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   One tablespoon, garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   One tablespoon fresh ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   One tablespoon crushed, unripened papaya or meat tenderizer
</P>
<P>
   One-half bunch chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Two green peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup gram flour (chickpea flour)
</P>
<P>
   One tablespoon cumin powder
</P>
<P>
   One tablespoon poppy seeds
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon garam masala (allspice)
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Two tablespoons plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon mace powder
</P>
<P>
   One teaspoon nutmeg powder
</P>
<P>
   In a frying pan, roast the gram flour over low heat for about
three to five minutes, or until you can smell the flour's aroma.
Similarly, roast the cumin powder.
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the ground beef and remaining
ingredients and mix well with your hands. Cover and refrigerate for
three to 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 or preheat the grill. Brush skewers with
oil. Shape ground beef mixture into small balls, then spread evenly
on the skewers to form kabobs. Bake or grill for about 10 to 15
minutes, lightly brushing with oil every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NAN
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 15, serving 10 to 12 people)
</P>
<P>
   One packet of yeast
</P>
<P>
   One cup unbleached, all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Two and one-half pounds unbleached, all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup whole milk
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup vegetable shortening, melted
</P>
<P>
   Two eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarter cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   Two or three crushed green cardamom pods
</P>
<P>
   Two drops kewra essence
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half cup warm water
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, dilute the rest with the warm water. Mix in one cup
of flour until a paste forms. Cover and store overnight at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, add the remaining ingredients, except the flour,
into the paste and mix with an electric mixer. Slowly sift in the
flour and mix.
</P>
<P>
   Place the dough onto a working surface and knead for about 10
minutes or until smooth. If the dough appears tough, add a little
milk to maintain a soft consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Place dough in a large bowl, cover and let stand for three hours
until dough rises. Preheat the oven to 500. Once the dough has
doubled in size, knead it again.
</P>
<P>
   Shape dough into small balls, about the size of your palm,
keeping the dough covered while you work to prevent it from drying.
Roll each ball out to about 6 to 8 inches in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Place nan on a greased baking sheet and pierce, multiple times,
with a fork. Bake about five to seven minutes on the top rack.
Spread unsalted butter on each side of nan as you take each from
the oven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
