<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIND OF BLAH? TRY SOME BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is it: The end of another school year.
</P>
<P>
   On this dreaded occasion, parents annually go crazy with the
anticipation of filling the hours of each day between now and
September when relief comes up the road in the form of a yellow
bus. The bellowing begins immediately, with kids constantly
screaming, ``I'm bored. There's nothing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To assist in dealing with these little ... (I'm sorry. I
apologize for the momentary brain-lock that caused me to start
typing the truth) who sit around and eat so much junk they will
resemble Monica Lewinsky by July 4, allow me to present a novel
idea: No pun intended, but how about buying a bunch of books and
have your kids read, say, two per month, and then, perhaps, pay
them to provide you with an oral or written report.
</P>
<P>
   I mean it beats buying a gun and having them clip half the kids
they go to camp with, doesn't it? Plus, they might actually enjoy
it _ reading, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   You might start with ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' by Harper Lee.
This is a story that stands up to time.
</P>
<P>
   Add ``The Big Sleep,'' by Raymond Chandler to the list. It's a
detective tale set years ago, yet it holds up well. No swears. No
sex.
</P>
<P>
   And you cannot go wrong with ``The Grapes of Wrath,'' by John
Steinbeck. One of America's all-time great novels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoeless Joe'' and ``The Thrill of Grass,'' both by W. P.
Kinsella, ``The Great Escape,'' by Paul Brickhill, ``A Night to
Remember,'' by Walter Lord and ``The Golden Compass,'' by Philip
Pullman and you'll actually have enough time as parents to sit down
and read something yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Freedomland,'' by Richard Price. This is positively one
of the best books of the decade, never mind the year. It is an
incredible trip to places few ever see; existence in a housing
project where expectations never exceed the boundaries of a sunset,
where a catastrophic lie takes on a life all its own and comes to
define a whole culture invisible to so many outside the brick
buildings where hope is a bad dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to Hunt,'' by Stephen Hunter. The man can tell a story.
He's done it before with ``Black Light'' and ``Point of Impact''
and he's done it again here with a book that will give you a
sunburn because you won't leave the beach until the very last page.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Monk Swimming,'' by Malachy McCourt. He's Frank's brother,
part of ``Angela's Ashes,'' and he's brought us his own
recollections but you might want to give Malachy's work a good
leaving alone unless you're willing to have others gawk at you as
you laugh out loud at the world he offers up as well as the life he
has lived, loaded down with fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' by Joe Connelly. It is amazing that a
guy who drove an ambulance for a living can write as well as
Connelly. He could make an accident report read like a song. This
is a terrific piece of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Children,'' by David Halberstam. Perhaps the finest
reporter in the country, Halberstam takes you on a trip back to the
origins of the civil rights movement and re-introduces readers to
the true best and brightest among us: the children who changed a
whole culture, an entire nation, our politics and the life we lead
today with the simple steps forward taken when much of society cast
a blind eye on a vicious inequity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the City,'' by Buzz Bissinger. There has never
been a better portrait of how a big city _ Philadelphia _ functions
and how one mayor _ Ed Rendell _ operates to push, pull and prod
the cement of bureaucracy as well as the souls of individual
citizens toward a better place. This is actually more of a novel
than it is current history, filled with insight and anecdotes that
make you feel good about politics and people, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arkansas Mischief,'' by Curtis Wilkie. This is Jim McDougal's
amazing story about the guy who sits this morning in the White
House and when you read it all you can think is: Bill Clinton is
actually Joey Buttafucco with a Yale diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Official Negligence,'' by Lou Cannon. Don't buy this book if
you think the LAPD was entirely at fault for the beating of Rodney
King. Cannon presents the truth and it is not a pretty picture for
those with pre-set minds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for fun, go get these paperbacks: ``Reading in the Dark,''
by Seamus Deane, a novel about Ireland. ``An Albany Trio,'' by the
great William Kennedy. ``Wait Till Next Year,'' by Doris Kearns
Goodwin. ``The Congressman Who Loved Flaubert,'' by Ward Just.
``Winter's Tale,'' by Mark Helprin. ``Compulsion,'' by Myer Levin
and ``Nobody's Angel,'' by Tom McGuane.
</P>
<P>
   Call me Labor Day. Let me know how things worked out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
