<HEADLINE>
TEENS UPDATE `ADOLESE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody says awesome any more _ except for, like, 'rents and
young'uns. What used to be awesome back in the day is now phat.
Nobody gets stoned on pot, either. They get lit on ism. Then they
hook up with a playah who sweats them and maybe they end up hittin'
it or whatever. If they can't get nice, they say later and they're
Audi 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What(eds.: cq) up? Just current ``adolese'' as spoken by
teenagers in and around Boston. Dawgs, benjamins, hoopdee, gank,
deeze are all part of what fictional English dialectician Henry
Higgins called ``the new small talk.'' It's what enables
16-year-olds to communicate _ and to confound their elders.
</P>
<P>
   Hereupon, a lexicon of what teenagers are saying 24/7 (eds.:
cq), gleaned from high-school cafeterias and corridors. It's all
good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ah-ight  &LR; (or:  &UR; iiiiigh... &LR; ): All right. if:  &UR; Yeah, ah-ight &LR;  (with
rolling eyes): Hell, no.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; all about that &LR; : to favor. ``Third Eye Blind? Yeah, I'm all
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; anyway &LR; : (with dismissive wave of the hand): No more on this
subject. also:  &UR; yeah, bye
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; back in the day: &LR;  prior to 1995 or whenever. also:  &UR; old school
</P>
<P>
   beats &LR; : music. ``What beats you got?'' &UR;  &LR; also:  &UR; tunes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; benjamins &LR; : dollars. also:  &UR; change &LR; ,  &UR; chedda &LR; ,  &UR; ducats, flow,
loot &LR; . ``It's all about the benjamins, yo.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; bitch out &LR; : yell at. also: &UR; scorch
</P>
