<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PEOPLE SPEAK, WITH GOOD IDEAS AND PIZAZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People are wonderful. People are funny. Some people are
critical, usually in a friendly manner. People are helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Why this rhapsody about people? Because the people referred to
are readers who respond to the handyman's column that pontificates
about all things bright and beautiful around the house.
</P>
<P>
   We recently wrote about new products that manufacturers send in
the hopes of some free publicity.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the free publicity (as if they need it!) goes to
those readers who respond to the handyman with their own ideas.
They are very helpful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Driveway sealing
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with driveway sealers. The handyman wrote recently
that driveway sealing was mostly cosmetic, and that you can't make
a silk purse out of a sow's ear.
</P>
<P>
   One brickbat came in by return mail.
</P>
<P>
   George E. Mariani Jr., executive vice president of the E.A.
Mariani Asphalt Co. of Tampa, Fla., begged to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of over simplification, asphalt pavements lose
their strengh and flexibility as the asphalt binder (the glue that
holds the rock together) ages. The aging process accelerates in the
presence of sunlight and moisture. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Proper application of maintenance techniques (sealing) can
extend the service life of the pavement by at least 50 percent and
typically much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Good point. I will concede the point that sealing is good in
southern climates, where the sunlight and moisture are more intense
than in northern climes, and I appreciate the observations. I will
also observe that Mariani sells asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Another letter on sealing, but this one is not a brickbat:
Nicholas Ratti Jr. of Bristol, R.I. did some research:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sealing may extend life. The range of many `promises' I
received is 25 to 33 percent. I've personally received no promise
of double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise is always stated to be contingent on the sealer
being reapplied no less often than every three years, and this
routine must begin before the pavement is one year old, or any
promise is void.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost is about 15 percent of the cost of repaving. If done
every three years, it adds 5 percent to the cost of pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do the math yourself to see that it probably is not
cost effective. ... My unsealed driveway is 22 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes a ball game!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; More about mildew &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mildew is old hat to many people, but one reader had a problem
of some green stuff, like dusty green spots, that appeared on his
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Jack Forbes of Wakefield: ``It sounds similar to something
I had. A trip to the libary suggested this: Mildew can also occur
in a green and _ rarely _ a reddish hue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dealt with the problem with a one-to-three bleach-to-water
mixture, plus more ventilation, and the problem has not returned in
a good five years.
</P>
<P>
   Wrote Mike Davis of Roslindale, Mass.: ``I suggest it is mold,
as on bread. Source: probably shoes brought it in. A mild bleach
solution brushed on might stop it. Try it in the closet first so
not to fade the rug.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Warped doors
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When a reader asked how to straighten out warped French doors,
she mentioned that the makers of the doors, the Atrium Door Co.,
had gone out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, wrote Joel Kessel of Lynn (Mass.) Lumber. ``We are the
Boston supplier for Atrium. We stock screens, track, weatherstrip,
and hardware for this brand. We can also get old style panels.''
</P>
<P>
   The handyman should have known that Lynn Lumber is one of the
last bastions of the super lumber store that carry a vast inventory
of unusual things.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Galloping windows
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reader told the handyman that when he replaced the ropes in
his weight-balanced window, using the original weights, everything
worked except that the bottom sash dropped down after it was
raised. What's wrong, he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman offered the opinion that maybe the paint on the
sash was sanded and scraped off, making the sash looser in its
grooves. The solution was to take off the side stops and reinstall
them tighter against the bottom sash, so the friction would help
keep the sash up where it belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, wrote Donald Michaud of Salem, Mass., who suggested
that the bottom sash weighs more than the weights, and is therefore
not counterbalanced.
</P>
<P>
   But why, he asked, offering these reasons: The bottom sash may
have had the glass replaced with heavier glass. The bottom sash may
have an overload of paint. The weights might have been too light in
the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   One solution is to buy or get heavier weights, said Michaud.
</P>
<P>
   Another, Michaud offered, is to shorten the sash cords. They may
be too long, and when the sash is up, the weights hit bottom,
unable to hold up the sash.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Hand nailing roofing shingles
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a brickbat about the handyman's suggestion to hand nail
roofing shingles instead of using staples or a power nail gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found your ignorance in this matter overwhelming,'' wrote
Gary Cassiday of Danville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Cassiday wrote that air nailers (power nail guns) do have
advantages, and can be used without failures in roofing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now because of your ignorance in this matter all roofers will
have to defend the use of air nailers. I am sure in the future
roofers will be asked about this article and we will be criticized
because of your stupidity. Maybe you should transfer to the cooking
section because you don't know (expletive deleted) about roofing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this letter won't be published because you would have
to admit being wrong. However, it is your responsibility to tell
your readers that the staples are a cheap way out for the roofer
but that the nail coils (power nail guns) are just as good if not
better than hand nailing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee whiz, Mr. Cassiday, it was an opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
