<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SUCCEED AS A STEPFATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When psychologist Larry Ganong's stepson came home from college
one vacation, he left a note in the kitchen: ``Mom and Larry, back
at 10.'' As short as the note was, Ganong got stuck on the first
three words. He had been Stuart's stepfather for eight years. This
was the first time a note included him.
</P>
<P>
   The story drives home a dramatic but discouraging fact for
stepfathers: It can take a long time for children to accept you.
</P>
<P>
   How attachments do or don't develop depends a lot on what
happens when you first move in. Even though children may like you,
indeed perhaps because they do, assume you have to start over once
you live on their turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a tremendous loss for them. Access to their
mother is changed,'' says psychololgist Emily Visher, cofounder of
the Stepfamily Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling their mother has been ``stolen'' (one 8-year-old's word)
makes children jealous and resentful. Feeling their father's place
is being usurped makes them feel guilty: ``If I like this man, then
I'm being disloyal to my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinical psychologist Sam Osherson tells stepfathers not to see
a child's anger as a sign of failure. ``They have to be angry at
you in order to grieve what they have lost, which is the intact
family,'' he says. ``No matter how long ago their father lived with
them, even if those years were awful, this is a concrete reminder
of what was and what will never be again,'' and it affects children
of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   What can further get things off to a bad start is if a
stepfather immediately assumes a disciplinary role.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Discipline issue
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this is very common. Whether a mother seeks his
help with discipline or the stepfather wants to ``shape those kids
up,'' the result is disaster, says University of Missouri
researcher Marilyn Coleman, who is married to Ganong. They are well
known for their studies on stepfamilies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't successfully discipline children you don't have an
emotional bond with,'' says Coleman. ``The older the child, the
truer that is. It ticks them off: `Who's he to tell me?''' An only
slightly exaggerated rule of thumb, she says, is that it takes as
many years to bond as the number of years you haven't lived
together.
</P>
<P>
   For most stepfathers, it's hard not to involve yourself in
discipline if the kids are bratty to you or their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learning to keep your mouth shut is difficult,'' sympathizes
Cambridge and Newton psychologist Patricia Papernow, who
specializes in stepfamilies. ``If you have to say something, make
it an `I' statement _ `I have a hard time hearing you talk to your
mother that way' _ rather than a directive: `Don't you talk that
way to your mother!''' Papernow is author of ``Becoming a
Stepfamily'' (Analytic Press).
</P>
<P>
   It's not that you can't have input, just that it needs to be
behind-the-scenes with your wife, not in front of her children.
``It's the Golden Rule of stepfathering,'' says University of Miami
psychologist Margaret Crosbie-Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   She says stepfathers who try to discipline or expect too much
too soon from their stepchildren end up feeling inadequate,
frustrated, and disappointed. ``You start to think, `I don't need
this grief,' and disengage from the kids,'' says Crosbie-Burnett,
whose area of research is stepfamilies' adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   As human a reaction as that is, it creates more trouble. ``When
you withdraw,'' she says, ``a kid says to himself, `I knew he
didn't really care about me.' Then he feels justified to pay less
attention to you or give you an even harder time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Realistic expectations
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can't eliminate children's negative reactions but you can
mitigate against them by having minimal expectations. Advises
Crosbie-Burnett: ``Make the goal to have a friendly, respectful
relationship. To have fun together. Maybe love will come from that,
maybe it won't. Don't look for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinicians say closeness is more likely if stepfathers:
</P>
<P>
   _Talk with stepchildren of all ages about their father. Whether
he's dead or alive, involved or not, Papernow advises,
``Acknowledge his presence, real or emotional. Tell her, `I'm not
trying to replace your dad.' Acknowledge his role: `You have a
strong pitching arm, you must get that from your dad.''' Such
comments not only give a stepchild permission to think about Dad
without guilt, but establish you as someone she can talk to about
Dad. Mom may get too angry.
</P>
<P>
   _Create one-to-one time with each child. ``This is the sure way
to form a bond as long as you do it on the child's agenda,'' says
Coleman. She tells of one man who took his 10-year-old stepson
hunting ``to make him a man.'' ``The kid went along _ he didn't
want to get his mother mad _ but he hated it and hated his
stepfather more,'' says Coleman. Another man she knows offered to
take his 11-year-stepdaughter shopping because mother and daughter
fought over clothes. ``He could give his opinion without being
emotional. It brought them closer,'' Coleman says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
