A5215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-18 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T TELL A BOOK BY ITS TITLE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Had F. Scott Fitzgerald had his way, ``The Great Gatsby'' would
have been ``Trimalchio at West Egg.'' Would it still be an American
classic under that title? (``Robert Redford IS &UR;  &LR; `Trimalchio at West
Egg'!'') And Margaret Mitchell's ``Gone With the Wind,'' would we
love it as ``Pansy''? Because that's what Mitchell planned to call
it, after Pansy O'Hara, its feisty heroine.
</P>
<P>
   I've always assumed that once the book was written, coming up
with a title would be easy. This is not necessarily the case,
according to Andre Bernard's ``Now All We Need Is A Title.''
Bernard notes in the introduction that his book was originally
called ``Untitled.'' He thanks his editor at W.W. Norton for
discarding his ``lousy'' original and coming up with the new one.
Obviously editors do not always know best, Trimalchio and Pansy
notwithstanding. The same goes for authors. And publishers. ``I am
trying to think up a good title for you to want me to change,''
Raymond Chandler once wrote to his publisher, Alfred A. Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler had an ear for a good title, and kept long lists of
possibilities in his notebooks, among them ``All Guns Are Loaded,''
``Lament But No Tears,'' ``Too Late to Sleep.'' Not all writers
have the knack, as Bernard's book makes clear. The great Charles
Dickens was to a large extent title-deaf. He very nearly called
``Bleak House,'' his ninth novel, ``Tom-All-Alone's Factory That
Got into Chancery and Never Got Out.'' He agonized over titles and
inundated his editor with suggestions, some of which were odd
indeed. ``Hard Heads and Soft Hearts'' was one title he put forward
for the novel that eventually was published as ``Hard Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Some writers admit they can't come up with good titles. Eudora
Welty has said she's just no good at them. Ann Beattie used to
submit her stories untitled to The New Yorker. As a schoolboy,
George Plimpton amused himself by inventing titles. But once he
started writing books he came up dry. His original title for
``Paper Lion'' was ``Where Are You, Dink Stover?''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard's little book is an eccentric collection of anecdotes
meant to amuse, and it does. He includes some wonderful stories.
Jean Stafford, Robert Lowell's first wife, claimed he revised his
work so extensively that a poem originally titled ``To Jean: On Her
Confirmation'' ended up called ``To a Whore in the Brooklyn Navy
Yard.'' Dylan Thomas titled a play ``Llareggub,'' a Welsh-looking
word that, read backward, expressed his feelings for his audience.
A friend persuaded him to change it to ``Under Milk Wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard leaves readers wanting to know more about certain
authors and titles. What, exactly, was the thinking that went into
changing Jacqueline Susann's working title ``They Don't Build
Statues to Businessmen'' to ``The Valley of the Dolls''? Who argued
for ``At This Point in Time'' over ``All the President's Men''?
</P>
<P>
   He sheds light on some odd titles, among them ``Naked Lunch,''
which the author, William Burroughs, said means exactly what the
words say: ``a frozen moment when everyone sees what is on the end
of every fork.'' Anthony Burgess's ``A Clockwork Orange'' comes
from a Cockney expression, ``queer as a clockwork orange,'' i.e.,
something that doesn't exist. It wasn't, as some thought, a
reference to a hand grenade, ``a cheaper kind of explosive
pineapple,'' as Burgess once put it.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset Maugham explained that ``The Moon and Sixpence'' means
``reaching for the moon and missing the sixpence at one's feet.''
Maugham, Bernard writes, was proud of his titles, and liked to say,
``A good title is the title of a book that's successful.'' Which
makes one wonder all the more about what might have happened to
``Trimalchio at West Egg'' and ``Pansy.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
