<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLLUTION WON'T STOP BY ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was on a talk show the other day with Jan Schlichtmann, the
lawyer whose fight against corporate polluters in Woburn, Mass. is
described in the book ``A Civil Action.'' We'd agreed to go on the
radio in Boston to share some stories about the effectiveness of
citizen activism, but before we got a chance, the male host
challenged the very premises we were working on.
</P>
<P>
   ``These big corporations have deep pockets,'' he insisted.
``Don't they look at all these suits and protests as just the cost
of doing business?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cynicism isn't an excuse for not taking action,'' Schlichtmann
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Later the host turned to me. ``I know you've got an active group
in Marblehead, but we have a lot of blue-collar listeners who are
struggling to survive. How are they going to organize citizen
committees?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that hard,'' I remember saying. ``I put a press
release in the paper and 72 people showed up, every one of them
ready to pitch in and work. People finally realize that pollution
is putting their health in jeopardy and all over the country
they're responding to a call to action.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the conviction in my voice, I realized how far I've
come.
</P>
<P>
   Just six months ago, I was the one putting down the newspaper
with a sigh of hopelessness. Bad news about the environment filled
me with such despair that it was hard not to picture my
grandchildren dying from famine on a ruined planet. Now here I was,
more hopeful than I've been in years, exhorting someone else to
have faith.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it strange? I am probably more aware than ever of the
dangers posed to my community by pesticides, poorly maintained
school buildings, and the plume of poisonous particulates drifting
over from the Salem Power Plant, yet because I'm working with
others who care as deeply as I do, I feel passionately optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Let me share a few inspiring stories.
</P>
<P>
   Last week our Board of Health, working with the Marblehead
(Mass.) Pesticide Awareness Committee, issued a statement
committing itself to the reduction and eventual phaseout of
pesticide use, on both public and private property. In addition,
every schoolchild will be bringing home a handout explaining that
warning flags on lawns indicate the presence of poisons that can
cause serious acute and long-term health problems.
</P>
<P>
   It was citizen action _ public presentations, organic gardening
workshops for landscapers, letters to the editor _ that created the
context in which our elected officials were able to act quickly and
decisively.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, by a 2 to 1 landslide, our town passed a Proposition
2 1/2 override for funds to renovate our ``sick'' school buildings.
At the same time, our School Department began offering an
EPA-sponsored program called ``Indoor Air Quality Tools for
Schools'' to parent teams committed to clean up every one of our
elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   It was citizen action _ a public forum, meetings of PTAs, a
massive telephone effort _ that educated parents and helped school
officials to respond promptly to the health risks of poorly
maintained schools.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another group has been sharing its concerns about the
Salem (Mass.) Power Plant with federal and state officials, and
with officers of the company about to purchase it. Though members
of the Marblehead Cancer Prevention Project will be joining others
on the June 21 Cancer Walk in Salem, those working to ensure the
conversion of the power plant to a cleaner fuel will be holding up
signs outside the plant, pointing out to the 17,500 walkers why we
should no longer tolerate the release of arsenic, cadmium, lead,
mercury, and uranium into our air.
</P>
<P>
   An aware and active citizenry sends a powerful message to those
who will have the responsibility for cleaning up one of the
dirtiest power plants in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Cynicism isolates, while coming together in a shared undertaking
energizes. It's as if, riding on the Titanic, we finally feel the
great ship of state shifting its direction. The peril is still
straight ahead, but every hand on the wheel exerts a tiny bit more
pressure in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics, stand aside.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of you, come add your strength to ours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
