<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEDIA JOURNAL FILLED WITH SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to think of any magazine _ with the possible exception
of John Kennedy Jr.'s star-soaked George _ that got a splashier
launch than Steve Brill's Content. Even before the monthly journal
of media criticism from Court TV founder Brill hit the newsstands,
his story accusing independent counsel Ken Starr of improper media
leaks became the talk of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has since sent Brill a letter saying the article bordered
on ``libelous,'' and Brill has asked Starr to release a log of his
contacts with reporters. Whatever Nieman Foundation curator Bill
Kovach is earning as Brill's ombudsman, he already looks like the
most underpaid man in America.
</P>
<P>
   But the real question is whether Brill can sell media to the
masses. The magazine is claiming a 225,000 initial circulation, but
Brill is aiming for about 500,000. Two other respected media
monitors, the Columbia Journalism Review and the American
Journalism Review, have circulations of about 27,000 and 25,000,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the 152-page debut issue, Content is a different
animal. It is attractive and ambitious, with stories running the
gamut from the bookers of guests for TV news shows to the
authenticity of letters that fill teen magazines. And unlike AJR
and CJR, its tone is more that of detective than academic.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue does a number of smart things _ aside from
selling itself with the Starr ``Pressgate'' story. It covers the
good as well as the bad: the triumphs of the Chicago magazine
writer who unmasked the inflated investment claims of the
Beardstown Ladies and the New York Times team that tracked down
corruption at the Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But the magazine's best moments come with the tidbits that shed
light on how journalism really works. Pieces on how Stephen Glass's
fabricated stories made it past the New Republic fact-checkers and
on the meaning of the term ``off the record'' illuminate how basic
standards can vary from news outlet to news outlet. And the hubris
of today's media celebrity is illustrated in the story about the
television bookers. A letter trying to persuade Louise Woodward's
attorneys to put their client on ABC's ``PrimeTime Live'' declares,
``Please know that Diane (Sawyer) is eager to personally meet with
you.'' Doesn't that sound a little like ``Her majesty will see you
now''?
</P>
<P>
   Editorial director Michael Kramer writes that Brill's Content
vows allegiance not to the journalistic fraternity, but to the
media consumer. The problem is a statistic on the last page of the
magazine: Only 7 percent of Americans believe ``journalists are
more honest than most people.'' Brill's gamble is that a lot of
those media consumers are going to pay to read about people they
hold in such meager esteem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives have long said that the Washington press corps is
infected with liberal bias. And surveys like the Freedom Forum
study revealing that 89 percent of those journalists voted for Bill
Clinton in 1992 provide some evidence. But a new poll of Beltway
journalists commissioned by the liberal media watchdog Fairness &AMP;
Accuracy in Reporting (FAIR) indicates that the Washington press
corps is ``more conservative than the general public on a range of
economic issues from taxes to ... Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveyed were 141 Washington bureau chiefs, editors, and
reporters; 66 percent of them are male and 89 percent white. But
the most enlightening number was household income: 52 percent have
annual household incomes of over $100,000 and only 5 percent are
below the $50,000 mark. The study solicited their views on economic
issues and compared them with what FAIR says are benchmark polls
administered by other pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-two percent of the journalists surveyed characterized the
economy as ``excellent'' and ``good,'' as compared with only 66
percent of the general public; 57 percent of the journalists said
``too much power is concentrated in the hands of a few large
companies,'' compared with 77 percent of the public; 65 percent of
the journalists said NAFTA has had a positive impact on the US,
while only 32 percent of the public agrees; 39 percent of the press
corps saw protecting Social Security and Medicare from major cuts
as a top priority, compared with 59 percent of the public; 32
percent of the media respondents felt requiring employers to
provide health insurance is a top priority, as opposed to 47
percent of the public; and 43 percent of the journalists favored
government-guaranteed health care, compared with 64 percent of the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   Although FAIR assails what it calls the ``liberal media myth,''
the study concludes that ``painting journalists as the core of the
`conservative media' does not do justice to the complexity of the
situation. Like many profit-sector professionals, journalists tend
to hold `liberal' social views and `conservative' economic views.
Most of all, they can broadly be described as centrists.'' And
well-heeled centrists at that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
