<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WILDE-BOS &LR;      06-18 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WILDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON TRUTH, JUSTICE AND THE CULT OF OSCAR WILDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
OSCAR WILDE'S LAST STAND 
By Philip Hoare 
Arcade, 256 pp., illustrated, $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oscar Wilde had been dead for 18 years in 1918, but his case and
cause remained vivid in the public imagination when an adventurous
theater company sought to give the British premiere of his play
``Salome.'' To add to the attraction, Richard Strauss's opera based
on the play had taken the world by storm a decade before,
reawakening interest in its source.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Pemberton Billing, a member of Parliament and a
self-appointed protector of the public morals, was outraged. In his
newspaper ``The Vigilante,'' he published an attack on Maud Allan,
the American dancer who was cast in the title role. Billing
denounced Allan as the leader of a ``cult of the clitoris,'' and
strongly suggested that the subscription list for the private
performance would yield the names of some of the 47,000 members of
the British establishment who, according to Billing, shared Wilde's
perverse sexual inclinations and therefore became susceptible to
blackmail by German agents.
</P>
<P>
   Allan had no choice but to retaliate by suing for libel, and for
five days the sensational trial monopolized the attention of the
nation, and indeed the English-speaking world. There was a
prominent cast of characters, including the King's former mistress,
who was in the courtroom fearing to be called to the stand;
Billing's mistress, eager to testify; the director of Naval
Intelligence; Lord Alfred Douglas, whose affair with Wilde was the
cause of the writer's downfall and who was now ``reformed''; not to
mention the exotic danseuse herself, sister of an executed
murderer, a favorite guest at No.10 Downing Street, and center of
controversies throughout her career. Allan was famed for the
illusion of near-nudity she created in her dance, ``The Vision of
Salome'' (though in later years she remarked, ``That costume today
would take me to the North Pole and back and keep me cozy and
warm'').
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom was the scene of bizarre, even incredible displays
of arrogance, ignorance, chicanery, prejudice, and duplicity. The
subtitle of Philip Hoare's ``Oscar Wilde's Last Stand'' calls this
``the most outrageous trial of the century,'' but there are too
many other claimants for that position; it was certainly one of the
most preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Hoare, author of lively biographies of Stephen Tennant and Noel
Coward, devotes about half of his book to gavel-to-gavel coverage
of the trial in all of its Alice-in-Wonderland absurdity. The trial
was being used by both sides to advance political and social
agendas, and both sides were capable of dishonorable behavior _
Billing would stop at nothing, and liberal politicians, rightly
fearful of his demagoguery, financed a plot to engineer his fall.
The judge, Charles Darling, repeatedly lost control of the
courtroom; neither defense or prosecution focused on facts.
Ignorance about sexual matters and a philistine approach to
literary and aesthetic issues led to repeated explosions of
hilarity and displays of partisan support or disapproval. Eight
decades later, one reads some of the courtroom exchanges with
comparable hilarity, incredulous, but streaked with an uneasiness
because of what was at stake _ and because of the further
atrocities ignorance and intolerance have led to in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of Hoare's book traces the biographies of its
principal participants, before and after, and thoroughly and
admirably investigates the context of the trial _ sexual,
psychological, artistic, historical, political, and sociological
(the trial pitted middle-class values against upper-class
irresponsibilities and lower-class realities).
</P>
<P>
   Wilde had been an avatar of the modern world, as Hoare notes:
``He exemplified the coming age; the cult of the personality, the
new, incestuous ties between the media and culture.'' The Billing
trial addressed the cult of Wilde and, in essence, the century that
was defining itself, and in doing so it raised issues of truth,
justice, and tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Hoare proves a learned, witty, intelligent guide to significant
aspects of subcultural history that have not been very thoroughly
explored; quite deftly he fits the pieces of the known and the
unknown together. He has an eye for the memorable detail (Goering,
at his final arrest, was wearing red nail polish, and his toes were
painted too) and the telling quip. That the Germans maintained a
list of Britons susceptible to blackmail is probable; the British
certainly maintained comparable lists of Germans. (In the Second
World War, the Nazis had a list of Englishmen scheduled for
extermination, and the list became public. Rebecca West wrote to
Noel Coward, ``My dear, the people we should have been seen dead
with.'')
</P>
<P>
   Hoare, of course, is as partisan as any participant in the trial
he is covering _ it shows in observations like, ``Unlike racism,
anti-Semitism and homophobia play on the fear of the superior,
rather than the inferior.'' But he is an intelligent and generous
partisan. (His final verdict on Billing is, ``His campaign was
ridiculous, prejudiced, laughable even; yet Billing believed it,
believed that society was threatened by perversion and that it was
his duty to fight it. In that he was an honourable man, for all his
dishonourable ways.'') At the end of the trial there was a swift
verdict in favor of Billing, but as Hoare points out, the
aftershocks would be felt for decades, long after the trial itself
and its personalities had been forgotten. Some of those same issues
still arise in courtrooms and newspapers today, and they are not
funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
