<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-RICCI-BOS &LR;      06-18 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-RICCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICCI OPTS FOR THE `OPPOSITE' PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of actresses my age only do that because they
think people will think they're stupid if they don't. It's like
their way of proving to people that they're smart, and I don't feel
like I need to prove myself to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Her strappy platform sandals kicked off, Christina Ricci is
curled up on a couch in her Boston hotel suite, explaining why she
has no intention of attending college. Jodie Foster did it nearly
two decades ago, and Claire Danes plans to do so in the fall, and
Ricci, at her family's insistence, sent out applications, and was
accepted into Columbia University. But come September, she won't be
swapping soundstages for lecture halls, or movie scripts for
textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like (actresses who attend college) think everyone will
say, `She went to college for four years, what a smart girl she is,
she knows acting is a silly job.' It's like, are you serious? I owe
so much to acting,'' she said. ``For me to go to college would be
like admitting actresses are stupid, and I especially think it's
horrible to go to school just because you think other people will
think better of you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to go, but then I realized why I was going, and
that I really didn't want to go,'' Ricci said. ``If people think
I'm stupid then ... let them think I'm stupid. I don't feel like
going to college.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, had she attended Columbia she would have studied
creative writing, not drama since ``that would be a true waste of
time to go and study something I've been doing for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci, for more than half of her 18 years, has been a
professional actress, perhaps best known for her morbidly hilarious
turn as Wednesday in ``The Addams Family'' films. Yet, if it
doesn't seem as if Ricci has grown up before our eyes, perhaps that
is because she has never quite seemed just another child actress.
Perhaps it is her world-weary eyes or the refreshingly candidness
that would make most publicists faint. She is an old soul wrapped
in the increasingly voluptuous body of a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Addams Family'' to Ang Lee's wrenching family drama,
``The Ice Storm,'' Ricci has always brought an unsettling maturity
and tangy flavor to her roles. With her world-weary eyes and
deadpan delivery, she is making a far smoother transition from
child to adult roles than, say, Macaulay Culkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never played parts that were happy, adorable little kids.
Even in movies where I probably should have been happy and
adorable, I wasn't,'' said Ricci, releasing a long stream of smoke
from an ever-present Parliament. ``I guess that helped me be seen
as more than just a cute kid.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing cute nor childlike about Ricci's latest
character in ``The Opposite of Sex,'' which opens Thursday. Ricci
plays Dedee Truitt, a nasty bit of Southern discomfort who wreaks
havoc in the lives of just about everyone she encounters. Within
the movie's first half-hour, she trashes her stepfather's funeral,
steals her half-brother's hunky boyfriend, and fingers him as the
father of her unborn child. The film also stars Martin Donovan,
Lisa Krudow, Ivan Sergei, Johnny Galecki, and Lyle Lovett.
</P>
<P>
   Ricci received the script from her mother, and was immediately
interested in playing Dedee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard enough for adult women to find strong characters,''
said Ricci, between sips of Coke. ``But for teen-age girls, you're
always either someone's daughter or someone's girlfriend or the
whiny pain-in-the-ass victim or the bitch who's totally out to ruin
people's lives. Dedee isn't out to ruin people's lives, she just
happens to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With her Lolita pout and soulless eyes, Dedee is the kind of
unholy creation who walks into a room, opens her mouth, and sucks
out all the oxygen. Politically incorrect to a fault _ few groups
emerge unscathed by her barbed observations _ Dedee would have
Wednesday Addams running for the rosary beads and holy water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so nice to be able to say things you're never allowed
to say in movies. You think they'd never ever allow a script like
this to be made,'' Ricci said. ``It was really nice, and really
fun, and this movie totally reflects a unique sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Roos, who both wrote and directed the film, did not create
Dedee with Ricci in mind. In fact, Roos, who makes his directorial
debut with the film, but has such screenwriting credits as ``Single
White Female'' and ``Boys on the Side,'' wasn't sure Ricci was
right for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she was too young. I thought of her as this little
freaky Wednesday,'' he said. ``But once we flew to New York to meet
her, she was very compelling. I instantly felt, `This is who the
character is.'''
</P>
<P>
   After auditioning 50 actresses for the role, Roos was attracted
to Ricci's vulnerability, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a lot going on behind whatever it is she's
doing or saying. It's her eyes, her face, and her talent that make
you believe this is a real person and not just a collections of
words, gestures, and attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Ricci, who recently moved from New York to Los
Angeles, has worked on seven films including Terry Gilliam's take
on Hunter S. Thompson's ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas.'' (As a
14-year-old runaway who paints portraits of Barbra Streisand, Ricci
was the best thing in that misfire of a movie.) She recently
completed ``200 Cigarettes,'' with Courtney Love and Ben Affleck;
``Buffalo 66,'' which sauntered out of this year's Sundance Film
Festival with big buzz, opens next month month, and she's also in
the new John Waters's film ``Pecker.''
</P>
<P>
   Since graduating from high school, Ricci has worked virtually
nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got kind of panicked, like, `Wow, now I really need to make
money so I better take this seriously,''' she said.``In the past
year, everything I've done I've done because I liked the script,
and I liked the role. I really thought those where good movies, and
they were like my sense of humor, so I really enjoyed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Few would argue that Ricci has ever been anything less than a
serious actress. A native of Santa Monica, Calif., Ricci grew up in
Montclair, N.J. She appeared in a school play, and by age 8, was
traveling to New York regularly to appear in television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came really naturally to me, it was really fun for me,''
she said. ``I was getting paid, I didn't have to go to school for a
while, and I got lots of attention which is all I ever wanted when
I was little.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ricci is still getting lots of attention in the onl career
she has ever known. Ricci is content to work at the only job she's
ever known. While most of her recent films could be classified as
independent, she's not adverse to big-budget films _ after all
``The Addams Family'' movies garnered hundreds of millions. But as
with most aspects of her life, Ricci won't adhere to popular logic,
whether it concerns the ivy-covered halls of academia or Hollywood
success. And if anyone has a problem with that, well, Ricci, really
couldn't care less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wouldn't scoff at $21 million, but I would hate to do a
big movie that was cheesy and awful,'' she said. ``It's much more
important that I could live with myself. I don't need any more
self-loathing in my life, you know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-CARING-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-18 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARING-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Coleman says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _Get feelings out in the open, including your own. Visher tells
every stepfather to have an early conversation, something like
this: ``I know this feels strange, having me live here, and it may
take time to figure out how to live together, but I know we will.
You may feel like we never will and that's OK. If you ever want to
talk, just ask.'' Visher is co-author of ``How to Win as a
Stepfamily'' (Brunner Mazel).
</P>
<P>
   _Look for family activities that include the stepfather. ``If
Mom and the kids are great skiiers and the stepdad isn't, it's a
lousy activity because it perpetuates him as an outsider,'' says
Papernow. ``But if Mom's the outsider _ she's the one who can't ski
_ that connects the kids and stepfather.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dealing with rejection
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Children under 8 are typically more open to overtures but a
child of any age may reject them and be downright nasty to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't eat the toast because you made it?'' says Osherson.
``Leave it on the table, tell him it's there if he wants it, and
get to the heart of the issue: `I know this is hard, getting used
to each other. But that's what we have to do: get used to each
other. It will take time.'''
</P>
<P>
   That lets him know three things, says Osherson: You aren't going
to let yourself be the object of abuse, you aren't going to strike
back, and you aren't going away. Visher adds that behind most
nastiness is another ``n'' word: neediness.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you are respectful and kind to your stepchildren
doesn't mean they will be. Don't overlook that the problem may be
lack of communication or miscommunication. ``If you want them to be
civil, spell out exactly what that means,'' says Papernow. ``Does
it refer to a tone of voice or a greeting in the morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Ganong says that with teenagers, the going can be tough and have
nothing to do with you as a stepfather. ``When Stuart and his
brother, Jay, were 15 and 16, they didn't have a decent
relationship with any adult,'' he says, ``including their
biological father, who they were close to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR PARENTS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Think of yourself as a consultant to your stepchildren. Try to
find one way in which you can be a hero because you can teach them
something they want to learn that nobody else can.
</P>
<P>
   _Children's jealousy and resentment of a stepdad typically
diminish if they still have time alone with their mother.
</P>
<P>
   _Mothers play a large role in easing their husband's transition
into the family: Talk with your children about what will change and
what will stay the same. Don't undermine his efforts. (Psychologist
Coleman tells of one mother who insisted on tucking her children
into bed after the stepfather because he ``didn't do it good
enough.'') Set reasonable expectations: ``You don't have to love
him but you have to treat him with respect as you would any other
adult.'' Pat him on the back in front of the kids: ``Thanks for
helping. I appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Stepdaughters and teens are most resistant to physical
affection from a stepfather. If she pushes you away or freezes up
when you offer a hug, back off but do try again after some time
passes. Otherwise, she'll think you don't care anymore.
</P>
<P>
   _The warmer you are toward their biological dad, the easier it
is for children of any age.
</P>
<P>
   _With several children in a family, the oldest is likely to
resist most because he feels the loyalty bind the most. In general,
9- to 13-year-olds are the most resistant; they're very opinionated
and have preconceived ideas of what a family should be. &UR;  &LR; Kids under
6 are the most open; they tend to want the family to succeed. Teens
often don't care because they've developed support groups outside
the family.
</P>
<P>
   _Food can make children resentful of a stepfather, especially if
Mom changes what she cooks to please him. A good antidote: Let
everyone take turns choosing menus.
</P>
<P>
   _Stepfathers who have their own children shouldn't expect or
pretend to love their stepchildren the same.
</P>
<P>
   _Men who become stepfathers because the biological father died
may have a hard time because kids idealize a dead father and make
constant comparisons. A good comment to make: ``I can't do this the
same way your dad did but I'm doing my best.''
</P>
<P>
   _For a recommended reading list or support groups in your area,
contact the Stepfamily Association of America at 800-735-0329.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended for parents of children with
disabilities: the University of Buffalo's ``Let's Play!'' Web site
offers an extensive collection of resources. Visit it at
http://cosmos.ot.buffalo.edu/letsplay/.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)nws.globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
