<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPLING SOME ITEMS ON THE SPORTS MENU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picked-up pieces gathered while watching futbol and pumping out
the basement ...
</P>
<P>
   --When the Red Sox are done with old Fenway, why not make it the
permanent site of the Baseball Hall of Fame? This radical idea was
first mentioned to me by George Will last month. He said he wasn't
sure where he'd heard it first, but the more you think about it,
the more sense it makes. We reluctantly concede that the Red Sox,
(itals)someday(unitals), are going to build a park rather than
refurbish Fenway. The old yard won't be allowed to stand empty
because real estate in the Fens is valuable. So why not bring
Cooperstown's shrine to Boston?
</P>
<P>
   Hardball historians have conceded that Cooperstown has nothing
to do with the birth of baseball. Since it's stripped of that
mythology, there's really no sense to keep the Hall there. It's
difficult for fans to find and too small to accommodate the masses
who want to tour the Hall. Sure, much of the small-town charm would
be lost, but bringing the Hall to Fenway, to
(itals)Boston(unitals), would make it accessible to millions of
tourists and fans passing through the Hub without losing the
nostalgic feel of Cooperstown. And it would enable Fenway to live
with a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   --It is contemptible, self-important, and embarrassing that Sox
general manager Dan Duquette has issued an order that none of his
minor league people be allowed to give interviews without first
getting clearance from Boston. This is the kind of arrogance that
makes other teams root against the Red Sox. Any team in baseball
should be happy that the press cares enough to talk to minor league
people. In the scheme of life, it's just not that important, Dan.
It's only baseball, and you should remember what it was like in
Montreal and be happy anybody cares.
</P>
<P>
   --The National Hockey League just completed its fourth
consecutive 4-0 Stanley Cup finals. It is as if the sport is cursed
since the 1994 strike. It's been all downhill since the Rangers won
the Cup in '94. Since 1995, the NHL has had as many four-game
finals sweeps as the NBA has had in 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   --David Stern was no doubt happy to have hundreds of European
press at the NBA Finals, but they did clutter the press
conferences, making Ahmad Rashad sound like Mike Wallace (we're
still not sure if it was a European or an American who asked
Scottie Pippen after Game 5, ``Scottie, would you rather win this
in six games or in seven?''). It was definitely the ``B'' team of
chain-smoking Euro writers at the NBA Finals this year because any
European sportswriter who's any good would be watching futbol in
France. Oui?
</P>
<P>
   --It's beginning to look like the Red Sox might hang in there
throughout the summer. By now, most of you have given up the ghost
of chasing the Yankees. Keep an eye on the Rangers and Angels. One
will win the West and the other will battle the Red Sox for the
wild card. Unless Baltimore or Toronto makes a move, that's the way
it's shaping up as we near the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   --Here it comes: Jose Canseco missed Tuesday's game with back
spasms.
</P>
<P>
   --Like most of us, Jack McCallum of Sports Illustrated has a
favorite Larry Bird story. He traveled with the Cetlics to Spain in
1988 for the McDonald's Open. The Celtics were scheduled to meet
with King Juan Carlos, and when McCallum tried to arrange a brief
interview with Bird, Larry told him, ``Maybe we can do it tomorrow
after we do that king thing.'' (itals)That king thing.(unitals)
Love it.
</P>
<P>
   --Erik Hanson? No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   --Happily, it's not news anymore when John Hirschbeck works home
plate for an Orioles game. Roberto Alomar went 1 for 5 against the
Yankees when Hirschbeck worked the plate in Baltimore Monday.
</P>
<P>
   --Pats fans who can't make the trip should drink Coronas when
the Bob Kraft AC plays Dallas at Mexico City Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   --Apocalypse Now or Serenity Now? There haven't been many years
when both the Red Sox and Cubs have had a chance at postseason
play. A Red Sox-Cubs World Series would almost certainly bring out
the ``end of the world'' cult. The Sox haven't won since 1918, the
Cubs since '08, and the Sox' last Series win was against the Cubs.
Stephen King has already predicted that a Cubs-BoSox World Series
could only end with an atomic bomb detonating after it got to 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   --Is Luc Longley the worst player to start for an NBA champion,
or did Marc Iavaroni retire the trophy with the 1983 Sixers? Send
your entries to Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   --How did ``The Babe Ruth Story'' miss the Top 400 list?
</P>
<P>
   --Don't trade Jim Leyritz. Happy or not, he'll produce.
</P>
<P>
   --Too often, we write about ``all-time greats'' on these pages,
but we lost one for sure June 4 when the Washington Post's
92-year-old Shirley Povich died at his home in Washington. A native
of Bar Harbor, Maine (where there were a lot of boys named
Shirley), Povich went to Washington when he was 17 and caddied for
President Warren Harding. His first Post story about the Washington
Senators ran in 1924. He was named sports editor in '26 and wrote
more than 15,000 columns over seven decades. He covered Babe Ruth's
alleged ``called shot'' in the 1932 World Series. He and his wife,
Ethyl, were married for 66 years. Asked about the secret of their
marriage, Povich said, ``We take it one decade at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
