NYT-06-18-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-WINGS-BOS &LR;      06-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINGS HELD UP FOR THE LONG SKATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, they turned out to be marathon men. If the New
Jersey Devils of 1994-95 were the NHL's best sprinters, winning the
Stanley Cup in a lockout-shortened season, the 1997-98 edition of
the Detroit Red Wings proved their mettle over the very long haul.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Conn Smythe Trophy as playoff MVP Tuesday
night at MCI Center in Washington in the wake of Detroit's 4-0
sweep of the Capitals in the finals, Wings captain Steve Yzerman
said he said he couldn't wait to get his uniform off and crash.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL season began Oct. 1, a full 30 days before the NBA
season, yet the finals ended two days later than the NBA's _ and
that's only because they were wrapped up in the minimum number of
games. When most people were firing up their gas grills and shorts
and tank tops had become the fashion order of the day, hockey
players were still suiting up for a winter sport that was
threatening to last practically until July 4 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's really over. The season that wouldn't end finally has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been difficult with the Olympic Games in the middle
of the season _ there were so many games, and I think every player
felt the same way,'' said Yzerman, who looked spent as well as
elated. ``We were playing four games a week, and it just seemed
like once the season started, it never stopped and you never got a
chance to catch your breath. We had the Olympics, came right back
and started playing again, and the playoffs are just incredibly
draining. So you just haven't had a chance to just sit at home for
a night on the couch and do nothing and watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty much exhausted, so I'm just looking forward to
taking it easy for a while because it's just been one day after
another, just preparing for a game nonstop since September. It's
been a draining year, but obviously a really enjoyable year. It's
just time to slow down for a little while.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Chicago Bulls added to their legend and dynasty, the
Red Wings became the first back-to-back Cup champions since the
1991 and '92 Penguins. So what is next for the Wings, besides some
well-deserved rest? It remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Scotty Bowman, who has won eight Stanley Cups as a coach
and another as director of player development with the Penguins,
could go for No. 9 behind the bench next year, which would break
the record he now shares with Toe Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman said he would sit down with his family and make a
decision in the next couple of weeks once the emotion has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I hope he comes back for another year,'' said
Yzerman. ``He's in charge of this team. The players have grown
extremely fond of him. We know what Scotty and the staff wants us
to do. They kind of know what to expect from us, so we have a
pretty good relationship. But he's the guy who drives the team and
he puts the fire on the team and he doesn't allow the players to
get big egos or get overconfident or get too comfortable. He keeps
you motivated. He keeps you a little on edge. He's had a tremendous
coaching career. We've got a good thing going and we'd like to
continue it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly possible they could. For the most part, the core
of the team will remain intact, and there is plenty of young
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of our forwards apart from myself and Igor
Larionov are all within the ages of 22, 23-29, so that group is
going to be together for a number of years, and that will keep the
team competitive,'' said Yzerman. ``We really didn't look toward
winning the Cup until the playoffs started this year. We didn't
talk about it too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the NHL, no one was talking about it much at
the end. Sunday's TV rating for the final NBA game was 17.6.
Saturday's Game 3 of the NHL finals did only a 3.1. Consider that
the golf ratings for Sunday were 5.9.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this is golf season. One Detroit writer said you
know the NHL season is too long when it ends as the US Open is
about to start. The Red Wings made it to the finish line. The
marathon is finally over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
