<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERKINS-HOUSE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     06-18 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERKINS-HOUSE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 YORK, Maine: ... curator Johnson.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he never met Perkins, Johnson can claim to know her
mind better than most. As a graduate student, he lived in the
house. ``When you've living in someone else's house, you absorb a
lot about them.'' A sure guide to Perkins's taste was the pile of
magazines whose pages she marked for ideas. If her house resembles
any other, says Johnson, it would be Beauport, Henry Davis
Sleeper's cottage on Gloucester's Eastern Point, now maintained by
the Society for the Preservation of New England Antiquities.
Sometimes to the point of camp, Sleeper was the master of interior
vistas and vignettes composed of a miscellany of decorative
objects, some rare or valuable and others merely entertaining but
all companionable. ``I can't find any documentation that Elizabeth
Perkins and Sleeper met but they had to,'' says Johnson. A tour of
such ``decorator Colonial'' houses would also have to include Bert
and Nina Little's Cogswell Grant in Essex, Mass.; restored by SPNEA
to showcase the couple's collection of Americana, it will open in
August.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Perkins family
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old house was falling down when the Perkinses bought the
property for $1,300 a century ago. A Vermont family, they had
migrated to New York City and bought farmland just north of where
Central Park would be built following the Civil War. Farming didn't
pay nearly as well as land development and on their acres the
Perkinses put up houses and apartments. A formal photograph of the
young Elizabeth Perkins shows her in debutante white satin, an
heiress on offer. In the event, she never married. The various York
villages had their own social sets and Johnson says snobby York
Harbor considered the Perkinses' summer place, despite its now
enviable location on the York River, on the wrong side of the
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Perkinses began by enlarging the house, a simple four room
and ell structure. No architect guided them as they incorporated
bits of neo-Palladian, Georgian, and Federal elements from old
Maine houses. In 1904, the Perkinses added a one-story kitchen wing
and a big porch off the dining room. The following year, it seemed
the friendly thing to throw a tea party for delegates to the peace
conference in Portsmouth, N.H., ending the Russo-Japanese War.
There have been other improvements over the years; 1920 saw a
``period'' garage and upstairs a modern bathroom for Perkins. When
a parlor wall blocked the river view, the windows were
reconfigured. The rooms filled with antiques and Americana; a
French Aubusson carpet was sent up from the New York apartment.
Trinkets followed Perkins home from her South American holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Every room has a story or two to tell. Perkins stripped the
dining room of its 18th-century horsehair plaster and paneled it in
dark wood to make it older and more rustic. The room was lit only
by candles. Perkins obviously loved the centuries-old trick of
insinuating light into murky places. Almost every surface in her
dining room is freighted with silver, either shining metal or
lustrous china, and when the candles are lit, light winks back.
</P>
<P>
   The 1954 restoration banished much of this sleight of hand to
the attic. ``It took away her decorative intent,'' says Johnson. As
a result, the interiors looked uncertain, lacking in personality.
Perkins was in danger of being restored out of her own home. There
had been a serious side to her. Johnson says Perkins can stand in
preservation circles with the Wells family who created Old
Sturbridge or William Sumner Appleton, founder of SPNEA. She was
remarkable, moreover, as a lone woman doing preservation work in a
field dominated by male antiquarians. ``Men looked at her
bemused,'' says Johnson. ``She was strong willed: She did what she
had to do to get things done. Old York would not be what it is
without her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
House comes alive
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the attic treasures came downstairs and, with the
help of old photos, took their rightful places, the house came
alive. Rather than a historical document, the Perkins House ``is a
stage set set up for entertaining,'' says Johnson. There is a
little more work to do. The cast-iron furniture will go back on the
porch. There are plans to restore the 1935 boat house in which
Perkins staged theatricals. Something of that flavor will be
conveyed when the Old York Historical Society throws a gala party
on Saturday between 4 and 7 p.m. to celebrate the four-year
restoration of the house. It will be 1910 again, with music of the
day and servants to pass the Champagne. Strolling the lawn that
goes down to the York River will be people costumed as Perkins's
friends and visitors, among them humorist Mark Twain, actress Ethel
Barrymore, modern dancer Ruth St. Denis, and novelist Sarah Orne
Jewett. Perkins herself may make a cameo appearance. Will she wear
one of the soignee gowns that hangs in her upstairs dressing room
with her Red Cross uniform?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
INFORMATION FOR VISITORS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Elizabeth Perkins House, one of seven Old York Historical
Society museum buildings, is open to the public Tuesdays through
Sundays through September. For information about admission and
about the decorator show house benefiting the society July 18-Aug.
15, telephone 207-363-4974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
