<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-HEJDUK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEJDUK LEADS THE NEW WAVE IN US SOCCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-JEAN d'ARDIERES, France _ Frankie Hejduk isn't supposed to
be here. He's supposed to be paddling belly down on a surfboard
somewhere near La Jolla, waiting for a phat set.
</P>
<P>
   ``My buddies are always giving me stick for doing what I'm doing
now,'' says the man who brought the US soccer team out of its coma
with one mad dash in its World Cup opener against Germany Monday.
``They're home playing in the waves. But I'll have plenty of time
for that when I'm retired _ and they're working.''
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk has enough to do on dry land here. With the Americans
facing an early trip home if they can't beat Iran in Lyon Sunday,
the 23-year-old Hejduk (pronounced HAY-duck) will be off the bench
and into the starting lineup as coach Steve Sampson's favorite set
of jumper cables.
</P>
<P>
   With his shoulder-length locks, wraparound shades, and beach
cultcha approach, Hejduk seems an unlikely candidate to crank up
his side's juiceless battery. But he has exactly the qualities
Sampson knows the Americans need if they're to make it out of the
first round here next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``His complete lack of concern as to who's on the other side,''
says Sampson. ``His free spirit and wonderful attacking
personality. And his great speed.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Yanks were trailing the Germans by a goal at halftime
in Paris and looking timid and tentative, Sampson sent Hejduk onto
the pitch at the Parc des Princes and told him to get something
going.
</P>
<P>
   Within five minutes, Hejduk got hung with a yellow card for a
senseless trip. But a couple of minutes later, he came sprinting
through the German defense and launched a diving header that keeper
Andreas Koepke barely got his gloves on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how much trouble it took for him to go from that wide
midfield position to the near post,'' marvels Sampson, whose team
wound up losing to Germany, 2-0. ``That's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more so because Hejduk had his shorts on backward. Hoping
to get his mates moving, he'd turned the shorts around in the
dressing room at halftime. ``Rally cap, bro,'' Hejduk proclaimed.
``Rally cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk (``Last time I try that trick'') hadn't figured he'd be
going in for Mike Burns when play resumed. Six months ago, he
hadn't figured he'd be here at all after oversleeping and blowing a
team trip to China a year ago January. ``I set my watch alarm but I
didn't hear it,'' Hejduk says. ``Slept right through. I was in a
panic state. By the time I called Steve, the plane was almost in
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant curtains for Hejduk on the national team. ``He was
done for, and justifiably so,'' says Sampson. So Hejduk went back
to the Tampa Bay Mutiny, his Major League Soccer club, and took
stock. ``I didn't know whether I wanted to do this for a living or
not,'' he says. ``Then I realized what an opportunity I was
missing. Here I was letting it slip away. Missing that trip woke me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk had always drifted with the time and tide. Now he began
putting down roots. He proposed to his girlfriend, Kim (knee-deep
in the Pacific surf, fiancee in one arm, surfboard in the other),
got married, and had a son in February. ``I was always carefree,
had money, didn't worry about anything,'' Hejduk says. ``Now I had
someone to support and be a role model for.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he'd cleared the air with Sampson (``I admitted my
stupidity'') and gotten another chance with the national team.
Sampson, a Southern Californian himself, figured that anybody who
could drop off the edge of a 20-foot wall of water could probably
handle himself against the German midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever been bodysurfing? I have,'' says Sampson. ``I've been
crushed by a 5-footer. I'm not even thinking about 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk planned on being a pro surfer like his buddies. ``I'd get
up at 5, go surfing, go to school, then play soccer at 4,'' he
says. ``It was like that until I was 18.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA offered him a soccer scholarship, but Hejduk, who'd won the
state high school surfing championship, wanted to shoot the pier at
Huntington Beach. ``My parents weren't happy about that,'' he says.
``They wanted me to do the school and soccer thing.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hejduk did, and ended up making the 1996 Olympic team and
getting a shot with the national squad. Nobody else had his
flat-out speed and his unusual mix of daring and nonchalance.
That's why Sampson gave him a second shot and stuck with him after
Hejduk pulled a hamstring this year. Hejduk was the first man he
went to when the Yanks needed reanimation against the Germans, and
he was an obvious choice (along with Tab Ramos) when Sampson
decided to sic a couple of attack dogs on the Iranians this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   This time there's no flight to China to worry about. Lyon is
only 45 minutes down Route A6, the match is at 9 p.m., and Hejduk
has his wake-up call wired. ``Alarm clocks,'' Frankie Hejduk says.
``Now I set like six of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
