<SLUG> BC-JUNETEENTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMANCIPATION DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AKILAH MONIFA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Many folks are familiar with African-American
History Month in February, Kwanza in December, Martin Luther King's
birthday, Malcolm X's birthday and Uhuru Day (which commemorates
the 1965 Watts riots in Los Angeles).
</P>
<P>
   Juneteenth predates them all. It commemorates the end of
slavery, the seminal event in African-American history.
</P>
<P>
   There are numerous versions about how this holiday began.
</P>
<P>
   But first, some background history. The Emancipation
Proclamation took effect on Jan. 1, 1863, while the Civil War was
raging. In theory, it freed the slaves in all states which were
``in rebellion against the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, President Abraham Lincoln knew it would have little
effect, but he wanted to gain the support of abolitionist groups.
According to one version of how the holiday began, the Emancipation
Proclamation was read to slaves in Houston on June 19, 1863, more
than five months after the effective date. As word of the end of
slavery spread, Juneteenth was coined to commemorate the freedom
day.
</P>
<P>
   Another version has Gen. Gordon Granger, the Union Army's
commander in Texas, landing in Galveston on June 19, 1865, and
issuing a proclamation about the end of slavery _ as well as the
end of the Civil War, which had actually ended two months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another version, which makes little sense, has Juneteenth as
a celebration of the Thirteenth Amendment. Enacted on Dec. 18,
1865, it abolished all slavery and involuntary servitude.
</P>
<P>
   When I first heard about Juneteenth about 15 years ago, I heard
that many African Americans in Texas, where the holiday originated,
do not celebrate July 4 as Independence Day, but Juneteenth. There
are several folklore stories about why the news of freedom took so
long to spread.
</P>
<P>
   One version is that slaves were intentionally kept ignorant
about their freedom in order to allow the crops to be harvested.
Another version has one messenger traveling by mule from the date
of the Emancipation Proclamation to deliver the news and it simply
took more than five months to arrive from Washington. And another
version has the messenger being murdered before he could deliver
the message.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it has been a state holiday in Texas since 1980.
It's called ``Emancipation Day'' and is celebrated on June 19.
</P>
<P>
   Today it's celebrated in most of the states as the date when
slavery ended in the United States. Although primarily an
African-American holiday, it has now evolved into an acknowledgment
of the past and celebration of the cessation of slavery by all
peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Juneteenth.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Akilah Monifa is a free-lance writer, lawyer and adjunct
professor of law at New College of California in San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
