<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN STORY FITS NBC TO A TEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plenty of drama in this year's US Open. The main story line is
the competition between some of the hottest pros: Ernie Els, Mark
O'Meara, David Duval, Tiger Woods, Colin Montgomery, and Tom
Watson.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the subplot involving Casey Martin has received most
of the media attention and will command at least initial face-time
from NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll defintely be covering Casey's opening tee shot,'' said
NBC analyst Roger Maltbie. ``We feel it's a special occasion. It's
newsworthy and we want the viewing public to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Martin is one of overcoming huge obstacles. He was
born with a circulatory disorder that has whithered his right leg
and causes him to walk with a pronounced limp.
</P>
<P>
   Casey sued the PGA and won the right to use a motorized cart on
the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But even that decision was not a panacea. Martin has had trouble
with a single-passenger cart issued to him for practice rounds at
the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the USGA announced that it had decided to
allow him to use a standard cart.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to allow Martin use of a cart was not well-received
by a significant portion of the golfing world.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson has been the latest to express disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough position the Tour has taken, but I think the Tour
is right in the sense that the game should be played walking,''
Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Maltbie took exception to those who snickered about walking
being a part of golf. ``No one is questioning Casey's need for a
cart,'' Maltbie said. ``But to portray the other golfers as
non-athletes was unfair. Whether you have played for fun or
competitively, everyone knows that if you had to play 36 holes on a
hot, humid day on a hilly course, your game will be affected. Your
legs become tired and it will defintely affect your swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Maltbie and NBC's Johnny Miller agree that the network will
cover the Martin story as long as it's relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll focus on who is shooting the scores,'' Maltbie said.
``If Casey is 6-over, his coverage is over.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC plans live coverage thursday and Friday from 2 to 6 p.m. The
third and fourth rounds will air Saturday and Sunday from 2 to 8
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
