<SLUG> BC-GLF-EQUIPMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF MANUFACTURERS NOT OUT OF THE WOODS YET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the US Golf Association announced Wednesday that it will
continue to study advances in club and ball design and construction
before imposing new _ and much feared _ restrictions, golf
equipment manufacturers proclaimed themselves relieved and pleased.
</P>
<P>
   For now.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, major equipment makers in the $2.5 billion
industry, including Titleist and Spalding in Massachusetts, had
mounted a public relations offensive. They feared that the USGA,
the governing body of professional and recreational golf, was
poised to adopt Draconian restrictions that would even ban clubs
currently used on the professional tours and at the local country
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking a more conservative and rational approach and
they've done a good job of listening to the manufacturers and the
consumers,'' said Scott Kreelman, executive vice president of
Spalding.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers feared that the USGA would use the eve of the
US Open in San Francisco to announce new rules that would ban
several new clubs and balls and sharply curtail future research and
design.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of new technologies and the impact on the game is
being played out amid enormous stakes for the manufacturers and the
USGA alike.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers of clubs earned $1.7 billion in wholesale business
in 1997, an increase of 74 percent in just four years, according to
the National Golf Foundation, an industry-supported research group.
Manufacturers of golf balls made $667 million in wholesale business
last year, an increase of 23 percent from 1993.
</P>
<P>
   New USGA rules would strike at the heart of the industry, which
relies heavily on major advancements in technology to market new
products every few years. But when top USGA officials took the
microphones at The Olympic Club golf course in San Francisco
Wednesday, they were anything but confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not uncomfortable with what we see on the market
today,'' said David Fay, USGA executive director. ``We don't
believe that clubs submitted at this point have lessened the skill
to play the game at championships such as the US Open or at a
recreational level.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay and other USGA officials outlined a plan to establish a
formula to measure the ``spring-like effect'' that occurs when a
club face hits a ball. What the officials, and many golfers, are
concerned about is that new technology may be artificially putting
more power into shots.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for determining the maximum allowable effect will be
sent to manufacturers in a proposed protocol within the next few
weeks, Fay said. The companies will then be allowed the rest of the
summer to comment on the proposal, before meeting formally with the
USGA to discuss the issue further in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Fay also said that the USGA continues to examine golf balls in
an attempt to determine an acceptable level of design advancements.
He said no restrictions are currently contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   Some manufacturers, though, remain concerned that the USGA may
eventually seek to halt the enormous strides in technology that
have made clubs lighter, more accurate, and capable of striking a
ball farther.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USGA still feels it needs to protect the game from
equipment manufacturers, and I strongly disagree with that,'' said
Donald Dye, chief executive of Callaway Golf Co., the Carlsbad,
Calif., manufacturer that has led the way in club designs. ``But,
at least now, consumers will feel comfortable buying what we have
in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The USGA's concern is that younger, stronger players, combined
with space-age technology and materials, will overwhelm courses.
The association has already turned down a bid by the Merion Golf
Club outside of Philadelphia to host its fifth US Open because the
course is not long enough. Perhaps most alarmingly, the famed Old
Course at St. Andrews in Scotland is planning to lengthen its
layout, a massive bit of construction and landscaping that some in
the sport consider to be sacrilegious.
</P>
<P>
   And, on June 9, the Augusta National course, which annually
hosts the Masters tournament, announced plans to lengthen a few
holes and to add trees to counter the game's big hitters. Just a
year ago, Augusta said it would never consider such changes.
</P>
<P>
   The average drive on the PGA Tour has increased from 260 yards
to 269 yards in five years. In that time, several companies have
introduced clubs and balls, each promising to deliver easier,
longer, more accurate play. Perhaps the major factor in the
increase of sales of clubs is this repeated introduction of new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Titleist, a division of Fortune Brands in Fairhaven, and
Spalding, in Chicopee, control 70 percent of the market in golf
balls. Both companies have been fighting a continual war for market
share.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the battle is waged in company laboratories, where as
many as 50 research and design workers compete. New balls with new
promises of longer, more accurate flight are introduced virtually
every other year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spalding and Titleist are in a tong war right now,'' said
Richard Haskell, the retired executive director of the
Massachusetts Golf Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the companies are highly motivated by the bottom line
in terms of what they make and whatever advancements they can get
out on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Callaway is a strong example of how new designs lead to greater
sales. In 1989, the year before its revolutionary club, the Big
Bertha, was launched, the company reported sales of $20 million.
Last year, after consecutive progeny of Big Bertha were brought to
market, the company was reporting sales of $842 million. Sales now
surpass that of its four next rivals combined; before the birth of
Big Bertha, it was the sixth-largest club maker.
</P>
<P>
   And when it appeared that the USGA might eliminate the
large-headed clubs, Callaway's stock plunged, falling 54 percent in
the first quarter of this year. Wednesday, with the encouraging
announcement by the USGA, Callaway stock rose by 1 1/4, closing at
19 13/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5255 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-MARTIN-BOS &LR;      06-18 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASEY MARTIN DEBATE ROLLS ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was late Wednesday afternoon and Casey Martin
had just tapped his last stroke for fun before the start of the US
Open today. A downhill putt from directly above the hole on the
18th green of The Olympic Club, a seeming simple putt, but one that
snaked left, right, and left once again _ three breaks within 10
feet _ and then Martin walked away from his practice round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey?'' a media member approached Martin just above the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got one question,'' said Martin, not in petulance, not
in anger, but not in any need to practice for the media anymore,
either, ``so make it good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the basic ``how do you feel heading into your first
Open?'' question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' replied Martin, the words pouring out
quickly. ``People have treated me great ... the USGA has treated me
great ... I'm just overwhelmed ... it's wonderful ... OK?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer wasn't much better than the question, but at least it
was finished in 10 seconds. Martin then headed up the steep hill
from the 18th green to the clubhouse. Here Martin was so much more
at home, stopping to autograph an Olympic pin for this boy, a
charcoal drawing of the Olympic clubhouse for this woman, an
Olympic hat for that man, a golf ball for this boy, and a US Open
program for that girl. From one side and to other of the gallery
ropes Martin alternated, signing everything, answering every call
of ``Casey?'' with his attention and then his pen.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, Martin had walked the 30 yards the
clubhouse. His limp had not seemed as pronounced on the uphill walk
as it had on the golf course, but his wide smile was as warm as
this Pacific day itself. It had been just as wide on the golf
course, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Martin teed off on the 11th hole, for instance, Mark
Cunningham, a 33-year-old from Sacramento, was waiting below the
tee. Cunningham recently had cancer surgery and he made a point to
head out to Olympic ``just so I could see Casey.'' The club and
USGA had provided Cunningham with a one-person cart _ exactly like
the one that misfired for Martin during an earlier practice round _
so he could get around the hilly course.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham motored his cart from hole to hole just as Martin,
now with a regulation two-person cart, motored from hole to hole,
parking it at spots USGA official Jerry Waterman suggested, leaving
it behind a green here or off to the side of a green there.
Cunningham, though, knew he had parked his cart at exactly the
right spot there just below the 11th tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casey?'' shouted Cunningham to Martin. ``Casey?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin spotted him and came over to Cunningham. Martin gave his
autograph to an ecstatic Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger who?'' shouted Cunningham. ``There's only one golfer,
it's Casey.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, time and again and again and again, Martin's
popularity immense. Indeed, the whole debate over the bedrock
principle of sport _ competition is not competition unless all
compete under the same rules _ and whether Martin and his cart have
violated that principle can be conducted in the abstract.
</P>
<P>
   To little avail, though.
</P>
<P>
   That's because with Martin limping so painfully once he steps
from his cart and moves to his ball, the debate seems to melt away
as it moves so vividly from abstract to reality. And, after a hole
or two, the cart seems barely noticed. Except when Martin is about
to park it near a green and needs to consult wih USGA officials
about where to park it, or what's the best route to the next tee.
</P>
<P>
   But, for those who have not seen Martin, who have not seen his
long and powerful drives, his irons flying on a string to the
green, and then his limp, the principle of sport _ the same rules
for all _ is more compelling. Jack Nicklaus typifies this opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Nicklaus said earlier this week. ``I met Casey
a long time ago and I said hello to him. But I don't know him at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But golf's legend once again repeated his opinion that a court
of law should not be fiddling with the bedrock principle of sport.
``I don't like the (court ruling) as it relates to the game of
golf,'' said Nicklaus, pointedly distguishing between what the
ruling did for Martin and what Nicklaus believes the ruling will do
for golf. ``But I understand the ruling and, from Casey's
standpoint, I am delighted for him as an individual. But I worry
what its ramifications are for the game of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin is now a celebrity and celebrity now means more than
substance in America. Americans with disabilities have rights.
Courts have now intervened in sports through the Americans with
Disabilities Act. But for Nicklaus, there is a law stronger than
any court ruling, stronger than any President's order, stronger
than any act of Congress that worries him _ the Law of Unintended
Consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not questioning what Casey Martin the individual is,''
said Nicklaus. ``I am just questioning what is really the ultimate
question, what is happening to the game of golf. But somebody else
along the line is going to use (the court's ruling), I promise you.
I promise you it's going to happen, that somebody's going to come
in and say he sprained his ankle. `I sprained my ankle; I need to
have something.'''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, said Nicklaus, some other golfer not so clearly
disabled as Martin is going to demand a cart ``and you are going to
have a mess someplace. I promise you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson agrees with Nicklaus. ``The compassion must go to
Casey,'' said Watson. ``I wish him well. It's a tough position the
Tour has taken, but I think the Tour is right in the sense that the
game should be played walking. The compassion goes from me to
Casey. He's got a powerful golf swing and it's a shame that he has
that affliction. That creates a problem for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Switch now to golfers who know Martin, to those who know the
person as much as the principle of sport. The abstract melts so
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that Casey qualified,'' said Tiger Woods, a
teammate of Martin's at Stanford. ``He earned his way out here. I
think it's great. And I think it showed a lot of courage on his
part to deal with all the things he had to deal with, with the
lawsuit and all the distractions of trying to play golf. Casey
shows a lot of guts. This is what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are others, who tread the diplomat's path. Colin
Montgomerie typifies that group. ``I think it's great for him to
qualify the way he did,'' said the Scot. ``I wish him all the
success because none of us would like to be in the position that
he's in.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you feel about Martin's riding a cart?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not for me to discuss,'' replied Montgomerie. ``That
is for the USGA and R&AMP;A (Royal and Ancient) to discuss. That is not
for me to comment on. I just wish him every success.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, for his part, said earlier in the week that he
understood the comments from Nicklaus and Watson ``and I don't hold
anything against them. I just don't agree with them.'' As much as
anything, said Martin, this week of his first Open, is one in which
``I'm just trying to relax and have fun and, you know, enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   The bedrock principle of sport conflicted with a golfer's desire
to golf. As Casey Martin played his final practice round Wednesday,
snippets of debate could be heard on virtually every hole from the
gallery, such as this from the seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for him. He has a right to play,'' argued one man.
Only to be countered by his companion, ``But carry it all the way
through. Say a guy's handicapped and wants to play in the NBA and
says he has a right to play in the NBA and if he weren't
handicapped, he'd be good enough to be in the NBA. Should a court
allow him to play in the NBA in a wheelchair?''
</P>
<P>
   Martin may or may have heard this, but he already has heard all
the words. ``I am a Christian,'' said Martin. ``I have been
trusting Jesus with my life and He has been a faithful friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Abstract principle, human courage, a clash open for all to see
this week in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
