<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-COURSE-BOS &LR;      06-18 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-COURSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A GIVEN: THE 17TH IS A KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A gallery surrounding a green at a United States
Open will cheer anything, much like parents at a nursery school
recital. Even the mere fact of putter meeting ball. Anything to
justify seven hours of forced whispering, $7 hamburgers, and $5
croissants.
</P>
<P>
   But what reverberates loudest in the memory banks from the 1987
US Open at the Olympic Club is the silence of the gallery at the
17th green day after day. The sounds of silence. It was gruesome,
golfer after golfer trudging off the 17th tee to the 18th green, a
few ``tsk-tsks'' heard but so little applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally do not like the 17th hole,'' Bernhard Langer said
back then, a few minutes after walking off the green in a cloak of
silence, not even perfunctory applause. ``It is the worst golf hole
I've ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogeys do not garner applause and double bogeys generate averted
eyes and maybe a tactful glance away from the golfer and toward the
streets of San Francisco, which run by the 17th hole. Golf
galleries are polite, if anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what they can do with this hole,'' Dave
Eichelberger said 11 years ago after smudging his score card on the
17th. ``They can take a stick of dynamite to it and blow it up.
Matter of fact, they should.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17th symbolizes the Olympic Club; all three Opens played
here have had their destinies decided on the final holes, destinies
that have swatted three golf greats _ Ben Hogan, Arnold Palmer, and
Tom Watson _ and elevated one total unknown, Jack Fleck, one near
anonymity, Scott Simpson, and one other, Billy Casper.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the 17th that caused angst for virtually every golfer
on virtually every day of the three Opens played at Olympic, a
course as baroque as San Francisco itself. The course has 40,000
trees, is held hostage by winds off the Pacific Ocean, and, while
very short for an Open course _ only 6,800 yards _ is fickle and
subtle and nuanced.
</P>
<P>
   The 17th, Olympic's toughest hole, once was a 520-yard par-5 but
was shortened by some anonymous USGA Director of Masochism to a
428-yard par-4 for the three Opens played here. More recently, it
has been lengthened again.
</P>
<P>
   Still, golfers feel Olympic has tinkered with God's master plan.
The 17th is a dogleg left that slopes right; even in San Francisco,
a dogleg left that slopes right is deviancy.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1987, Bob Gilder was so exasperated by his bogey on the
17th that he approached a USGA official off to the side of the
green and said he wouldn't move from that spot unless the USGA did
something about the hole. Gilder had driven his ball not simply to
Position A of the 17th fairway but to Position A-Plus, cutting the
dogleg perfectly and the having the ball land on the fairway near
the edge of the left rough.
</P>
<P>
   Gilder then watched in fury as his ball was caught by the right
downslope of the fairway and began rolling ... and rolling ... and
rolling ... until it rolled all the way off the right edge of the
fairway into the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, has it been mentioned that in the landing area the fairway
was all of 21 yards wide?
</P>
<P>
   And has it been mentioned that Gilder and virtually all the
golfers who had hit perfect drives but still ended up in the rough
now had a side-hill lie as they tried to hit a 3- or 4-iron from
the rough to an elevated green?
</P>
<P>
   ``You could really question whether the 17th should be a par-4
or a par-5,'' Roger Maltbie said the last time the Open was played
at Olympic. ``But the green is really designed for a par-5. It's a
very severe green to begin with, and it's designed to receive short
shots. But when you're blasting a 2-iron or 3-iron to the green
from the rough uphill to that green, well, you're thrilled if
you're just on the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, for the record, Gilder isn't still standing on that
spot next to the 17th green. He finally consented to move after the
USGA official he accosted promised that the grounds crew would not
use its Triplex mowers, which many courses use on greens _ for the
final two days of '87 Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a green on this course as fast as the fairway on
17,'' Jack Nicklaus said in 1987. ``There was a joke going around
that the Stimpmeter (a device that measures the speed of greens)
measures the speed of a ball on linoleum at 12, the green at 9, but
it reads the 17th fairway at 10.''
</P>
<P>
   But the USGA, once meanies who bent no ear to criticism, have
listened to the complaints of the golfers. This 1998 US Open at
Olympic will have an altered 17th hole, as the USGA tries to show
its softer side.
</P>
<P>
   The solution?
</P>
<P>
   Make the 17th a par-5 again, as it was designed?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, no.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the USGA has kept the 17th a par-4 but has moved the
tee back 40 yards, so that it is now a 468-yard par-4 and golfers
will have to hit even longer irons into a green built to receive
soft wedges. And, yes, it is still a dogleg left that slopes right,
but the slope in the new landing area is not as severe as in the
old one.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA may have gone soft, but the pros are not conned. They
know only one golfer will be atop Olympic heights late Sunday; the
rest will have wallowed in Olympic depths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fog billows and wind often bellows over the Lake Course of
Olympic, which Bobby Jones once described as ``the best in the
West'' and Ben Hogan said was his favorite Open course. Of course,
this being San Francisco _ where the normal can be abnormal _
eyebrows are not raised over there being not a single lake on the
Lake Course. But there is much else.
</P>
<P>
   There is no such thing as a flat lie on this course. When Mac
O'Grady finished his tour of Olympic in 1987, he sat in the
clubhouse, tapped a table in front of him, and said he was relieved
to find something _ anything _ at Olympic that was flat. Side-hill
lies are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers face shots at Olympic that they seldom, if ever, face
elsewhere. That's because so many of the fairways, not just the
17th, are reverse-banked, which means they are banked in the
opposite direction of their slope. Modern golf architects never
would dare attempt to get away with a hole such as the 17th or the
fourth, both reverse-banked dog-legs left.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic's galleries often wear parkas and mittens in June,
reminding one of Mark Twain: ``The longest winter in my life was
the summer I spent in San Francisco.'' Olympic is an evening-gowned
vampire, every fairway lush but sloped, every rough so
innocent-looking from afar but so inescapable when found.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Olympic's greens are minuscule and tiered. ``Olympic is
such a hard course,'' said Johnny Miller, a San Franciscan who grew
up playing the layout. ``Olympic's greens would be difficult to
approach from flat lies.'' But there are no flat lies, so golfers
must hit from those side-hill lies, said Miller, ``to the smallest
greens you'll ever see.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the weather is nice, Olympic can be nice. Despite all the
griping from the pros, there were 24 sub-par rounds on the Friday
of the 1987 Open, trying a tournament record. And more golfers made
the cut in that Open than had made the cut in any previous Open ...
despite the slope of the fairways and despite the greens of
postage-stamp size.
</P>
<P>
   For Tiger Woods, the Olympic experience may be mind-fraying.
Woods has said that ``the most difficult courses for me are where
they've narrowed the fairways in the landing area'' _ which is par
for all Open courses, of course, but at Olympic, the landing areas
in the fairways seem all the more narrow because of the sloping
fairways.
</P>
<P>
   And Woods would not be the first ``name'' to have been humbled
by Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Ben Hogan thought he had won a record fifth US Open
when Fleck, an unknown club pro, birdied the 18th hole and forced a
Monday playoff, which Fleck won. That was the end of the Ben Hogan
era of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven years later, Arnold Palmer was up by seven strokes with a
mere nine holes to play when he decided _ the Open victory clearly
his _ to go for Hogan's scoring Open record. To this day, the 1966
Open is a touchy and sensitive subject with Palmer, as Casper
caught him on the 18th, forcing a playoff, which Casper easily won
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th hole on that Sunday is still etched in the memories of
Olympic members and golf fans. On the 18th tee, Casper listened to
his intuition and, instead of the iron he had used in three
previous rounds, chose a driver which he used to put the ball
squarely in the middle of the fairway. Palmer, with that so-quick
and so-flat swing that could so easily cause trouble, hit one of
his common shots, a hook into the left rough. Instead of thinking
about Hogan's record, Palmer was left thinking of how Hogan had
been caught by Fleck. Which Palmer was.
</P>
<P>
   The 1966 Open was the end of the Arnold Palmer era of golf.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Tom Watson took a one-stroke lead into the final round,
but Simpson birdied 14, 15, and the 609-yard 16th _ a truly
memorable series of consecutive birdies _ to edge Watson by a
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   That 1987 Open was the end of the Tom Watson era of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Three of golf's all-time greats saw their careers turn on
Olympic's slopes and begin their slides downhill, faster ... and
faster ... and faster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
