<P>
   CHINA-MOTOROLA _ BEIJING _ Motorola, determined to grow into a
$2.5 billion business in China by the year 2000, on Thursday held a
festive grand opening for the 1,000 headquarters employees who
moved into the company's 18-story North Asia Center headquarters at
one of the most prestigious spots in downtown Beijing. And on June
29, with President Clinton in town, Motorola will take one more
step toward that goal when it signs a $225 million agreement in the
Great Hall of the People to expand a semiconductor component plant
that already makes 1.4 billion components a year. One of the
striking features of the new building is a mockup, about 10 feet
tallk of a Chinese Long March rocket that launches Motorola's
Iridium satellites. The rocket mockup stands in the center of the
Motorola's mini-museum on the first floor of the Asia center.
Reporters weren't allowed to enter the building officially and
weren't invited to the opening. A corporate PR vice president
assures in an interview afterword that the expansion in China isn't
linked to the cutback of 15,000 Motorola jobs elsewhere in the
word. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photo available on the Associated Press photo wire.
</P>
