<HEADER>
A5280 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-X-FILES-FILM-HNS &LR;      06-18 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-FILES-FILM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE X-FILES' STICKS WITH FORMULA OF SUCCESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The truth is . . . out there on the big screen. ``The X-Files''
is selling the same thing it sells on television. Selling it very
well.
</P>
<P>
   The packaging is bigger, brighter and a lot more expensive, but
creator/producer/writer Chris Carter has wisely stuck with the
formula that has been so successful for him and his
weirdness-besieged FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   That means lots of dark lighting, clandestine meetings in
alleys, gross, yucky dead bodies, strange things only half-seen
and, of course, the emotionally-intimate teamwork of agents Scully
and Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Even the title, ``The X-Files,'' is the same. ``Fight the
future'' is just an advertising slogan.
</P>
<P>
   To appeal to a wider audience, Carter has thrown a few scenes of
background information into the movie. He's added some light jokes
that are more accessible than the dark humor of the show. The
heroes, FBI agents Scully and Mulder, play a running game of
``gotcha.'' When Mulder can't find a restroom in a bar, he seeks
relief in an alley on a poster of ``Independence Day''.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the movie is complicated and can only explain so much.
So, in what follows, there is some basic background information.
</P>
<P>
   Plot? Oh come on, you didn't really expect us to tell you that,
did you? Well, maybe a few tips, off the record, but nothing
classified.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Agents Dana Scully (Gillian Anderson) and Fox Mulder (David
Duchovny) have spent the last five years investigating X-files
cases, strange phenomena relating to space aliens and other
mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder, who saw his sister Samantha abducted by what he believed
were aliens when he was young, tends to accept anything as
possible. Scully, a doctor, is a skeptic, assigned to Mulder to
keep him grounded in reality. Or maybe she's just there to make
sure his investigations don't get too near (ominous drum roll) The
Truth.
</P>
<P>
   After all that time together, Scully and Mulder still see most
things differently, yet they have a very close relationship.
Strictly professional, but close.
</P>
<P>
   Many people have obstructed their investigations. This includes
a mysterious international syndicate of elderly men who have some
connection to the aliens.
</P>
<P>
   As the fifth season of the TV series closed, several weeks ago,
the X-files were shut down. Mulder and Scully were re-assigned to
the FBI terrorism detail.
</P>
<P>
   When we first see them in the movie, they are investigating a
bomb threat at a federal office building in Dallas. Mulder finds
the bomb, but too late to prevent catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   (The image of the bombed-out building is a coldly manipulative
recreation of the Oklahoma City bombing, meant to give the movie
resonance by playing off reality and our emotions. It's tasteless
and disturbing.)
</P>
<P>
   The bombing is just a cover-up. North of Dallas, some kids (one
of whom is now grossly dead) recently discovered an ancient cave
where something very inhuman is living in the form of an oozing
black oil. The boy's remains were in the bombed building.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder is tipped off to the cover-up by Dr. Kurtzweil, a
gynecologist who moonlights as a conspiracy nut. Martin Landau, in
the movie's best performance, is perfectly cast as the haunted and
hunted Kurtzweil.
</P>
<P>
   How far out are Kurtzweil's theories? When he explains them to
Mulder in a dark alley behind a bar, Mulder says, ``They call me
paranoid.''
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI holds hearings to blame the Dallas explosion on
Mulder and Scully, Mulder gets drunk in a bar and briefly explains
the premise of the series to a bartender. The scene plays as an
inside joke for fans and a catch-up for non-fans.
</P>
<P>
   Between hearings, Scully and Mulder flit around the country,
following trains, hiding in corn fields, groping through a morgue
(an ``X-Files'' staple) and meeting in dark alleys. The mysterious
syndicate, which we see quite a bit in this movie, tries to keep
the aliens and its relationship to the aliens secret.
</P>
<P>
   How serious is the alien threat to humanity? Here's a hint from
a member of the syndicate: ``We are nothing but digestives for a
new race of alien life forms.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder we're pulling for Scully and Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   The climax finds Mulder trying to locate Scully in the vast
emptiness of Antarctica. At least, it appears to be a vast
emptiness. It is here that some of the series' Big Questions are
answered, sort of. And much of the movie's big budget is expended.
</P>
<P>
   How good is the movie? If you are a fan, it's pretty darn good.
</P>
<P>
   But also aggravating if you are expecting answers to all your
questions. Why on earth would Carter want to give us that? The
thing that keeps ``The X-Files'' interesting is NOT knowing the
answers. (Besides, Carter hasn't made them all up yet.) A few
questions are answered, and a few suspected answers are clarified.
</P>
<P>
   The movie looks very good, still dark and moody but with some
big action scenes and special effects. But if you are expecting
total disclosure, or ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' meets James Bond,
you are doomed to disappointment. ``The X-Files'' on screen is just
a good, big-budget episode of ``The X-Files'' on TV. Expect that
going in and you will be pleased, not disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The movie could not incorporate all the characters or plot
elements from the show. Significantly missing is the sister
Samantha story line. Carter actually wrote a few sentences about
Samantha into the show, but cut them out as confusing to non-fans.
Maybe next season.
</P>
<P>
   Also absent: the little chess-playing boy from the last TV
episode, agent Krycek, the alien bounty-hunter and many more. You
will, however, see plenty of cigarette-smoking man, well-manicured
man, the syndicate, bees, black oil and . . . but that's telling
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Now the big question for some fans: Do Scully and Mulder kiss?
If you haven't heard this on the grapevine or internet yet, why
should we spoil it? Let's just say Carter manages to have his
little joke twice in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not a fan already, it's pretty hard to imagine what
this movie can offer you. You'll be able to follow the story and
action well enough, even if some of the ``X-Files'' mumbo-jumbo is
blurry. But you won't have the investment in Scully and Mulder to
make it seem important.
</P>
<P>
   Director Rob Bowman, who often directs the TV show, has done a
good if not spectacular job of giving the show a movie size. The
pace is rapid but not frenetic. And the look by Bowman and director
of photography Ward Russell is dark and shadowy when needed, but
makes use of budgets and sets that let them open up to more light
and scale.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a special effects story, but when effects are
needed, they are convincing enough.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is all solid, though only Landau really grabs our
attention. Armin Mueller-Stahl and Blythe Danner are seen only
briefly as new characters.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson and Duchovny essential come off as they do on TV, not
exactly knocking us over on screen, but sufficient. Anderson's
intensity sometimes overwhelms Duchovny. There's even a joke in the
movie about Mulder's stone face being not much different from his
worried or scared face.
</P>
<P>
   As on the show, Mulder usually gets the best lines and most
action, while Scully tags along saying, ``Mulder, wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Will you need to see the movie to understand the show next
season? No, not really. A few things change, a character or two
dies (or seems to). But by the end, we're pretty much back where we
started. Just like on TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``THE X-FILES &UR; '' &QL; 
 &LR; Starring: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson, Martin Landau &QL; 
Opening: Friday &QL; 
Rated: PG-13 for some intense violence and gore. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
