<P>
   NY-CENTENNIAL-FESTIVAL (New York) _ New York's music is the
world's music, the sound of every group to arrive since the Dutch
were met by the Indians. To commemorate the centennial of the
annexation of Brooklyn and the consolidation of the five boroughs
into one city, the musical celebration will be as varied, scattered
and unpredictable as the city itself. From brass bands to Central
American punta music to jazz, oldies and alternative rock, the
centennial offers glimpses of New York's many musical worlds. By
Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   BONNARD-RETROSPECTIVE (New York) _ When Pierre Bonnard died in
1947, at 79, Cahiers d'Art published an editorial by Christian
Zervos, one of Picasso's mouthpieces. Picasso called Bonnard a
piddler. He said: ``Don't talk to me about Bonnard, that's not
painting, what he does.'' And worse: ``He is not really a modern
painter.'' Zervos parroted Picasso's view, and since Cahiers d'Art
was the most influential art magazine, his opinion spread. The
Bonnard retrospective opening on Sunday at the Museum of Modern Art
should change some minds. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   BRADY-PORTRAIT-EXHIBIT (New York) _ ``Mathew Brady's Portraits:
Images as History, Photography as Art,'' at the International
Center of Photography Midtown, is billed as ``the first time since
his studio closed over a century ago that the full range of his
work is gathered together in one place.'' Mary Panzer, curator of
photographs at the National Portrait Gallery of the Smithsonian
Institution, which organized the exhibition, selected more than 100
images for this show, including Civil War photographs. She also
wrote the accompanying book, ``Mathew Brady and the Image of
History'' (Smithsonian Institution Press). By Vicki Goldberg.
