<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ This time around, Japan may have actually
put some teeth into the effort to clean up the nation's debt-ridden
banks. In trading Thursday, the yen held its gains against the
dollar and Asian stock prices soared, jumping 4.4 percent in Tokyo
and 6.4 percent in Hong Kong. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-ASSESS (Washington) _ The United States has embarked on a
risky strategy to prevent a broader meltdown of economies around
the globe, from Russia to Latin America. The problem, Clinton aides
readily admit, is that the huge currency intervention the United
States launched Wednesday actually takes some of the pressure off
Japan to act _ and unless Japan acts, the temporary effects of
buying yen will be washed away. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The trade deficit in goods and
services jumped in April as exports tumbled because of Asia's deep
downturn. The higher-than-expected trade gap suggested that
economic growth in the United States is slowing, easing inflation
fears but underscoring American vulnerability to the worsening
situation across the Pacific. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Undated) _ South Korea's Financial Supervisory
Commission, the new regulatory watchdog for the nation's ailing
financial system, signs a virtual death warrants for 55 companies
that it deems unviable. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-INFOSEEK (Undated) _ Seeking a bigger presence on the
Internet, Disney buys 43 percent of Infoseek, a company that helps
users navigate the World Wide Web, in exchange for $70 million and
Disney's majority holding in Starwave. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   GM-AUTO-STRIKE (Detroit) _ Developments in the strike by UAW
workers against General Motors. . By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN-MORGAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Lehman Brothers and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter post earnings for the latest quarter that are
considerably higher than expected. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The Dow was flat at midday, and the long
bond was up 12/32 point, with the yield at 5.71 percent. The dollar
stood at 137.27 yen, down from 136.37 yen in late New York trading
Wednesday. By David Barboza.
</P>
