<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-JOHNSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIRKY DESIGNER IGNORES CRITICISM TO PURSUE HER OWN VISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Playful designer Betsey Johnson's April runway
show in New York took a very bad hit from the fashion press. Trashy
and irrelevant. Tasteless. Over-the-top. Unsalable.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Johnson, the 55-year-old sprite who started her career 30
years ago designing for the ultra-hip Paraphernalia and Betsey
Bunky Nini stores, thought her show was a shot in the arm. ``It
turned out phenomenally for us. The press just didn't understand
it. I wanted to establish myself more as: Me. Special. Cool. Hip.
Hot. I had to go to extremes. I felt that I was losing my creative
designer personality on the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shows are so much more unrealistic,'' chimes in Lulu
Johnson, Betsey's 23-year-old daughter and design partner.
Johnson-the-Younger is in charge of the new, pricier Ultra line.
``Still, Betsey can't stand to see a model dressed head-to-toe
properly like you'd be on the street. With Betsey, you have to use
your imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a regular fixture in San Francisco in 1987 when her
first boutique went in and she was painting Pippi
Longstocking-on-speed self-portraits on Pepto Bismol-pink walls.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't changed all that much since then. Her quirky style
remains the same: She dresses like a rich hippie with a combination
of flash (real diamonds combined with rhinestone rocks) and trash
(a slip dress designed to show off her black lace bra).
</P>
<P>
   She does her signature cartwheels on the runway at the close of
her shows in cut-offs. And in her gold and orange hair, she has
more extensions than the telephone company. She got married last
August to Brian Reynolds, a Briton, and, for the last year, she has
flown into the San Francisco area almost every weekend to stay with
Brian and his teen-agers at their home in Atherton.
</P>
<P>
   On her way to London, she decided on this recent pass-through to
do some press and press the flesh of the society kids.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is: They're not Johnson's core customer _ women who are
not afraid to rock 'n' roll and show some copious breastage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it when the rock stars and hip-hop girls come into the
store,'' Johnson enthused over caviar and Champagne at the Balboa
Cafe last week. Her current hit list includes Drew Barrymore,
Madonna, Salt-N-Pepa, 'Lil Kim, Minnie Driver and Helena Bonham
Carter. Closer to home, novelist Danielle Steel shops for her
teen-agers at Betsey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The new collection, called ``Starlet,'' is
Fredericks-of-Hollywood-meets-Coolio. Models frowned down the
runway wearing long bicolored and platinum blond wigs, scanty
lingerie, burn-out velvet slip dresses cut so close you could read
their DNA, hipbone-skimming pants and puffy, quilted lame coats
lined in fake fur, the latter an obvious steal from hip-hop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, always fascinated with old-fashioned tattoo ``flash''
art, features denims with red, gold and blue flash patterns
translated to bustiers, bra tops, muscle T's and scanty bikinis
(for men), and women's bikini's (shown on Victoria's Secret
supermodel Stephanie Seymour, wearing little more than panties, a
monkey fur coat and a black-lipsticked scowl).
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as this show really helped me re-establish my energy
and where I'm going in terms of extreme fashion,'' says Johnson,
``it is not a true reflection of what is salable.''
</P>
<P>
   She explains that she designs 40 to 50 new pieces for her 23
boutiques each month. ``Our best customer is in the store two to
three times a week and we always want to have something fresh and
new for them.''
</P>
<P>
   She listens to her store managers and her salespeople about what
her ``girls'' want.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Betsey customer has more of a choice. With ``Starlet,''
she has established the genesis of a lingerie line. Also, in the
New York and Los Angeles boutiques, what was seen on the runway is
available, like couture, for custom customers, women like Madonna,
who will come in and drop $3,000 on tulle bras or gold-mesh dresses
_ reconfigured with nude slips or linings.
</P>
<P>
   It is a look. Definitely a look, this Betsey Johnson thing. Not
just cute dimity-patterned dresses, which are really Liberty of
London silks over-dyed in tropical colors just like the
lavender-and-turquoise slip dresses worn by Johnson and Johnson
over lunch, but a full range: from uber-Goth, fully covered dresses
and skirts that were so popular last season to this year's
body-revealing designs that have taken their cue from Johnson's
love affair with hip-hop culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom seems to be getting younger and younger,'' jokes Lulu
who, like her mother, sports a lightening bolt tattoo over her left
breast. Lulu is the one who tells her mom to cool it, that
sometimes she's getting too far out.
</P>
<P>
   And most of the time, Betsey listens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
