<HEADER>
A5308 &Cx1f; ttg-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(JT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 HER FATHER'S DAUGHTER   (For release Sun., June 21)   By SUSAN SWARTZ    
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was thinking about my dad while I was stuck in high grass with
a mulish lawn mower, cursing each unsuccessful yank of the cord and
sneezing my head off.
</P>
<P>
   I inherited his allergies. Also, his impatience and probably an
instinct to verbally abuse machines that don't go.
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, teach me how to mow the lawn. That was his
Saturday morning chore. He'd be mowing like a maniac in the air
thick with pollen and dust and exploding with ferocious sneezes
that were louder than the mower. Eventually, with a red and wet
face, he'd appear at the kitchen door, announce that it was
``hotter than the hub of Hades'' and go for his reward, one of his
Genesee beers kept at room temperature in the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of my allergy attack, I smiled thinking how much my
father would have cringed over my free-form mowing style. He always
started at the same corner by the garage and finished at the other
corner, near the creek, making perfect right angle turns.
</P>
<P>
   Often, when I indulge in haphazardness or do something
spontaneous or lavish I think of him. He was a man of such
exactness and economy that it caused my sister and I to grow up and
commit small rebellions. These include tipping more than the
standard amount and jumping fully clothed into swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't until my epiphany in high grass that I saw I
owe more to him than I'd been crediting.
</P>
<P>
   I think my dad helped give me a voice. I didn't realize that
before because my memory is full of him keeping the peace at the
dinner table. If anyone would start to say something disagreeable,
his classic warning was ``don't go upsetting your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this I used to say that my father liked to stifle
free speech, but I wasn't being altogether fair. Maybe he felt a
need to protect my mother. Maybe he'd been taught by his own father
to not upset his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, my father was open to debate, as long as my mother
wasn't in the room. The two of us haggled. We stormed. Over
household rules and who I could or couldn't date. I can't remember
many topics that were all that engaging, except for our furies over
Nixon and Watergate. But we enjoyed the sparring.
</P>
<P>
   To go even further, I could probably say my father made it OK to
stand up for my opinions. His was the first authority I challenged
and because I wasn't punished or resented for expressing myself I
kind of kept on.
</P>
<P>
   While I never heard him exclaim that women should have the same
rights, advantages and opportunities as men, he never advised me to
be quiet and submit graciously to a man's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible my dad encouraged me to be a feminist. Isn't that
something?
</P>
<P>
   I was always my mother's daughter. I have no trouble coming up
with what I get from her, including some aspects of her looks and
personality. In the special way children romanticize their parents
after they're gone, I think of my mother when I see sunsets and
hear certain piano tunes and walk in the garden in bare feet.
</P>
<P>
   As for my father, I know I can't stand owing people even a cup
of coffee because of how he'd go on about moochers. I know he liked
hot peppers and couldn't abide a limp handshake but I didn't know
his yearnings or where he looked for magic.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't know him like I knew my mother because he was an old
style dad. Mothers were everyday. Fathers were weekends and
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't spend a lot of time with him. Most of the time his nose
was to the grindstone because that's what his generation of dads
did. He was the bread winner, the head of the family, the king of
his castle. Those are roles that don't allow much intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Some who worry about the breakdown of the American family blame
it on fathers abdicating their rightful rule. They want to restore
control to dads, but I think they would be taking something
precious away if they did that.
</P>
<P>
   The way it is now with many families, both parents have to work.
Indeed, both often desire to work. But, no matter the motivation,
both workers also have to be parents.
</P>
<P>
   When moms work late, dads have to leave early to drive to ballet
school. Dads as well as moms take lunch hours to go see the
principal. Dads, too, know the names and phone numbers of their
kid's friends and stay home when the third grader has a stomach
ache.
</P>
<P>
   Those who would return us to the Fifties Dad forget that heads
of households were pretty clueless on what was going on at home.
Fathers checked in to administer punishment, pat you on the head
and ask how school was going. Many of today's fathers know more
about family matters than their own dads ever guessed at.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that dads cook and grocery shop and know when it's
time to buy vitamins, they're also accessible. If that's because
Mom isn't there for the time being, the kids still win.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's important to honor your father. But you get to
know him better if he's in the kitchen and not on some throne.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
