A5311 &Cx1f; ttg-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER GAVE DAD A NEW PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDITOR'S NOTE: In an annual ritual, Jim Loftus is celebrating
Father's Day by writing a column in place of his wife, Mary Loftus,
a columnist for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. Here are his
reflections on fatherhood:) (JT)  
 By JIM LOFTUS    
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sonogram was inconclusive. The doctor vague. ``Could be a
girl,'' he told me, ``but don't paint the baby's room pink just
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't need to be told that. In almost half a century, the
number of women in my immediate family numbered exactly one: my
mother. Of four siblings and six cousins, all but one were male. My
father had sons. I had a son. My brothers had sons.
</P>
<P>
   These were my thoughts in the days just prior to my second
child's birth. During that wait, I performed the daddy equivalent
of ``nesting'' _ wandering the toy section of department stores.
Since I was anticipating another boy, I was standing in a deserted
aisle admiring the latest MicroMachine playset when something
bumped my shoulder from behind. I turned around to find a Barbie
doll that had fallen off a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   It was an omen.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later I was the father of Sarah, an 8-pound, 2-ounce
baby girl.
</P>
<P>
   Having had no sisters, I was befuddled by a daughter. My son and
I bonded immediately, and to this day, I need only lose my adult
veneer to enter his world of action figures, miniature cars and
dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   A few days after this Father's Day, Sarah will be 2 years old. I
have yet to overcome my confused wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Since Adam was a toddler, we would tussle and pillow fight on
the bed until we were exhausted. When I roughhouse with Sarah, she
tries to figure out the game but ends up bewildered more often than
not.
</P>
<P>
   Adam's Godzilla toy frightens her.
</P>
<P>
   Building with blocks and knocking them down bores her.
</P>
<P>
   I've decided Sarah has taken it upon herself to teach me about
daughters. I am learning to play with dolls.
</P>
<P>
   I am learning that stuffed, cuddly animals may not be used as
handy missiles in a playroom battle.
</P>
<P>
   I am learning the names of Winnie the Pooh's playmates. (I am a
softer Dad. A low-volume Dad. A now-I-have-a-daughter Dad.)
</P>
<P>
   When my father visited last month, he spent hours sitting in his
favorite over-stuffed chair with Sarah on his lap. The patriarch of
five boys, my dad knows nothing of daughters, or granddaughters,
but his relationship with Sarah is one of enchantment. He simply
delights in her and the novelty of her gender.
</P>
<P>
   I envy that.
</P>
<P>
   But being her dad is more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah has made me an ardent feminist. To have a daughter is to
never look at women the same way again. It's impossible to imagine
her being anything but the best person for the job ... any job she
wants.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dad thing, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Loftus, a former journalist and sheriff's detective, is now
head of corporate security for Rooms to Go. He wrote this for The
Ledger of Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
