<SLUG> BC-FASHION-GOWNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA GOWNS: SPARE THE FIGURE BUT NOT THE POCKETBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For women searching for the perfect gown for the
opera this fall, be warned. You'd better have the perfect figure
and be at least 5-feet-8-inches. And have a very hefty checkbook.
</P>
<P>
   At least that was the main message at the Nordstrom opera gown
show given in conjunction with the San Francisco Opera Guild last
week. In the main, it was: minimalist, pared down, body-hugging and
figure-revealing stuff with no sleeves, low or no backs, glamorous
but inconvenient trains, and decolletage for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   With one proviso: If you have any kind of breasts at all, save
them for Michael Casey, who still respects a womanly anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom did away with the usual stark white ramp and allowed
the models to pose in constructed, froufrou vignettes of rococo
chairs and crystal chandeliers that dotted the store's fifth-floor
corporate dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Nordstrom stylist decided to gild the lily on
a large number of gowns by copying Dolce and Gabbana's silk floral
corsages and plopping huge globs of live flowers onto the
shoulders, waists and lower backs of gowns, obscuring the lines. It
was garish and unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 80 dresses shown, several were drop-dead sizzlers,
including a powder blue lace John Galliano for Christian Dior. It
was frilly, quite Parisian, and would look smashing on a tall,
toned person of the blond persuasion. Melinda Eng, a Seattle-based
designer, is probably the find of the show. Her pared-down clothing
with the (fairly) reasonable price tags were youthful, without
being too girlish, and almost Vera Wang-ish in their simplicity.
And Randolph Duke-for-Halston's gowns are glamour personified.
</P>
<P>
   Nordstrom showed the sleek-as-paint cranberry jersey that Minnie
Driver wore to the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wang's long, bronze coat with the jeweled cuffs over
a self-gown of silk charmeuse was absolutely traffic stopping.
Michael Casey's fairy princess gown with a dropped waist bodice of
gold and silver embroidery and huge silver tulle skirt was the
prettiest full-on ball gown of the entire collection, although
Tomasz Strazewski's black strapless with the black velvet bodice,
black satin skirt and pale satin lavender inserts was a close
second.
</P>
<P>
   For those women who cannot wear your basic slip dress, there
were gowns by Katherine Regehr, Mary McFadden, Chris Kole, San
Carlin and Stephen Yearick, whose designs are fairly standard, have
their devotees and smack of conservatism. They also have sleeves
and big skirts.
</P>
<P>
   For consistently beautiful dresses, however, the design team of
Mark Badgley and James Mischka have honed their skills and are
turning out some of the most beautiful gowns anywhere. Nordstrom
showed burn-out velvets, gold sequins and beaded lace gowns in the
neutral palette the team specializes in, with one exception, and it
is a sensational departure: a black-and-burgundy beaded, devore
velvet that could stay in the wardrobe of a truly fashionable woman
for years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
