<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-XFILES-SPI &LR;      06-18 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-XFILES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`X FILES' FILM TRANSLATES WELL FROM TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Years back, when a hit television show like ``Dragnet,'' ``Peter
Gunn'' or even ``Star Trek'' tried to make the big transition to
feature motion picture, the inevitable question was: Can it rise to
the level of the superior medium?
</P>
<P>
   But in the '90s, as movies seek ever broader demographics and
film writing becomes increasingly infantile, the question a critic
must ask is the reverse: Will the series lower its standards to the
crass demands of the big screen?
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, Fox's feature version of its own TV show,
``The X-Files,'' seems amazingly true to itself. At least, it's
shadowy, straight-faced, labyrinthine in structure, as paranoid as
Oliver Stone in a dark alley. And the producers haven't written in
a part for Eddie Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone not a regular viewer, however, it involves a certain
culture shock. Though the exposition is handled neatly (mostly in
one barroom confession), the film is quite happy to leave many of
its conventions (and recurring characters) unexplained. And its
lack of a neat resolution (which fans expect) may leave the
uninitiated feeling numbly unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The story is a takeoff on the old ``2001'' premise, with aliens
landing here in pre-historic times and leaving not a sentinel this
time but a virus, which they intend to use as a weapon when the
time is right to help them take over and colonize the Planet Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the present day and some Texas kids stumble upon the
virus-storage site (or whatever it is) and pretty soon Agents
Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian Anderson) are trying to
foil a 50-year-old plot between the virus-carrying aliens and a
band of high-placed human collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   As written by series creator Chris Carter, the script is more
complex and challenging that we're accustomed in our summer
blockbusters. So much so that I'm not sure I even understand its
premise, the whole alien-virus dynamic, who is trying to do what to
whom and why. Just who the heck is that monster the caveman is
fighting in the opening sequence anyway?
</P>
<P>
   And its James Bondian last act, with Mulder popping down to
Antarctia to save the world, is too long, too drawn-out, too
absurd. Other scenes are just as silly. As when Scully flies to
D.C. after a rough night in the Texas desert but doesn't think to
brush the dust off her shoulders _ or notice a bumblebee in her
hair _ until she goes into an investigative hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the film's brooding, sci-fi noir style is ultimately so
powerful and so overwhelming that the voluminous incongruities of
the script do not sink the ship. The magic of the piece is that it
so thoroughly sweeps us away in the intensity of its paranoid
delusion that we end up accepting everything the writers throw at
us.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the series stars _ Duchovny and Anderson _ also
comes across intact. It's hard to imagine either ever breaking
through to become authentic movie stars, but their restrained
yuppie dullness (which is almost broken here with a first kiss) is
curiously comfortable and appealing. They definitely work in these
roles.
</P>
<P>
   The producers also fulfill the mandate of the ``X-Files''
journey to the multiplexes: they make good use of the big screen.
The several effects sequences _ an Oklahoma City-like bombing, a
pursuit by thousands of bees, a flight across the Antarctic snows
as a gigantic mothership rises from under the heroes' feet _ are
impressively mounted and well integrated into the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Files: Fight the Future. Directed by Rob Bowman.
Screenplay by Chris Carter. Cast: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson,
Martin Landau, Blythe Danner, Armin Mueller-Stahl. 20th
Century-Fox. 121 minutes. Rated PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
