<SLUG> BC-FILM-MULAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MULAN' IS A MASTERPIECE OF STATE-OF-THE-ART ANIMATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news about `Mulan,'' this summer's cartoon musical from
Disney, is that it's a masterpiece of animation that defines the
current state of the art. Several of its scenes are so epic _ and
so stunning _ that they're genuinely thrilling. Visually, the movie
just takes your breath away.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Lion King'' was a staggeringly beautiful evocation of the
East African savannah and ``The Little Mermaid'' was a extravaganza
of underwater kitsch, this film also creates its own unique visual
world: an imaginatively stylized explosion of chinoiserie _ Chinese
patterns, motifs and embellishments.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not all this exotic beauty will appeal to a child
audience or revive the public's waning interest in the feature
animation genre is hard to predict. The film is much less of a
musical than its predecessors (with no show-stopping song). As good
as it is in most respects, it fails to be the kind of emotional
grabber that would make it an instant classic.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an authentic Chinese legend and set in some unspecified
dynasty of the late Middle Ages, it's about Mulan, the spunky
daughter of a wealthy North China landowner who disguises herself
as a man and takes her ailing father's place in the Emperor's
defensive war against the invading army of Huns from beyond the
Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a cheeky miniature dragon named Mushu (voice of
Eddie Murphy) provided by the quarrelsome ghosts of her ancestors,
the young girl makes it through basic training, distinguishes
herself in battle and meets the young man of her dreams before her
disguise is uncovered and the action shifts to a grand climax in
the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   It's roughly the same story as Warner Bros.' recent animated
musical, ``Quest For Camelot,'' but so much better in every way
that there's simply no comparison. It should instantly re-establish
the faltering (after ``Pocahontas'' and ``Hunchback of Notre
Dame'') Disney animation department as the industry's best, and
bolster it from the big challenge of DreamWork's upcoming ``Prince
of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   Every shot is a treat to the eye, and the backgrounds _ aping
the muted colors and minimalist landscapes of Chinese scroll
painting _ are especially pleasing. The big scenes _ vast battle
sequences, an avalanche of snow sweeping away a whole army of Huns,
tens of thousands of extras milling before the entrance of the
Forbidden City _ are even more striking. It's the movies' most
effective combination of computer animation and traditional
hand-drawn cels to date.
</P>
<P>
   The character animation is also first rate, and superior to
anything put out by Disney's competitors in ``Quest'' or Fox's
recent ``Anastasia.'' The fact that Mulan comes off as a realistic
and appealing young woman helps the film work on a level that, say,
``Pocahontas'' did not. And the non-humans _ dragon, horse, falcon
and cricket characters _ are all imaginative conceived and
reasonably charming.
</P>
<P>
   With only four Matthew Wilder and David Zippel songs cutting
into the story _ all of them unobtrusive and none (including the
intended show-stopper, ``I'll Make a Man Out of You'') particularly
memorable _ much less effort seems to have been taken to make the
film work as a musical. This is actually a blessing, because the
milieu and story-line of ``Mulan'' really doesn't lend themselves
to songs and big production numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring downside to the movie is the decision to have
Eddie Murphy supply the voice of Mushu and to talk in a litany of
'90s ghetto jive. What is this about? The filmmakers go to infinite
lengths to create a stylized world of Ancient China and then turn
around and poke holes in its delicate fabric every time the dragon
opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   According to Variety, Murphy's there to give the movie a ``wider
demographic.'' But it's a shame, because he definitely breaks the
fable, and cheapens the experience. What if, back in 1942, Disney
had hired Groucho Marx to ad-lib the voice of Thumper in ``Bambi.''
Or given ``Snow White'' a Jack Benny-like sidekick to widen the
demographic with cheapskate jokes. Would those movies seem half as
magical to us as they do today?
</P>
<P>
   Mulan. Directed by Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft. Score by Jerry
Goldsmith. Voices: Ming-na Wen, Lea Salonga, Eddie Murphy, B.D.
Wong, Donny Osmond. Disney. 87 minutes. Rated G, suitable for all
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
