<HEADLINE>
DON'T LET YOUR MIND GET IN THE WAY OF A GOOD GOLF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A few days ago I thought a niblick was a can of
corn. Now I'm a golf expert.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in a hip, ironic, politically correct city consumed
by golf, Tigermania and the U.S. Open. Sure, I could have gone out
to the Olympic Club and made fun of the toffs in their togs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I could have condemned golf as a crime against nature,
sport, good politics and our legally established domestic meaning
of the word ``partners.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, I went to the Mission Bay Golf Center to take a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're having fun, you aren't playing golf,'' said Jim
Smith, the cashier at the place.
</P>
<P>
   I must have been playing some great golf.
</P>
<P>
   I was sweating up my polo shirt trying to make a dozen parts of
my body bend in unnatural ways under the expert tutelage of
instructor Rodger Langlois.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't fun. And I hadn't even gotten to the really
ridiculous part of golf _ trying to put the little ball in a little
hole.
</P>
<P>
   When Smith asked me how I'd done, I told him I'd been hitting
pretty close to 150 yards (well, on occasion) with a 7-iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quit right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mission Bay Golf Center is that driving range you see as you
get off Interstate 280 in San Francisco, the one speckled with golf
balls as big as hail.
</P>
<P>
   It has none of the disadvantages of the Olympic Club. You don't
have to apply and wait for years to pay the equivalent of an
average family's yearly income just to get in. You just pay for a
bucket of balls.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to have partners or talk or make excuses to
anybody. Nobody watches where your ball goes, and golfers and
parked cars are protected by screens.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you lose your ball. They're all lost.
There's a kid in an armored harvester picking them up. How many
country clubs offer moving targets?
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to walk anywhere or ride in a ridiculous cart.
You play among people of all ages, races, social classes and
genders. And you don't actually have to stuff the little ball in a
little hole.
</P>
<P>
   I knew it was my kind of place because I had to wait for my
lesson behind a dozen kids from a YMCA day camp. The tension
mounted, though, when I saw that some of them really could whack
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Langlois, a fundamentals kind of guy with a gentle voice, told
me that these 8- to 13-year-olds were the perfect age to learn
golf. ``They're so easy to change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I had a hard time turning my hips to follow through.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but when I did, the ball easily went 40 yards farther than
the longest ball of the best camper who was just learning the game.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them already had taken lessons. A couple of little girls
had their own clubs. On Friday, Langlois will take them out on a
real course. Just give these kids a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the backbone of the sport,'' Langlois said proudly as
the kids packed up and left.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the next hour hitting balls while Langlois
adjusted my posture, I didn't want to talk about backbones.
</P>
<P>
   That's the last time I say golf isn't a sport. Either it's a
sport or I'm completely out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   Golf is a sport you really can't teach yourself. Langlois told
me that, and he wasn't just trying to sell lessons. He said that
just two weeks ago Tiger Woods went back to Butch Harman for a
tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best players in the world have an instructor to go back
to,'' Langlois said. I'm not so sure that's reassuring, especially
considering lessons cost $40 per half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I'm a golf expert, let me give some tips to folks like
me who learned to be repelled by golf in the Eisenhower
administration and now are fascinated by it because even
Cablinasians are admitted to country clubs.
</P>
<P>
   First, don't think you can play golf just because you were a
pretty good hitter as second-string catcher in high school.
Baseball and golf are as similar as radicchio and arugula.
</P>
<P>
   Langlois finds out what other sports you've played, just to use
as a basis for telling you what not to do. He theorized that I
hooked rather than sliced because I had played tennis back when I
had knees.
</P>
<P>
   The following are the key elements of golf, not as the careful
Langlois taught them to me, but as I sit here in my plaid shorts
remembering them.
</P>
<P>
   One: Take every limb, joint and extremity in your body and put
them in unnatural positions.
</P>
<P>
   Two: Move all of the above unnaturally over and over again.
Remember to keep your tongue tense, your lips pursed and follow
through with a muttered ``Damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Three: Keep your mind on trying not to think about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, golf is a mental sport that requires a blank mind.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the mind in golf is to remember bad jokes to tell
your compatriots, jokes somewhat better or dirtier than ``If the
object of golf is to get the lowest score, why play at all?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1436EDT &QL; 
