<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLENTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMS OFFER TWO DIFFERNT LOOKS AT MODERN ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pair of movies open this week that deal with the complicated
nature of modern romance in very different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Heaven,'' which played in the Seattle International Film
Festival, updates Henry James' ``The Wings Of the Dove'' to present
times and to Seattle without losing the essence of the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hav Plenty'' is a screwball comedy that features an attractive
black cast. It was made in 1996, but is just now being released.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Heaven,'' which also acknowledges a debt to Terrence
Malick's 1977 classic ``Days Of Heaven,'' belies its low budget and
manages to give the story a '90s slant.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to the iconoclastic casting of Canadian
Molly Parker and Australian Aden Young, as the white-trash, poor
lovers, Cynthia and Buck, and Brit Joely Richardson as their
employer, the dying, rich Eleanor.
</P>
<P>
   The couple scheme to make Ellie to fall in love with Buck, marry
him and ultimately leave him her vast riches.
</P>
<P>
   But as in James' dark novel, the young man falls in love with
the sad, tragic heroine, played with beautiful vulnerability by
Richardson, and, for the first time, has purpose in his life
because he's actually needed. The actors manage to transcend the
awful melodrama of the material (a death scene is embarrassingly
histrionic) and are so capable that they even make some dreadful
lines seem viably heartfelt and potent.
</P>
<P>
   The other plus is the marvelous cinematography of Claudio Rocha,
who shot ``The Whole Wide World,'' and ``Picture Bride.'' Never has
Seattle looked so beguiling on film. Seattleite Meg Richman
directed and wrote ``Under Heaven'' and she has a way with actors
and, with a background in art, knows how to blend style, color and
light to create a Pre-Raphaelite look. It gives the film a sense of
timelessness that binds it to James' turn-of-the-century story
despite its modern setting.
</P>
<P>
   Richman, who recently adapted the W. Somerset Maugham novella,
``Up At The Villa,'' for the screen (it's currently in production
and set to star Kristin Scott Thomas and Sean Penn), clearly has a
gift for period pieces and knows how to translate works based in
the past for present day sensibilities. Had she excised some
overwrought dialogue, ``Under Heaven'' might actually have been
heavenly.
</P>
<P>
   With ``Hav Plenty,'' writer and director Chris Cherot says he
``basically lied'' in order to get his first movie made, though he
swears it's based on his own, true-life story.
</P>
<P>
   The film explores modern romantic relationships among a group of
black friends and family over a New Year's holiday and, in some
ways, it's a fresh take on a soggy, familiar tale.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Plenty (Cherot) is a struggling writer living off the good
nature and generosity of his pals. He's been in love with one,
Havilland Savage (Chenoa Maxwell), for years. When she invites him
to her family's D.C. home on New Year's Eve, Lee hits the road in a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But Havilland is engaged to famous singer and songwriter Michael
Simmons (Hill Harper), an unctuous type who autographs a picture
for a fan named Melissa and tells her, ``You can't spell Melissa
without an M and an E.'' He's smooth and glib and, more than
likely, not very faithful to his fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and after several comic mishaps, Lee finds himself
sleeping in the same bed with the woman he loves but things don't
transpire quite the way they should. Even after he admits his
feelings, it may be too late to salvage a relationship with the
wary Havilland.
</P>
<P>
   There are some clever moments and the cast is extremely
attractive and makes the one-dimensional characters more engaging
than they should be. But there's so much information missing and so
few reasons why Lee and Havilland shouldn't get together that the
film doesn't feel cohesive and flowing and it doesn't make much
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a welcome change from recent black comedies like
``Woo'' that are an insult to the actors. Compared with that
unfunny project, ``Hav Plenty'' is a breath of fresh air. Cherot at
least tries to find a new voice and reinvent a tired genre. The
problems may stem from the film's low budget, but it's a shame he
could't tie the story together in a less rough and raggedy way.
</P>
<P>
   Under Heaven. Directed and written by Meg Richman. Cast: Joely
Richardson, Molly Parker, Aden Young. Banner Entertainment. 112
minutes. Rated R for nudity, language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Hav Plenty. Directed and written by Christopher Scott Cherot.
Cast: Cherot, Chenoa Maxwell, Hill Harper, Robinne Lee. Miramax
Films. 92 minutes. Rated R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
