r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULAN-REVIEW-LADN     06-18 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND STORYTELLING GIVES `MULAN' TIMELESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3{ Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With ``Mulan,'' Disney has toned down the hype
that typically surrounds its new animated features _ and with good
reason.
</P>
<P>
   The movie doesn't need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' stands on its own as an example of what the Mouse
House still does best _ classic storytelling, bold animation
technique and zippy songs. These elements combine to make this
Disney's most appealing animated film since ``The Lion King,'' a
movie that will captivate children, and entertain and emotionally
involve adults.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's last three animated features _ ``Pocahontas,'' ``The
Hunchback of Notre Dame'' and ``Hercules'' _ haven't necessarily
been bad. Indeed, ``Hunchback'' managed to capture the spirit of
the Victor Hugo novel and make it affecting and accessible for
kids. But these three films all suffered from what Disney now calls
the ``sincerity'' issue. They were so overhyped that the public
became cynical about the studio's motives. Was Disney making movies
or merchandising vehicles?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the answer lies somewhere in between. And it still
does. With ``Mulan'' though, Disney seems to be starting to address
the issue and, in the process, created one of its most engaging
heroines. Mulan is interesting, quirky, full of energy, suffering
from little self-doubt and, physically, doesn't even faintly
resemble the kind of lap-dance ladies the studio has been drawing
of late. (See Pocahontas or ``Aladdin's'' Jasmine or
``Hunchback's'' Esmerelda.)
</P>
<P>
   Mulan's most obvious quality, though, is her selflessness, which
becomes evident early when she takes her frail father's place in
ancient China's war against the invading Huns. She does this out of
love, both for her father and her country. It also seems like a
pretty natural decision: Although she's not exactly a tomboy, an
early misadventure with a matchmaker indicates that Mulan isn't
exactly at home with the womanly arts.
</P>
<P>
   Having chopped off her hair and borrowed her father's armor,
Mulan joins her fellow conscripts, a motley crew of screw-ups led
by a handsome young captain named Shang. Naturally, at first Mulan
has trouble pulling off her ruse and Mushu, a little dragon (voiced
by Eddie Murphy) sent by her ancestors for protection, proves to be
more of a hindrance than a help. This reinforces the film's message
that Mulan doesn't need help from a sidekick _ or a man _ to get
by.
</P>
<P>
   It's a refreshing twist to the Disney formula, as is the fact
that the romance is more or less an afterthought. After all, it's
hard to save China and still worry about impressing the opposite
sex _ even in an animated film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' does remain true to many of the Disney animated
traditions. Matthew Wilder and David Zippel have written five
rousing songs (without the standard schmaltzy love ballad) that fit
nicely within the film's dramatic framework, and Murphy's dragon _
along with a goofy dog and a bouncy cricket _ provide the requisite
comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, Murphy's humor seems a bit out of place in
the film's Chinese sensibility, and that can be occasionally
off-putting. Certainly no one under the age of 12 will mind, but
Disney's continued reliance on this kind of schtick might be a
little annoying to viewers caught up in Mulan's touching,
compelling story. Unlike ``Aladdin,'' where Robin Williams' genie
dominated a lighthearted cartoon tale, ``Mulan'' has serious themes
and a delicate mood, a state that can be easily disrupted by a
jive-talking dragon.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously Disney is still casting its net wide enough to reel in
the broadest possible audience. We would be naive to expect
otherwise. But when the finished product is as accomplished as
``Mulan,'' it's pretty easy to set aside such small quibbles and be
swept along with the gorgeous animation, heartfelt storytelling and
catchy songs that make this Chinese legend truly a story for the
ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
