<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5366 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XFILES-REVIEW-LADN     06-18 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XFILES-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`X-FILES' MOVIE HOOKS A SKEPTIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First off, a disclaimer: I don't believe in UFOs,
aliens or Trilateralists. Roswell is just a spot on the map, LBJ
didn't whack JFK, and O.J. was not set up by the Japanese mafia.
</P>
<P>
   I don't watch ``The X-Files'' either, which makes me something
of an anomaly among journalists, most of whom see a government
conspiracy of some sort lurking around every corner. (The latest:
Ginger Spice quit the Spice Girls because she was seen in the White
House with Clinton. That's why she didn't come to the States with
Posh, Sporty, Scary and Baby _ the Feds wanted to keep her quiet.)
</P>
<P>
   I do believe in good movies, though, so I was curious. Could I
watch the ``X-Files'' film and not become lost in a murky labyrinth
understood only to Internet geeks and dateless shut-ins? Or would
all the conspiracy-speak and black helicopters simply wash over me
like the liquid from a bottle of Snapple iced tea (whose old label
did NOT depict a slave galley, conspiracy freaks _ it was the
Boston Tea Party).
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, all of my doubts were erased once the lights went
down and the opening images from the ``X-Files'' movie came on the
screen. Not only did I end up enjoying this spooky romp down
paranoia lane, I probably ended up liking it quite a bit more than
some of the die-hard ``X-Philes'' surrounding me. As a neophyte, I
brought no baggage to the show. I had no expectations, no questions
and no demands, other than to be entertained. And the movie did
that quite effectively.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers do the nonbelievers a favor by tossing out some
early exposition to explain things and generally make sure everyone
is on the same page. Of course, even if you've never watched the
show, you probably know Mulder (David Duchovny) and Scully (Gillian
Anderson) are a couple of FBI agents who investigate wacky
paranormal-type stuff. Mulder is the true believer in all things
alien; Scully's there to effectively poke holes in his crackpot
theories.
</P>
<P>
   She has her work cut out for her in this movie. In the film's
first half hour, there's an Oklahoma City-like bombing of a Dallas
office building (paging Lee Harvey Oswald!), a creepy scene where a
kid comes down with an alien virus, and a lot of talk about
biological warfare, mutating diseases and the end of the world as
we know it.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, we're given just enough information to keep us
happy, even though we're really still stumbling around in the dark.
Martin Landau does a wonderfully loopy turn as a conspiracy nut who
leads Mulder to the truth, which involves an alien colonization
scheme worthy of Lyndon LaRouche's weirdest tracts. It's hardly an
original story line _ ever see ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers''?
_ but series writer-producer Chris Carter brings enough of his own
modern-day lunatic fringe element to make it his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' becomes a little repetitive toward the end _ too
much deadpan dialogue, one too many trips to the cornfield (bees
and corn are two of Carter's favorite things). Also, for a series
that's supposed to be so cutting-edge, there are an awful lot of
familiar plot conventions here, like car bombs, back-alley
informants and a helicopter chase scene quite reminiscent of
``North by Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that doesn't diminish the movie's creepy fun or the
nicely empathetic turns by Duchovny and Anderson, who make the jump
to the big screen with performances that provide knowing portraits
of their characters. Besides, how can you not like a movie that has
a drunken Agent Mulder relieving himself outside a bar _ on an
``Independence Day'' poster. If that's what they mean by ``The
Truth Is Out There,'' then count me in as a believer.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: I'll be tuning in this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
