<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5377 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-BEAT-LADN     06-18 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-BEAT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERY SPECIAL EFFECTS ON CARAMEL'S DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Some people collect stamps, some collect coins.
Caramel singer-bassist Andy Curran collects vintage effects pedals.
</P>
<P>
   The milk crate Curran keeps at home in Toronto, filled with old
wah-wah pedals, fuzz-tone and distortion effects, came into play
during the making of Caramel's self-titled debut, which boasts the
standout track ``Lucy,'' now getting airplay at rock stations
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Geffen Records disc is packed with high-quality material and
strange guitar noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The producer and myself are especially into guitar sounds,''
Curran explained. ``If we had heard a certain effect before, we
wouldn't use it. I used the pedals I've searched the world for _
and my old vintage amps.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Lucy,'' for example, the guitar was run through three or
four '60s effects pedals and an old theater speaker. Curran says
the goal ``was to make it sound like the speaker was blowing up.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage, Caramel was able to duplicate the sound of the record
after adding a second guitarist and singer, Virginia Storey.
</P>
<P>
   The members of Caramel recorded the album around day jobs. A
friend in promotion sent the indie release to stations in Boston
and Sacramento, which immediately added ``Lucy.''
</P>
<P>
   Geffen talent scout David Simone beat the major-label rush to
Caramel's door by a week, scooping up the band at a hometown gig.
</P>
<P>
   ``He saw us in Toronto, and 48 hours later we had a deal on the
table,'' Curran, 37, said. ``I felt like Dorothy when her house was
being sucked up by the tornado. It was bizarre. And we still don't
even have a booking agent.''
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE BUFFALO ROAMS: The credits to ``Jubilee''
(Slash/Warner Bros.), the latest album from North Hollywood's Grant
Lee Buffalo, read like a who's who of the new studio mafia.
</P>
<P>
   Along with ubiquitous multi-instrumentalist Jon Brion, the
well-reviewed album features cameos from keyboardist Rami Jaffee of
the Wallflowers, alt-country studio king Greg Leisz, E of the Eels,
Michael Stipe and Robyn Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was less planned than you would imagine,'' singer-guitarist
Grant Lee Phillips explained. ``Some people we were dying to work
with were asked to come by; others just happened to drop by the
studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he added the ``Buffalo' part to the band name six
years ago ``at a time when I was trying to figure out my beliefs
and obsessions as an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant Lee Buffalo contributed to filmmaker Todd Haynes' ``Velvet
Goldmine,'' which deals with London's '70s glam-rock scene and is
due this fall.
</P>
<P>
   A VERITABLE `GOLDMINE': Where did the name ``Velvet Goldmine''
come from? It's actually the title of an obscure David Bowie song
originally found only on the B-side of the 1975 British reissue of
``Space Oddity.'' The song is also included as a bonus track on
Rykodisc's reissue of Bowie's classic 1972 concept album, ``The
Rise &AMP; Fall of Ziggy Stardust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
