   FILM-XFILES (Undated) In the '90s, as movies seek ever broader
demographics and film writing becomes increasingly infantile, the
question a critic must ask is the reverse: Will the series lower
its standards to the crass demands of the big screen? For better or
worse, Fox's feature version of its own TV show, ``The X-Files,''
seems amazingly true to itself. At least, it's shadowy,
straight-faced, labyrinthine in structure, as paranoid as Oliver
Stone in a dark alley.
