<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILE-WILDE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WILDE' IS A FASCINATING GULP OF PERSONAL HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great Irish playwright, novelist and wit Oscar Wilde had a
lot of bad luck in his life, but history has been extremely kind to
him. He's been the focus of a regular revival of admiring interest
every few decades since his death _ including a big ongoing one in
the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   He's been especially lucky at the movies _ the subject of no
less than three successful, mostly complimentary, British biopics _
``Oscar Wilde,'' starring Robert Morley; ``The Trials of Oscar
Wilde,'' starring Peter Finch and filmed in 70mm (both released in
1960); and ``Wilde,'' which debuted last month in the Seattle
International Film Festival and moves into a regular run today.
</P>
<P>
   All three films cover the same basic territory: Wilde's triple
life as a somewhat scandalous man of letters (``The Picture of
Dorian Gray'') and playwright (``The Importance of Being
Earnest''); a loving (if absent) husband and father; and
not-so-secret homosexual, whose affairs with various aristocratic
lovers and off-the-street ``rentboys'' eventually lead him to
become the most famous man ever publicly prosecuted for sodomy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the three films, this new one is, of course, by far the most
sexually explicit (perhaps more than it needs to be), as well as
the most intellectually honest.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde (Stephen Fry, in a performance that won him the best actor
award at SIFF) comes off less as a martyr than a man who foolishly
lets his obsession for an unworthy young lover lead him into big
trouble that he might well have avoided.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a fascinating gulp of personal history, directed
with assurance by Brian Gilbert (``Tom &AMP; Viv'') and filled out with
an exceptional supporting cast that includes Jude Law as Wilde's
selfish lover, Tom Wilkinson as the lover's vengeful father,
Vanessa Redgrave as Wilde's widowed mother and Jennifer Ehle, as
Wilde's long-suffering wife, who emerges as the movie's single
noble character.
</P>
<P>
   Another worthy film opening this weekend after a debut in the
Seattle International Film Festival is the unique German drama,
``Beyond Silence,'' which played not in this year's SIFF but in the
1997 edition _ and went on from there to earn a best
foreign-language Academy Award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A first film directed by young filmmaker Caroline Link, it's a
finely crafted, deeply engrossing drama of a young woman (Sylvie
Testud as an adult, Tatjana Trieb as a child), who grows up to
become her deaf parents' sole link to the hearing world.
</P>
<P>
   When she becomes interested in music and shows a special gift
for the clarinet, the attraction is discouraged by her stubborn
father (Seattle actor Howie Seago), a family crisis ensues, the
story gradually widens out to include several other characters in
the extended family, and the film comes together to be an unusually
poignant family saga.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Beyond Silence'' may well be the most striking and
original of all the deluge of first films in the last two editions
of the film festival. It's impeccably cast, sensitively scripted
and directed with a glossy visual flair and original storytelling
style that often recalls Link's great filmmaking countryman,
Douglas Sirk.
</P>
<P>
   Wilde. Directed by Brian Gilbert. Screenplay by Julian Mitchell.
Cast: Stephen Fry, Jude Law, Vanessa Redgrave, Jennifer Ehle. Sony
Pictures Classics. 116 minutes. Rated R for nudity and explicit
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Silence. Directed by Caroline Link. Screenplay by Link
and Beth Serlin. Cast: Sylie Testud, Howie Seago, Emmanuelle
Laborit, Tatjana Trieb. Miramax. In German with English subtitles.
100 minutes. Rated PG-13 for mature theme.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5408 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GALAPAGOS-CAPSIZE-BOS     06-18 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALAPAGOS-CAPSIZE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF TERROR OFF THE GALAPAGOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: N.H., Fla., Ore.; a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ABBY FUNG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Moby Dick started to founder, Tom Sheridan, a 68-year-old
MIT professor on vacation with his wife, grabbed the boat's rail as
dishes began crashing down and passengers started screaming.
</P>
<P>
   It took only three seconds for the 70-foot Ecuadorian boat,
chartered by Boston-based Elderhostel, to capsize last Wednesday,
plunging 15 American vacationers and eight crew members into the
seas of the Galapagos archipelago, 600 miles off the coast of South
America.
</P>
<P>
   In the three hours that followed, two passengers died. Two
others remain missing, and one is recovering from severe injuries.
The surviving 11 passengers and eight crew members clung to a
dinghy, rafts, or life rings as waves crested 15 feet over their
heads and currents pulled them apart. An investigation as to the
exact cause of the accident is underway. ``All of a sudden, an
exceptionally big swell picked our boat up and tilted it on its
side,'' recalls Mary Jo Cannarella, 62, of Nashua, N.H., one of
four New Englanders on the Moby Dick. ``We expected it to right
itself, but it didn't. It hung on the balance at a 30-degree angle,
and another wave gave it a push and knocked it over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The water was rising very, very fast,'' she added. ``I knew I
had to get out of the (cabin), or I would be trapped and drown. In
the first few moments, I was thinking `This can't be real.' Yet I
was swimming for my life. Then as I was clinging to the ring buoy,
I thought, `This might be my moment of death.' However, I didn't
give up my determination at any moment. I had a brief thought about
sharks, but I didn't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The disaster occurred in the early evening of the third day of a
seven-day cruise of the Miami-built ship's maiden voyage, shortly
after the tourists set sail under a double rainbow bound from
Espanola (Hood) Island to Puerto Ayora. Out of sight of land,
amidst scattered islands famed for their unique plants and animals,
cocaptains Carlos and Freddy Penaherrera, natives of the Galapagos
with 26 combined years of sea experience, were trying to control
the vessel in unexpectedly heavy seas.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers weren't especially concerned. Most were engaged in
recreational activities when the boat ran into trouble, survivors
recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were heavy swells,'' Cannarella says. ``The captain was
going at a slower pace than usual, but he wasn't having problems
navigating. We were assured that this was quite normal for that
part of the channel. Other than a few people being seasick,
everything was going along okay. We weren't worried.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Freddy Penaherrera: ``A large wave lifted the rear
of the yacht, the bow dove steeply, just as a gust of wind caught
the vessel broadside, knocking it partly over. Then a second wave
hit, knocking it down completely. Furniture and people were tossed
about inside and outside the vessel. In just a few seconds, our
boat was sinking.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 15 minutes before the vessel was completely submerged,
the crew worked frantically to free as much lifesaving equipment as
possible. Passengers thrown into the sea were yelling to find each
other in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan and his wife, Rachel, 70, had been on the bow area of
the second deck talking with Joe Cannarella, 64, Mary Jo's husband.
After the boat tipped, the three were dragged under the hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept trying to surface, but our heads kept striking the
hull, then the boat passed over us and we emerged at the stern,''
Sheridan says. ``Joe's arm was lacerated by the propeller as it
went by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I flew across the lounge,'' says Mary Jo Cannarella, who was
inside the boat when it tipped over. ``Within three breaths, the
water was up to my neck. Five breaths and it was over my head. I
refused to die and rammed my head repeatedly against the glass
window now above me. The window popped and I scrambled through to
the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   Another passenger, Martha Brooks of Corvallis, Ore., who is
nearly blind, followed the light through the now open window,
escaping to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Brewer of Florida found herself pinned by furniture and a
window. ``Until the water reached my nose, I was yelling to others
not to panic. Then the water went over my head. The man pinned next
to me was dead, but I felt it wasn't my time to die. I heard the
glass shatter, felt I had a chance, wriggled under the furniture,
found a hole in the glass, and I was free. At the age of 70, I held
my breath for more than two minutes for the first time in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer was the last out of the boat alive.
</P>
<P>
   Once outside, Mary Jo Cannarella said: ``Five of us were
clinging to that one ring buoy. One person was trying to climb up
on it and kept pulling us under water. We could have died on that
small ring. Then two of the women caught a glimpse of a dinghy and
decided to swim for it to save the rest of us. Amazingly, they made
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others drifted and swam to join us,'' she added. ``Then
Richard Sayer, who couldn't find his wife, said, `I'll go. I'm
ready to go.' We said, `No, hold on,' but he said `good-bye,' let
go, and went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Drifting about half a mile away, the Sheridans and Joe
Cannarella managed to make it to what became a small flotilla of
life rafts tied to a dinghy. Passengers and crew huddled together.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, those in the dinghy spotted a small boat in
the distance and fired two flares. The boat didn't respond. Soon
after, a larger boat, the Angelino II, appeared on the horizon. It
had spotted the flares.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo Cannarella, Vera Brower, and the others on the buoy ring
also saw the boat responding, but realized they could easily be
overlooked. They gathered strength to paddle directly into the path
of the oncoming ship.
</P>
<P>
   The ocean seas were rough. Johnny Fong, 24, a crew member aboard
the Angelito II, jumped in and swam out wearing a life vest and
carrying a ring attached by a rope to his vessel. One by one, he
accompanied each passenger as they were towed to the boat and
hoisted in, taking 20 minutes for each rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors arrived at Puerto Ayora, Santa Cruz, at 2 a.m.,
more than seven hours after the Moby Dick sank. The entire village
turned out to take them to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Sheridan rushed to contact her four children and her
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, those well enough to travel flew home, the
Cannarellas and the Sheridans taking the same plane to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Neither couple blames Elderhostel, which sends 33,000 older
travelers overseas every year. This was the travel agency's first
fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   The Cannarellas have already planned another trip. Their
destination: the Galapagos Islands. Says Mary Jo, ``We definitely
want to go back again and finish what we started.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Freelance writers Ty Harrington and Kathleen Mangan, who were
in Ecuador at the time of the accident, contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
