<HEADLINE>
HEAT TAKING TOLL ON POULTRY FARMERS IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Torrid heat has claimed more than 200,000 chickens
and turkeys in one South Texas county, poultry farmers say, and the
toll could worsen if temperatures continue to soar past 100
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkeys, hens and broilers all got a good lick Sunday,'' said
A.M. `Buddy' Lindeman Jr., 65, a poultry farmer in Gonzeles County,
southeast of San Antonio. The temperature hit a record 107 degrees
on Sunday
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still. It was hot. The air did not move, and the
chickens just couldn't take it even with the fans and misters in
the house,'' said Lindeman, who estimates he lost around 18,000
birds.
</P>
<P>
   The expected high on Thursday in the San Antonio area was 102
and forecasters said it could reach 100 on Friday. The National
Weather Service issued heat advisories in parts of north and
southeastern Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Grauke, the lab production manager for Tyson Foods in
Gonzales, estimated his loss at around 160,000 birds out of 6
million the company was raising in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost some broilers. The hens and pullets fared OK,'' Grauke
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We furnish the birds to the grower, and they raise them. Tyson
owns the birds, and the grower is paid to grow them for us. We
raise a little over a million a week here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grauke said growers face the unpleasant task of cleaning up the
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a short period of time to render them or bury them.
That's your only choice. You just want to get rid of them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the death toll, it won't result in a shortage of split
breasts or leg quarters in the supermarket, Grauke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This loss is not even a drop in the ocean for the industry or
for Tyson. No one likes to lose birds, but we sell 35 million a
week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the loss of the fowl is expected to hurt farmers,
especially the sweltering heat continues, said Travis Franke, the
Gonzales County agricultural extension agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good situation now. I haven't heard a financial
figure yet, but it will be significant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While deaths of poultry are a normal summertime hazard, Franke
said, this is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, they happen in July or August when the
temperatures reach 100 degrees. This year it was in June,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but I wish it would go away. If this
is any indication of what is yet to come this summer, it's gonna be
a bad year,'' Franke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
