<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR JUNE
18, 1998. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALASKA -- TOBACCO. Alaska's senators voted to scuttle the
tobacco debate, saying the bill had become too bulky and violates
the balanced budget agreement. (Working). Gorman
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- VCHIP. (For Hollywood). The vaunted television
program-blocking device mandated by Congress last year is released
to the sound of one hand clapping. Wallison
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- INTERIOR. The House Appropriations subcommittee in
charge of parks and the environment is expected to pass the first
draft of their 1999 spending plan, including money to protect the
recently-declared-threatened Preebles jumping mouse, as well as
several land buys in Colorado. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- FTC. The Colorado delegation is uniting to fight the closing
of the Federal Trade Commission office in Denver, asking the
subcommittee that doles out FTC funds to block the plan, and asking
the investigative arm of Congress to conduct an independent review
of the plan. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- TOXICS. Polk County is the 22nd most polluted county
in the United States, according to statistics released today by the
Environmental Protection Agency. Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. Wallison
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA. TRASH -- An amendment to restrict the interstate flow
of trash was approved by the Senate today. Wolfberg
</P>
