   -- ONLINE-TRADING-OXLEY. Calling online investing ``the biggest
success story on the Internet,'' Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Findlay, today
held a subcommittee hearing on online securities trading. The
hearing included the first-ever stock transaction during
congressional business. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- BOEHNER-LAWSUIT-STARR. Comparing the allegation that
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr illegally leaked information to
reporters WITH the claim Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., illegally
leaked information to reporters. Why do Boehner and Gingrich think
this is different? (Working, NOT for today). Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- CARS. Four Michigan Congressmen urged the House to
create national areas that can be used as secular shrines to
automobiles. Stebbins
</P>
<P>
   NEVADA -- RICHARDSON. Nevada lawmakers react to the nomination
of Bill Richardson to head the Department of Energy. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO -- RICHARDSON. Bill Richardson, who has jumped from
U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations to would-be DOE secretary,
said he credits his work in New Mexico for helping him garner the
new post. Gorman
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- RICHSN. The Senate will not fast-track
President Clinton's nomination to make U.N. Ambassador Bill
Richardson the Secretary of Energy, but he is likely to win
confirmation, a key committee chairman said today. Williams
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- PERRY. Armed with figures showing the drastic financial
hit farmers will take as a result of the drought, state Agriculture
Commissioner Rick Perry came to Washington seeking relief. Brown
</P>
