<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-CASUAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AIRLINES SWITCHES TO `BUSINESS CASUAL' DRESS CODE _ FOR
NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bob Crandall is out; casual is in.
</P>
<P>
   In what is being hailed as the first major change at American
Airlines headquarters under new Chairman and Chief Executive Donald
Carty, the airline now allows employees to dress ``business
casual'' every day.
</P>
<P>
   Crandall, who retired in May as the airline's chief, was a
button-down kind of guy who always wore suits and liked to see his
employees dress for success.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he acquiesced in allowing casual dress on Fridays for
nonuniformed employees who didn't have direct contact with
customers. The new policy extends that to the rest of the week _
for now.
</P>
<P>
   The policy, which applies to about 20,000 management employees,
will continue through Sept. 4, according to a memo to employees
from Jaynne Allison, vice president for human relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard from our employees that they believe they are
more productive'' in casual dress, Allison wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the policy is continued after summer might depend on how
tasteful employees are in their casual dressing, the memo hints.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans, T-shirts, short shorts, halter tops and athletic shoes
are out, but golf shirts, open-neck button-down shirts,
Dockers-type pants and sleeveless shell tops for women are allowed,
airline spokeswoman Andrea Rader said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sitting here in a business suit today because I felt like
dressing up,'' she said. ``But it's sure great to have the
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have tried but abandoned casual dress because
``employees did not exercise good judgment and became too careless
_ and too casual,'' Allison's memo says. ``Let's not be one of
those companies.''
</P>
<P>
   As a guide to what is appropriate, Allison said:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find yourself standing in front of your closet,
trying to figure what to wear, try imagining what you would expect
to see if you were visiting another company's corporate
headquarters. My guess is that provides a pretty high standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Crandall began his vacation after a retirement party by stepping
onto an American Airlines flight to England wearing an open-collar
shirt and blazer. It might have been the first time, some observers
said, that he ever flew without a tie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
