A5545 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX     06-18 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN POISED FOR WORKPLACE ADVANCEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget ``Year of the Woman'' proclamations. How about ``Century
of the Woman''?
</P>
<P>
   Many elements are in place for women to make major strides in
the workplace in the next century, according to two interesting
books now out.
</P>
<P>
   One is a bestseller by ABC Washington correspondent Cokie
Roberts called ``We Are Our Mothers' Daughters'' (Morrow, 197
pages, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   Although this book may seem an odd choice for a business column,
Roberts does an excellent job of showing just how far the women's
movement has come in terms of business.
</P>
<P>
   Women own one-third of all U.S. businesses, or about 8 million
enterprises, according to the U.S. Census Bureau. That number is
expected to grow to one-half of all businesses in a few years.
Currently, women-owned businesses employ about a quarter of the
work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of women-owned businesses outpaces that of all
businesses by nearly two to one,'' Roberts writes. ``And once a
woman starts a business, she's more likely to keep it going than
her male counterpart.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts uses her own interesting career, as well as those of
several other women, to highlight the advances made by women in
virtually every aspect of work, from the military to consumer
advocacy to business.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts notes that her career began just a few months before the
Civil Rights Act became law. (In an interesting side note, she
explains that women were included as a group along with minorities
in the language of the law only in an attempt by Howard Smith of
Virginia to split the vote and defeat the bill. It passed anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   Her family was also involved in the women's movement,
particularly her politician mother and sister. Roberts' mother,
Lindy Boggs, who filled the house seat of her husband, Hale Boggs,
after his death, was instrumental in having women included in
legislation that was designed to protect minorities against
discrimination in the credit industry.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 50 women in the House of Representatives and nine
in the Senate, Roberts writes, and their votes are affecting
legislation on issues from gun control to child-support enforcement
to the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts writes eloquently of today's female experience, whether
as reporter, consumer advocate, soldier or entrepreneur, or as a
sister, wife or mother.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting study of women's advancement in the
workplace is titled ``Advancing Women in Business/The Catalyst
Guide: Best Practices from the Corporate Leaders'' (Jossey-Bass,
244 pages, $26).
</P>
<P>
   Written by the staff of a nonprofit research and advisory
organization focused on women called Catalyst, this book is based
on the current practices at some of the businesses Catalyst has
identified as winners. In fact, many of the companies have won the
Catalyst Award for successful women's advancement programs.
</P>
<P>
   Although not as personal as Roberts' book, this book does offer
concrete examples of how many firms have successfully hired,
retained and promoted women, to the benefit and profitability of
the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more companies now understand the importance of using
the widest range of talent available,'' the Catalyst staff writes.
``These companies and firms are focusing on a soup-to-nuts
approach, ranging from hiring and recruitment to career pathing and
mentoring, all based solidly on commitment from top leadership and
on fixing accountability for making change happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When you consider that women now constitute 46 percent of the
total work force and that more than half of the bachelor's and
master's degrees awarded every year go to women, it is becoming
increasingly more evident to many companies that women must be
considered a key part of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies highlighted in the book are Texas
Instruments, J.C. Penney Co. and Motorola, as well as Deloitte &AMP;
Touche, Dow Chemical, Knight Ridder and McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Many women, particularly in the middle of their careers, ``slow
down, get derailed, disappear, or opt out of competition for
advancement,'' the authors write. This book offers ``an antidote.''
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
