<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENU-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OFF THE MENU': FOR A HOLLYWOOD INSTITUTION, JUST DESSERTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In times of rapid change and shifting trends and enthusiasms,
the passing of institutions goes unrecorded all too often. By the
time anyone can react, the wrecker's ball has swung or the doors
have closed and the furnishings have been sold off here and there.
Cultural anthropology and archaeology are left the poorer.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in the case of Chasen's, the Los Angeles restaurant that
opened its doors in 1936; drew the elite of the movies to dine on
its high-cholesterol Hobo Steak and chili in the heyday of
Hollywood glamour, and closed on April 1, 1995, in part a victim of
more modern tastes, to make way for a shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, two New York independent filmmakers with senses of
history and humor among their virtues saw in the passing of
Chasen's both the loss of an important link to another era and the
opportunity for a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The result is ``Off the Menu: The Last Days of Chasen's,''
directed by Shari Springer Berman and Robert Pulcini. Their
valuable, poignant and often funny film mingles behind-the-scenes
views of the restaurant during its final week and interviews with,
and reminiscences by, the dedicated core of its staff, as well as
with the many luminaries who rushed back for a final visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're sick, nobody calls you,'' says Pepe Ruiz, the
bartender who invented the restaurant's Flame of Love cocktail.
``When you die, everybody comes to the funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   To compound the nostalgia, ``Off the Menu'' employs
black-and-white film clips from the days when the restaurant was
patronized by stars like Clark Gable, John Wayne, Spencer Tracy,
James Stewart, Humphrey Bogart, Frank Sinatra, Burt Lancaster, Kirk
Douglas, Gregory Peck, Greta Garbo, Lana Turner, Barbara Stanwyck,
Lauren Bacall, Elizabeth Taylor and Grace Kelly, not to mention a
succession of presidents, J.Edgar Hoover and gangsters like Mickey
Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   David Brown, the producer, observes that Chasen's at its peak
was not so different from some of today's crowded, trendy New-Age
restaurants, although ``alcohol was the drug of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chasen's heyday, the film notes, was also a time when the
restaurant's Hispanic kitchen staff could scarcely hope to venture
into the dining area, much less aspire to rise beyond the most
menial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So as the reminiscences roll on and the staff works with
polished professionalism through the final week, including the
party on Oscar night, watching ``Off the Menu'' becomes akin to
leafing through a sociological scrapbook in the company of people
who were there when the pictures were taken.
</P>
<P>
   The film is generous in its appreciation of the staff that
helped to make Chasen's so popular, giving ample time to the
outspoken and uninhibited dining room captain, Tommy Gallagher, who
called Sinatra ``Frank''; to the fussy and demanding Raymond
Bilbool, who commanded the banquet staff, and to their colleagues,
from maitre d' and waiters to coat room and ladies' room
attendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the Menu'' is a poignant farewell.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   OFF THE MENU: The Last Days of Chasen's
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Shari Springer Berman and Robert Pulcini; directors
of photography, Ken Kobland and Sandra Chandler; edited by Pulcini;
music by Mark Suozzo; produced by Alicia Sams and Julia Strohm;
released by Northern Arts Entertainment. Running time: 90 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH APPEARANCES BY: Steve Allen, Angela Bassett, Jackie
Collins, Matt Dillon, Gerald Ford, Merv Griffin, Bob Hope, Samuel
Jackson, Jessica Lange, Sally Kirkland, Jay Leno, Johnny Mathis,
Suzanne Pleshette, Don Rickles, Donna Summer, Quentin Tarantino,
Yanni, Fay Wray and many others. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
