<HEADER>
A5557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRADY-PORTRAIT-EXHIBI     06-18 1363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADY-PORTRAIT-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY REVIEW: A RECORDER OF HISTORY MANUFACTURED IT, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mathew Brady was the most famous American
photographer of his day and is still one of the best known of ours,
and yet in a peculiar way he is not well known.
</P>
<P>
   The outline of his life is clear enough, but so few personal
documents survive that he might as well have carried on his
correspondence by e-mail. His very birth date was uncertain,
perhaps even to himself. At an advanced age he reluctantly told an
interviewer he was born ``near 1823 or 24.'' Death being one of the
few certainties in the lives of the famous, we know he died in
1896.
</P>
<P>
   His work is familiar but may not be his. He is enshrined as the
recorder of the Civil War, though he was only one among many.
What's more, most of Brady's photographs of the war were taken by
his employees and issued under Brady's name, as were his portraits.
</P>
<P>
   By 1851, when he won an international medal in London, his
eyesight was so bad that he could not handle a camera well. He
brought in the clients, posed them and lighted them, and no one
thought him less a photographer because an employee took the actual
picture. It is strange to think that a man who does not see well
decides to become a photographer; one wonders how many
photographers have been nearsighted and intent on seeing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathew Brady's Portraits: Images as History, Photography as
Art,'' at the International Center of Photography Midtown, is
billed as ``the first time since his studio closed over a century
ago that the full range of his work is gathered together in one
place.'' Mary Panzer, curator of photographs at the National
Portrait Gallery of the Smithsonian Institution, which organized
the exhibition, selected more than 100 images for this show,
including Civil War photographs. She also wrote the accompanying
book, ``Mathew Brady and the Image of History'' (Smithsonian
Institution Press).
</P>
<P>
   Brady's career began in 1844 and spanned every medium of his
time, from daguerreotypes to ambrotypes to stereographs and cartes
de visite and ``Brady Imperials,'' paper prints some 24 inches high
by 20 inches wide. The daguerreotypes and ambrotypes in this show
are unfortunately placed so low that most visitors must stoop
repeatedly to view them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Panzer's thoughtful, occasionally elegiac book brings up
many of the issues involved in the recording and manufacture of
history through images. The exhibition tries to navigate between
Brady's self-proclaimed dual roles as historian and artist, with
history generally winning out in the labels, which expound the
subject's achievements more often than the photographer's. They
also quite properly credit the Mathew Brady Studio as author.
</P>
<P>
   The portraits are fine, honest, grand but not officious,
straightforward and American. Some are elegant, a few eloquent, and
all far outdo the common run of studio portraiture. The men are
rock-solid and apparently prepared to tackle destiny if need be,
heroes of a sort but revealed by the camera to wear ill-pressed
clothes and tend to overweight. Still, without their attendant
history to say why we should care, they do not often stop the
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Brady proclaimed his intention to capture an image of every
distinguished American and thereby write a textbook of his time.
The belief was that faces could teach lasting lessons; as Thomas
Carlyle wrote, ``Often I have found a Portrait Superior in real
instruction to half-a-dozen written `biographies.'''
</P>
<P>
   The photographs were meant to forge an identity for a nation
still uncertain of what set it apart and in need of a unifying
principle as slavery threatened to sunder it. Brady sought America
in the character of its leading citizens and memorialized it in the
new kind of monument created by photography. He wrote history on
the spot so that future citizens could read in his pictures what
their country stood for when it was still young.
</P>
<P>
   But history is notoriously fickle. It immortalizes some people
who played major roles in their day and simply discards others. Men
like Ulysses S. Grant and Jefferson Davis still stir up curiosity
about whether visual clues to character might shed light on events
they influenced. Just enough might be known about Horace Greeley to
make his tentative, even poignant expression a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But many of Brady's sitters are today mere strangers standing
still while time and viewers inexorably move on. Among lesser
figures, only the power of a personality has great interest now _
William Marcy, for instance, confronting us with a tense gaze and
the look of having braved a storm or two in his political career
and survived _ but not every personality is electric.
</P>
<P>
   A few exceptionally well-turned compositions can have their own
power, as in the photograph of actor Edwin Booth, the brother of
Lincoln's assassin, and his small daughter, who clings to him and
turns back to the photographer with some distrust.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Panzer suggests that history passed Brady's portraits by
while he was still alive, for the idealistic notion of heroic
leaders did not survive a war that many of those leaders may have
brought about. Brady went bankrupt after the Civil War, not once
but twice, and ended up poor. That was mainly because he was a bad
businessman and constantly in debt, but his war pictures did not
sell well when peace arrived, and Ms. Panzer says the postwar
audience was more interested in family pictures than politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathew Brady's Portraits'' proposes other arresting histories.
One is the story of how images were manipulated long before the
computer came along. When Brady photographed General Sherman and
his staff, one general was absent. Brady took this man's portrait
later and pasted it onto the group image, then rephotographed it so
no one would know. Other photographs had sumptuous backgrounds
added by painters in Brady's employ, much as film and television
today project the Alps or outer space behind an actor on a set.
</P>
<P>
   After Lincoln's assassination, painter Alonzo Chappel asked
Brady to take photographs of everyone who had been in the room the
night Lincoln lay unconscious, each person posed as Chappel
specified. The painter then faithfully copied these portraits in a
picture showing all the visitors in the room where the president
died. This careful document was a fiction. The room was too small
to accommodate all those people, who visited by ones and twos
throughout the night. The photographically exact painting was an
early form of docudrama.
</P>
<P>
   The ``full range'' of Brady's work here includes a lot of
nonphotographic media: lithographed and engraved copies of Brady's
photographs in newspapers and journals; paintings made by artists
Brady hired to copy his portraits for exhibition in his gallery;
even a sculptured portrait, the presence of which is not explained.
</P>
<P>
   The show ends up being a history of the way photographic images
gained a wide audience in the mid-19th century through engraved
copies in illustrated journals or lithographs sold separately. By
1860, small, inexpensive images brought actual photographs into
many homes.
</P>
<P>
   And already the emphasis was on images of famous people, famous
for more solid achievements than those of many celebrities today.
Indeed, until early in this century, the press printed more
articles about politicians and businessmen than entertainers. Yet
Brady's subjects were the celebrities of his day, and he benefited
from fame by association.
</P>
<P>
   He was himself a star and worked hard to keep his name before
the public. Distinguished citizens had him take their portraits
because they intuited, if they could not yet have spelled it out,
that the world was becoming dependent on images, which in one guise
or another were already turning out to be the keys to fame, success
and whatever immortality life on earth affords. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathew Brady's Portraits: Images as History, Photography as
Art'' remains at the International Center of Photography Midtown,
1133 Avenue of the Americas, at 43rd Street, through Sept. 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
