<SLUG> BC-ETHNIC-STUDIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FACULTY DEFEND ETHNIC STUDIES PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some faculty in the University of California
system have jumped to the defense of ethnic studies programs amid
questions raised by Ward Connerly, a university regent who has
staunchly fought affirmative action in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to defending the curriculum, the professors
questioned whether the regents should be involved in curriculum
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legitimacy and credibility of the university depends
entirely on its ability to conduct research freely without
political intimidation,'' said Ling-chi Wang, chair of the ethnic
studies department at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Wang said the university, not just his department, should be
concerned with Connerly's remarks this week calling for a review of
ethnic studies.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly is the man behind the regents' 1995 decision to ban
race-based admissions and hiring and, in 1996, the passage of
Proposition 209, the ballot initiative that effectively abolished
affirmative action in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly, who is black, questioned the validity of a course such
as black history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their contributions aren't being represented, you correct
that in an overall history course,'' he said. ``I'm not sure you
need a separate black history curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned the legitimacy of women's studies, along with
gay and lesbian studies or any discipline that probes issues of
identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like personal ancestry, or your heritage, to the extent
that they're important, you get them at home, or you should have it
in high school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly has asked for more information about ethnic studies
courses _ how many students take them, what they learn, what they
do afterward. He said he planned to talk to more professors from
all fields before bringing up the matter at a meeting of regents.
</P>
<P>
   Connerly acknowledged that curriculum matters are the
responsibility of the faculty at each campus. For the board of
regents to review a department would be unprecedented.
</P>
<P>
   He said the only way to do away with a department would be by
manipulating the budget. However, university system spokesman Rick
Malaspina said regents only distribute money from the overall
University of California budget to individual campuses and have no
say in how each campus chooses to allocate the money.
</P>
<P>
   Regent William Bagley, a San Francisco lawyer, described his
reaction to Connerly's comments as ``involuntary muscular
contractions in my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The board should not be determining what curriculum is
taught,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   California campuses have courses that include African-American,
Asian-American, Native-American and Hispanic studies. The programs
were born out of the Third World student strikes at San Francisco
State in 1968. Gender and womens studies also emerged at that time.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco State and Berkeley were the first universities to
establish ethnic studies programs in 1969 and many schools around
the country followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Asian-American Studies Center at the University of
California at Los Angeles is the largest in the country, with an
endowment of more than $1 million and more than 2,000 students
enrolled in 70 classes each year.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic programs go beyond identity issues, and students who take
the courses are of all races, one professor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I taught ethnic studies at Sonoma State, it was mostly
white students,'' said Gin Yong Pang, a Berkeley-based professor.
``Many were interested in community work, or they'd say, `Our state
is becoming very diverse and I'm going to be working with a very
diverse population. If I have no idea where these people are coming
from, it's going to be very frustrating.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Connerly said the faculty who do question ethnic studies
programs are afraid to be vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some faculty members with serious reservations about its
academic merit just don't want to go on the record,'' he said.
``There's a lot of political correctness involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
