<SLUG> BC-PLENTY-FILM-REVIEW-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HAV PLENTY': A FEATHERWEIGHT BUT REFRESHINGLY BUOYANT SOCIAL
COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a male character in Christopher Scott Cherot's witty
screwball comedy ``Hav Plenty'' asks a woman he has just met,
``What's your first impression?'' she retorts, ``I'll let you know
when you impress me.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, an up-to-the-minute examination of the mating habits
of well-heeled young black professionals in New York City, is
packed with such snappy exchanges among competitive, upwardly
mobile characters who, despite their vanity and self-absorption,
are disarming in the vulnerability that occasionally leaks through
the cracks of their brittle exteriors.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator and self-deprecating observer of this scene is an
aspiring young novelist and screenwriter named Lee Plenty (Cherot),
who is the only member of his group to have no money. Temporarily
homeless and suffering from writer's block, Lee is camping out in
the apartment of Havilland Savage (Chenoa Maxwell), an old college
friend, while she's visiting her mother in Washington. Beautiful,
chic, haughty and avidly materialistic, Havilland, who works in
publishing, is on the verge of becoming engaged to Michael Simmons
(Hill Harper), a pop-soul singer and songwriter whose debut album,
``Love 40,'' has just gone platinum.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, whom some are hailing as ``the new Marvin Gaye,'' is so
pleased with himself that he greets friends and fans alike with the
same annoying little slogan, ``Hey! Love 40, baby!'' One of the
songs on his record, whose lyrics Lee recites in a tone of mild
derision, is a swatch of smarmy braggadocio called ``Crack Addict''
that's not about drugs. As the movie opens, Havilland has already
caught Michael cheating once and has begun having serious doubts
about their future.
</P>
<P>
   Lee happens to be Michael's polar opposite, an anomaly in a
world of macho preening. He takes a self-effacing pleasure in
announcing that he is broke and ``homeless'' and then gauging the
revulsion that his admission incites. His statement that he doesn't
date prompts some women to assume he must be gay. But Lee's air of
exaggerated indifference exerts its own magnetism. And after
joining Havilland and her family in Washington for New Year's Eve,
he finds himself resisting the aggressive sexual overtures of four
different women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hav Plenty'' may be a featherweight social comedy without a
political bone in its body, but its characters are refreshingly
buoyant. Havilland, whom Ms. Maxwell embodies with a perfect
mixture of heat and hauteur, is a woman who appears to have
everything, including an attitude. And the movie shows you exactly
how that attitude and the expectations that go with it can act as
an impenetrable barrier to any real personal fulfillment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The funniest character is Havilland's brassy best friend,
Caroline (Tammi Katherine Jones), who changes her hairdo every few
hours and ludicrously lards her conversation with French phrases.
Caroline is the kind of compulsively contrary person who, when
reading a warning sign not to flush a toilet, immediately presses
the lever to see what will happen, then afterward refuses to take
the blame.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Lee, the filmmaker's obvious alter ego, who binds this
froth into something that feels like a lighter-than-air hybrid of
Woody Allen and Spike Lee. It turns out, of course, that despite
his strenuous disapproval of her values, he has been in love with
Havilland since college.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then, Lee turns to address the camera and announce
what will happen next. As he is about to have his first serious
relationship talk with Havilland, he invites us to follow him into
her bedroom and watch as he makes a complete fool of himself. With
his self-deflating cool and amused insight into the shallowness of
the buppie world in which he drifts, Lee is one of the most
original and likable characters to pop up in a movie in quite a
while.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HAV PLENTY'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed and edited by Christopher Scott Cherot;
director of photography, Kerwin Devonish; music by Wendy Melvoin
and Lisa Coleman; produced by Cherot and Robyn M. Greene; released
by Miramax Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Christopher Scott Cherot (Lee Plenty), Chenoa Maxwell
(Havilland Savage), Hill Harper (Michael Simmons) and Tammi
Katherine Jones (Caroline Gooden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 105 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hav Plenty'' is rated R (under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has sexual situations and profanity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
