<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONNARD-RETROSPECTIVE     06-18 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONNARD-RETROSPECTIVE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A DREAM WORLD OF PAINTING, YIELDING ITS SECRETS
SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Pierre Bonnard died in 1947, at 79, Cahiers
d'Art published an editorial by Christian Zervos, one of Picasso's
mouthpieces. Picasso called Bonnard a piddler, saying: ``Don't talk
to me about Bonnard. That's not painting, what he does.'' And
worse: ``He is not really a modern painter.''
</P>
<P>
   Zervos parroted Picasso's view, and since Cahiers d'Art was the
most influential art magazine, this opinion spread.
</P>
<P>
   In the 50 years since then, Bonnard's reputation has largely
recovered, though I think Americans still don't appreciate him
enough. He doesn't fit comfortably into the history of modernism,
so we tend to regard him as an anachronism: an Impressionist after
Impressionism was dead. Puritanical, we're also a little wary of an
art of such paradisiacal beauty, whose complexity and peculiar
sadness isn't immediately apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonnard retrospective opening Sunday at the Museum of Modern
Art should change some minds. It's a tendentious show. The stress
is not on the early years, when he earned a niche in history as one
of the Nabis, who emulated Gauguin, but on his later years. The
idea is that Bonnard remained a modernist and didn't just turn into
a demode painter of bonbons on the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no one who has looked seriously at his work can have
thought of him as a lightweight hedonist, much less a piddler,
though he did paint some bad pictures because he painted a lot.
Never mind; his best work deserves to be ranked with Matisse's and
Picasso's, and if you doubt this, spend time in the show's last
rooms with the paintings of his wife, Marthe, which are mysterious
elegies of love. His self-portraits, as a group, are also
unequaled, and that's not forgetting Rembrandt's, van Gogh's,
Beckmann's or Picasso's.
</P>
<P>
   I dwell on Picasso because his genius seems the antithesis of
Bonnard's. The photographer Cartier-Bresson, who knew them both,
once explained Picasso's disdain for Bonnard by saying that Picasso
``had no tenderness.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, Bonnard's art is tender, and it also requires
patience by a viewer to grasp its precise emotional pitch. You can
appreciate the pictures superficially because they're ecstatically
colored. But unless you look long and hard, you don't really get
Bonnard _ his rigorous geometry, the way his compositions are
locked in place yet everything seems fluid and shimmering, as with
Cezanne.
</P>
<P>
   And on one level that's the point of the art: it's about looking
hard and recognizing that things appear different when seen out of
the corner of your eye or squinting into the sun or staring from
light into shadow.
</P>
<P>
   A good example is his ``Breakfast Table,'' the parts of which
disentangle themselves only after we stare at it. Like other
Bonnards, it first looks flat, as if the forms were flowers pressed
between pages in a book. Someone has compared Bonnard's patchy
images to tweed. The woven surfaces yield slowly to depth.
</P>
<P>
   We gradually make out a landscape through a window, a teapot on
the table, the edge of a chair, the open door beside a radiator _
and Marthe gingerly inspecting a teacup with the same curiosity
that we have about the whole image. Proust, Bonnard's literary
analogue, wrote about ``optical illusions which prove to us that we
should never succeed in identifying objects if we did not bring
some process of reasoning to bear on them.'' And that's what's
happening here: Marthe struggling to put a name to what she sees.
</P>
<P>
   Only after a moment do we notice that there's another figure in
the picture, too: the mirrored reflection of the artist behind her,
looking at us looking at her looking at the cup.
</P>
<P>
   I think the source of Bonnard's intimacy is not that he painted
cozy interiors but that he inhabited his pictures in this way. He
once told a model that he wanted her not to sit still but to move
around the room while he painted. ``He wanted both presence and
absence,'' she concluded. Put differently, he tried to convey his
presence: to imply the interaction between him and his subject.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, critics like to link his pictures of Marthe
bathing to Degas' nudes because they look similar at first. But the
difference is that Degas maintained a clinical distance, while
Bonnard sometimes almost seems to project himself right into the
image of Marthe.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he paints his knee or thumb in a corner of the picture
to make explicit that he's there. Sometimes he's present implicitly
in the surface of the paintings, which looks caressed and nervously
fussed over. One friend of Bonnard's said that Bonnard loved and
cared for Marthe but also ``feared her, put up with her.'' They met
in 1893 and stayed together until her death in 1942. For a few
years, in the early 1920s, he had a relationship with a model named
Renee Monchaty. They spoke about marriage but he wouldn't leave
Marthe. Renee killed herself.
</P>
<P>
   One story has it that he found her body in a bathtub. Bonnard
depicted her in ``Young Women in the Garden'' as a kind of robust
flapper-angel: a beaming blond with emerald eyes. Marthe is a dour
shadow figure looking on. The picture was begun in 1923. Bonnard
returned to it at the end of his life, after Marthe was dead,
adding a cornflower backdrop for Renee, a halo.
</P>
<P>
   Marthe, by contrast, was often likened to a startled bird: a
dark-haired, slight woman of fragile health, apparently given to
delusions, with a hoarse, asthmatic voice. Her suspicion of
everyone except Bonnard shaped their vagabond life in secluded
villas and cheap hotels. He was a successful painter, yet they
seemed to revel in monastic discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   He dressed like a retired government clerk, and he drew on any
odd scrap of paper, which he then stuffed into his rumpled jacket.
He also sketched on the pages of a little pocket calendar in which,
every day, he noted the weather. It's a pity the show doesn't
include his drawings. Their relationship to his paintings would
make another good exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   At the small pink stucco house on a hill in Le Cannet, near
Cannes, where Bonnard and Marthe finally settled, he devised a
cramped, jerry-built space with a little bamboo table for his
paints and a chipped plate for a palette. He tacked his canvases to
the wall, several at a time, close together, like postcards on a
bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There's a wonderful photograph by Brassai, from 1946, showing
several of these pinned-up canvases, and Bonnard, in a hat and
furry slippers, bending over to touch up one picture of an almond
tree. It's the pose of a man feeding birds, a stooped figure of
sweet humility.
</P>
<P>
   Was he suffocated in marriage? Who knows? Love affairs are
always inscrutable from the outside. A self-portrait from 1931,
which is in the exhibition, shows him as a scrawny shadowboxer,
fighting who knows what demons. Mostly he seems to have spent a
life contentedly painting what was immediately around him because,
for his purposes, that was enough. He often spoke about dreaming
while painting, and this may have meant partly that he escaped into
art but also that he allowed the images to assume their own lives:
letting the shapes shift and the forms take on new guises. ``People
always speak of submission to nature,'' he said. ``There is also
submission to the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   So he painted the mix of jasmine, mimosa, honeysuckle and
wisteria in the garden behind the house at Le Cannet as if it were
Eden. Occasionally he would sneak away from Marthe, through the
garden, to walk the dog or to meet friends for coffee.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise they were together, alone. She is in 384 pictures
by him, her face mostly blurred or obscured. It makes sense that
her tub, as he paints it, has often been compared to a coffin or a
womb. It can be either. Bonnard, a master of indirection, was a
lifelong disciple of Mallarme. I recommend reading the letters
between Matisse and Bonnard. Matisse was enraged after Bonnard's
death by Zervos' editorial in Cahiers d'Art and scrawled across his
copy of the magazine: ``I certify that Pierre Bonnard is a great
painter today and assuredly in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But the letters are something else: understated, modest. They
can make you weep, though it's just two codgers moaning about the
weather and their health because everything that's really important
goes without saying.
</P>
<P>
   And that's essentially how it is in Bonnard's art. Things don't
happen, they're implied.
</P>
<P>
   Above all you find this with his pictures of Marthe. He's
unflinching when it comes to aging in his self-portraits,
heartbreakingly, but she remains in the pictures of the 1940s
uncannily as she was in ``Siesta'' of 1900. Only the light changes.
Increasingly Bonnard paints gaily patterned rooms where big bowls
of fruit sit on the tables and the open windows allow the beaming
summer sun to pour in on perfumed breezes of orange and lavender.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Marthe, sitting at the table or standing before a
mirror, a ripe reflection of youth, eternally 25. Sarah Whitfield,
the curator who organized this exhibition for the Tate Gallery in
London, where it was shown this spring, suggests in the catalog
that we see these pictures as images embalmed in memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These works crystallize what has always been Bonnard's primary
mood, that of elegy,'' Ms. Whitfield writes. ``He has often been
described as a painter of pleasure, but he is not a painter of
pleasure. He is a painter of the effervescence of pleasure and the
disappearance of pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. Walking through the show I suddenly recalled a favorite
passage from Nabokov's ``Speak, Memory'': Uncle Ruka finds some
French children's books from his own childhood in Nabokov's
schoolroom. Nabokov comes across the same books decades later and
they trigger the recollection of Ruka recollecting his past:
</P>
<P>
   ``I see again my schoolroom in Vyra, the blue roses of the
wallpaper, the open window. Its reflection fills the oval mirror
above the leathern couch where my uncle sits, gloating over a
tattered book. A sense of security, of well-being, of summer warmth
pervades my memory. That robust reality makes a ghost of the
present. The mirror brims with brightness; a bumblebee has entered
the room and bumps against the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is as it should be, nothing will ever change,
nobody will ever die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonnard'' opens on Sunday at the Museum of Modern Art, 11 W.
53rd St., where it remains through Oct. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
