<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-FITNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL ROOM FOR BIRDIES, BURGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ David Duval, one of the golfers in the U.S. Open
field who has recently discovered the magic of fitness, was waxing
on the vital topics of the day _ the height and fluffiness of the
rough, the hardness of the greens, the state of the club face in
modern society and the debatable virtues of ``The Fountainhead'' _
when someone asked him if, given the choice and equality of
paycheck, he would rather play golf or go fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real good question,'' he said with a laugh, making it
clear without saying so that he would rather sit on a boat
terrorizing the local trout than shoot 70 anywhere in the world.
``I don't know how to answer that.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, he does. Even though he lost 40 pounds to improve
his stamina, to the point where you just want to give him a
sandwich on general principle, there is a part of him that sees the
value in a hamper full of goodies, an ice chest full of more than
just ice, and a day without exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, a man of the people. The Eva Peron of the PGA, if you
must strain for an analogy.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, we suspect there are more of them out there _
``them'' being golfing flatbellies who stifle their natural craving
for a properly prepared dish of linguine and sausage in search of
the proper way to hit a sand wedge or some other fascist silliness.
</P>
<P>
   We have heard ad nauseam of the legion of golfers who are now
doing hours of flexibility and strength work because of the sudden
minirash of back injuries, because better fitness might allow them
to play a couple of extra years on the Senior Tour down the road,
and because it is good for the PGA Tour to display its clientele as
athletes in the truest 31-waist sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, we've had enough of it. Better for us civilians to
take solace in the tales of those who either took the cure but
aren't fanatics about it, or those who defy convention. Your Colin
Montgomeries, your Fuzzy Zoellers, your John Dalys, your Tim
Herrons yearning to have a good round and then top it off with a
proper dinner instead of two hours on Satan's treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Westwood, the big-haired Englishman, says he lost seven
pounds for the betterment of his game but admits he has put back on
at least a couple since arriving in town. Tom Lehman, who dropped
25 pounds over the winter and lost his rhythm, now says he has
found it again and hastily adds, ``I read somewhere that I'm a gym
rat now, that I work out for an hour every day ... that's not true.
I just lost some weight.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of attitude we need to see more of this week.
As the modern golfer gets farther and farther from his or her less
angular forebears, it is heartwarming to know that not everyone in
the field wants to be able to lay on his bed at night bouncing
quarters off his stomach. It is not, you see, the true golfing way.
</P>
<P>
   The golf establishment has always had this problem coping with
those who claim that golf is not an athletic endeavor, let alone a
sport. This is, of course, nonsense, because golf meets all the
criteria for membership _ it requires the use of your body in a
pursuit that requires skill and strength, it is a sport whose goal
can be quantified (one stroke equals one stroke, period), and you
neither have to wear rhinestones nor smear your hair with gelatin
to impress the Romanian judge with the bad posture and the squint.
</P>
<P>
   This is also why golf struggles so with the Casey Martin issue,
because it fears the communist notion that people will think golf
is not really about skill and artistry but about riding around the
course on a modified sofa and minibar and throwing the empties out
the back every other hole.
</P>
<P>
   The level of discourse in that matter has become so grindingly
dull that Martin spent much of Monday and Tuesday being asked about
the number of seats on his cart. Nothing this side of ``NASCAR On
The Air'' delves into such vehicular detail, and with less benefit
to society.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, it's enough to make your brain leak out your ear. Or to
hit the guilty party with a dictionary until his brain leaks out
his ear.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the best outcome this week would be for Montgomerie,
or Herron, or Zoeller to win the tournament _ or for that matter,
even Guy Boros if you want to add to Olympic's tradition of
rewarding the previously underknown. The Olympic Club is a tough
place to walk, true, but the Texas Open is played on a far more
hilly course in San Antonio (they use carts in some portions of the
grounds) in heat that would make Bolivians cranky, and the last
three winners were Duffy Waldorf, David Ogrin and Herron _ total
throw-weight 655.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, a victory by one of the above will spare us
another long acceptance speech by the winner in which he thanks his
wife, his kids, his primary through tertiary sponsors, and his
personal trainer Gunter. Not necessarily in that order. Because
athleticism, shotmaking and the odd cheeseburger are not mutually
exclusive, and never have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
