<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARLAND-TRIBUTE-NYT &LR;      06-18 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLAND-TRIBUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING JUDY, OVER AND UNDER THAT RAINBOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here was the voice quivering with a scary,
heartbreaking fragility one second, then thrillingly confident the
next, and always hovering perilously on the line between tears and
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the eyes, wide and scared and darting like the gaze of
a frightened deer one second, but fiercely mirthful the next as the
cherry lips spread into a grin of voracious playfulness. And don't
forget the hands, crossed on the chest one second, then suddenly
flung upward to the sky, the tiny fists clutched and shaking with
an iron determination.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was Judy Garland as seen in film clips from her 1960s
television show and flashed onto the walls of Carnegie Hall. These
clips, of which there were not nearly enough, along with a final
galvanizing concert recording of Garland singing ``Over the
Rainbow,'' were the only heart-stopping moments in a disappointing
and often dreary two- evening celebration of Garland's music on
Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The simple, sad fact of the tribute is that even on old
black-and-white videos, Garland's voice and stage presence are so
mesmerizing that no one could begin to compete with the raw
emotional power surging through her body like a kind of natural
electricity. Many tried, not the least of them Lorna Luft, one of
Garland's two daughters (Liza Minnelli was conspicuously absent),
and the evening's co-host with a robotically formal Robert Stack,
an early Garland pal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luft has a solid, medium-large, pleasantly rounded voice
with no defining personality, and her interpretations of several
Garland signature songs (including a big pumped-up ``The Man That
Got Away'') performed to the brassy orchestral arrangements Mort
Lindsey created for Garland, lacked inner fire.
</P>
<P>
   They were dutiful, affectionate imitations whose tone was in
keeping with Ms. Luft's blandly upbeat reminiscences of growing up
with ``mama.'' To hear Ms. Luft tell it, life with Garland was a
protracted episode on a cheery sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Following Ms. Luft's lead, a bunch of second-rank singers were
trotted out to perform Garland signature songs and pay stiff verbal
tribute. Vikki Carr, Gogi Grant, Nancy Dussault and Pamela Myers
were among the old-style Las Vegas and Broadway belters who went
through the motions of ``feeling'' Garland's spirit and came up
empty. Their male equivalents, Robert Goulet and Jack Jones, also
turned in performances that had the same pallid professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the hollow emoting and sanitized praise, a few
performers succeeded in making personal statements. Over two
evenings, the only live vocal performance with emotional bite was
Weslia Whitfield's lingering, pungently accented version of
``You're Nearer.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Herman appeared both evenings to sing his clever rewritten
version of ``That's Entertainment'' (renamed ``That's Judy
Garland'') and to announce that the ``trick'' behind composing his
Broadway showstoppers has always been to imagine them sung by
Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Of the many anecdotes told, only those related by Shana
Alexander and Elaine Stritch conveyed a vivid sense of the ball of
lightning that was Judy Garland. Ms. Alexander who was backstage
with Garland on the night of her historic Carnegie Hall concert on
April 23, 1961, remembered holding the singer's lighted cigarette
as she clutched the curtain and prepared to make a stage entrance
during which she ``actually got bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stritch, as is her way, cut to the chase with tales of
partying with Garland until 6 a.m. In summing up Garland's power as
a performer, Ms. Stritch seemed genuinely awestruck by the
phenomenon of someone who, as she put it ``reached out to an
audience with absolute 100 percent truth.'' Hyperbolic? Yes. But
also accurate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
