<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MULAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY FIGHTS THE GOOD FIGHT WITH A GORGEOUSLY ANIMATED `MULAN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Disney still high on the Southern Baptist Convention's
dartboard of decadence, the studio couldn't have timed the release
of its 36th animated feature any better.
</P>
<P>
   Just as 1996's ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame'' _ with its
messages of religious persecution and lustful villainy in the
clergy _ rang out in theaters just days after the convention
announced its national boycott of the Walt Disney Co., ``Mulan''
also arrives with its irony intact.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the convention asserted in a revised statement of
beliefs that ``a wife is to submit graciously to the servant
leadership of her husband''; this week Disney unveils the story of
strong-headed young Chinese girl who forces an entire culture to
rethink its long history of subjugation of women.
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant coincidence, or a piece of sociopolitical marketing
savvy on the grandest scale? As deliciously devious as the latter
would be, considering the amount of time it takes to produce an
animated film _ ``Mulan'' has been in the works for the past five
years _ a pleasant coincidence seems most likely.
</P>
<P>
   But ``pleasant'' is hardly a strong enough word to describe the
lavish work of art that is Disney's latest animated effort.
Gorgeously animated, delightfully voiced and expertly unfolded,
``Mulan'' stands as one of the studio's finest cartoon features
since ``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   Ming-Na Wen gives voice to the headstrong Fa Mulan, another
well-rounded addition to the Disney pantheon of strong female
characters. Filled with good intentions, Mulan struggles to bring
honor to her family and earn the respect of her father, but she
never quite gets it right.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hun army invades China, Mulan is distressed to learn
that her aged, infirm father will be required to fight. So later
that night she takes his armor and sword, disguises herself as a
man and runs away to fight in his place.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that revealing her deception will mean certain death for
their daughter, the family prays to their ancestors to protect her.
The best the family spirits can muster is a scrawny, snakelike
dragon named Mushu (Eddie Murphy) who, along with a lucky-cricket
friend Cri-kee, sets out to help Mulan become a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   It's no easy task, especially considering that Mulan's fellow
fighters are a few noodles short of a bowlful. There's Chien-Po
(Jerry S. Tondo), the gentle giant; Yao (Harvey Fierstein), the
diminutive tough guy; and Ling (Gedde Watanabe), the lanky
loudmouth. Of course, Mushu's lamebrain advice usually lands Mulan
in hot water with her commanding officer, Captain Shang (the voice
of B.D. Wong), a stern taskmaster and top-notch soldier.
</P>
<P>
   The troops are whipped into shape soon enough, just in time to
witness the aftermath of devastation of a nearby village by the
Huns, led by the evil Shan-Yu (Miguel Ferrer). When the armies
finally clash in an amazing computer-animated attack sequence that
blows away the wildebeest stampede in ``The Lion King,'' Mulan's
quick thinking saves the day. But then she is injured, and her
secret is revealed, forcing her expulsion from the army.
</P>
<P>
   Shan-Yu and the Huns aren't finished, however, and it's once
again up to Mulan to save the emperor from certain death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is a departure for Disney on a number of fronts. While
technically a musical, the Jerry Goldsmith score and Matthew Wilder
songs lack the kind of magic composer Alan Menken brought to
Disney's animated efforts. But like ``Hercules,'' ``Mulan'' is more
of a movie with songs in it than a full-blown musical, and a few
tunes _ namely ``Reflection'' and ``A Girl Worth Fighting For'' _
hold up well.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike almost every Disney film in recent memory, the plot
doesn't center on a love story. It focuses instead on the coming of
age of a young girl. And the studio explores Chinese mysticism and
faith more deeply and accurately than any culture it has Disneyfied
to date.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are pretty close to the Disney mold of late:
strong woman, goofy sidekicks, intimidating bad guy. Wen's Mulan is
a charming heroine, and Murphy steals every scene he's in, making
his mischievous dragon the first Disney creation to give Robin
Williams' Genie in ``Aladdin'' a run for his money. But the showy,
camp-it-up style of Disney's most memorable villains instead gets
the strong, silent treatment in the menacing embodiment of Shan-Yu.
</P>
<P>
   Created almost entirely by Disney's Orlando, Fla., facility,
``Mulan'' promises to take the studio in a bold new direction, the
single distinction that's kept it at the top of the animation game.
Let's hope DreamWorks, Fox and Warner Bros. are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is rated G and is suitable for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Mulan''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: G
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Voices of Ming-Na Wen, B.D. Wong, Eddie Murphy
</P>
<P>
   Length: 87 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: 4 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
