<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-EQUIPMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USGA TAKES SOFT STANCE ON NEW CLUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ On the subject of Big Bertha and the other war
clubs of modern golf, what the U.S. Golf Association didn't say is
more notable than what it did.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Director David Fay said Wednesday that the USGA has
developed a ``conformance'' test to measure the spring-like or
trampoline effects of clubs, a growing concern in this age of
strong and long hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Fay said particulars of the test _ which will be based on the
rebound velocity of a golf ball off a club face _ will be released
to manufacturers within the next few weeks, in advance of a meeting
with manufacturers and others this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the current crop of clubheads was pretty much cleared for
continued use.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there may be exceptions that we are not aware of,'' Fay
said, ``we expect that all clubs that (already) have been submitted
to the USGA will satisfy the new standard.''
</P>
<P>
   That was it for sweeping change on the eve of the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA didn't directly address effects of several other
technological advancements in golf equipment that have been under
serious scrutiny, including balls, putter lengths, loft limits of
irons and number of clubs in bags.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's major manufacturers have talked of possible
lawsuits to help protect their billion-dollar business.
</P>
<P>
   They liked at least some of what they heard from Fay and USGA
President Buzz Taylor, who said: ``We are perfectly satisfied with
what we see today. But we don't know what is coming tomorrow. There
are an awful lot of people that have an aerospace or high-metal
technology background that are now involved in the game of golf,
and our consultants have suggested that there are materials around
the corner which may create a problem for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   John Solheim of Karsten Manufacturing, which makes Ping
products, said, ``I'm very happy to hear that our clubs meet their
specifications. But there's still a cloud of indecision over the
whole thing. I really feel they need to make field tests (of
clubs), not laboratory tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Ely Callaway of Big Bertha-making Callaway said, ``We're quite
pleased the USGA executive committee came to the conclusion that
modern-technology clubs are not a threat to the game _ and are in
fact good for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the interests of the golfers of the world, we want to
make improvements so that clubs are a little more forgiving,
accurate and get greater distance. We don't want to be inhibited. I
think the USGA threw up some caution on that _ and that's not good
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Solheim added, ``Innovation is part of the game,'' and noted the
potential effects of the USGA's club restrictions on the
recreational players who don't hit the ball like Tiger Woods or
John Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 25 million golfers,'' he said, ``and only 2 million
of them have handicaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay tried to downplay any dispute with the manufacturers. Asked
if the USGA would try to make peace with the equipment companies,
he said, ``I didn't know we were at war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
