<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIOGRAPHY' LOOKS AT THE NELSON FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though it was commonly referred to as ``Ozzie and Harriet,'' the
full title gives the game away. ``The Adventures of Ozzie and
Harriet'' posited everyday family life as a dynamic, exciting
activity, and the show went a long way toward convincing 1950s
middle America that was true.
</P>
<P>
   The images trotted out in this two-hour installment of
``Biography'' influenced and arguably warped the perspectives of
millions of less-than-picture-perfect families: Ozzie sitting in
the living room in a jacket and tie, reading the paper; Harriet
cheerfully making sandwiches in the kitchen while the whole family
looks on. Eventually, their younger son, Ricky, would pick up a
guitar and become a teen idol with hits like ``Travelin' Man,''
while his brother, David, steadfastly represented neglected
siblings everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Coming along just when television was making its first major
impact, the Nelsons helped shape the American family's sense of
what it ought to be: close-knit and carefree. The documentary's
shrewd selection of a major Nelson problem shows Ozzie desperate to
find some tutti-frutti ice cream late at night.
</P>
<P>
   Covering three generations, this ``Biography'' episode is wider
in scope and more intriguing than most. It includes family movies
and interviews with the surviving Nelsons, notably David himself,
and all four of Rick's children. Still, it adheres to the form of
this immensely popular A&AMP;E series. It is straightforward and kind
rather than deeply probing, despite a few stabs at social
commentary. What is most surprising is how effectively its images,
both from the television show and from real life, linger.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary begins with a quick glimpse at Ozzie and Harriet
before they married. He was a teetotaling band leader; she was a
singer with a slightly sultry image. ``She was a babe in the
'30s,'' says their granddaughter, actress Tracy Nelson, the most
articulate and revealing source on camera here.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Ozzie had a brainstorm: a radio show called ``The
Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet,'' in which they played themselves.
Eventually, their children joined them. Inthe show's television
run, from 1952 to 1966, America watched the Nelson boys grow up and
marry, yet stay remarkably close to home.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to make too much of the way the Nelsons portrayed
themselves, blurring art and reality. ``Biography'' doesn't mention
that Jack Benny, and George Burns and Gracie Allen, were already
doing that. The difference is that the Nelsons depicted themselves
not as the show-business family they were, but as a typical family.
</P>
<P>
   The least believable element was that Ozzie had no apparent
employment on the show. Off-camera, he was a smart, controlling
businessman; he made a deal with ABC to broadcast the series for 10
years, with himself as producer, director and head writer.
</P>
<P>
   Though it tries, ``Biography'' doesn't convincingly depict a
vast distance between the Nelsons' on-air and off-air
personalities. Peter Graves, the narrator, says, ``The real David
Nelson, a typical self-conscious teen-ager, looked upon his
television character as a separate invention.'' But we never quite
see how.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the show ended that the perfect image began to
crack. But there were rumblings before that. Tracy Nelson recalls
being told what she calls ``an outrageous story'' by her mother,
Kris, who was three months' pregnant with Tracy when she and Rick
married. To preserve the family's wholesome image, Ozzie persuaded
the hospital to change Tracy's birth certificate; the infant was
even put in an incubator, though she wasn't really premature.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Most of the family's problems centered on Rick, who became a
casualty of his own fame and image. His story is the most affecting
here, his absence the most haunting.
</P>
<P>
   He tried, with occasional success, to put together a new musical
career. He and Kris entered a tumultuous phase of drug use, and
eventually divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our parents both effectively lost their minds at a certain
point,'' says Matthew Nelson, Rick and Kris' son (who with his
twin, Gunnar, made records as Nelson in the 1990s and repeated
their father's teen-idol success). Recalling her years as part of
the country's most idealized family, a sober Kris Nelson now says,
``I spent my whole life trying to fight that fairy tale: first
trying to be it and then trying to just tell the truth and get away
from that perfection that everybody was insisting on.''
</P>
<P>
   This Biography may overstate the importance of Rick's later
music, but not the strain of trying to outrun his youthful success.
``If memories are all I sing/ I'd rather drive a truck,'' he wrote
in the song ``Garden Party,'' his biggest adult hit. He was touring
in 1985 when his plane crashed and he was killed, at 45. By then,
Ozzie had died. David's wife, Yvonne, speculates that Harriet (who
died in 1994) dealt with her son's death by choosing to believe he
was simply on the road.
</P>
<P>
   With such revelations, the Nelsons become wrenchingly real. This
``Biography'' may leave deep social analysis to others, but it
brings the Nelsons vividly to life, and makes it possible to
understand how these sincere, appealing characters exerted such a
wishful hold on America's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY'
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie and Harriet: The Adventures of America's Favorite Family
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Sunday on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   Produced for A&AMP;E by Peter Jones Productions; Peter Jones,
director and writer; Andrew Tilles, supervising producer; Peter
Jones and Selina Lin, producers; Peter Graves, host; Robert Israel,
music; Michael Cascio, senior vice president of programming, A&AMP;E,
and executive producer of ``Biography,'' CarolAnne Dolan,
supervising producer of ``Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   With: Graves, David Nelson, Kristin Nelson Tinker, Tracy Nelson,
Art Linkletter, Billy May, Fred De Cordova, Dr. Joyce Brothers,
Dwight Yoakam and Pete Fornatale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
