<HEADLINE>
A CENTENNIAL SERENADE TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ This city really knows how to give a party. This
weekend, it will celebrate the 100th anniversary of its
consolidation with a colossal three-day birthday revel in all five
boroughs.
 &HT;    Centennial Weekend, the apex of the yearlong New York City 100:
Greater New York Centennial Celebration, will salute the city on
land (with parades, street fairs, walking tours and exhibitions),
at sea (a harbor festival on the Hudson River with everything from
ferryboats to kayaks) and in the air (simultaneous fireworks in the
five boroughs on Saturday night, bursting over 24 miles of sky).
 &HT;    There will be festivities indoors (historic house tours,
prix-fixe meals at $18.98), on the pavement (centennial sidewalk
sales) and in greener places (a weekend festival at various
botanical gardens). At 3 p.m. on Sunday, bells will ring
simultaneously in all the boroughs.
 &HT;    There will also be lots of music: jazz and Latin bands at Coney
Island in Brooklyn, the Queens Symphony Orchestra in Flushing
Meadows-Corona Park, a sock hop at Orchard Beach in the Bronx, a
Dixieland band at South Beach on Staten Island, rock at the South
Street Seaport in Manhattan and an international music festival at
the World Trade Center. (A look at the musical line-up, by Jon
Pareles, follows.)
 &HT;    On Sunday, more than 100 institutions will waive admission fees
or offer free events as birthday gifts to the city. A complete list
can be found at the New York City 100 Web site: www.nyc100.org.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK SINGS ITSELF A CENTENNIAL
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JON PARELES
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This city's music is the world's music, the sound of
every group to arrive since the Dutch were met by the Indians. To
commemorate the centennial of the annexation of Brooklyn and the
consolidation of the five boroughs into one city, the musical
celebration will be as varied, scattered and unpredictable as the
city itself.
</P>
<P>
   From brass bands to Central American punta music to jazz, oldies
and alternative rock, the centennial offers glimpses of New York's
many musical worlds. (There are also scores of nonmusical events:
walking tours, exhibitions and free admission on Sunday to many
museums and gardens in all five boroughs.)
</P>
<P>
   One major event is synchronized: a citywide display of fireworks
Saturday night at 9:30, which is expected to set a new record for
the widest geographic pyrotechnic display, covering 24 miles. The
fireworks are to be accompanied by free concerts: classical works
from the Queens Symphony Orchestra in Flushing Meadows-Corona Park;
Latin and Irish music on Coney Island Beach in Brooklyn, and high
school marching bands, Dixieland jazz and 1950s oldies (from Randy
and the Rainbows) at the South Beach Boardwalk on Staten Island.
There are more oldies (from the Regents, the Mellow Kings, and
Johnnie and Joe) on Orchard Beach in the Bronx, and, at South
Street Seaport in Manhattan, a concert by Rachid, a progressive
soul songwriter who shares Prince's mystical streak, slinky tenor
voice and willingness to explore.
</P>
<P>
   New York City 100, which is coordinating the weekend's events,
has also hooked up with other performances around the city. Many
are by local groups, but some feature nationally known musicians.
</P>
<P>
   One is a benefit concert that the songwriter Ani DiFranco is
giving for the Battery Park Conservancy. Ms. DiFranco is a
hard-strumming acoustic guitarist whose words rush out like
passionate conversation. Her songs about making her way through the
world with humor and rage and compassion have earned her a fervent
following, particularly among college students. Her fans are likely
to be singing along, verse and chorus, on every song.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Fete de la Musique,'' an annual summer solstice celebration
partly sponsored by the Alliance Francaise, does not confine itself
to French music, although it does include Autour de Lucie, a
thoughtful alternative-rock band that appeared last year at some
Lilith Festival shows. It also includes opening and closing
invocations by Silver Cloud, an American Indian group, and a solo
singer from Belgium, Bernard Massuir, who has been compared to
Bobby McFerrin.
</P>
<P>
   Its centerpiece, however, is a performance by Philip Glass,
presenting music he collaborated on with the Gambian griot Foday
Musa Suso for the production of a play by Jean Genet, ``The
Screens.'' There's some piquancy in French sponsorship for the
music; the play itself is about French colonialism in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the exploitation and brutalization of one culture
by another,'' Glass said in a telephone interview. ``I was at the
premiere in 1964 in Paris, and there was a riot. The French
considered it so insulting, they tried to shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   To create a combination of African and Western music for ``The
Screens,'' Glass decided to work with Suso, who plays the kora
(harp-guitar), and other African instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always very self-conscious about being a
conservatory-trained musician who's used to looking at notes on a
page,'' Glass said. ``I've spent the rest of my life trying to make
up for what I didn't learn at school. For this, we went to the
studio, and I didn't allow myself to write anything down.''
</P>
<P>
   For the concert, at the World Trade Center Plaza, Glass will be
performing with Suso, as well as the saxophonist Jon Gibson and a
percussionist, Zohar Fresco, playing some of the music for the
first time outside the recording studio.
</P>
<P>
   The Goldman Memorial Band is devoting its Sunday concert at
Damrosch Park to New York music from Sousa to Copland to Bernstein
to Rodgers and Hammerstein. And in the Bronx on Saturday, a
lesser-known New York community will be making itself heard with
``Punta Rock Explosion '98,'' a festival of Garifuna music. The
Garifuna, descended from West African and Carib Indians who were
exiled from St. Vincent to the coast of Central America, now live
in Honduras, Belize, Guatemala and Nicaragua. Some 75,000 live in
New York, where the bounce of traditional punta music now meshes
with electric guitars.
</P>
<P>
   It's just one more example of New York's cultural plentitude,
which is worth celebrating for another 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
