<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-NOTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS PROGNOSTICATE 
</HEADLINE>
   U.S. Open Notebook  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF and JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although the journalists polled by the U.S. Golf
Association picked Colin Montgomerie to win, the players themselves
have offered many, many other choices.
</P>
<P>
   A few free samples you won't get from the scalpers outside the
admission gates at the Olympic Club:
</P>
<P>
   David Duval likes Justin Leonard, Davis Love III, Ernie Els, Jim
Furyk and Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman picks Phil Mickelson, Duval and ``as crazy as it may
seem,'' Jack Nicklaus, who is 58. ``Even at his age, if he can just
put the ball in the fairway, I know he is going to make a lot of
pars, and if he makes a lot of pars, you know, even-par might
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson puts his money on Montgomerie and Lee Westwood. ``I
think Colin Montgomerie is a real threat to win here,'' he said.
``He works the ball left to right, and it is the perfect golf
course for Colin. I think left to right is the shot this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Simpson, an underdog winner in 1987, likes Love, Duval,
Leonard, Furyk and Els, but also says, ``I do not think there's any
reason why David Ogrin couldn't win the tournament. ... Start
looking down the list and how are you going to say Tom Watson can't
win or, who knows, even Nicklaus.''
</P>
<P>
   The forecast on the winning score has been anywhere from 7-under
to even-par _ depending on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First Watson said it was the worst, most difficult rough he has
ever seen in the U.S. Open, and that's 27 Opens. Then Tiger Woods
observed that when he was playing the 13th hole Tuesday, the
grounds crew was watering the rough and not the ever-quickening
greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that kind of interesting,'' Woods said. ``They were
watering the front part, probably two yards (on the) front part of
the green, so that anything that hits there is going to stop.
Anything that hits after, it will bounce and fly over.''
</P>
<P>
   Explained course superintendent John Fleming: ``We are counting
on the good weather. That is what little irrigation we are doing
... going around in the mornings trying to get irrigation on the
rough grass, so that it does what rough grass is supposed to do and
not just limp over.''
</P>
<P>
   USGA agronomist Tim Moraghan says players needn't worry yet that
the rough has gone over the top and become too penal at these Open
venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can't find your golf ball and we start to slow down
play and it really begins to make fun of the best players in the
universe, that is when I don't think it is quite proper,'' he said.
``I want it to be a challenge out there, but I don't want it to
embarrass someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can play basketball with a 30-foot rim or football and
narrow the goal posts more, but it is not fair and you can't allow
the athletes to display their marvelous talents. That is where we
have to draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Moraghan reputedly has a single-digit handicap.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   USGA Executive Director David Fay was asked if the Olympic Club
rough was higher than ever, or if that was only an illusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the primary rough is between 5 and 6 inches,'' he said,
``but growing grass is not so scientific that you can say it is 5.1
inches or whatever. I suspect that the competitors in the '55 Open
(at Olympic) might look at this rough and say, `How come it is so
low?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Roos, who ran the tournament that year, said that the
deepest portion of the rough in '55 was ``forget it'' territory.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's chances of winning this Open aren't the only thing
people are talking about. His fetish for tidiness also has
attracted some attention, as tourmate Brad Faxon noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's a fetish,'' Leonard said. ``I think people
have fetishes about cheese and chocolate. It's just that I am a
pretty organized person. I don't have labels on everything. I don't
even have one of those labelmaker deals, but you know, I just like
knowing where my stuff is.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Watson figured the USGA committee wouldn't do anything to
regulate equipment advancement and turned out to be prophetic. He
does, however, have a concern with the way the game is going, as
well as thoughts on how to change the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe like Jack Nicklaus, that the ball has become too
easy to play,'' Watson said. ``Given the issue of the ball versus
the equipment, the ball should be addressed. They should come up
with a ball that's harder to play in windy conditions. The
aerodynamics of today's ball just aren't enough to keep the game
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While twentysomethings like Leonard and Woods captivate the golf
scene, there's still plenty to be said for the older players. Fred
Couples and Watson were both playing well entering this year's
Open, and of course, Mark O'Meara, at 41, is the current Masters
champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a good mix once again,'' O'Meara said.
``I've said this before, but the golf ball is just sitting out
there on the ground. It doesn't know how old you are. It doesn't
know if you're 20, 30, 50, 60 or 70. It just sits there waiting to
be struck. That's what makes this game so special.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
