<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-18 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For more than 20 years, Karen B. Cohen, a New Yorker
and a longtime supporter of the Metropolitan Museum of Art, has
been collecting works by Eugene Delacroix.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, 40 of her Delacroix paintings were shown for
the first time in New York when the Met mounted an exhibition
devoted to North American collections of Delacroix, the French
Romantic painter and draftsman. Now Ms. Cohen has promised 21 of
these works to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gift not only marks the 200th anniversary of the artist's
birth, it also doubles the size of our Delacroix holdings,'' said
Philippe de Montebello, the Met's director.
</P>
<P>
   The Met was the first American museum to collect Delacroix
consistently, beginning in 1903 with its purchase of ``The
Abduction of Rebecca'' (1846). Ms. Cohen's gift makes the museum's
Delacroix holdings the largest of any institution outside France.
</P>
<P>
   The works, which date from the 1820s to the 1850s, include early
studies after Raphael; exotic scenes from Morocco; renderings of
wild animals Delacroix observed at zoos in Paris, and narrative
scenes. A watercolor, ``The Sea at Dieppe,'' is one of his few pure
landscapes and is on view until July 20 at the Grand Palais in
Paris in its exhibition, ``Delacroix, the Late Years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a well-rounded and deep collection,'' said George
Goldner, the Met's curator of drawings and prints, who added that
from Sept. 15 to Nov. 30, selections from the gift will be on view
at the museum's Robert Wood Johnson Jr. Gallery. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to increase attendance at its Pierre Bonnard
retrospective, which opens on Sunday and runs through Oct. 13, the
Museum of Modern Art is offering a variety of promotions.
</P>
<P>
   First is the ``Bonnard Bonanza,'' which for $67.75 includes
admission to the museum and the Bonnard show; a three-course lunch
with a French menu at Sette Moma, the museum's restaurant; a
softcover exhibition catalog; an audio tour of the show, and a 10
percent discount at any of the museum stores.
</P>
<P>
   The package is available without the lunch for $41.75. There is
also ``Bonnard and Broadway,'' a $116.50 package that includes
admission to the museum and the Bonnard show, a ticket to a
Saturday matinee of ``Ragtime'' and a three-course lunch at Sette
Moma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine and Bonnard,'' at $25.75, provides admission to the
museum and the Bonnard show, an audio tour of the exhibition and a
French wine tasting at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of 10 or more can sign up for a tour of Lincoln Center's
theaters as part of ``Music and Bonnard,'' which costs $27 and
includes admission to the museum and exhibition, dessert and coffee
at Cafe Vienna at Lincoln Center and a 15 percent discount on a
future performance at the Lincoln Center Festival or the Mostly
Mozart concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Advance tickets are not necessary for the Bonnard show, but
admission is $12.50, $3 more than its general admission; that
includes entrance to the entire museum.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, museums have offered hotel packages and
discounts on airplane and train fares to encourage visitors to see
special exhibitions. Two years ago, the Philadelphia Museum of Art
used this strategy to lure visitors to its blockbuster Cezanne
exhibition. That same season, the Museum of Modern Art offered a
discount package to a Manhattan hotel during its hugely popular
``Picasso and Portraiture'' show. The success of that promotion
inspired the museum's efforts for the Bonnard show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one-stop shopping,'' said Elizabeth Addison, the museum's
deputy director for marketing and communications. ``It's a way of
reaching a broader audience. For instance, someone who's interested
in seeing a Broadway show but who wouldn't have necessarily gone to
see Bonnard could be introduced to the museum by getting our
`Broadway and Bonnard' package.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum has also set up three kiosks that resemble
touch-screen cash machines at the entrance to the Bonnard show.
Instead of spewing out money, the machines will offer detailed
information about Bonnard's work and life as well as analyses of
his paintings and working methods.
</P>
<P>
   The same information and more will be available on the museum's
new Web site (www.moma.org/exhibitions/bonnard).
</P>
<P>
   The audio guides and Bonnard brochures are different for this
show, museum officials said. Rather than providing the usual
sequential walk-through, John Elderfield, the Modern's chief
curator who was the curator for the show, selected one painting in
each room to highlight. The brochure also addresses only selected
paintings rather than providing a general overview.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to slow people down,'' Elderfield said, ``because the
longer you look at these paintings, the more you see.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the J. Paul Getty Museum opened its $1 billion
campus in the Brentwood section of Los Angeles, it has lost two of
its most important curators.
</P>
<P>
   This week the Getty announced that David A. Jaffe, its paintings
curator, would leave at the end of the summer to become senior
curator at the National Gallery of Art in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an offer I simply couldn't refuse,'' said Jaffe, who was
at the Getty for four years. ``The National Gallery has a dream
collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Turner, the Getty's drawings curator, who is on leave,
has also resigned, effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe's job has been considered enviable because he has had a
giant acquisitions budget. But now that the new building is open
and the walls filled, there is speculation that his successor will
not be able to buy as aggressively. Jaffe said that was not so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
