<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ICONS OF MODERNISM TO BE AUCTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whether it's fashion or nostalgia for a more innocent
past, Americans are falling in love with the 1950s. When the
William Doyle Galleries in Manhattan sponsored four lectures on
Modernism and the decorative arts in January, nearly 250 people
attended each presentation, and hundreds were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No lecture series here ever generated this much interest,''
said Eric Silver, an expert in the decorative arts at Doyle. ``They
opened up the gallery to a whole new group of people. We're getting
a new audience here.''
</P>
<P>
   William Doyle is holding its first auction of 20th-century art
and design on Wednesday, at 175 East 87th St. The viewing begins
Saturday at 10 a.m., and the sale includes both fine and decorative
arts. There are, for example, drawings by Elie Nadelman, gouaches
by Ossip Zadkine and Sonia Delaunay, paintings by Tom Wesselman and
Larry Rivers, and sculptures by Lynn Chadwick and George Rickey.
</P>
<P>
   Architects, interior designers and collectors, however, are
focusing on the postwar furniture in the sale. There are modern
classics like the aluminum armchairs that Warren McArthur designed
about 1950 for Mayfair Industries (a set of six is estimated to
sell for $1,200 to $1,500); both a Swan chair ($600 to $900) and an
Egg chair ($300 to 500) by Arne Jacobsen of Denmark, designed for
the Fritz Hansen Co.; an oversized armchair and round matching
ottoman done by the American industrial designer Warren Platner for
Knoll International in 1966 ($900 to $1,000), and a pair of painted
metal and wooden daybeds by George Nelson, with a Jack Lenor Larsen
cover ($800 to $1,200 for the pair).
</P>
<P>
   The design revelations are many. An unknown, Jens Risom of
Sweden, created an amusing doughnut-shaped occasional table with a
horseshoe-shaped, wrought-iron base. (Estimate for three: $400 to
$600.) There is also an anonymous stainless-steel chandelier with
33 candle arms arranged in a spiral ($400 to $600), as well as a
pair of brown leather and gilt-brass floor lamps with gooseneck
arms ($1,200 to $1,800).
</P>
<P>
   Several of the lots were consigned by a Long Island woman who in
the 1950s had commissioned a completely modern interior for her
house. Today, she seems like a design pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of guts to buy this furniture then, especially
when all your friends were decorating in a traditional style,''
Silver said. ``Most people wouldn't go near it then. They bought
Georgian furniture and French pieces. Now it's all considered
classic design. You can see pieces just like these in museums.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the lots in the Doyle sale are similar to the design
icons featured in a 1983 exhibition at the Philadelphia Museum of
Art called ``Design Since 1945.'' Many are also on view in the
design galleries of the Museum of Modern Art. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in Monaco, Christie's is selling the contents of a
house in Roquebrune, France, that was owned by the American
photographer Henry Clarke until his death in 1996. Clarke
bequeathed his belongings to the Pasteur Institute in Paris, which
consigned them to Christie's for one of the auction house's
high-profile, twice-yearly sales in Monte Carlo. (The Pasteur
Institute was also the beneficiary of the recent Duke and Duchess
of Windsor sale.)
</P>
<P>
   Clarke was the quintessential American in Paris: a handsome
blue-eyed blond with the wit and charm of his Irish heritage and a
very strong American accent in his French. He moved to Paris in
1949, and by 1950 Alexander Liberman, the editorial director of
Conde Nast, had put him under an exclusive contract to shoot
fashion for French, British and American Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   He photographed celebrities like Sophia Loren and all the top
models of the day: Suzy Parker, Bettina, Douvima, Fiona Campbell
and Veruschka.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Michael Gunther, an American professor of photographic
theory and history at the Institut d'Etudes de Sciences Politiques
in Paris, said Clarke donated his archive of negatives and signed
prints to the Musee de la Mode de la Ville de Paris. Christie's is
selling only Clarke's paintings, furniture and objets d'art.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke was born in 1918 in Los Angeles and as a young man moved
to San Francisco and took a job as a window dresser at I. Magnin.
``Even then he was aware of objects and how to arrange things
beautifully,'' said Gunther, a longtime friend who is executor of
the estate.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, Clarke moved to New York and got a job as a
prop man in Vogue's studios. Someone lent him a camera, and he
began to take black-and-white photographs. He watched Cecil Beaton
at work and took courses at the New School for Social Research with
Alexey Brodovitch, a famous Russian art director who worked at
several fashion and art magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke moved to Paris right after World War II. Gunther said
that Clarke soon became a great photo technician and began to
develop his signature style: showing aloof beauties in couture
gowns in formal surroundings, either in a studio, an apartment or
on a Paris street.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bowman, a photographer who worked for Vogue years later,
said, ``Henry Clarke is all about elegance, and he was `it' until
elegance went out of favor and Liberman declared that `the elegance
of the past is not relevant today.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gunther, who has organized several shows of Clarke's work over
the years, has a different take on the Clarke style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Clarke made images with a vigor that gave them
equilibrium and force,'' he said. ``He maintained an ideal distance
from his subjects. His pictures had the architecture of the mise en
scene. He would spend hours, if not days, choosing accessories for
his models. There was a sophistication of treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite models, Bettina Graziana, said: ``He was
very careful about decor, because it was the background for
dresses. He bought the flowers. He borrowed the antiques to make a
set. It was like theater. He had a lot of imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monte Carlo sale reflects these same qualities. There are
fine 18th-century French antiques mixed with charming prints he
picked up in India, and seashells from all over the world. He would
put an Old Master next to a Leon Bakst study for a Nijinsky costume
for the ballet ``Peri'' (estimate: $260 to $330). There's a
19th-century micromosaic from Italy and a Georges Jacob armchair
upholstered in green leather from about 1765.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the things are truly precious: an 18th-century
serpentine covered vase (estimate: $12,000 to $17,000), an Italian
porphyry-and-marble bust of an Italian emperor ($11,000 to $15,000)
and a rare 17th-century terrestrial globe by Hondius Jodocus I
($51,000 to $67,000).
</P>
<P>
   But the objects themselves are not the story here. As in his
pictures, Clarke had the knack for putting it all together in a
charming way in his 16th-century priory on a hillside overlooking
the Mediterranean. He defined elegance and style for a generation,
and evidently lived the same way at home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
