r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANDANGLE-TEX     06-18 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANDANGLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU LIVE IN ALBANY, TEXAS, CHANCES ARE YOU'RE A VETERAN OF THE
STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Texas _ It takes almost 20 years in this West Texas town
to progress from a prairie dog to a dance-hall girl. It takes about
the same to sprout from a simple tree to a full-fledged cowboy,
whippin' and spurrin' across a grassy, 1-acre stage.
</P>
<P>
   They are all parts in Albany's annual Fort Griffin Fandangle, a
communitywide theatrical event that chronicles the early
development of the area and its people.
</P>
<P>
   It takes place Thursday through Saturday nights on the last two
weekends of June. This is the 60th anniversary of the massive
prairie show, which began in 1938 at the high school football field
and has developed its own 1,600-seat outdoor theater north of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 411 people involved,'' said Betsy Parsons, the show's
director for the past five years. ``We have 44 high school dancers.
I have six babies under a year old; we have 50 kids under 6. There
are 96 kids between first grade and eighth.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is a pecking order for parts, Parsons explained.
The young girls who think they have outgrown portraying fuzzy
animals or prairie flowers know they cannot ascend to the saloon
scenes until they've graduated from high school. The boys who want
to ride know they have stiff competition from the local cowboys who
earn their livelihood in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long, dutiful wait for some, but Parsons said there are
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children aren't afraid to perform in front of people,''
she said. ``Our kids gain so much confidence from this experience.
They know how to speak to people. They know how to conduct
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result,'' she added. ``There are not many shy adults in
Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are not many people who haven't been a part of
Fandangle, which is a big part of life here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets kind of tough sometimes,'' said Tunny Hollingsworth, a
71-year-old retired cowboy whose first Fandangle was 1953. ``You
work all day on the ranch, then go to practice at night until
midnight or 1 a.m. Then it's back to the ranch, where you're up at
4 in the morning again.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice for Fandangle begins in February. It is once a week
until May, then every night until its over.
</P>
<P>
   Hollingsworth can't remember how many years he's been in the
show. Not all of them, he said, maybe 25 or 30. Maybe more. ``You'd
have to ask my daughter,'' he said. ``She'd know. She's been in
30.''
</P>
<P>
   In most rural ranching communities, cowboys and oil-patch
roughnecks would be reluctant to perform on stage, some in costumes
and makeup. But in this community 125 miles west of Fort Worth,
Hollingsworth said, it is expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen Fandangle one year before I was in it,'' he
recalled. ``I knew it was made up by the townspeople, and all the
cowboys around were in it. There are probably 40 or 50 working
cowboys who do this every year. You get used to it, and if you
don't go one year, you miss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Fandangle serves as a melting pot for the community, he
and several others said. Doctors and lawyers work alongside cowboys
and oilfield drillers and welders.
</P>
<P>
   Hollingsworth said he thought about leaving the production this
year and handing the reins of his wagon over to someone else.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my daughter that I didn't want to be in it again, and
she said they'd kill me if I didn't show up,'' he said with a
laugh. ``I figured I'm too young to die, so I'm doing it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the longhorn cattle used in the production keep coming
back. The 18 head used in the Fandangle come from Fort Griffin
State Park and are part of the ``Official Texas Herd.'' One has
been in the show for 14 years, several others for 10 to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done it so many times they know their cues,'' swears
Bob Echols, who was in the first Fandangle as a baby 60 years ago.
``Near the beginning of the show, there is a song called the
`Cowboy's Prayer.' In the last verse they sing, `When it comes my
time to go ...' and the longhorns know that's their cue to turn and
leave.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
