<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-D'AMATO-HORMEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO ASKS LOTT TO ALLOW SENATE VOTE ON HORMEL NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sharply worded letter to Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato said Thursday that he is
``embarrassed'' that Republican senators have held up the
nomination of gay rights advocate James C. Hormel to be ambassador
to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear that Mr. Hormel's nomination is being obstructed for
one reason, and one reason only: the fact that he is gay,'' D'Amato
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more, on a personal level, I am embarrassed that our
Republican Party, the Party of Lincoln, is seen to be the force
behind this injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   The nomination has been blocked from a floor vote by Sens. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., Robert C. Smith,
R-N.H., and one anonymous senator. The four senators have used the
ancient Senate tactic of placing ``holds'' on the nomination,
effectively keeping it off the floor. Only the four senators or
Lott can remove the holds.
</P>
<P>
   The four conservative Republicans argue that Hormel, 64, a San
Francisco philanthropist, Democratic Party donor and homosexual
rights activist, would try to promote a ``gay agenda'' in
Luxembourg, a predominantly Catholic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has declined to overrule their objections and allow a floor
vote, saying it would take too much time. Neither he nor his press
secretary, Susan Irby, had any immediate reaction to D'Amato's
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Lott set off a debate on homosexuality earlier this week when,
in a cable TV interview on ``The Armstrong Williams Show,'' he said
homosexuality was a sin and likened it to alcoholism, sex addiction
or kleptomania.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey joined in
and said the Bible ``is very clear'' in holding that homosexuality
is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Lott, D'Amato said Hormel's ``academic,
business and community service credentials are outstanding and are
easily equal to or greater than those of most ambassadorial
nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, a Republican from New York, said Hormel ``clearly
understands that his own personal philosophies... are not to
influence his ambassadorial duties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this day and age, when people ably serve our country in so
many capacities without regard to sexual orientation, for the
United States Senate to deny an appointment on that basis is simply
wrong,'' D'Amato declared.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, the
nation's largest gay and lesbian organization, which Hormel
founded, said D'Amato's letter shows ``that momentum is building''
in favor of Hormel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong indication that there is strong movement within
the Republican caucus to move this nomination to the floor,'' Smith
said. ``It underscores the bipartisan support and means the battle
is shifting to the Republican caucus. We're cautiously
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne, Feinstein, D-Calif., says she has rounded up at
least 60 senators who support a Senate vote on Hormel's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., made it clear Thursday that he's not
one of them. He voted against Hormel's nomination in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and said he would vote against him
again if the nomination reaches the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   A person's sexual conduct ``is within what could be considered
and what is eligible for consideration'' for ambassadorial
nominees, Ashcroft told reporters. The Senate has a responsibility
to weigh such issues in determining whether a U.S. ambassadorial
nominee is ``the kind of representative (the American people) want
to have for the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has been a leader in promoting a lifestyle which,
at the level of his promotion of that lifestyle and the kind of
leadership he's exhibited there, is likely to be offensive to both
Americans and individuals in the setting to which he will be
assigned.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions, Ashcroft said he agrees that
homosexuality is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, my tradition, the Bible defines what's a sin. The
Bible defines homosexuality and homosexual behavior as a sin. And
it basically says sex is a gift of God that ought to be preserved
for people who are married.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
