<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-18 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   The Future of Theater
</P>
<P>
   The news this week that after 33 years, Isabelle Stevenson would
hand over day-to-day operations of the American Theater Wing to a
new president, Roy Somlyo, marking a transition for the industry
group, provided another opportunity to ponder the ageless question:
What is Broadway becoming?
</P>
<P>
   A couple of other developments this week provide further grist.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Lane, the veteran producer and owner of the Palace
Theater, sent out letters this week to other Broadway producers
asking them to join the Producers' Network, a new organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to convene some casual brainstorming sessions to
go over the ever-changing face of the theater,'' he said.
``Independent producers, in particular, really need a venue to keep
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he will convene champagne brunches in his Manhattan
home every two months, beginning in October, to discuss issues of
importance with other independent and corporate producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no dues,'' he said. ``It's just come on over,
the bar is open. I just feel that the theater is at a real
watershed and the role of the producers, especially the independent
producers, needs to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, David Merrick announced a reorganization of his
philanthropic foundation, which from now on will focus on
developing American musicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that the future success of developing American
musicals on a broad scale, not only in New York but around the
country, is in the subsidized, not-for-profit arena, unencumbered
by commercial concerns,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ships Passing in the Night
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing more frustrating for a producer than having
your star not win a Tony Award, it's having your star win a Tony
and then leave the show.
</P>
<P>
   But the Roundabout Theater Company has come up with a solution
for the departure of Natasha Richardson on Aug. 4 from its revival
of ``Cabaret,'' which won the Tony as best musical revival and also
awards for Ms. Richardson and her co-stars Alan Cumming and Ron
Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Aug. 4, Jennifer Jason Leigh will take over the
role of Sally Bowles, the desperately seedy nightclub singer who
provides a window into life in Weimar Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Louise Wilson, who plays a well-meaning landlady in the
musical, is also leaving in late July, and auditions will be held
next week to replace her.
</P>
<P>
   Summer of Betrayal
</P>
<P>
   Uta Hagen will be interrupting her summer in Montauk, N.Y., to
comeback into the city next month and star in a new production of
``Collected Stories'' by Donald Margulies, at the Lucille Lortel
Theater. The play had been performed last year at the Manhattan
Theater Club, with Maria Tucci in the role of a teacher and writer
who is befriended and betrayed by a protege.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old lady and it's hard to find interesting, challenging
material for an older person,'' said Ms. Hagen, who made her
professional debut in 1937, playing Ophelia. ``When I read it, I
flipped over it. It's a very provocative play in terms of ideas.
It's a play about betrayal, which we've all experienced.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside a Kamikaze
</P>
<P>
   Masayuki Imai has performed his play ``The Winds of God'' four
times in America and is now mounting its first commercial run at
the Judith Anderson Theater, with performances beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The play is about two Japanese men, flung back in time, who
slowly come to realize that they are kamikaze pilots in the closing
days of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was young, I liked the kamikaze because they were so
strong; like supermen or samurai, they do not fear dying,'' the
actor and playwright said. ``But when I read more books and did
interviews, I noticed that they were not really supermen, just
human beings, and that they were afraid of dying, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a Break
</P>
<P>
   Brian Murray is on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   There is no other word for it. He is playing Sir Toby in
Nicholas Hytner's production of ``Twelfth Night'' at Lincoln
Center, the 10th show in which Murray has appeared in New York
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it incredible and wonderful that it's happening,''
Murray said. ``It's like being in a rep company, going from one
play to the other, which is how I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The longest gap he had between plays in this period was about
six weeks, he said, but often he went from one directly to the
next. That's what he did this time, finishing work on ``Long Day's
Journey Into Night'' for the Irish Repertory Theater one night and
beginning rehearsals the next day on ``Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   One of these days, he said, he's going to have to get organized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some time to get my life in order, to clean up my glove
drawer, if you know what I mean,'' Murray said. ``When going from
one play to another, the pressure is fairly steady. You don't get a
chance to organize your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Treat Williams will play Manuel, the Portuguese fisherman at
the center of ``Captains Courageous,'' a new musical based on the
Rudyard Kipling story, at the Manhattan Theater Club in the late
fall or early winter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Primary Stages has announced its new season, which will
include Leslie Uggams in ``The Old Settler,'' a play by John Henry
Redwood, and ``This Lime Tree Bower,'' a play by Conor McPherson,
the young Irish playwright whose ``St. Nicholas'' was a hit at
Primary Stages last season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Capitol Steps, the Washington-based satiric troupe, will bring
their new show, ``Unzippin' My Doo Dah and Other National
Priorities,'' to the John Houseman Theater beginning on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cathy Rigby is returning to Broadway with a revamped
production of ``Peter Pan,'' for a limited engagement beginning
Nov. 20. She has played the role in holiday productions twice
before. ``But this time, we redid the whole production from the
ground up,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
