<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-ATTIRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO WEAR TO TEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You may think you'll be as natty as all get-out
if you show up at the Olympic Club in your old yellow turtleneck
and those burgundy-and-butterscotch plaid pants.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Think layers, says Orel Hershiser. Think earth tones. Think
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   You can find Hershiser, the veteran San Francisco Giants
pitcher, on Page 45 of the 1998 AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach program, flicking
his way out of a sand trap dressed in a signature dark knit shirt,
the collar tipped with brown, his left hand wrapped in a white
glove, a black Titleist cap on his head. Hershiser has not only
played Pebble Beach, rubbing cap brims with the best of them, but
has flailed at the game across four decades, watching golf fashion
go through half a hundred changes.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who first started playing golf when he was five years
old, claims the joke garb of years past _ the pastel-plaid look,
those closets full of golf clothes in the colors of candied
sprinkles _ is gone, making way for a more common-sense approach to
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Layers,'' says Hershiser. ``You definitely need layers at the
Open, because of the way the weather could change. And an umbrella
... in case of rain, and to lean on walking up those hills at the
Olympic (Club).
</P>
<P>
   ``The colors ought to go with the scenery _ the ocean, the
trees, the greens,'' he says. ``Some muted greens and blues.
Nothing exotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gallery is as much a part of the course as the scenery, as
much as the manicured greens and the trees,'' Hershiser says. ``The
gallery has an obligation, I think, to present itself well, to
dress well. That's kind of old-fashioned, I guess, but that's the
way I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser acknowledged he would ``dress differently for the AT&AMP;T
than if I had an invitation to golf with someone at a private club.
When you're in a celebrity golf tournament, people want to see you
in nice clothes _ color-coordinated, classy clothes. But a private
club _ people use it as an oasis, to get away from things _ so I'd
dress more casually. A comfortable pair of slacks, a nice brown
sweater.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser likened the difference to wearing a uniform at a
private school and wearing the more casual uniform of a public
school. Golf does have a uniform, he says _ ``Whenever you have
people with the same beliefs, the same interests ... whether you're
talking about nightlife people wearing a lot of black or ladies at
a luncheon with a certain length of skirt, there's going to be a
uniform of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   For golf, in the '70s and early '80s, that uniform consisted of
liberal splashes of lime green and lemon yellow, sky blue and
mandarin orange, framed by white belts and white golf shoes.
Hershiser shudders at the memory. ``Unreal,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of pastels, but not those neon colors, thank
goodness.'' He laughed, adding, ``If I'd known back then what I
know now, I would've stayed away from the pastels, too.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hershiser, the best change in golf fashion has come ``in the
quality of the clothes. Early on it was tacky slacks, paired with a
Polo or Izod. Now people are wearing clothes that are both classy
and comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain slicks they've got now? There's extra material in the
shoulder to give you room to swing, and the material itself ...
awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Top-notch clothes, once available only to those who could speak
golfese, are now available to everyone, Hershiser says. Which is
not to say everyone takes advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a lot of Cosby sweaters out there, knit in
colors that belong on the inside of a cow's stomach. There are
still shirts cut from circus tents, still a lot of retro-bumble
looks on the green. Just last year Jack Lemmon strolled Pebble
Beach in brown plaid pants and a thin white turtleneck, leading a
black poodle on a leash. And some of the dignity golfers have
gained from ditching the dextral shirts and plus-fours of past
years has been lost in the mawkish flood of corporate-logo,
one-size-fits-all ballcaps.
</P>
<P>
   Turn to the Pro-Am program again and there's Jesper Parvenik,
the bill of his big, white SAP cap turned up, looking for all the
world like a self-obsessed kulak. There's the double-swoosh team of
Tiger Woods and Fluff Cowan. There's the odd bodkins of the beret
craze, which may have run its course, and the smarminess of
galleries dressed to wash the dog.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the history of clothes on the links. More than any
other sport, golf has to live down its past years of truly
laughable fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All fashion went ugly-up in the '70s _ Nehru jackets and
hip-slop bell bottoms, leisure suits and platform shoes, wide,
white belts and polyester collars stitched with brown yarn, all
vying for the championship of the ``Love Ya, Baby'' look. And no
sport embraced the pure grotesque of it the way golf did.
</P>
<P>
   Men making hundreds of thousands of dollars a year routinely
walked out on the course wearing something pulled from the Kabuki
rack at Kmart, maundering around in colors cut from an over-ripe
grapefruit, preening in front of each other like tropical fish.
</P>
<P>
   Without golf, the turtleneck sweater would've died the death it
deserved long ago. Golf, by itself, has kept white belts and white
shoes alive. And the only place you can still see yellow pants off
the golf course is along the strip in Vegas, worn by men who have
long since lost touch with the word ``Goofy.''
</P>
<P>
   In no other sport has plaid become a way of life _ a statement
of cherry-red and charcoal fashion made between the waist and
ankles, a scream for help unheeded by everyone around. In no other
sport have the colors of Popsicle been embraced as they have in
golf. And no other sport has made the wearing of funny hats such a
serious business.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a bit much, says Hershiser. He'd just as soon stick
with ``some good black slacks, black golf shoes, a shirt in neutral
colors,'' he says. ``Nothing too crazy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
