<HEADER>
A5760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE21-COX     06-18 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A veritable font of first, last lines
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 21: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Jayson's wife thinks he's bugging me.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jayson: Lay off. Ron's a good man. Anybody who'll do half
my work is all right by me.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Jayson is among the readers who responded to a recent column
about memorable first lines and last lines in literature. Some
called, others wrote; most sent e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   None sent more than Jayson. From Dr. Seuss (``One fish two fish
red fish blue fish'') to the Argentine writer Ernesto Sabato (``It
should be sufficient to say that I am Juan Pablo Castel, the
painter who killed Marla Iribarne''), Jayson is not just widely
read. He's generous with what he knows.
</P>
<P>
   Gentle, too. Others would have gone in for the kill when I
confessed that I couldn't immediately identify the author of ``One
fish two fish red fish blue fish ...''), even if it did sound as
familiar as star-belly sneetches.
</P>
<P>
   Not Jayson. He just reminded me that it was Dr. Seuss _ as if
I'd known all along.
</P>
<P>
   Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Called up from memory
</P>
<P>
   Jayson also passed on a number of other opening lines that were
on the top of his head but not mine. Two of them:
</P>
<P>
   ``Take care to chop the onions fine.'' From ``Like Water for
Chocolate'' by Laura Esquivel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virginians clattered into Philadelphia with the glitter,
almost, of Magi.'' From Garry Wills' ``Inventing America.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of Jayson's I recognized, and it's the reason we
remember certain strings of words, whether at the beginning or the
end of a book. Read once, they are not forgotten, any more than a
song called up from memory on the sound of the first note:
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother died at the moment I was born and so for my whole
life there was nothing standing between myself and eternity; at my
back was always a bleak, black wind.'' From ``The Autobiography of
My Mother'' by Jamaica Kincaid.
</P>
<P>
   The column to which Jayson and others responded arose from a
casual reading of David A. Spector's ``Call Me Ishmael: 801
Memorable First and Last Lines in Literature,'' a nightstand
paperback that begins with Henry Adams and ends with Emile Zola. In
between were 799 lines that had a particular magic. All were of one
sentence, which disqualified the eminently qualified Rahim
Ghassemian, the editor of Pardis, a newspaper published in Farsi
and read by Atlanta's large Iranian community.
</P>
<P>
   Ghassemian, who has translated Shakespeare and Raymond Chandler
into Farsi, first nominated opening passages from Honore de
Balzac's ``Pere Goriot,'' then J.D. Salinger's ``Catcher in the
Rye,'' and then this from Chandler's ``The Long Goodbye'':
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I laid eyes on Terry Lennox he was drunk in a
Rolls-Royce Silver Wraith outside the terrace of The Dancers. The
parking lot attendant had brought the car out and he was still
holding the door open because Terry Lennox's left foot was still
dangling outside, as if he had forgotten he had one. ...''
</P>
<P>
   It's vintage Chandler: a voice distinctively his own, the words
transparencies for describing a certain high-class sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   After the details of the story have faded, it's the voice and
the words that remain. David Moore offered this last sentence from
Edward Abbey's ``Black Sun'': ``The guy we counted on, well, he
moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Abbey could have written it, but all of us know that guy.
</P>
<P>
   More than `regional' renown
</P>
<P>
   Sara Tucker mentioned a writer with a very different voice.
Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings, once one of the most popular of American
novelists, has been undeservedly overlooked if not forgotten. She
is often called ``a Florida writer,'' whatever that might be, but
her real terrain was larger. Her best-known novel, ``The
Yearling,'' ends:
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere beyond the sinkhole, past the magnolia, under the
live oaks, a boy and a yearling ran side by side, and were gone
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Read out of context, it borders perilously on the sentimental.
But on the last page of Rawlings' novel, it has the tone-perfect
finality of a bedroom door closed at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Words open doors as well as close them. I wasn't surprised that
many readers _ but not Ron Jayson _ mentioned the first sentence in
William Kennedy's ``Ironweed'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Riding up the winding road of Saint Agnes Cemetery in the back
of the rattling old truck, Francis Phelan became aware that the
dead, even more than the living, settled down in neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   A sentence like that _ exact in its imagery, measured in its
cadence _ could not have been written in a better way. It could not
even have been written another way. It is pure perfection as it is,
as individual as the writer who chiseled it into our memory.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
