<HEADER>
A5762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-FILES-COX     06-18 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FILES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No answers, much action follow
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' is like a weird fan dancer, a sexy-creepy
performer who obscures as much as she (he? it?) reveals. First we
see a sexy glimmer of leg, next a hairy hand holding a pistol, next
the rubbery belly of a monster fluke worm. Glimpses, never the
whole picture.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way creator Chris Carter likes it. His movie is more
of the same. It's a chimeric beast, fusing Nixon-era conspiracy
paranoia with a millennial dread of biological warfare, domestic
terrorism and little green men from outer space. Oh, and there's a
sexy lead couple to keep our eyes soothed when the plot gets too
shaggy.
</P>
<P>
   As FBI agents Mulder and Scully, David Duchovny and Gillian
Anderson take a smooth step up from television to the big screen.
The script tweaks their patented deadpan style without veering into
camp. As for those Internet rumors of romance, the movie handles
the characters' celebrated sexual tension with a scene that's the
equivalent of a knowing wink.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cheesy old ``Star Trek's'' transition to this glossier
medium, ``The X-Files'' translates smoothly. That's no surprise,
since the show's rich, dusky production values give it a visual
edge over standard TV fare.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but you're wondering what the movie is about?
</P>
<P>
   Well, as a fan of the show, the last thing I want is a bunch of
``X''-ers angry at me for giving stuff away. So forgive me if this
review remains as opaque as a typical episode.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is a variation of the show's ``mythology'' plot lines.
More complicated than ``Twin Peaks'' ever was, the mythology
presents a shadowy network of corrupt men in power (played here by
Martin Landau, John Neville and Armin Mueller-Stahl), somehow
involved with a planetary colonizing project involving alien life
forms. The movie draws on staples from past shows, including that
pesky alien ``black oil,'' virus-laced bees and that uber-villain,
the Cigarette-Smoking Man (William B. Davis).
</P>
<P>
   It also tries to give good ``boo'' value with a brutal species
of aliens. Unfortunately, these mean E.T.'s, whose icky treatment
of humans owes a debt to the ``Alien'' franchise, never turn into
the super-scary monsters the movie needs.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the problems here. ``The X-Files'' film is bigger
than the TV show, but not significantly better. It has more gore
and the occasional profanity. But it never accelerates to that
stratospheric level of action, suspense or awe that we hope for in
a summer movie. It's well-made but feels long. And it depends on
coincidences we're less likely to question on the small screen.
</P>
<P>
   You may wonder about logistics, for instance. How does Mulder
get so easily from D.C. to Antarctica when his every move is being
watched? You may also marvel at his knack for always choosing the
right direction during a chase and his luck at literally stumbling
into a secret entrance to a vast military site.
</P>
<P>
   The film may seem too familiar to series fans, too confusing to
newcomers. A colleague who doesn't watch the show followed the plot
OK. But she was bothered that Mulder and Scully acted so surprised
by the conspiracy and alien elements. Haven't they been
investigating these things for five years? While she had a fine
time watching, nothing about the movie made her eager to tune into
the series.
</P>
<P>
   Fans may get a headache from trying to match the film's
semi-explanation of things with the hints and snippets the series
has dropped. The movie does not tie up a lot of loose ends. After
all, the series is committed for another two years; creator Carter
isn't ready to knock down his own house of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, a better analogy for ``The X-Files'' would be to call
it a shell game. No matter how many times we get cheated, it makes
us want to play one more round. The film is a disappointment, but
in the same way that explains the success of the series: It leaves
us wanting more. It's a tease, always promising to show us the end
of the world, then having us make do with some running, some
gunfire, some explosions ... and a kiss that never quite happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files:
</P>
<P>
   Fight the Future''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson. Directed by Rob
Bowman. Rated PG-13 for mild language, gore and violence. At metro
theaters. 2 hours, 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Bigger but not really better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
