<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WILDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Wilde' too earnest for own good
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The importance of being Oscar _ Oscar Wilde, that is _ has
varied over the years. There's Oscar Wilde the esteemed playwright
(``The Importance of Being Earnest'') and novelist (``The Portrait
of Dorian Gray''). There's Oscar Wilde the world-renowned wit and
elegantly foppish, self-impressed man-about-London. And finally,
there's Oscar Wilde the early martyr for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   It is the third Wilde who dominates director Brian Gilbert's
``Wilde,'' a well-intentioned and well-made movie that, alas, gives
Wilde's colorful life a kind of
not-that-there's-anything-wrong-with-that whitewash. Oh, it shows
pretty boys together and gives an occasional glimpse of the full
monty, but overall the picture is so sympathetic, so compassionate
and so decorous that it verges on dull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde's'' most daring gambit is its opening scene. We're in
the wide open spaces of the Wild West. Or rather, the Wilde West.
The writer visited America in 1882, and the picture starts in
Leadville, Colo., where a mine shaft is dedicated to him while he
discreetly ogles the brawny miners.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in his life, however, Wilde (Stephen Frye) is
still very much in the closet _ even to himself. What many people
probably don't know, and what this movie manages to convey in its
Cliffs Notes way, is that he tried Victorian conformity. He marries
and has two children. But one night while his wife (Jennifer Ehle)
is upstairs in the nursery, a houseguest (Michael Sheen) introduces
Oscar to his true sexual inclination.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster strikes when Oscar falls hard for handsome, heartless
Lord Alfred Douglas (Jude Law), a petulant brat with a title and a
tyrannical father, the Marquess of Queensberry (Tom Wilkinson).
Oscar's toxic infatuation leads to his becoming a pawn in a
poisonous struggle between a nasty son and a nastier father. The
result? Victorian England's trial of the century.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, ``Wilde'' is a safe gloss on a life that was
anything but. However, at its center is a gem of a performance.
Frye, best known to American audiences as Peter in``Peter's
Friends,'' gives a sweet, regretful portrayal that has all the
nuance and intelligence his movie lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde'' is dutiful and well-behaved. Wilde was neither. It
makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilde''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stephen Frye and Jude Law. Directed by Brian Gilbert.
Rated R for nudity and sex. At Phipps. 1 hour, 56 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A dutiful, well-behaved movie about a man who was
anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
