A5768 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-WOLFE-COX     06-18 0552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WOLFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First installment of new Wolfe novel appearing in Rolling Stone
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Wolfe's big novel on big men and big money in Atlanta will
not be published until Nov. 12, but readers can get a preview of
``A Man in Full'' in the July 9 issue of Rolling Stone, which hits
some newsstands today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Man in Full'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $27.50), Wolfe's
first major work since ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' 11 years
ago, traces the convergence of the lives of three men: Charlie
Croker, an Atlanta real estate developer and conglomerate magnate;
Roger White, a black lawyer in a white-glove Atlanta firm; and
Conrad Hensley, the 23-year-old son of hippie parents.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect any mention of Atlanta or any of the Georgia
characters in this excerpt, however. They won't appear until
October, when the next two chapters are published in Rolling Stone
and Men's Journal.
</P>
<P>
   In the first installment, titled ``The Suicidal Freezer Unit,''
we meet Conrad Hensley as he reports to work as an ``ice weevil''
at a San Francisco frozen food warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad, a young father with two children, is working the
$14-an-hour job in hopes of buying a condo. But he soon learns his
future at Croker Global Foods Warehouse is as precarious as the
footing on the ice-patched floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conrad burrowed on, a weevil with the best of them, into the
Salisbury steaks, fish, burgers, gravy stock, ice cream, orange
juice, cut fava beans, margarine, pepperoni pizza, chipped beef,
bacon and waffles, and the ruckus rose, and the cries rang out _
Crash 'n' burn! _ and the produce crashed, and the pickers yahooed,
and Dom's big voice bellowed over the speakers: ``Cleanup! Cleanup!
Kilo 9! Kilo 9! Come on, Ferdi! You, too, Birdie! On the double!' _
and the light-night frenzy ran through the chamber like a rogue
hormone.''
</P>
<P>
   While Conrad struggles to keep his job, a continent away the
owner of Croker Global Foods Warehouse is enmeshed in his own
personal and financial problems. Croker, a middle-aged former
football hero, has a 28,000-acre South Georgia plantation, a young
and demanding ``trophy wife,'' a half-empty office tower in Atlanta
and a huge amount of debt.
</P>
<P>
   As Croker's financial woes intensify, Atlanta is thrust into a
racial crisis when Fareek Fanon, a young man who scratched his way
out of the slums to become a star college football player, is
accused of raping an Atlanta blue blood's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   And that's all the tight-lipped publisher has revealed so far.
According to Rolling Stone, the novel is still a work in progress.
``I don't have much more to go,'' says Wolfe, 67. Meanwhile,
Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux has planned a 1.2 million-copy first
printing and a major media blitz this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Having his books serialized in Rolling Stone has become a
regular event for Wolfe. His nonfiction best seller ``The Right
Stuff'' began as a four-part feature commissioned by the magazine
in 1973. ``The Bonfire of the Vanities'' was serialized in 27
installments in 1984 and 1985. And in 1996, Wolfe's novella
``Ambush at Fort Bragg,'' which was released only on audiotape, was
published in two parts in the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
