<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR? THINK RED  
 UNDERACHIEVER NO MORE  
 BITING THE HAND ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Don't bother writing a political movie! At least for
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has never been too welcoming of films about politics,
but the recent box-office disappointments, ``Primary Colors,''
directed by Mike Nichols and starring John Travolta, and
``Bulworth,'' directed by and starring Warren Beatty, have made
similar projects even more dicey.
</P>
<P>
   Both films were critically acclaimed. ``Bulworth,'' a farce
about a California Senate candidate (Beatty) in the grip of a
nervous breakdown, who speaks bluntly about race, class, power of
money and just about everything else, was, by all accounts, one of
the more provocative films of the star's 30-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Primary Colors,'' based on the novel by Joe Klein about a
Southern governor who resembles Bill Clinton, earned some of the
strongest reviews of the year and was termed one of Nichols' best.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the two movies generated an extraordinary number of
magazine covers, television interviews and newspaper stories.
Beatty, who was also co-writer and co-producer of the film,
appeared on everything from the Sunday morning talk shows to Howard
Stern.
</P>
<P>
   But neither film stirred enthusiasm at the box office.
``Bulworth,'' made by Fox Filmed Entertainment, grossed about $24
million, while Universal's ``Primary Colors,'' which cost about $64
million, has grossed less than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Studio executives say they are proud of the films. And they
blame the public's dislike of politics and politicians for the
lackluster box-office performance.
</P>
<P>
   As one person involved in ``Primary Colors'' said: ``The day
before the film opened, I went to the dentist, and the hygienist
said to me: `I'm so sick of politicians. I don't even care if it's
John Travolta playing a politician. I don't want to see that
movie.' And that's what hurt the movie _ this distaste for
politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Producers here say the airwaves are so glutted with politics and
scandal that making a movie about a president or senator in trouble
seems redundant. Worse, it seems unentertaining. Audiences hear
enough bad news about politicians on television; who wants to pay
for it?
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hollywood has had commercial success with some political
films, like ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington''(1939), ``State of the
Union'' (1948) and ``Advise and Consent'' (1962). There have been
some more recent hits, too, like ``All the President's Men''
(1976), about the two Washington Post reporters whose coverage led
to the fall of President Richard Nixon, and ``Dave'' (1993), about
a presidential look-alike who moves into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``Wag the Dog,'' a satire about a president who
wants to start a war to divert attention from a sex scandal, also
proved successful. The movie cost less than $20 million to make and
grossed about $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Primary Colors'' and ``Bulworth'' have been high-profile
disappointments. Asked if he would approve a political film, the
head of one studio remarked: ``It would have to be exceptional. And
for a very reasonable price.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the current embargo on political films cannot endure. For
years Hollywood studios had a similar sentiment about sports films,
believing that movies about baseball or football fell flat at the
box office. Then came the 1989 Phil Alden Robinson drama, ``Field
of Dreams,'' starring Kevin Costner. The film was a hit, and
studios happily opened the gates to sports films.
</P>
<P>
   It will take one big hit political film. Then there'll be an
avalanche.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
