<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE     06-18 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: an avalanche.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Underachiever No More
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Platt grew up mostly in Asia. A diplomat's son who spent
years in Hong Kong, Beijing and Taipei, and had attended a dozen
schools by the time he was a teen-ager, the 38-year-old actor
recalled: ``I would hang around my parents' parties, and their
friends would ask what I was going to do and the only answer I
could think of was `I'm going to be an actor.' It's what I did
best. It's what I enjoyed. Of course, I had no idea what that
entailed.'' He laughed. ``I was sort of an underachiever.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Platt is a character actor who appears to be working nonstop and
has a movie surfacing, it seems, just about every month. He played
Beatty's harried associate in ``Bulworth''; he has a villainous
role (``I'm joyfully greedy'') in the Eddie Murphy comedy ``Doctor
Doolittle,'' opening on June 26, and he portrays a sweet-natured
schoolteacher in ``Simon Birch,'' an adaptation of John Irving's
novel, ``A Prayer for Owen Meany,'' which opens in September.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, he will appear as an out-of-work actor in the
1930s in the comedy ``The Imposters,'' directed by Stanley Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky,'' Platt said, in a bit of an understatement.
``There's been a nice, steady trickle of work. It sometimes surges.
Now it's surging.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt, who lives in New York's Greenwich Village with his wife,
Camilla Campbell, and their two small children, said his
peripatetic early life was both a blessing and a curse. His father,
Nicholas Platt, now president of the Asia Society, was a diplomat
who served abroad for years and was ambassador to Pakistan and the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a kind of global perspective, but the price you pay is
a certain rootlessness,'' said Platt, speaking from Toronto, where
he is making ``Three to Tango,'' a comedy. ``In an odd way, acting
was a funny way to plug into some kind of weird stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt recalled that as a 3-year-old in Taipei, he once imitated
a water buffalo at a backyard barbecue _ and was hooked on acting.
``I knew I was destined for the stage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Platt said his parents were entirely supportive of his acting
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had the wisdom to let me do what I wanted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He attended Tufts University, and lived in Boston for several
years to work in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends were all moving to New York, beckoning me to come,
but I was terrified,'' he said. ``In hindsight it was a smart
decision to stay in Boston. I was part of the semiprofessional
theater scene there. It was such an important part of my
preparation. I never would have been able to play the parts I
played had I moved to New York immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   By late 1986, Platt had arrived in New York and, to his
surprise, began working almost immediately at Lincoln Center, the
Manhattan Theater Club and Playwrights Horizon. ``I got lucky very
quickly,'' he said. ``In one evening, in a series of one-act plays
at Playwrights Horizon, I played an Indian waiter, a deranged
Vietnam vet and a demented Elizabethan manservant. It was
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Film work followed, including ``Married to the Mob,'' ``The
Three Musketeers,'' ``Indecent Proposal,'' ``Flatliners,'' ``Funny
Bones'' and ``Dangerous Beauty.'' Perhaps his most memorable
experience was one of his first movie jobs, the 1988 film
``Crusoe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flown to the Seychelle Islands,'' Platt recalled, ``and
found myself sitting around nude beaches, eating smoked fish and
being paid more money on a daily basis than I would have been paid
for the whole run of an off-Broadway play. It was obvious my values
would be imminently corrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt said his favorite comment about acting came from Sir Alec
Guinness, who once observed that the best actors only have four or
five faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be lucky if I get two or three,'' Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   Biting the Hand ...
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton often comes to Hollywood to raise money. But
last weekend, before attending another fund-raising event here, he
stopped in Springfield, Ore., and made two speeches in which he
denounced, of all places, Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   At Thurston High School, the site of a shooting by a 15-year-old
boy on May 21 that killed four and wounded two dozen, Clinton said
Hollywood bore a heavy share of the responsibility for the recent
school shootings by producing movies, television shows and songs
that romanticize violence.
</P>
<P>
   In a radio speech the same day, he said children had become
increasingly numb to violence, and he deplored the ``mindless
killing'' that had become ``a staple of family entertainment.'' He
said that ``when children see cinematic conflicts resolved not with
words but with weapons, we shouldn't be surprised when children,
from impulse or design, follow suit.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Clinton flew to Los Angeles to attend a glittering
$800,000 fund-raising event for the Democratic National Committee
at the home of the entertainment mogul Lew Wasserman. The guests at
the $10,000-a-couple sirloin dinner included Barbra Streisand,
James Brolin, Rob Reiner, Sidney Poitier and assorted agents,
executives and stars.
</P>
<P>
   But there, Clinton was far less pointed on the issue of the
entertainment industry's responsibility for violence by children.
He mentioned his visit to Oregon and said studies showed that
random and repetitive violence in the media made ``children more
deadened, desensitized to the immediate consequences of it.'' But
then he veered to other subjects. There was no criticism of
Hollywood in its own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
