u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      06-18 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FULL GRAB BAG OF VARIED TITLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a biological weapon called Trixie gets loose in little
Evans City, the Army sends a large contingent to seal off the town
and prevent anyone from leaving. Trixie either kills people or
turns them into homicidal maniacs, which makes for a busy time for
soldiers in gas masks and for citizens, whose terror and outrage
aren't eased by the fact that the Army decides not to tell them
what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the military and civilians are fighting pitched battles,
with moms and dads appropriating M-16s to pick off the troops, who
return the favor in front of horrified offspring. Looks as though
the entire town will have to be eradicated, but that's a job for
the B-52 headed their way with just the right-size warhead to
insure the problem stays confined to Evans City.
</P>
<P>
   With little money and only the crudest special effects, George
A. Romero's 1973 film ``The Crazies'' puts on as realistic and
involving a show as anything coming out of the big-budget Hollywood
action mill.
</P>
<P>
   Together with Romero's ``Night of the Living Dead,'' ``Day of
the Dead'' and ``Season of the Witch,'' ``The Crazies'' fills out
an interesting horror package from Anchor Bay Entertainment, of
Troy, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 90s the company has put together all kinds of
properties _ public domain material, old studio films, television
classics, cult items _ into one of video's most eclectic
inventories.
</P>
<P>
   A riffle through the Anchor Bay catalog turns up, among hundreds
of titles, ``Mystic Pizza'' (1988), Tom Mix matinee serials, Lewis
John Carlino's ``Sailor Who Fell From Grace With the Sea,'' Sam
Raimi's ``Evil Dead'' and ``Evil Dead 2,'' two Monty Python titles
from Handmade Films, 4 Jerry Lewis and 11 Bob Hope movies, 5
episodes of ``Prime Suspect'' with Helen Mirren, 10 Hopalong
Cassidy titles, ``Brideshead Revisited'' and a dozen ``Saturday
Night Live'' special editions.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, new releases include horror titles from Hammer
Films, Sam Peckinpah's ``Straw Dogs'' and ``Far From the Madding
Crowd'' from PBS's Mobil Masterpiece Theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most recently we've been gearing up to put out remastered
versions of Hitchcock's `Rebecca,' `Suspicion' and `Notorious,' ''
said Jay Douglas, Anchor Bay's vice president for acquisitions.
Those videos are due in August. Next month will come David
Cronenberg's ``Shivers'' and King Vidor's ``Duel in the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Bay looks for deals with companies like Hammer and
Handmade and ABC Circle Films, which owns much of the Selznick
library. Other films are picked up after studios let their rights
lapse. ``Our goal is to elevate these old films and B movies, if
that's what you call them,'' Douglas said.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally that requires completely new editions. Next week,
for example, Anchor Bay will reissue Peckinpah's western ``Junior
Bonner,'' with Steve McQueen, in the wide-screen format rather than
the customary panned-and-scanned square. ``You can't watch that
movie panned and scanned,'' Douglas said. ``It looks like
`Gunsmoke' or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Bay also has four cassettes of ``Gunsmoke.'' Information:
(800) 745-1145. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast Cheap and Out of Control &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Errol Morris' documentary explores the human condition through
the eyes of four very different visionaries: a topiary gardener who
prunes large bushes into the figures of animals, a lion tamer, a
molecular scientist who perfects robots and an expert in the
behavior of the tiny mole rat.
</P>
<P>
   Blending conversation and inventive camera work, Morris savors
their individuality while joining them into a loose but overarching
whole. Perhaps most interesting is Morris himself, ``a
one-of-a-kind filmmaker,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York
Times, ``capable of melding science, philosophy, poetry and sheer
whimsy into an elaborate meditation on mankind's mysteries.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Columbia Tri-Star Sony. $99.36. Laser disk,
$34.95. 80 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release date:
Tuesday.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Sarajevo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tackling its subject head on, Michael Winterbottom's film jumps
into random death and commonplace horror with an oddly diluted
result. Tensions between British and American war correspondents
(Stephen Dillane and Woody Harrelson) work well in concert with the
setting, but the arrival of a relief worker (Marisa Tomei) is too
obviously dramatic and undercuts the near-documentary feel.
</P>
<P>
   Overly fancy camera work and a flippant tone also don't help a
film that ``winds up less affecting than a more poetic or
roundabout approach might be'' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Miramax Disney. $103.91. Laser disk, $39.99. 101
minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Postman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from a much better novel by David Brin, Kevin Costner's
post-apocalyptic Western lands in what's left of a blistered United
States in 2013. Drawing inspiration from the long-dismantled postal
service, a former clerk (Costner) inspires a band of stalwart
survivors and leads them against murderous renegades.
</P>
<P>
   That makes for a 1950s-style showdown but too late for a film in
which ``the accumulated bad lines and bogus sentimentality become
so cloying that the best defense against a mounting queasiness is
an awed amusement'' (Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. WarnerTime Warner. $105.77. Laser disk, $39.98.
177 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: Tuesday.(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Magoo &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A schizoid comedy is bracketed at beginning and end by animated
excerpts from the myopic cartoon figure of the 60s. In between, the
shortsighted antics of a live Magoo (Leslie Nielsen) send him in
pursuit of a ruby, which is called the Star of Kuristan and comes
with a lovely representative (Jennifer Garner) of that country.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the chase leads to Brazil and a criminal named Peru.
Actually, the film works for a bit as a thriller but is
``incomplete as cartoon, indecisive as comedy and halting as
adventure'' (Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)1997. Disney. $107.11. Laser disk, $39.99. 87 minutes.
Closed captioned. PG. Release date: Tuesday.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Other new titles of interest, some of which may have
had a theater release at one time or appeared on television.(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKMAIL and MURDER. Both films are among a half-dozen early
Alfred Hitchcock titles recently reissued by RepublicViacom(DG). In
``Blackmail'' (1929, 86 minutes), a young woman (Anny Ondra) kills
a man who tries to rape her and then gets trapped between the
investigating detective, who is her boyfriend, and a blackmailer.
</P>
<P>
   When Hitchcock completed the film, it was silent, but he was
later asked to add dialogue, making the movie his first talkie. In
``Murder'' (1930, 108 minutes), a peer of the realm (Herbert
Marshall) is the one jury member convinced of the innocence of a
young actress accused of murder. The films are $9.99 each.
</P>
<P>
   COBRA (1925, 75 minutes) and THE SHOWOFF (1926, 82 minutes),
both silents. In ``Cobra,'' a promiscuous Italian count (Rudolph
Valentino) beset with romantic problems comes to New York with the
notion of starting a quiet career in the antiques business. Right.
Soon a new set of women, from husband-hunters to extortionists, are
lined up around the block.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Showoff,'' the slapstick actor Ford Sterling has the
title role, but Louise Brooks steals the film as the fetching girl
next door. Kino (independent). $24.95 each. Information: (800)
562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   VARIETY AND VIRTUOSITY: AMERICAN BALLET THEATER NOW. Performance
highlights from a salute to the company, broadcast on PBS's Great
Performances series, include Antony Tudor's ``Leaves Are Fading''
and James Kudelka's ``Cruel World.'' Among the stars are: Susan
Jaffe, Jose Manuel Careno, Amanda McKerow, John Gardner. 1998.
Kultur (independent). $29.95. 83 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
