<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-FANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE U.S. OPEN, AUTOGRAPHS ARE A SIGN OF THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Many players in the U.S. Open are familiar with
the crowds that turn out for such events and the resulting demands
for their signatures. But someone forgot to tell one caddie just
what such an event can mean in terms of security measures.
</P>
<P>
   The man made the mistake of seeking an autograph from Tiger
Woods while Woods stood on the putting green. Within seconds, a
handful of security guards descended upon the caddie as if he had
been wielding a switchblade instead of a pen.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear if he got the autograph. What he did get was a
lesson in what it's like to pursue an autograph from Woods, the
most coveted prize for autograph hounds.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's final practice rounds were the last chance for fans
to seek autographs or snap pictures. And though several people have
been rewarded by patient golfers, there was a little more
desperation on the Olympic Club Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes haven't been ugly this week. But more than a few kids
have complained about overzealous adults running them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think they would give us more of an opportunity,''
said Tina Smith, 14, from San Diego. ``They want the autographs
just as much as we do.''
</P>
<P>
   The hottest spot for autograph seekers had been just above the
18th hole. As the golfers walked through a narrow path leading to
the clubhouse, arms, books, pendants and hats all hung over the
ropes, blocking the players' route, awaiting approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was crazy out there on Monday, but they got it under
control,'' said George Mason, a U.S. Open security volunteer.
``It's been amazing to see how many people want these autographs.
Some kids don't even know whose signatures they're getting. They
just know it's a golfer. Sometimes, they'll ask a friend who a
player was and the kid will say it was a nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   While some golfers are less conspicuous than others _ a
volunteer in front of the locker-room door wouldn't allow David
Duval to enter on Monday because she didn't recognize him _ there
are some who have no trouble with identification. Woods tops that
list.
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation adores him most. The older one
understands how to benefit from his appeal. Woods doesn't mind
signing his name, but he's also discovered the trickery involved in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get kids and other people who are out there to watch golf
and want an autograph,'' Woods said. ``Then you get people who are
collecting autographs for business purposes. That's where we as
players have a problem. A lot of adults are sending kids out as
runners, paying them to get an autograph. Then they go mat it,
frame it and sell it. That's when it's hard to distinguish between
a genuine fan and someone trying to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   To combat such problems, some golfers sign their autographs to a
particular person. Others only sign items they endorse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1740EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
