<HEADLINE>
STRIKING FLINT WORKERS SAY THEY'RE FIGHTING FOR ALL GM EMPLOYEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Dave Schneider, a striking electrician at General
Motor's metal plant, knows he's probably not a popular man in
Arlington, Texas, where the Michigan strike has triggered about
2,300 layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But Schneider and his fellow strikers in Flint say they are
fighting for all GM workers, even though it might not seem that way
to the idled employees at the Arlington assembly plant and other
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is going to be bad feeling down there,''
Schneider said as he walked the Flint picket line. ``Just tell them
to hang in there. We're sorry they got laid off, but we've got to
do what we've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As impact of strikes at two GM parts plants ripples across the
country, the workers who touched off the chain-reaction layoffs are
grappling with the consequences of their action. By choking off the
supply of fenders, hoods, odometers, air filters and other critical
parts, the 9,200 Flint strikers have forced more than 84,000
layoffs at GM plants in 13 states.
</P>
<P>
   Even GM's foreign operations _ a primary source of the strikers'
resentment _ have suffered. More than 18,000 Mexican workers have
been sent home, as have 50 in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   In Arlington, the strike has forced nearly 1,800 layoffs at the
GM assembly plant, plus 500 more at Lear Corp. and Mackie
Automotive Systems, two GM suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The shock waves from the dispute have generated mixed feelings
of pride and discomfort among the striking workers. Analysts
predict that the shutdowns will cost the company as much as $500
million a week, giving the striking workers some powerful leverage
in the settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this plant is so unproductive, how is it we brought this
whole company to its knees?'' striker Kim McKinnis asked.
</P>
<P>
   But other striking workers expressed unease with the fate of
union members at hobbled GM plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of the country doesn't understand. They see us as
greedy,'' said Elvis Strahly, who has worked for GM for 26 years.
``We're not out here for more money. We're not out here for more
benefits. We're out here because they didn't live up to their
commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flint strikers contend that their effort to stem the loss of
jobs to foreign plants will help all GM workers, especially those
in Arlington with its proximity to Mexico. They see themselves as
the front line in a battle with a company that has become
increasingly dependent on foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fighting for future jobs,'' said striker Larry Cuevas.
``If they slap me, they'll slap you. It's better we stop them in
Flint than wait until they get that close to the border.''
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say they have no intention of pulling out of
the United States or Flint. They cast the strike as a contest
between the GM's need to compete in the global market and the
desire of the United Autoworkers Union to retain uncompetitive
production practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's environment in the marketplace, we need to have our
costs down and as finely tuned as we can,'' GM spokesman Gerry
Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have made almost no progress resolving their
differences, and both sides are bracing for a long shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wins in a strike. We lose. GM loses. The workers in
other plants lose. But it's one of the necessary evils of
collective bargaining,'' Cuevas said. ``We don't go to a strike
unless they put us out there.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
