r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     06-18 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOCRISY, MENDACITY AND THE TOBACCO PROPAGANDA CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 21)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hypocrisy and Mendacity are familiar figures in the
nation's capital. They stalk the halls of Congress, the executive
offices of government and the gathering places of lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   They are particularly venal when special interests, with little
concern for the public welfare, feel endangered in their quest for
money.
</P>
<P>
   A good example of that venality was the tobacco industry's
$40-million dollar propaganda campaign that sought to show that the
congressional effort to lay heavier taxes on cigarettes was just
another quest by greedy politicians for more money to increase the
size of government.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, the campaign succeeded when the Senate voted last
week to kill the tobacco bill aimed at discouraging teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the industry's slick TV spots was there any
suggestion that tobacco kills people or that revenues from the tax
would have been used to reduce teen smoking, accelerate the war on
drugs or reduce taxes on the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the commercials was that the increased tobacco tax
would just be one more way of taking money from middle- and
lower-income people to support a more massive bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take much memory to recall that not long ago the
heads of the major cigarette companies lined up before a
congressional committee and swore under oath that they did not
believe tobacco was addictive. Talk about deceit!
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to garner more money from tobacco revenues, the TV
spots suggested, the two political parties were abandoning
traditional doctrines _ the Republicans, their opposition to
taxation, and the Democrats, their support of working people.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans did not abandon their opposition to
taxation. They latched onto the tobacco industry's argument and
made it their own. They, too, contended that the attempt to
increase the tobacco tax was simply a battle between big government
and the little people.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco campaign was similar to that conducted to great
advantage by Republicans in 1994. That year the GOP hammered
relentlessly at the fact that the Clinton administration and
congressional Democrats had passed a monumental tax increase.
Nowhere was there any mention of the fact that the tax was levied
against the richest 1 percent of the populace and not the middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   Nor have the Republicans acknowledged subsequently that the
economic package, of which that tax hike was one key element, may
have helped produce the prosperity that Americans now are enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   The recent campaign also bore marked similarity to the
successful drive, financed in 1994 by the medical and health
insurance industries and promoted by the GOP, to kill Clinton's
plan to extend health care coverage to millions of Americans who do
not now have it.
</P>
<P>
   Some things never change.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP was informed by one of its pollsters that it could
nullify Democratic criticism of its alliance with the tobacco
manufacturers by asserting vehemently that it simply was opposing
traditional Democratic tax-and-spend policies.
</P>
<P>
   That is demagoguery of an ancient variety. It reaches back to
the days when the Democrats campaigned successfully to make Herbert
Hoover appear the arch villain of the Great Depression or when
Republicans won elections by asserting that Harry Truman, Adlai
Stevenson and the Democrats were ``soft on communism.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, however, that the voting public may now be too
wise to buy such subterfuge.
</P>
<P>
   The people may not be willing to sacrifice the lives of their
fellow Americans, including many who are young, to the money and
power of the big tobacco companies. They may realize that if the
tobacco tax were bad for them, its chief sponsor in the Senate
would not have been Arizona's John McCain, a Republican, a genuine
war hero and one of the most principled members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party has a corner on virtue. The Democrats, like the
Republicans, take care of those special interests that pump money
into their campaign coffers. A current criticism leveled at the
Clintonites is that they have permitted contributions from wealthy
Chinese individuals and institutions to influence their policy
toward China.
</P>
<P>
   The president denies the accusation. But as his journey to China
approaches this week, critics assert that he has abandoned human
rights and become a Chinese pawn.
</P>
<P>
   We will not know whether that's true until his state visit is
completed. What we do know is that many Republicans appear to have
taken up the tobacco industry's cause in response to contributions
made to their party.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., the poster boy of the religious
right, recently assailed the proposed tobacco settlement in the
exact terms used by the cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, a candidate for president in 2000, talked about how
awful it would be for people earning less than $30,000 annually to
have to pay the tax.
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention that tobacco takes lives, that millions of
Americans who never smoked or who gave up smoking would not have
been taxed because they do not buy cigarettes or that millions of
dollars from the sale of cigarettes have gone into Republican
coffers _ and to those of some Democrats, too.
</P>
<P>
   Using some of the tobacco tax revenue to fight drugs or to end
the tax penalty imposed on married couples who work may or may not
have been valid. But there were various ways in which the
legislation could have been compromised and strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hypocrisy and mendacity that characterized the behavior
of the measure's opponents succeeded in killing it outright.
</P>
<P>
   Now American voters will have a ready-made issue upon which to
decide who should control Congress as we enter the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1745EDT &QL; 
