<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-SMALL-BIZ-0618-COX     06-18 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-SMALL-BIZ-0618-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL-BUSINESS OWNERS AIR THEIR CONCERNS AT NATIONAL SUMMIT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For a diverse bunch, their worries are remarkably
similar.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, restaurant owners, computer software designers, travel
agents, printers and furniture builders were among the small
business owners visiting the nation's capitol Thursday to fight for
less government intrusion and lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax code has 7 million words,'' said Charles Anderson, a
veterinarian from Waco, Texas. ''Why can't we have a code that is
simple and fair and everyone can understand?''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson echoed a popular sentiment at the first-ever
``Congressional Small Business Summit'' organized by the
influential National Federation of Independent Business, with
cooperation from the American Farm Bureau Federation and five
smaller business associations.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is one of NFIB's 550 voting delegates who traveled to
Washington for the three-day event.
</P>
<P>
   Many said the forum was not only an opportunity to meet people
with similar needs from across the country, but also to give a
strong, united political voice for small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been forgotten for a long time,'' said Jan Triplett,
co-director of Entrepreneurs Association, a business based in
Austin, Texas that links small firms with consultants, investors
and new American and foreign customers.
</P>
<P>
   Triplett, a NFIB delegate, said many small business owners don't
have the extra time or money that other special interest groups
have to lobby for their agendas. ''We don't have lawyers on our
staff,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Passarelli, a wholesale florist from Oregon, said that
scarce resources also put small business people at a disadvantage
in legal battles over land use.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we stand a chance?'' he said. ``We're just trying to
grow roses.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuit protection was among the needs NFIB members expressed in
surveys. They also want a federal exemption from state standards
for health benefits and less burdensome environmental and safety
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In panel discussions and brainstorming sessions Thursday,
participants said the Endangered Species Act and many wetlands
regulations have infringed upon their property rights. In addition,
many delegates said public elementary schools have allowed
environmental groups to set curricula and portray business as an
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cultural war and we need to get involved in it,''
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFIB has some 600,000 dues-paying firms, 900 employees and
an $85 million annual budget. It was ranked this year as the
nation's most powerful business lobby in a survey of Washington
insiders by Fortune magazine.
</P>
<P>
   On one of its major priorities, the NFIB had reason to celebrate
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Despite opposition from President Clinton, the House approved a
measure Wednesday that would eliminate the tax code effective Dec.
31, 2001, except for provisions relating specifically to Social
Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill is a positive sign that Washington is hearing the
voice of small business,'' said Jack Faris, NFIB president.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
