NYT-06-18-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      06-18 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stalled low pressure over Maine will cause unsettled weather to
linger over New England. Clouds will be most prevalent across
northern New England while southern sections will be partly sunny
after patchy morning coastal fog. Scattered thundershowers with
locally heavy rain will develop through the region during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A frontal system marking the leading edge of very warm and humid
air will move east from from the Ohio Valley toward the interior
Northeast. A cluster of thundershowers over the eastern Ohio Valley
early Friday will weaken as it drifts toward the central
Appalachians Friday morning. The showers and thundershowers will
regenerate Friday afternoon from western Pennsylvania to the
Carolinas. A few strong thunderstorms with gusty winds and hail are
expected in the Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual heat will persist over a large area from the southern
Plains to the Southeastern States. Converging winds will promote a
band of strong thunderstorms which will move through the Tennessee
and lower Mississippi Valleys. A few isolated thundershowers will
bring little relief to the fire-plagued areas of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Another pool of unseasonably cool air will drift over the
northern Rockies and northern Plains. Showers will be common near
west-facing slopes in Montana and Wyoming. Scattered showers will
linger over the northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West Coast states will be warm with ample sunshine.
However, low clouds will remain in the cool air near the northern
coast of Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: A Different Spin
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, a damage survey team in Pennsylvania uncovered
evidence of an unusual twister. The damage pattern revealed that
clockwise winds surrounded the center of the tornado. Over 90
percent of tornados spin counterclockwise. A tornado develops when
the motion in large slowly rotating thunderstorms is concentrated
into a narrow violent swirl. Since larger scale storms are affected
by the earth's rotation, the slow spin is usually counterclockwise.
Rarely, the turbulent motions near a thunderstorm can make small
areas of clockwise rotation that lead to tornados that spin in
reverse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
