<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-CROWDS-HNS &LR;      06-18 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-CROWDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF FANS FIND WAYS TO GET TO THE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A question keeps popping up when walking through
the U.S. Open crowds at the Olympic Club: Doesn't anybody work?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do. But my boss said take the day off. He said it's a
once-in-a-lifetime chance. Enjoy it,'' said Maureen McGowan, an
American Express accountant who spent Wednesday with her husband
watching the pros warm up for the Big Event.
</P>
<P>
   John Kavanagh, an attorney, works, too. Just not much while the
U.S. Open is in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left a message on my voicemail for my clients letting them
know I'll be out on the course,'' said Kavanagh, standing near the
McGowans. ``I wouldn't miss this.''
</P>
<P>
   By the looks of things, a lot of people are calling in sick,
have a generous boss or simply are going AWOL to take in the U.S.
Open. Although the tournament began with Thursday's opening round,
the days leading up to the real golf had their own appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Through Wednesday, the pros were loose, making side bets with
one another, chatting with the spectators, munching on the free
apples and bananas provided at the start of each hole, teeing off a
second or even a third ball if the first or second one missed the
intended mark. Onlookers also bent the rules during the practice
rounds, snapping pictures, talking above a whisper and shouting
``You the man'' at what during tourney play would be considered
inappropriate moments.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan, who spent a good chunk of the day at the 10th tee and
the nearby 17th, kept her automatic camera busy, capturing
superstar Tiger Woods, veteran Jack Nicklaus and her favorite
up-and-comer, Matt Kuchar from Georgia Tech, who won last year's
U.S. Amateur. She was so close she could hear his soft Southern
accent when he was conferring with his caddy.
</P>
<P>
   McGowan, who spent the day in the gallery with her husband,
Brian, had never been to a major golf tournament before and had a
mini-anxiety attack over what to wear in the fashion-conscious
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through four outfits. I even washed my tennis shoes,
but they didn't dry in time so I'm wearing these thongs,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And what attire did she settle on? A yellow tye-dyed blouse and
a denim skirt. Brian McGowan had on a white polo shirt, white
tennis shoes and gray Bill Blass shorts.
</P>
<P>
   An injured carpenter who has been off the job for more than a
year, Brian McGowan loves to golf, but has been kept off the course
with a bum elbow. For now, he's content to watch the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do admire their talent. Just look at that,'' he said,
as Paul Azinger teed off, smashing the little, white, dimpled ball
down the fairway in a smooth stroke that looked effortless.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife live in Ingleside Terrace, not too far from the
Olympic Club, and scored some tickets from a neighbor who works for
one of the corporate sponsors. If the freebies hadn't come through,
they had planned to volunteer for the event and work at a hot dog
stand.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest draw on the course, of course, was Woods, pulling in
the most fans at each stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the top of his head. I couldn't get any closer,'' said
Angela Fung, a data analyst from Oakland who sacrificed one of her
vacation days for the U.S. Open. ``But I did get to see Fred
Couples.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples, referred to by the in-the-know spectators as ``Freddy''
or ``Boom-Boom,'' was another fan favorite, with folks lined up
three or four deep to watch him drive the ball, although only those
in the front had a clear view. The other fans relied on the sounds
of the crowd reaction to learn whether the shot was on line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, you learn the good spots to see the play,''
said Kavanagh, the lawyer. He used to caddy at the Olympic Club as
a boy and attended the last U.S. Open played there in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   And to say he knows the terrain well would be an understatement.
He can recite all the course stats, comment on the quirky rolls of
the greens and answer obscure questions about the players. But one
inquiry stumped him: How did he get past the fashion police wearing
black pants to a place where khaki rules?
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' he said, ``I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
