<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUGGENHEIM-ART-REVIEW     06-18 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUGGENHEIM-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: PEGGY GUGGENHEIM, CELEBRITY. OH YES, COLLECTOR. 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A hundred years ago this August, Peggy Guggenheim was
born. The wild daughter of a wild father, she was a conversational
magnet for much of her lifetime. Forever in and out of love, she
was a conspicuous dresser _ even her sunglasses made news _ and, in
the popular imagination, a more than conspicuous party-giver. In
her later years, she was a more or less a permanent American
presence in Venice in a strange house on the Grand Canal that she
filled with what many a visitor thought were strange works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Much of all this is touched upon in a new exhibition called
``Peggy Guggenheim: A Celebration'' at the Guggenheim Museum
uptown. This is, of course, her family museum, and her second
cousin Peter Lawson-Johnston is its longtime chairman. The show is
likewise a family affair, in that its curator is Karole P.B. Vail,
Peggy's granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say that it is a curious and somewhat insubstantial
affair, in which the center of attention is Peggy the celebrity,
rather than Peggy the champion of 20th-century art at its highest
level. But even on a wet Sunday morning, it draws an eager
audience. What people go to see, or to dream about, is the private
life of Peggy Guggenheim (who died in 1979). They fantasize about
her phantasmagorial ups and downs, and about having the run of her
palazzo in Venice.
</P>
<P>
   This latter preoccupation is much encouraged at the Guggenheim
Museum. What the visitor sees first is in effect an outsize and
open-ended photograph album in which most of the images are framed
and hung on the wall. Peggy herself is almost always present. Many
of the photographs of her and her friends or acquaintances are by
very gifted people, among them Berenice Abbott, Man Ray and Gisele
Freund.
</P>
<P>
   Other photographs are the more telling for being snapshots made
on the wing, like the image of Peggy in 1941 at the Villa Air-Bel
outside Marseilles, where a young American named Varian Fry was
taking risks to get European refugees to safety in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But in almost every photograph, and even in the two portraits of
Peggy that were painted by Franz von Lenbach when she was 5 years
old, there is a continuous refrain. She looks out at us as if to
say, ``Will anyone ever really love me?'' That look of puzzlement
and disquiet rarely leaves her.
</P>
<P>
   The section of memorabilia includes objects that are an integral
part of Peggy's legend, like the silver bedhead designed by
Alexander Calder. Others, like the earrings designed for her by the
painter Yves Tanguy, take a little finding.
</P>
<P>
   Also on view are a very large number of pages from Peggy's
Venetian guest books. Anyone who has ever kept a guest book will
have come to dread the results when guest after guest has fumbled
with words and mismatched them with unfunny drawings. Not many of
Peggy Guggenheim's guests did much better than that. The signal
exception was Jean Cocteau, a more than practiced performer who
could turn on at a moment's notice and did not fail to do so when
in Venice in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from this show almost entirely is the Peggy Guggenheim
who most deserves to be remembered. As a collector, she was lucky
on three vital counts. First, she had timely and inspired advice
from Marcel Duchamp, among others. Second, she could buy major
works by Brancusi, Braque, Picasso, Leger, Kandinsky, Duchamp,
Delaunay, de Chirico, Dali, Klee, Miro, Masson, Magritte and others
in 1940 and 1941, when nobody else was buying. Third, she was
around in the early days of the New York School and put herself
wholeheartedly behind it.
</P>
<P>
   It is often held against her that she acted upon advice. But
what mattered more was that she was quick to act. Nor was it bulk
buying, as has been suggested. Her ideal may have been ``a painting
a day,'` but those were times at which it was essential to move
fast. Many artists in Europe were desperate to sell as the Reich's
shadow extended over the continent.
</P>
<P>
   What she bought was the nucleus of one of the great collections
of 20th-century art. Much of it is the Peggy Guggenheim Collection,
which now belongs to the Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   She was not lucky in her timing when she opened her gallery in
London in January 1938. She opened with an exhibition of drawings
and furniture by Cocteau. (His preface in French appeared side by
side with an English translation by Samuel Beckett. Neither was at
his best, but as a double act it could not have been bettered.)
</P>
<P>
   Peggy was able to follow this in March 1938 with the first-ever
exhibition in London of paintings by Wassily Kandinsky. Nothing was
sold, but with 38 pictures on the wall this was a gallant effort.
</P>
<P>
   When she opened her gallery called Art of This Century in New
York in October 1942, her situation was entirely different. Whereas
London in 1938 had been already apprehensive of World War II and
flaccid, not to say inert, in its response to new art from
overseas, New York in 1942 was full of European artists who had
arrived as refugees. A city in which Mondrian, Max Ernst, Leger,
Masson, Chagall and Tanguy were all within reach could not be
called provincial.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the burgeoning New York School, which included
Jackson Pollock, Clyfford Still, Mark Rothko and Robert Motherwell.
All of them were shown at Art of This Century in an environment
designed by Frederick Kiesler that was in itself a triumph of the
modern spirit. In that gallery, new paintings were shown in a new
way. Between 1942 and 1947, Peggy Guggenheim was an incomparable
impresario for the new American art. It may, in fact, have been her
greatest achievement.
</P>
<P>
   So it is the great defect of this exhibition that painting and
sculpture play so small a part in it. Art historian Leo Steinberg
once wrote in Peggy's guest book that hers was ``the only house in
Venice that does not make one feel ashamed to be of this century.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could possibly say that this is borne out by the present
show, where a desultory jumble of paintings of all kinds makes
nothing like a coherent statement. Pollock and Motherwell are there
with minor paintings. There is also a small bronze by Jean Arp.
Thereafter, the standard declines sharply into Surrealist odds and
ends.
</P>
<P>
   We should have been reminded of what Clement Greenberg, a
longtime champion of Art of This Century, said of Peggy Guggenheim
in 1980: ``Her place in history has grown in the last 30-odd years.
No question about it.'' That was the note for her centenary, but it
has not been sounded. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Peggy Guggenheim: A Celebration'' remains at the Guggenheim
Museum, Fifth Avenue at 89th Street, through Sept. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
