<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-X-FILES-TEX     06-18 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-X-FILES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`X-FILES' SUCCEEDS AT CREATING THE BIGGER PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's get the burning questions out of the way first.
</P>
<P>
   No, ``The X-Files'' movie doesn't answer all the questions
raised by the show. Yes, fans will enjoy it, if only for the
endless coffee-shop debates it will inspire. No, it probably won't
convert the unconverted.
</P>
<P>
   Do the show's heroes, Mulder and Scully, explore the phenomenon
of a nonplatonic relationship? Ain't telling.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, it looks good. If you're worried that this is merely a
TV series writ large, know that it has the good sense to make use
of its largeness. Some shots have a David Lean-esque quality, as
solitary figures or tiny objects traverse vast, barren landscapes
(although like the TV series, the movie plays fast and loose with
locations).
</P>
<P>
   Director Rob Bowman lights everything so brightly, it gives the
movie an odd, fakey look, as if he wanted you to know that most of
the picture was filmed on sets, but he has an eye for how specks of
dust and swirls of snow fall and dance in that bright light. Bowman
and screenwriter Chris Carter also make good use of silence, with
at least two long scenes that are nearly devoid of dialogue _ this
isn't the type of movie where you want a lot of talkers in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Would that they had showed such confidence more often. In trying
to educate the neophytes in the audience, the filmmakers rely on
words more than actions, an approach that bogs down the movie's
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Even if your TV has been on the fritz for five years, you
probably know that FBI Special Agent Fox Mulder (David Duchovny)
believes in conspiracies and extraterrestrials, and that his
partner, Dana Scully (Gillian Anderson), is a skeptic who remains
unconvinced despite years of evidence supporting Mulder's theories.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need Scully on her cell phone telling Mulder that
she's the rational one, and that they should do the rational thing,
in so many variations that it seems like she just learned the word
``rational'' and is trying out its different uses.
</P>
<P>
   Such overkill also occurs occasionally on the TV series, which
comes to the big screen with all its virtues and flaws intact. By
now, the chemistry between Duchovny and Anderson is so
second-nature that they could be a Tracy and Hepburn (or at least a
Lucy and Desi) for the '90s; not only does Anderson step into her
first big movie role without stumbling, her presence lifts Duchovny
to his best film performance. And at its best, the series is among
the best-written on TV, and its intelligent and complex writing
translates well to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Your enjoyment may depend on how much intelligence and
complexity you ``want'' from a summer ``event'' movie; ``The
X-Files'' can be so confusing that one newspaper started a weekly
column just to keep things straight, and Entertainment Weekly has
dedicated more than one article to sorting things out. Sometimes,
it seems like Cliffs Notes would help, too.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the movie itself goes, it furthers the series'
aliens-and-conspiracy plot with a couple of cave-bound discoveries,
an explosion at a Dallas federal building, an FBI inquiry or two,
and the introduction of a new, shadowy figure (Martin Landau).
</P>
<P>
   True fans of the show won't want to know more than that about
the plot. They'll steer clear of blabbing reviewers and fellow
X-philes until they can see the movie reveal its surprises for
itself, which it does with a refreshing
lack of predictability and a frustrating lack of closure _ or, at
times, logic. But that really doesn't matter here. Rookie watchers
just might not get it; they're likely to be entertained, but
they're equally likely to wonder whether the show's popularity is
part of some conspiracy itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' is rated PG-13 for profanity and violence.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``The X-Files''
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rob Bowman
</P>
<P>
   Stars: David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson
</P>
<P>
   Length: 120 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
