<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-ESTES19-COX     06-18 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-ESTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite ranking 16th, Estes will be home for Open
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ He was one of the hottest players on the PGA Tour,
about as consistent as anyone, and Bob Estes was more pleased with
himself than he had been in years when he made a prediction earlier
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the beginning,'' the Austin resident said in
March. ``They're not going to stop me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes. And no.
</P>
<P>
   Estes, who is playing his best golf since 1994, ranks 16th on
the tour's 1998 earnings list with $683,817. He has finished in the
top 10 in five tournaments. Yet, while the best players in the
world are at the Olympic Club in San Francisco competing for the
U.S. Open championship this week (week of Friday, June 19), Estes
is at home, mulling another alteration to his game _ cross-handed
putting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his high ranking on the tour's money list, Estes, 32,
failed to meet qualifying standards for the U.S. Open. The United
States Golf Association has several categories in which a player
can qualify, one of them a top-30 ranking on the PGA Tour's
earnings list the previous year. Estes finished 69th in 1997.
Players could also qualify for the Open by ranking among the top 10
on the 1998 money list through May 24, the final day of the
Colonial tournament in Fort Worth. Estes, who ranked 11th before
Colonial, missed the cut, earning only an early trip home. He shot
67 on Thursday but 75 on Friday, exhausted, he said, from pushing
himself so hard to play well enough to qualify for the U.S. and
British opens and PGA Championship, three of pro golf's four major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was absolutely fried,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Estes qualified for the British because he is ranked among the
top 20 on the PGA Tour and top 50 in the world rankings. He has
also played well enough to qualify for the PGA Championship. His
final option for the U.S. Open was a 36-hole qualifying event in
early June at the Woodmont Country Club in Rockville, Md., where
160 golfers arrived to claim 32 spots in the Open. Estes shot 148,
falling short by six strokes.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Estes has no one to blame but himself for having
to spend Open week in Austin. In another, he wonders why the USGA
has different qualifying standards for its men's and women's Opens.
The top 35 LPGA money winners from 1998 will compete in the women's
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are guys who I've been beating every single week this
year but who finished in the top 30 last year, and they are in the
Open,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   USGA spokesman Rich Skyzinzki said there are different standards
because more men try to enter through the qualifying tournaments
that are open to any professional and amateurs with a handicap
index of 1.4 or lower. (The women's maximum is 4.4).
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more than 7,100 men try to qualify (for 156 spots),''
Skyzinski said. ``We had 1,000 women.''
</P>
<P>
   So Estes, a former national collegiate player of the year at the
University of Texas, will have to call on the resiliency that has
enabled him to recover from swing problems and injuries the last
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Estes has undergone more makeovers than Dennis Rodman while
trying to regain the form that enabled him to finish a career-best
14th in earnings in 1994, when he won the Texas Open, his lone
victory in 10 years on tour.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1994, Estes developed soreness in his right elbow, he
says, from swinging shafts that were too long and heavy and from a
weak grip, hands turned to the left. His grip was causing him to
address the ball too steeply, inducing extra vibrations.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Estes' neck and shoulder muscles became too tight
from the intensive weight training he had undergone in hopes of
adding length to his shots. The 6-foot-1-inch Estes had increased
his weight to 195 pounds, 15 more than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Estes slipped to a disappointing 41st on the 1995 earnings list.
That spot looked great from where Estes landed in '96, when he
stumbled to 149th, losing his fully exempt status to compete on
tour. He survived the 36-hole cut in only seven of 26 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Estes began pulling himself toward respectability last year,
finishing 69th in earnings despite holding his clubs like a
baseball bat, an uncommon grip. He said it helped alleviate pain in
his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   This year Estes switched to a stronger grip, turning his hands
to the right and his game up several notches. He made the change
without using instruction from a swing coach. Estes now wishes
someone had advised him earlier in his career to use a stronger
grip, which produces right-to-left shots that tend to carry farther
than the left-to-right shots from a weak grip.
</P>
<P>
   Estes ranks ninth in scoring average, 70.04 strokes per round.
He has made 15 cuts in 16 events. He tied for second at Bay Hill in
March and finished third at Greensboro in April.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he is not satisfied, particulary with his putting.
Though he ranks 20th in that category, Estes said he needs to
become better to elevate his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hardly ever three-putt, so my total putts always look
good,'' Estes said. ``But I don't make nearly enough mid-length,
15- to 20- and 30-footers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not those putts that cost Estes a victory this year,
though. At Greensboro, he led by one shot with two holes left but
made bogey at both, missing four-foot putts at each.
</P>
<P>
   So Estes will now try crosshanded putting, placing his left hand
lower than the right. Some golfers say that enables them to move
their putter down the line more easily. Proponents of crosshanded
putting say that the conventional grip _ right hand below left _ is
less steady, because the left wrist can break down, producing putts
that pull to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk, considered by some the best putter on tour, putts
crosshanded. So does Fred Couples. Tom Kite has alternated between
grips. Short-game guru Dave Pelz recommends crosshanded putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried it before but never committed to it,'' Estes said.
``I was never quite comfortable. But I think I've found a way to
hold the putter that I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
