<HEADLINE>
`LE CORSAIRE': BALLET WHOSE FINALE IS A ROUSING SHIPWRECK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The world will come crashing down in a huge shipwreck
at approximately 10:30 Friday night at the Metropolitan Opera
House, where American Ballet Theater is performing.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that Ballet Theater has bowed to popular taste and
created a dance version of ``Titanic.'' Instead, it has resurrected
``Le Corsaire,'' a seldom-seen, three-act Russian ballet that ends
with the spectacular sinking of a ship. The company will perform
the ballet on Friday night for the first time, and then Saturday
afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   The ballet, based on a poem by Lord Byron, was first performed
in London in 1837. Since then, 12 other versions of ``Le Corsaire''
have been created in Europe and most recently in the United States,
in a production staged last year by Anna-Marie Holmes for the
Boston Ballet. Kevin McKenzie, artistic director of Ballet Theater,
saw the production and loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people only know `Le Corsaire' from the famous pas de
deux and have never seen a full production,'' McKenzie said,
referring to the glittering bravura gala number. He added: ``That's
a shame, because it's such a spirited, extravagant ballet that's so
much larger than life. It's the Errol Flynn movie of ballets. And
there are so many challenging roles to showcase the principal
dancers that each performance becomes a mini-gala for the
audience.'' The lure of the ballet has probably not been the plot,
a complicated story of pirates, pashas and slave girls with names
like Conrad, Lankendem and Medora, set in Turkish-ruled Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holmes, the Soviet-trained artistic director of the Boston
Ballet, had danced the pas de deux and was drawn to the three-act
work after seeing a videotape of Konstantin Sergeyev's 1992
production for the Bolshoi Ballet. The Sergeyev staging was itself
inspired by versions by Marius Petipa, whose ballets helped define
ballet classicism in Russia, in the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Holmes acquired the sets and costumes from another Soviet
production, by Yuri Grigorovich, which she found stored in a
warehouse in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   To help with the production, she brought Vadim Disnitsky,
Sergeyev's assistant, to Boston, along with Natalya Dudinskaya, Ms.
Holmes' longtime mentor, a noted Soviet ballerina and the wife of
Sergeyev. Other Soviet dancers already in Boston _ Tatiana Legat,
Tatiana Terekhova and Sergei Berejnoi _ helped with the staging.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Kolpakova, a former Kirov Ballet star currently coaching
Ballet Theater dancers, helped with the Soviet style, which
emphasizes the line of the upper body more than American ballet
training does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victor Barbee, a very good, very logical actor, is helping
with the dramatic scenes,'' Ms. Holmes said. Barbee is a Ballet
Theater principal.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Holmes' first step in the restaging was to work with
company music directors on the score, which is by five composers.
Then came considerable editing and reassigning of dances and
dramatic bits to make the plot more plausible.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Ms. Holmes was worried about making changes. Ms.
Dudinskaya, who had learned the lead female role of the slave
Medora from Agrippina Vaganova, who in turn had learned it from
Petipa himself, was like a mother to her. ``I didn't dare,'' Ms.
Holmes said, laughing. ``But Kevin gave me the force to say let's
get the story better.'' The three-hour ballet has been cut by a
half-hour.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As far as Ms. Holmes is concerned, ``Le Corsaire'' has just
about everything: delicate solo dances for the women, powerhouse
dances for the men and Petipa's exquisite ``Jardin Anime,'' a group
dance in which flowers come alive, danced by a cast that includes
children from the School of American Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Why is ``Le Corsaire'' so little known outside Russia?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think impresarios saw `The Sleeping Beauty' and `Swan Lake'
as being the big sellers,'' Ms. Holmes said, adding that she would
like next to restage Soviet productions like ``Laurencia'' and
``The Fountain of Bakhchisarai.'' But she has no doubt about the
appeal of ``Le Corsaire'' at the Met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will knock your socks off,'' she said. ``And the dancers
are eating it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
