<P>
   METEORITE-POPULAR (Undated) _ If Hollywood's current fascination
with menacing meteorites has you hunkered down waiting for the big
one to hit, we have news for you: We're already being bombarded.
Every day. By billions of meteorite fragments tiny enough to be
invisible to the naked eye but numerous enough to add something
like 910 metric tons each year to the weight of the Earth. By KAREN
UHLENHUTH. Story will move in the ``l'' category..
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FIREWORKS-REVIEW _ (Undated) _ There are moments of
violence in ``Fireworks'' as shocking and unsettling as anything
dished out by Quentin Tarantino. And yet the overwhelming emotion
at the end of ``Fireworks'' is not of cathartic release but of
sadness and regret, tempered with a sort of tarnished nobility.
Three and a half out of four stars. By ROBERT W. BUTLER. Story will
move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-OPPOSITE-REVIEW (Undated) _ One of the first things teen
siren Dedee Truitt tells us in her voice-over narration for ``The
Opposite of Sex'' is that she hates movies with voice-over
narration. This prime slice of 16-year-old trailer-court trash is
the most outrageous character in writer//director Don Roos' comedy
of bad manners, but she manages to bring out edgy behavior in just
about everyone she encounters. Two and a half out of four stars. By
ROBERT W. BUTLER. Story will move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-JUNK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Or at least the painter of the
existential icon ``The Scream'' seems like an optimist compared to
the creator of ``Junk Mail,'' the new comedy//thriller from his
native Norway. This glumly amusing effort from writer//director Pal
Sletaune fairly oozes Scandinavian angst, from the pasty,
beard-stubbled visages of its characters to the slumlike buildings
in which it unfolds and the unrelenting gray atmosphere, which
baths every scene in a sort of dull, color-draining fluorescent
light. Three out of four stars. By ROBERT W. BUTLER. Story will
move in the ``e'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FATHER-ESSAY (Undated) _ Melanie Gray, an editor at the Kansas
City Star, writes of cleaning out her late father's house with her
sister. Story will move in the ``l'' category.
</P>
