<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5901 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHER-ESSAY-KAN &LR;      06-18 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-ESSAY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE FINAL CHORE FOR DAD: CLEANING OUT A BUREAU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MELANIE GRAY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: There we stood. The two of us. Strangers. In a
strangely familiar place. Home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might as well get started.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   My sister looked at me. I looked at my sister. I looked at
myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``How 'bout the bureau?''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK.''
</P>
<P>
   I walked over and pulled out a top drawer. The old blond dresser
had been in the dining room for as long as I can remember _ and
I'll be 38 this fall. So ... maybe 30 years? 32?
</P>
<P>
   Inside were hundreds and hundreds of ballpoint pens.
``Compliments of First National Bank of York.'' ``Brannen's
Radiator Repair. Don't Let a Drip Spoil Your Trip.'' ``Air
Products.''
</P>
<P>
   I clicked one on and scribbled on a scratch pad. No ink. Nothing
but that horrible sound of dry tip against dry paper. And a maze of
colorless ruts. I clicked on another. Nothing. And another. And
another.
</P>
<P>
   My sister laughed. I did, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   I picked out a couple of pocketknives and three compasses. Then
I turned the whole drawer upside-down in the trash bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next drawer.''
</P>
<P>
   The stuff in this one wasn't so worthless. A black-and-white
graduation picture of our cousin Jeanne from 1965. My third-grade
class picture. A VFW medallion. A miniature American flag. Lots
more pictures. Old pictures.
</P>
<P>
   She carefully sorts what I pull out. One box for the personal
things. Another for stuff that can go to Goodwill or some other
place like that.
</P>
<P>
   The third drawer goes faster. We're getting down a system here.
I pull, she sorts. She always has been the patient one, the
organized one.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time we're silent. And there's no background noise.
No radio. No TV.
</P>
<P>
   At first I feel funny. Uncomfortable. Pretty soon, though, I get
caught up in the pulling. She doesn't say how she feels _ and I
don't ask because I'm afraid to. I don't want to know. Not yet at
least. Anyway, she's probably caught up in sorting like I am in
pulling.
</P>
<P>
   Drawer four. More junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toss it.''
</P>
<P>
   I do. Five, six, seven, eight.
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a half has passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe how fast this is going.'' I sound almost
giddy.
</P>
<P>
   She's not mean about it, but she sets me straight. Like when we
were kids. The older one telling the younger one exactly how it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but we've still got the bedrooms, the living room, the
basement. And don't forget the attic.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right, of course. We have only just started. We have the
whole rest of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right.''
</P>
<P>
   She must hear how stupid I feel. Or feel tense like I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're right, though. We have made a lot of progress.''
</P>
<P>
   For some odd, silly little reason, I feel so much better after
she says that. But my feeling better doesn't have anything to do
with the cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   She must know that, too.
</P>
<P>
   I head for the old blond dresser's mate across the room. I pull
out a top drawer _ and she starts sorting.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Gray is an editor at The Star. Her sister, Sandra
Osentowski, lives in their hometown of York, Neb. Their father,
Raymond Gray, died Oct. 28, 1997, and it took the Gray ``girls''
about three months to clean out the family home of 50 years. In May
a young man from Minnesota rented the house. They hope he finds it
as snug and comfortable as they did. These days the sisters talk _
at length _ almost every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
