<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-MONTGOMERIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLIN MONTGOMERIE: `QUITE GOOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Colin Montgomerie explains why he's been a
runner-up in many recent golf tournaments: ``Well,'' he said. ``I
am quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly one way to look at it and that other three-time
U.S. Open groomsman, Tom Lehman, who has been no worse than tied
for the lead after the first three rounds of the last three Opens,
yet failed to even equal par on the final Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs are the voices of near-winning-experience at this 98th
U.S. Open, which opened Thursday on the Olympic Club's Lake Course.
And, in a game where the mind can be the enemy, both golfers have
spun sad moments into positive memories.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't lose the Open, they'd tell you: They nearly won it,
and came away with nothing less than the power to win it this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been tormented by it, ever,'' Lehman said. ``They
are good memories. There are not many people who have a chance to
play in the last group of a U.S. Open, much less three years in a
row. And not many guys go to the 72nd hole with a chance to win,
ever, much less two straight years. I think my memories have been
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, 34, has been the favorite of the media to win here,
perhaps because he sounded eerily like Mark O'Meara did on the eve
of his first majors victory, the 1998 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether I had to get over it within hours or days or months or
whatever, I will always take good memories from coming close to
winning major championships, I think,'' Montgomerie said. ``And I
am very proud of what I have achieved not only in major
championships but other tournaments as well. ... If I never make a
cut again or never hit a golf ball again, I will always have had a
successful career. That is what I am looking back at now, instead
of worrying about not having won a major.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was crying behind the 18th green last year after Ernie
Els made par to beat him by a stroke. Just a hole earlier,
Montgomerie stood over a 5-foot birdie putt that would have tied
him for the lead. He stood and stood, waiting for the rowdy
Americans at Congressional Country Club in Maryland to hush. And
then he missed the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting me down now, this majors business,'' he said
then, after his emotions subsided.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says, ``This major bug that people talk about _ and thank
you for bringing it up again _ is a problem that I am coping with
better than I did before. The more success I have around the world
limits the (emphasis on) lack of a major success.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie's recent successes include finishing in the top 10
in three of his five PGA Tour events this year and all five of his
European Tour events, which helps explain his confidence in his
game and his chances here.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, 38, has been having a different kind of year. He's
finished in the top 10 in only three of his 14 events and won none,
but was buoyed (also soaked) by a third-place finish at wet
Westchester last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Montgomerie, he has won a major _ the British Open in
1996 _ so he comes saddled with a lighter load of ``best player who
never won a (fill-in-the-blank)'' labels despite his Open
near-misses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know what it is that got me into contention, and so
I feel like that is something that I can just try to repeat, and
that if I'm playing well, staying patient _ like I have been the
last three, four years _ then I will probably be in contention
again,'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, like Montgomerie, trailed Els by a shot at the 17th tee
last year. But he followed a perfect drive by splashing a 7-iron
into a water hazard, and wound up finishing third.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman lived. Lehman learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you kind of get to the end, you feel like you have a
chance to win, (you get) a little too aggressive, trying to force
it,'' he said. ``Instead (you should be) trying to keep on hitting
conservatively, good shots, and letting somebody else make the
mistakes. So I think if I can get in that situation again this
year, I am just going to be looking toward more the middle of the
greens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
