<SLUG> BC-ST.LOUIS-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA REVIEW: `KATYA,' `FAUST' AND `DON PASQUALE' IN ST. LOUIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Opera Theater of St. Louis has grown remarkably
since Richard Gaddes founded it in 1976 as a Midwestern oasis of
contemporary works, operatic rarities and standard repertory,
performed in English by young singers at the beginning of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's budget was $139,000 that first season; in recent
years, it has hovered around $5 million. Today, the directorial
reins are held by a triumvirate _ Charles MacKay, general director;
Colin Graham, artistic director, and Stephen Lord, music director _
but the original vision has remained largely intact.
</P>
<P>
   It has also become a popular draw: the 30 performances at the
950-seat Loretto-Hilton Center at Webster University are virtually
sold out, meaning that around 30,000 tickets have been sold for the
four productions the festival is offering. This year's program
includes two 20th-century works _ Janacek's ``Katya Kabanova'' and
Alexander Goehr's reimagining of a lost Monteverdi work,
``Arianna'' (which will be heard later) _ and two classics,
Donizetti's ``Don Pasquale'' and Gounod's ``Faust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Katya,'' heard on Tuesday evening, ``Faust,'' on Wednesday
afternoon and ``Don Pasquale,'' on Wednesday evening, showed the
company to be in generally fine artistic health. That said, the
slightest work has the most opulent production: where ``Katya'' and
``Faust'' unfolded on spare sets that presumably telegraphed the
desperation of their principal characters, ``Don Pasquale,'' a
romantic comedy that serves mainly as a frame for coloratura
fireworks, was a picture of bright-hued realism.
</P>
<P>
   John Going, the stage director, had some innocent fun with the
work, moving it from Italy to Buenos Aires but keeping it in the
mid-19th century. If there is no reason for the move, there is also
nothing objectionable about it, and Phyllis Mead took the new
location into account in her amusing and often freewheeling
translation. The set, by James Wolk, offers a panoramic view of
Buenos Aires harbor as a backdrop, with walls, gates and palm trees
defining Don Pasquale's estate. Liz Covey's costumes _ ornate for
the gentry, motley for the household staff _ completed the picture.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this production a joy is an ensemble that is vocally
secure and adept at comic timing and interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Dunleavy negotiated the high-flying arias that Donizetti
created for Norina with technical ease and interpretive subtlety.
She also moved comfortably between the two characterizations
demanded of her: that of the graceful young lover and the demanding
shrew. Gregory Turay, a tenor with an attractive timbre and plenty
of power, sang Ernesto's music sensitively. Timothy Nolen played
the title role with a broader range of emotions than is typical,
and Jeff Mattsey was a suitably conspiratorial Dr. Malatesta.
</P>
<P>
   In his program notes, Going wrote of a thematic link between
``Don Pasquale'' and ``Faust,'' the point being that the aging
title character in each seeks to preserve his youth. But there are
stronger and deeper links between ``Faust'' and ``Katya.'' Katya
makes every effort to be a devoted wife, but her neglect by Tichon
and the abuse of her overbearing mother-in-law, Kabanicha, drive
her into the arms of Boris, whereupon guilt drives her to suicide.
Marguerite is driven mad by the consequences of her relationship
with Faust. In both cases, salvation is available only in death.
</P>
<P>
   These emotionally bleak stories inspired extraordinary music
from both Janacek and Gounod. When Katya is at her most conflicted,
the music conveys a great deal more about her turmoil and passion
than the libretto (heard in a translation by Norman Tucker). Gounod
achieved a similar effect in a more constricted harmonic language.
</P>
<P>
   JoAnne Akalaitis directs the ``Katya'' production, with sets by
John Conklin. Conklin usually achieves a lot with limited
resources, but he was not at his most imaginative here. The sets
are mainly concrete slabs, chairs and projected collages of birds,
trees and water that drill home aspects of Katya's hopelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Plette sang Katya's music with the intensity and dimension
it demands, and was closely matched in both vocal power and
purposefulness by Robert Brubaker, as Boris, and Sari Gruber, as
Tichon's sympathetic sister Varvara. Michael Hayes as Tichon and
Kathryn Day as Kabanicha provided the necessary texture and
familial counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's striking production of ``Faust,'' with sets by Erhard
Rom, and in a translation by Edmund Tracey, underscored the work's
religious component: in his finale, he has both Faust and
Marguerite shot by a firing squad, and Marguerite rising from the
dead to bask in the sound of the Heavenly choir as she cradles
Faust, pieta-like.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Mills conveyed Marguerite's youthfulness and faith
compellingly, and sang with a touching warmth and beauty. As Faust,
John Fowler was vocally strained, particularly at the top of his
range, and dramatically overwrought, but that made him a good foil
for David Pittsinger's spectacularly agile portrayal of
Mephistopheles.
</P>
<P>
   The cast also included Franco Pomponi, as the hot-headed
Valentin, and Valerie Komar, who sang nicely but tended to overact,
as Siebel, Marguerite's hapless suitor.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra for these productions is drawn from the St. Louis
Symphony. It played beautifully for David Loebel, in ``Don
Pasquale,'' and for Lord, in ``Katya.'' In ``Faust,'' which was
conducted with considerable energy by Emmanuel Villaume, the
playing was less consistently polished. ``Katya'' runs through June
26; ``Faust'' and ``Don Pasquale'' run through June 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
