A6026 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHAT! NO `DRACULA'? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RUSSELL BAKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To whip up some chatter about movies, the American Film
Institute polled 1,500 ``prominent'' Americans to select the 100
best American films of all time, and the results are in. So let's
chatter:
</P>
<P>
   Will no one save us from ``It's a Wonderful Life''? Not those
prominent Americans. This sentimental turkey stuffing, which is
served up every December with all the rest of Christmas'
inescapable fixin's, finished at No. 11 in the vote.
</P>
<P>
   It first appeared in 1946 when a generation hardened to reality
by the Depression and war let it pass without saluting. They knew
from bitter experience that the whole town never turns up to
slather its George Baileys in money and love.
</P>
<P>
   The movie caught on only later, in the television age when the
country was far enough removed from hard times to put up with such
hokum about human nature. Now here it is: officially certified by
the American Film Institute as the 11th-best movie of all time.
Mean old Lionel Barrymore, you told it like it was.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of seeming to pick on good, worthy James Stewart,
all connoisseurs of politics will surely agree that ``Mr. Smith
Goes to Washington'' is the worst movie ever made about a
politician. The portrait of the Senate is absurd and vicious. Mr.
Smith himself is a boob so dense that he should never have been
allowed to go to Podunk, much less Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this childish slur on the American political system finished
as No. 29 in the poll. There are three quite wonderful and very
wise movies about politics _ ``Advise and Consent,'' ``All the
King's Men'' and ``The Great McGinty.'' None make the list.
</P>
<P>
   And where is ``Dracula''? At No. 87 we find the Boris Karloff
``Frankenstein.'' (Hurray!) Yet ``Dracula'' is missing. Instead, at
No. 88 we find ``Easy Rider.'' Couple of guys on dope go around on
motorcycles and, all too briefly, meet Jack Nicholson. It
supposedly spoke eloquently to alienated youth of the 1960s, but so
did ``The Graduate,'' which makes the list as No. 7. How much
eloquent speech does alienated youth deserve now that it's moved on
to disillusioned middle age?
</P>
<P>
   No ``Dracula''! How can we take this list seriously?
</P>
<P>
   Especially when there is no Edward G. Robinson either. We get
two ``Godfathers'' (Brando version plus Part II with De Niro), but
no gangsters at all from the Warner Brothers mob, which included
Robinson, James Cagney and Humphrey Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   The incomparable Cagney barely makes the list with ``Yankee
Doodle Dandy,'' which squeaks in as No. 100.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Little Caesar'' to ``Key Largo,'' there is enough great
gunfire from Robinson to justify consolidating the two
``Godfathers'' into a single entry, thus making room for a figure
far more vital to American culture than Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here at No. 53 is ``Amadeus,'' a whimsical fiction based on
the improbable supposition that Mozart might have been murdered by
an envious colleague.
</P>
<P>
   If the voters were trying to prove that Hollywood can do
classical stuff as niftily as it does oaters and capers, it should
have passed up ``Amadeus'' in favor of Max Reinhardt's 1935 version
of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' starring such unlikely and
excellent Shakespeareans as Cagney and Mickey Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   That ``Gunga Din'' failed to make the top 100 speaks poorly
about the prominent voters. The greatest boys' adventure movies of
all time are obviously unknown to them.
</P>
<P>
   They also ignore ``The Man Who Would Be King'' and the
unsurpassable ``Prisoner of Zenda'' that starred Ronald Colman,
Madeleine Carroll, Raymond Massey and Douglas Fairbanks Jr. Nor do
they list a single one of Sean Connery's James Bond films.
</P>
<P>
   These prominent Americans must have been too busy becoming
prominent ever to have experienced the ecstasy of chewing Jujubes
while Gary Cooper was ordering his pirate's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   But you grown-ups, look at this: Goldwyn's silly 1939 version of
``Wuthering Heights'' is rated the 73rd best American film of all
time. This is the one in which Emily Bronte's monstrous Heathcliff
is turned into smoldering, beautiful, young Laurence Olivier and
ends up cavorting dead in the heather with his beloved.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the greatest Hollywood treatment ever of Victorian
fiction is completely overlooked. It is David O. Selznick's ``A
Tale of Two Cities'' with Ronald Colman mounting the guillotine and
Blanche Yurka knitting as heads roll. Just as good as Dickens, and
only half as long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
