</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCOMPANY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern sells controlling stake in U.K. utility
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Southern Co. is now the 49 percent minority owner of
South Western Electricity in Britain after selling a $170 million
stake to a Pennsylvania utility.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Southern, which bought South Western, or Sweb,
three years ago, announced Thursday it had sold 26 percent of the
utility to a subsidiary of PP&AMP;L Resources.
</P>
<P>
   PP&AMP;L already owned 25 percent. The Allentown, Pa.-based company
now owns 51 percent of Sweb, but Southern retains operational and
managerial control.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Boren, president of Southern Energy Inc., the Southern
subsidiary that operates Sweb, said the transaction is part of the
company's practice of ``seeking strong business partners in our
international investments.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale means the loss of $15 million to $20 million in annual
profits for Southern, Boren said. But there will be ``no real
impact'' on Southern's financial results because the proceeds would
go toward other investments, such as the pending acquisition of a
network of New England power plants for $537 million, Boren said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any portfolio,'' he said, ``we're constantly mixing our
assets.'' Southern acquired Bristol, England-based Sweb in
September 1995 for $1.8 billion. It was the first in a series of
high-profile foreign acquisitions that have since landed the
Atlanta company in Germany, China and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   It was also first in a series of investments by U.S. utilities
in Britain's power sector. Since Southern's acquisition, U.S.
electric companies have spent $20 billion on 12 British regional
electric distributors. Many are reportedly reassessing their
positions following disappointing financial results.
</P>
<P>
   But Edward Tirello, financial analyst at Bankers Trust New York,
said Southern ``has gotten all their money out'' of its investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the first ones in at the lowest price,'' Tirello
said. ``This is gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Southern's experience in Britain has not been trouble-free.
``There were definitely disappointments,'' Boren conceded.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Conservative government blocked the company's 1996
attempt to take over National Power, a major British power supplier
then valued at $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the newly elected Labor government imposed a
``windfall profits tax'' on utilities privatized by the
Conservative government. Sweb's tax was $155 million, equivalent to
two years' profits. Because Southern had just sold 25 percent of
Sweb to PP&AMP;L for $189 million, its share was $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boren said Sweb has been a major success. Southern has reduced
prices for Sweb's 1.3 million customers, cut staff, improved
customer satisfaction and reduced power outages, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern's performance record is the reason PP&AMP;L is leaving
current management in place, Boren said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McCarthy, a spokesman for the Pennsylvania company, said
PP&AMP;L didn't want to exert greater control because Sweb has been
successful under Southern.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Southern's stock closed down 25
cents Thursday at $28.06 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
