<HEADER>
A6034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS &LR;      06-18 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN FINANCE REVAMP SUFFERS SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Shays-Meehan campaign finance bill suffered a
setback Thursday when the House voted to change the rules of debate
and allow consideration of 258 amendments during seven more weeks
of floor action.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule was adopted 221-189 on a party-line vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This rule is an outrage,'' said Representative Martin T.
Meehan, the Massachusetts Democrat and co-sponsor of the bill that
would outlaw ``soft money,'' the unregulated contributions
collected by political committees. ``We've got to keep going but
this makes it difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, the Massachusetts Democrat, said:
``This would kill an ordinary bill, but this has enough public
support and legs. They think they are killing it, but this will
ultimately pass the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Shays, the Connecticut Republican and
co-sponsor of the bill, joined other Republican moderates in
agreeing to the new rule. He consented after House leaders pledged
to complete work on the legislation by the August recess, said
Shays spokesman Seth Amglott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the moderate Republican three-step,'' said Frank, who was
acting as an adviser on parliamentary questions for supporters of
the campaign finance bill. ``Ineffectual protest, followed by
abject surrender, followed by denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders argued that the campaign finance issue
deserved ``a full and open debate'' and proposed allowing
amendments not directly related to campaign finance. House Speaker
Newt Gingrich and his leadership team strongly oppose the
Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   The 258 amendments to be considered for this single issue is
more than the total number of amendments approved for debate by the
House Rules Committee in the past 11/2 years, said lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Representative J. Joseph Moakley of Massachusetets, the top
Democrat on the Rules Committee, said he had never seen so many
amendments allowed for one bill. ``Maybe under Boss Tweed, but not
in my lifetime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was at odds with the usual practice of limiting
debate and amendments since Republicans gained control of the House
in January 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the tactic was aimed at killing the Shays-Meehan
bill through ``death by amendment.'' They said the addition of new
provisions to the bill eventually would make it impossible to pass.
House minority leader Richard Gephardt said the change in the rules
for debate and amendments was a scheme aimed at ``talking the bill
to death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to delay this process so that this bill cannot
become law this year,'' said Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   Representative John Linder of Georgia, chairman of the National
Republican Campaign Committee, said changing the current campaign
laws is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need a massive overhaul of our campaign
finance laws,'' said Linder. ``Let's enforce the current law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meehan said, ``It is an attempt, and no one is fooled by
this blatant attempt, to drown the Shays-Meehan bill with frivolous
amendments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
