<P>
   CONGRESS-MISSILE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
mounts its most detailed defense of its satellite export control
policy, as top officials say that China's military has not
benefited from transfers of sensitive U.S. technology and
safeguards are in place to prevent leakage. By Eric Schmitt.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SUITS (New York) _ For months, cigarette industry
executives have said they would rather fight every lawsuit filed
against them than support federal legislation, but now with the
defeat of the bill, they are likely to get plenty of practice.
Today, over 800 lawsuits are pending against tobacco companies. For
cigarette makers, the rapidly-accelerating rate of lawsuit filing
is also producing a high-speed game of legal Russian Roulette. And
with ever courtroom wound suffered by the industry, such as a
recent verdict in Florida, more lawsuits are likely to come. By
Barry Meier. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ASSESS (Tokyo) _ News Analysis: In a few weeks, Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto will face nationwide elections as he
presides over the worst recession in more than half a century, a
limp stock market and the highest unemployment rate since records
began to be kept. Yet his governing Liberal Democratic Party is
overwhelmingly expected to do very well. The latest polls show it
with more than five times as much support as any other political
party in Japan. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-EMERGENCY-PLAN (New York) _ New York City, long viewed as one
of the world's most vulnerable places to terrorist attack, has
quietly undertaken an ambitious effort to foil strikes with deadly
germs or chemicals, according to city officials. (Eds.: This story
has already moved, but those papers that did not use it should use
the version moving tonight. Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file)
</P>
<P>
   reefer: ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The government releases trade
statistics showing that the U.S. economy is taking a bigger knock
from Asia's financial crisis than expected. By Richard W.
Stevenson. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MIDDLECLASS (Beijing) _ Like a phoenix rising from the
ashes of communism, the last few years have seen the a stunning
growth of a flourishing Chinese middle class. Ten years ago, this
group did not even exist. Today its core of independent businessmen
has been joined by a growing number of private-sector lawyers,
artists and employees of joint-venture companies. It is first
defined by what its members have: computers, microwaves, interior
decorators and increasingly, cars and homes. But the rapid
accumulation of material things has left its psychological mark as
well, infusing this group with a kind of independence, and carefree
optimism, that has not existed in China for decades. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With photo and
graphic. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   Inside story: CHINA-HOUSING.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-INFOSEEK (Undated) _ Walt Disney Co. has become the
latest media giant to enter into a partnership with an Internet
``portal'' company in order to compete with America Online.
Extending the borders of the Magic Kingdom well into cyberspace,
Walt Disney Co. agrees to buy what will turn into a controlling
interest in Infoseek, a popular Internet service that helps users
find what they are looking for on the World Wide Web. By Saul
Hansell. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ After taking losses in
their fight with the Yugoslav military and bolstered by a huge
infusion of weapons and fighters from Albania, separatist rebels in
Kosovo Province have begun to hit back in recent days. By Chris
Hedges. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) With map. 1,100
words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CENTENNIAL-FESTIVAL (New York) _ New York's music is the
world's music, the sound of every group to arrive since the Dutch
were met by the Indians. To commemorate the centennial of the
annexation of Brooklyn and the consolidation of the five boroughs
into one city, the musical celebration will be as varied, scattered
and unpredictable as the city itself. By Jon Pareles. (The story
has moved in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
