<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKEZONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING THE STRIKE ZONE A MAJOR-LEAGUE MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers pitching coach Dick Bosman teaches
pitchers to throw nothing but strikes. Hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo
emphasizes that hitters should swing at nothing but strikes.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is a strike?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard to quantify,'' Bosman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every umpire is different,'' Jaramillo said. ``I don't know
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   So what do you tell hitters?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just swing at strikes,'' Jaramillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Something you can handle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jaramillo, who watched as the Rangers accumulated the
second-most walks in the league through Tuesday, isn't the only one
who is mystified. Just exactly what constitutes the strike zone
remains a mystery in the major leagues. Manager Johnny Oates
fiercely debated that point yesterday with plate umpire Ted Barrett
and was ejected for arguing balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Official Baseball Rules define the strike zone as ``that
area over home plate the upper limit of which is a horizontal line
at the midpoint between the top of the shoulders and the top of the
uniform pants, and the lower level is a line at the hollow beneath
the knee cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Another common definition of the upper limit is the ``letters''
of a major-league uniform, meaning the team name across the chest.
But it's generally accepted in the major leagues that any pitch
above the waist is likely to be called a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that would be a high ball,'' outfielder Rusty
Greer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To think the strike zone is at the letters is absurd,''
pitcher John Wetteland said. ``As long as I've been playing
baseball, it's never been that way.''
</P>
<P>
   There should be no doubt about the width of the strike zone but,
as Rangers catcher Bill Haselman said, ``Umpires are pretty
consistent, but some might give the corners more than others.''
</P>
<P>
   A common myth in baseball says the strike zone is higher in the
American League. But John Burkett, who pitched seven seasons in the
National League, said, ``I don't see a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   American League umpire Jim McKean said there was a disparity 20
years ago when AL umpires wore balloon chest protectors outside
their uniforms. ``But it hasn't been the way for a long time,''
McKean said. ``It's the same in both leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual umpires do have different strike zones. In the AL,
John Hirschbeck and Durwood Merrill have a reputation for large
strike zones, while Terry Craft and Al Clark are considered the
toughest on pitchers. One veteran umpire watcher said John Shulock
and Tim Tschida are the best at calling balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's human nature,'' Burkett said. ``If you're sitting
on the bench, there will be one guy who says that pitch was a
strike, and another guy who says no, it was a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Ted Williams used to study umpire tendencies. It
was his belief that taller umpires called more high strikes and
shorter umpires had a lower strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I know what an umpire's strike zone is, I'm fine
with anything anybody wants it to be,'' Wetteland said. ``Different
umpires have different zones, but that's fine as long as they're
consistent. That's all anybody asks of us, it's just fair to ask
them to be consistent too. No one is perfect. Everybody knows I'm
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Another perception is that younger umpires have larger strike
zones, a reputation enhanced when rookie umpire Ed Bean was behind
the plate for Kenny Rogers' perfect game. However, it remains
difficult to get any pitch above the waist called a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, umpires will give a pitcher a little more outside and
take away balls that are up,'' Burkett said.
</P>
<P>
   But any pitcher throwing above the waist without Wetteland's
fastball is asking for serious trouble, whether it's a ball or a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a successful pitcher, most guys have got to pitch
down,'' Burkett said. ``If I throw a ball thigh-high, I'm going to
get killed. I'm in the love zone. I have to be around the knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer said he shudders at the thought of a 95-mph fastball at
the chest being called a strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to hit a 95-mile-an-hour heater at the letters,''
Greer said. ``I know because I've tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Bosman said the best way to get a generous strike zone from an
umpire is to throw strikes. As Bobby Witt learned early in his
career, hard-throwing pitchers who can't get near the strike zone
get no benefit of the doubt when they occasionally find the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitcher that pitches around the plate gets more pitches
swung at and gets more pitches called,'' Bosman said. ``It's part
of the penalties and rewards of pitching. If you get ahead in the
count, you get to use more of your repertoire and get a bigger
strike zone. If you get behind in the count, you have to use less
of your repertoire and get less of a strike zone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
