<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WAGES-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITAIN MOVES TO ESTABLISH NATIONAL MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Saying it wanted to end ``the scandal of poverty pay,''
the Labor government announced plans Thursday to establish a
national minimum wage for the first time in British history.
</P>
<P>
   The wage the government has set _ about $6 an hour for adults _
is not as high as union leaders had hoped. But in a country whose
once-powerful unions were all but emasculated by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher in the 1980s, the plan was seen as an important
victory for workers' rights. It will take effect next April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard fought over many years,'' said a spokeswoman
for Unison, the country's largest union, which represents some 1.3
million workers in various professions. ``It seems unbelievable
that it should have taken this length of time to get what is a
fundamental right for workers so they do have some minimum level of
protection against being exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the plan, Board of Trade president Margaret
Beckett said the gap between lowest- and highest-paid workers had
almost doubled in the last two decades. She accused the previous
government of abandoning the working poor to the whims of stingy
employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Britain aimed to be the cheapest rather than the best _ no
longer the workshop of the world, but the sweatshop of Western
Europe,'' she told the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, workers aged 22 and older will receive a minimum
of about $6 an hour. Those from 18 to 21 will receive a lower rate,
of about $5 an hour, which will increase to about $5.35 in June
2000. The minimum wage will not apply to younger people or to those
on apprenticeships.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, the government said, will increase the wages of some 2
million people who currently earn less than the proposed minimum,
some of whom are working for less than $1.50 an hour.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It will help remove the worst cases of exploitation in our
workplace, cases which have no place in modern Britain,'' Mrs.
Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Conservative Party, which has pressed for a
minimum income level, with pay subsidized by benefits, rather than
a minimum wage, attacked the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We left this government with a golden economic legacy,'' said
John Redwood, the Conservatives' spokesman on trade issues. ``Today
the government is doing its best to destroy it.''
</P>
<P>
   But industry groups said they felt that they could live with the
new plan. ``Any higher, and we would be moving into more dangerous
territory,'' said Adair Turner, director general of the
Confederation of British Industry, adding that he did not expect
the new wage to lead to major job losses or to exert too much
inflationary pressure on the economy. ``The level announced today
allows for a reasonable and workable way forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Labor government came into power last year, it has
been examining ways of putting a minimum wage in place. But the
question of what the rate would actually be has been the subject of
bitter debate.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Low Pay Commission, set up by the government
to study the issue, recommended that the rate be set at about $6 an
hour, the rate the government has adopted. But union
representatives have pushed for about $7.70 an hour, roughly half
of the median salary for men in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Unison general secretary Rodney Bickerstaffe said the new wage
``should be seen as a starting block, not a finishing line.'' The
union, he said, ``will continue to fight not just for a minimum,
but for a decent minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Unions have also bitterly opposed the two-tier system under
which younger workers will be subject to a lower minimum wage than
will people over 21. ``Young workers should not be singled out for
second-class treatment,'' Bickerstaffe said. ``Show me the
supermarket which gives discounts to young people or the landlord
who reduces the rent. It's unfair, and we will continue to press
for the rate for the job.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Beckett said the lower rate was necessary to keep young
people working and to encourage employers to train them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
