<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CABINET-HNS &LR;      06-18 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CABINET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NAMES RICHARDSON TO ENERGY, HOLBROOKE TO U.N. 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday named United Nations
Ambassador Bill Richardson as his choice for energy secretary and
tapped veteran diplomat Richard Holbrooke for the U.N. post.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his foreign policy team in the Rose Garden, the
president also called on Congress to pass legislation paying the
more than $1 billion the United States owes the United Nations in
back dues. The bill is stalled because conservatives insist on
including anti-abortion language in the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have worked closely together to make sure that our nation
remains the world's leading force for peace and freedom, for
prosperity and security,'' Clinton said. ``The lineup I announced
today maintains that exceptional standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate must confirm the selections.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 50, a former New Mexico congressman who gained a
reputation as an international trouble-shooter prior to being the
U.N. ambassador, will become the highest ranking Hispanic in the
administration. He replaces Federico Pena who served as
transportation secretary and most recently as energy secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued to signal his emphasis on clean energy
alternatives as he emphasized the issue of climate change in
announcing Richardson's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Congress' support, Bill Richardson will do his part now
to secure our energy future at a time when that is inextricably
bound up with our obligation as Americans to do our part to deal
with the problem of climate change and our obligations . . . to
build a security future for our country that allows economic growth
and protection of the planet,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson thanked Clinton for ``being the most prolific
appointer of Latinos of any American president. Your leadership in
this area is unquestioned.'' Richardson said the Energy Department
must also ``continue its leadership on energy issues because a
healthy energy sector is a critical element of a vibrant and
growing U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson pledged a ``safe and reliable'' nuclear stockpile to
support administration efforts to secure passage of the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and a continued emphasis on
cleaning up the environmental hazards created by the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also made a pitch for the United Nations, calling it
``good for America and good for the world.'' The international
organization, he said, advanced U.S. interests in regard to Iraq,
Kosovo, emerging democracies and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, 57, brokered the 1995 Dayton Accord that brought a
restless peace to Bosnia after four years of civil war and most
recently worked on quieting the issue of Cyprus that has long
divided Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ongoing service in the Balkan region has helped to keep
Bosnia's peace on track through some difficult moments. He has
helped advance our efforts to break the stalemate in Cyprus and he
has worked to defuse the alarming tensions and violence still
brewing in Kosovo,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Holbrooke will help fashion a United Nations
``that is leaner, more efficient, better equipped, that fulfills
the best ideals of its founders and meets the challenges of the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, his voice wavering, recalled his father taking him to
see the newly built U.N. buildings as an 8-year-old and telling him
they would become the most important in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father did not live to see how his dream for the U.N.
dissolved in the face of the harsh realities of the Cold War and
the inadequacies of the U.N. system itself. But I never forgot the
initial visit and my father's noble, if openly idealistic, dream.
Despite its many problems and failures, I still believe in the
importance, indeed the necessity, of the United Nations,''
Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the announcements to again pressure Congress to
pass the U.N. debt measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a world where developments beyond our borders have dramatic
implications within them _ from rogue states seeking nuclear
weapons and chemical and biological weapons, to pollution corroding
the atmosphere _ international cooperation is more important than
ever,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Congress to approve the legislation ``without
unrelated issues,'' a reference to the anti-abortion provision, so
the United States can ``live up to our legacy of leadership and pay
our debt to the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
