<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-RETURNS-BOS &LR;      06-18 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-RETURNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODWARD, ON HOME SOIL, SAYS US JUDICIAL SYSTEM FAULTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE AND PEGGY HERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, England _ For two years, the loudest voices in the
Louise Woodward saga have belonged to lawyers, judges, the media
and her supporters in her hometown of Elton who chanted, ``Free
Louise!''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after Woodward arrived back in England a convicted
felon, the disillusioned vocals fell &UR;  &LR; silent, and she spoke up for
herself: loudly, boldly and defensively.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear voice tinged with an American accent, Woodward
proclaimed her innocence in the death of Matthew Eappen, blamed a
flawed US justice system for her fate and insisted she has not sold
her story to the British press.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward &UR;  &LR; then made it clear: She was not to blame for the
child's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorrow for the death of baby Matthew,'' she said in a
brief press conference at the Manchester Airport. ``But like I said
time and time again, I had nothing to do with his death. I did not
hurt Matthew and I did not kill baby Matthew.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was asked if she had a message for the child's parents,
Sunil and Deborah Eappen, who filed a wrongful death lawsuit
against her earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't,'' Woodward replied.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time the 20-year-old au pair has spoken
publicly since she was found guilty of manslaughter in the death of
Matthew, the 8-month-old infant who died in her care in February
1997.
</P>
<P>
   After the brief press conference, Woodward and her family
returned to a remarkably subdued reception in Elton.
</P>
<P>
   Though yellow ribbons hung from trees and fence posts and one
sign proclaimed, ``Welcome Home Louise,'' no champagne receptions
greeted her. Reporters, not residents, were the only people
watching as her car passed through the middle of town to her home.
</P>
<P>
   And The Rigger, a pub now famous as headquarters of the Free
Louise campaign, was dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows a very deep respect that people stayed
away,'' said Christine Gray, a member of the local Woodward support
group. ``Everyone is celebrating her arrival behind closed doors
... people just wanted to sit and reflect on it themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The press conference and the drive home to Elton ended nearly
four days of pandemonium for Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the SJC upheld her manslaughter conviction but
refused to order a new sentence, freeing Woodward to leave Boston
for England. The next day, she caught a first-class seat on a
British Airways overnight flight.
</P>
<P>
   Though several reporters accompanied Woodward on the plane to
London's Heathrow Airport, bodyguards _ including a Massachusetts
state trooper in full uniform paid by the airline _ barred anyone
from getting close to her or her father.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a British cameraman apparently walked by
Woodward's seat and her father jumped up yelling, ``Leave my
daughter alone!''
</P>
<P>
   The first-class tickets, worth $4,200 each, were donated by a
benefactor who wished to remain anonymous, according to Andrew
Miller, the local Member of Parliament for Woodward's home district
of Cheshire. Miller, who organized the press conference at the
Manchester airport, maintained the tickets were not paid for by a
media organization.
</P>
<P>
   When the Woodwards arrived in London, a pack of British and
American reporters and cameramen trampled each other to get as
close as possible to the somber-looking father and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Though they were to fly from London to Manchester in a smaller
jet, British Airways told Woodward and her father that they could
not guarantee security from reporters on the plane. As a result,
Miller drove the Woodwards 200 miles north to Manchester Airport
for the press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to more than 100 reporters and photographers, Woodward
said she hopes that since all of her legal appeals have been
exhausted, the ``medical community'' will take up her case, review
the physical evidence of Matthew's death and help exonerate her. On
Tuesday, her lawyers, Harvey Silverglate and Andrew Good, said
evidence would be turned over to independant panel of experts to
prove Woodward's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she wants to ``educate people'' about shaken-baby
syndrome to ``hopefully prevent mistakes being made and rush to
judgment like what happened in my case.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward also insisted she did not get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   She blamed ``atrocious'' pre-trial publicity for a ``tainted
jury pool,'' and said politics influenced Middlesex prosecutor
Thomas Reilly's decision to try her for first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I'm upset about the conviction,'' she said. ``It's a
conviction I don't deserve, but I think in time the truth will come
out, in time I will be cleared.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the press conference, Woodward said she plans to
go to college and ``do what any normal 20-year-old would like to
do.'' But she also said her ordeal had changed her and that she's
learned a lot _ ``too much about American law.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward said she has agreed to an exclusive interview with the
BBC. The network later confirmed Woodward will talk with Martin
Bashir, the reporter who conducted the only television interview
with the late Diana, Princess of Wales. An air date for the
program, ``Panorama'' had not been set Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by phone in Chicago, Deborah Eappen's brother, Paul
Spellman, critized Woodward for failing to acknowlege his sister
and brother-in-law during the press conference, and said the family
is offended that she still won't acknowlege her responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unbelievable what she said; it's all hocus-pocus,''
Spellman said.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Elton, Woodward was escorted by local police to her
front door. She bounded out of a chauffered minibus and hugged her
sister Vicky. Cassie, the family's German shepherd, joined in the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodward family then posed for photographers on their front
stoop under rainy and gray skies, then disappeared into the house.
Later, Woodward withdrew to the bedroom she kept as a teenager,
filled with stuffed animals and lined with posters of British rock
groups Pulp and Pet Shop Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's arrival home was greeted with near and deliberate
silence from residents. Few villagers were on the street as
Woodward's calvacade drove by.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they are still embarrassed by images of supporters
quaffing champagne and singing soccer victory songs after
Woodward's conviction was reduced to manslaughter six months ago.
Others said they have become disillusioned after allegations that
the Woodwards misused money in their defense fund, and reports that
one of Woodward's lawyers, under arrest for drunken driving,
blurted out that she had come to believe her client was guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a party situation,'' said Sandra McCabe, a family
friend who said she plans to visit the family Friday. ``Matthew is
still dead and Louise is still convicted of his death.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff reporter Jordana Hart contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
