u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-POLL-HNS &LR;      06-18 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERRY, SHARP TIED FOR LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR'S RACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Republican Rick Perry and Democrat John Sharp are
virtually tied in their race for lieutenant governor with a third
of the likely voters undecided, the Texas Poll indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans lead all the other campaigns for statewide executive
offices, the poll showed, except for the attorney general's race,
where Democrat Jim Mattox is trying to reclaim the post he held for
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox has a 9-point lead over Republican John Cornyn, a former
Texas Supreme Court justice, with 18 percent of voters undecided.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 691 likely voters was conducted June 1-12 by
Scripps Howard and the Office of Survey Research at the University
of Texas. It did not include judicial races.
</P>
<P>
   In modern times, Republicans have never held the posts of
lieutenant governor, attorney general, comptroller or land
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, the current state agriculture commissioner, leads Sharp,
the state comptroller, 35 percent to 31 percent, in the race to
succeed Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who is retiring in January.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is virtually within the poll's margin of error of
3.7 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two percent of the respondents were undecided on the next
lieutenant governor, while 2 percent liked neither candidate or
didn't respond.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's support was identical to the 35 percent he received in a
Texas Poll conducted in March, but Sharp dropped 10 percentage
points from his March showing. The level of undecided voters,
meanwhile, increased from 19 percent to 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharp campaign said the survey undercounted Democratic
voters. A Perry spokesman said Sharp's support was ``plummeting''
because the Democratic nominee ``lacks issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin political analyst George Christian said Republican
candidates were benefiting from Gov. George W. Bush's popularity at
the top of the GOP ticket. Bush has a 53-point lead over Democratic
challenger Garry Mauro, according to the same poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``The massive Bush lead is having an influence on all this. It's
giving the whole election a Republican veneer,'' Christian said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party Chairman Bill White disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox's lead of 44 percent to 35 percent over Cornyn, White
said, ``shows that Bush has no coattails.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian said Mattox, who won two races for attorney general in
the 1980s and ran unsuccessfully for governor and U.S. senator
since then, led partly because he is better known than Cornyn.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also indicates that:
</P>
<P>
   1) Republican Carole Keeton Rylander, a Texas Railroad
commissioner, leads Democrat Paul Hobby, a Houston businessman, by
38 percent to 26 percent in the race for state comptroller.
Thirty-five percent of respondents are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   2) Republican David Dewhurst, a Houston businessman, is backed
by 37 percent of likely voters in the land commissioner's race.
Twenty-four percent favor state Rep. Richard Raymond of Benavides,
the Democratic nominee. Thirty-eight percent are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   3) Former Secretary of State Tony Garza, the Republican nominee,
leads Democrat Joe B. Henderson, 43 percent to 23 percent, for the
Texas Railroad Commission, with 33 percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   4) Former state Rep. Susan Combs of Austin, the Republican
nominee for agriculture commissioner, leads state Rep. Pete
Patterson of Brookston, the Democratic candidate, 39 percent to 27
percent with 33 percent are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In the lieutenant governor's race, Perry spokesman Ray Sullivan
said the Republican nominee still had to overcome Sharp's higher
name identification with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said voters' familiarity with Sharp was one reason that
the number of undecided voters, rather than Perry's poll numbers,
had risen while Sharp's had fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharp is still better known than Rick, and that will remain
the case until we go on TV,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp spokesman Kelly Fero said Perry's ``slim margin in
this poll is due exclusively to the fact that they polled more
Republicans than Democrats this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the March poll sample and the current poll sample included
31 percent Republicans, poll director Ty Meighan said. But the
share of Democratic respondents dropped from 34 percent in March to
25 percent in this survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news for Sharp is that he has a commanding lead among
independent voters,'' Fero said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas Poll, Sharp, who has been trying to
distance his campaign from that of Mauro, the Democratic
gubernatorial nominee, is favored by 30 percent of independent
voters, who are key to statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four percent of independents favor Perry, and 43 percent
are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox said he was ``delighted'' with the poll results in the
attorney general's race. He said Texans ``trust me as an
experienced leader who will make decisions based not on politics,
but what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said Mattox's lead was ``purely a matter of name
identification.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, we're going in one direction, and that's
up. I'm pleased that things are this close at this point,'' Cornyn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox leads Cornyn, 45 percent to 29 percent, among independent
voters, with 25 percent of independents undecided on the attorney
general's race.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox also had stronger support among Democratic voters, 78
percent, than Cornyn showed among Republican voters, 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, Rylander's son and campaign manager, said the
survey shows the Republican candidate for comptroller has a
``common sense, conservative record of achievement and a clear
vision for the future of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Justus, a spokeswoman for Democratic nominee Hobby, son
of former Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby, said undecided voters will ``embrace
Paul's fresh business approach'' to government.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, who is trying to become the first Hispanic Republican
elected to statewide office in Texas, has a 48 percent to 31
percent lead over Henderson among Hispanic voters and a 43 percent
to 21 percent lead among Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has a narrow, 31 percent to 29 percent, edge among
black voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2003EDT &QL; 
