<SLUG> BC-MA-FATHERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER FATHERS IN MASSACHUSETTS HOMES, AGENCY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nearly three out of every 10 households with children
in Massachusetts have no father in the home, according to a report
released Thursday by the Massachusetts Family Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a historically high level in this state,'' said
Matthew E. Daniels, president of the institute and author of the
report. ``We want people to recognize things are getting worse, not
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In its second annual report on Massachusetts families, the
institute estimated that 29 percent of families had no fathers
living with them in 1997, up 2 percent since 1995 and almost
quadruple the percentage in 1960. &UR;  &LR; The estimates were generated for
the institute by the Massachusetts Institute for Social and
Economic Research in Amherst using US Census data. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  In 1990, 20 percent of families in Massachusetts were headed
by single parents, according to the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said the continuing decline of two-parent families has
social costs, including higher rates of crime, child poverty,
welfare dependency, and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce fatherlessness, the institute advocated tax relief for
families, better child support enforcement, toughening penalties
for statutory rape, battling gambling addiction, and making it
easier for married couples to adopt children. The institute
describes itself as ``dedicated to strengthening families in
Massachusetts and restoring Judeo-Christian values to our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Jetta Bernier, executive director of the Massachusetts Committee
for Children and Youth, said the issue of fatherlessness resonates
with many child and family advocacy groups, liberal and
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, lack of education and job training, and the
failure of wages to keep pace with inflation, have made it
difficult for low-income men to form stable, strong relationships
with their children and their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, the work of the (institute) appears to be useful,''
said Bernier. ``They are clearly identifying some public policy
issues. But it is simply not enough for us to be blaming fathers,
particularly if we are not addressing the economic difficulties
they face to family formation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
