A6120 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-18 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; AVOIDING SUMMER'S STICKY SEAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; D &UR; on Radke &LR; , former president of a Wisconsin nudist club that
holds an annual summer car show, discusses in the latest issue of
Esquire how a nudist avoids sticking to the car seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``As any well-versed nudist will tell you,'' says Radke, ``one
never sits on a seat not covered by one's personal sitting-on
fabric, a.k.a. a towel. However, if sitting on vinyl brings
pleasure to your life, then a good oily sunscreen will prevent
sticking. But then again, sudden stops or sharp turns could
dislodge you from your driving position.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Radke's other tips for nudist drivers: ``Keep a lot of
change in the ashtray to facilitate the use of automatic lanes at
toll stops.'' Eschew wood-bead seat covers: ``The dimples are
unsightly and they itch.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; _  &UR; Stephen Solari &LR;  had a fine welcome home last Friday when he
tried to find his car at long-term parking at San Francisco Airport
and discovered that all the numerical designations on bus stops had
been switched. ``One was three, four was two, and so on,'' he says.
``Shouldn't the airport commission be restricted to pulling
practical jokes on tourists?''
</P>
<P>
   Airport spokesman  &UR; Ron Wilson &LR;  said the changes, a ``necessary
evil,'' were due to construction. ``Things change daily. There are
times when I get lost on the way to work, and I've been here 40
years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The nonprofit Peaceful Streets is holding a Father's Day Gun
Bake in Washington Square from 1 to 4 p.m. Sunday in which four
assault rifles will be pounded by blacksmiths into works of art,
then placed on doors to be painted by volunteers into a community
mural. This action-packed event also includes drumming, a favored
Father's Day activity for non-golfers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Down at Pier 17,  &UR; Dennis Conner &LR; , once described in the San
Francisco Chronicle as ``an overtly sexist sailing giant,'' is
building America's True, which will be the first boat to enter the
America's Cup races with a coed crew. MacArthur Park restaurant on
nearby Front Street is holding a fund-raiser for the project  &LR; June
25. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Browsing through the art books at Green Apple on Clement
Street,  &UR; Mark Glaser &LR;  came upon ``The Making of SFMOMA,'' addressed
to  &UR; Brooks Walker Jr. &LR;  and inscribed by ``dozens of people''
praising Walker ``for the building and his work as chairman of the
board of trustees for the museum.'' Never mind sloppy sentiment; it
must have been a duplicate copy.
</P>
<P>
   _ American Greetings says that 30 percent of its Father's Day
cards are humorous, but only 18 percent of Mother's Day cards crack
jokes. Elsewhere on the trail of national trends, Country Home
magazine notes that the 10 most searched-for items on the Internet
Antique Shop Mall are: Depression glass, Roseville pottery,
carnival glass, Limoges china, Beanie babies (you knew they would
sneak in there, didn't you?), dolls, cookie jars, McCoy pottery,
lamps and clocks.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cabaret'' comes to San Francisco in December, as part of an
eight-city tour. One rumor has it that &UR; Anne Heche  &LR; will play Sally
Bowles. &UR;  &LR; Meanwhile, in New York,  &UR; Jennifer Jason Leigh &LR;  is going to
take over in August when  &UR; Natasha Richardson &LR; 's contract is up,
reports People.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEMPELSMAN'S TREASURES ARE QUESTIONED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A judge in Sicily has concluded that antiquities bought by
 &UR; Maurice Tempelsman &LR;  _ the diamond trader who was  &UR; Jackie O &LR; 's
boyfriend _ in 1980 were looted from an archaeological dig in
Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report in the Times of London, Tempelsman paid
about $1 million for two marble heads, three feet and three hands
of statues made in 525 B.C. ``The Americans should understand,''
said the judge in his ruling last week. ``It's as if an Italian
collector had in his hands important documents that belonged to
George Washington, or Thomas Jefferson's manuscript copy of the
Declaration of Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times said that authorities are considering taking legal
action to get the sculptures back. Tempelsman's spokesman,  &UR; Gus &LR; 
 &UR; Weill &LR; , said that there was no evidence ``that they have anything
to do with things stolen in Italy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
