</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The wonderful world of `Mulan'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Let's not mince words. ``Mulan'' is the best Disney
animated feature since ``Beauty and the Beast'' or ``The Lion
King.''
</P>
<P>
   A quantum leap beyond the labored pretentiousness of ``The
Hunchback of Notre Dame'' or the self-conscious chic of
``Hercules,'' Disney's 36th full-length animated movie is far more
than a grand family film. It's a grand film, period.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a Chinese legend that dates to the fourth century,
``Mulan,'' opening today, is a timeless tale of individualism,
courage, brains-over-brawn and love between fathers and daughters.
Our heroine (voice by Ming-Na Wen, sung by Lea Salonga) doesn't fit
in with Chinese culture's expectations of a proper young lady;
namely, that the only way a daughter can honor her family is by
making a good marriage. Impetuous, curious and a tad rebellious,
Mulan makes a mess of her matchmaking session. She has the
requisite tiny waist, but she's not very good at the calm and
obedient part.
</P>
<P>
   Fate intervenes when the neighboring Huns invade. The emperor
(Pat Morita) decrees that every family must send one male to the
country's defense. Mulan's father, a war hero, is willing but
hardly able. He's elderly and infirm. So she pulls a National
Velvet _ cuts her hair, dresses like a guy and reports for duty.
</P>
<P>
   But now she's in double jeopardy. Not only could she be killed,
but if her disguise is discovered, the law mandates that she be
executed by her commanding officer, who just happens to be an
inviting young hunk named Shang (B.D. Wong/Donny Osmond).
</P>
<P>
   Good thing her ancestral spirits have sent along some
protection. Well, not protection so much as a disgraced little red
dragon named Mushu (Eddie Murphy), trying to prove himself worthy
of said spirits.
</P>
<P>
   The story and characters are irresistible. Mulan differs from
earlier Disney heroines like Ariel (``The Little Mermaid'') and
Belle (``Beauty and the Beast''). She's not dreamy/spunky; she's
more fast-talking and quick-witted. Her foray into a male domain is
less to prove anything than it is to save her father. She's not
trying to win medals or be a role model; she just wants to pass.
And Murphy, handed the comic sidekick role, is a glorious surprise.
He's as funky and funny as Robin Williams was as the genie in
``Aladdin.'' When Mulan heads off into combat, he nearly swoons
with pride: ``My little baby off to destroy people!''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a terrific story and great characters, the look
of ``Mulan'' is astonishing. It's completely unlike any previous
Disney effort. On one hand, there's the exquisite delicacy of a
falling cherry blossom; on the other, there's the thundering
excitement of the invading horde. The basic-training segments are
as slapstick silly as an old World War II comedy, and there's a
touch of Looney Tunes throughout (Mushu's double takes are worthy
of Daffy Duck). Yet there's also the Great Wall of China and the
Forbidden City, as awe-inspiring as outtakes from ``The Last
Emperor.'' And just look at the animated horses. The Chinese steeds
look like they're right off a silk screen or some ancient Chinese
porcelain. The enemies' mounts are much like the Mongolian ponies
that still roam the steppes.
</P>
<P>
   The score may be more witty than memorable, but it's a plus. So
are the film's enduring themes: girl power, special father-daughter
bonds, how ``being a man'' is more than just handling a sword.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulan'' is one of those small miracles the movies bring us
every once in a while. Don't miss it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
