<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6144 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTIMATE-COX     06-18 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTIMATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salacious goings-on amid teacupsBy Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I think you'll find us very generous,'' says Marjorie Beasley
(Julie Walters) as she welcomes new lodger Harold Guppy (Rupert
Graves) to her home in ``Intimate Relations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Generous'' is an understatement. Before long, Harold is
sharing bed and board, literally, with his sexually voracious
landlady. On the surface, Marjorie is an average middle-class
British housewife, circa 1954, busy with her sewing, her cups of
cocoa and her 13-year-old daughter, Joyce (Laura Sadler).
</P>
<P>
   But it's no wonder that the aptly named Guppy is soon hooked.
He's got all the comforts of home plus regular sex and some very
nice gifts. Things get more complicated, however, when Joyce
demands her share of the action. Their not-quite menage a trois
becomes a fertile breeding ground for sexual tension, blackmail,
jealousy and worse.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely based on a true story, ``Intimate Relations'' has been
crisply directed by newcomer Philip Goodhew. Unfortunately, he also
wrote the script, and here he runs into trouble. After a jaunty
beginning, the film turns increasingly bleak. Or rather, events do.
</P>
<P>
   Goodhew, however, remains true to his isn't-this-a-goof tone.
Unlike ``Heavenly Creatures'' or ``The Young Poisoner's
Handbook,''' similarly themed but far more successful films,
``Intimate Relations'' seems either uninterested in or incapable of
getting inside its characters' twisted heads.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Walters remains a formidable actress. Her deceptively
matronly Marjorie could whip Glenn Close's ``Fatal Attraction''
fanatic without looking up from her teakettle. But even she can't
save a movie that wears awfully thin without ever deciding what
it's about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
