<P>
   IRAN-GAME _ TEHRAN, Iran _ World Cup fever is here. Live
coverage of reaction to the U.S. vs. Iran World Cup game being
played in France on Sunday, June 21. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Both moving Sunday in both the (i) International and (s)
Sports categories for use Monday, June 22.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AWAITS _ SHANGHAI _ China's movers and shakers will
activate a global re-education campaign when President Bill Clinton
reaches the country on Thursday with an entourage expected here to
number from 1,000 to 3,000 aides, congressmen, journalists,
industrialists and think-tankers. ``The images of China in the
United States are not yet adequate,'' said Zhou Mingwei, director
general of Shanghai's foreign affairs department, a branch of the
Chinese foreign ministry. ``This is the most important opportunity
at this moment, at the end of this century and the beginning of the
new century, for America to have a better idea about China.'' Image
_ that was the word most-repeated by a range of Chinese interviewed
about the importance to their country of Clinton's unprecedented
eight-day visit. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-HISTBOX _ BEIJING _ A box on the earlier American
presidential visits to China and what they produced _ Nixon, Bush.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Tuesday, June 16, for use Sunday, June 21.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POWER _ HONG KONG _ The company that has called itself the
``900 pound gorilla'' of American electric utilities is finding
Asia a cruel and trackless jungle. Thorns in the form of generator
glitches continue to torment the reliability of Southern Company's
giant Shajiao C power plant here in China's booming southern
industrial strip. Elsewhere throughout the continent, nettles from
the Asian financial crisis have stung the prospects of four of the
five largest future power projects that Southern took on when it
bought control of its Asian subsidiary two years ago.
(Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-POWER-SIDE _ GUANGDONG PROVINCE, China _ ``The people
who run power plants are exactly alike all over the world,'' says
Jim Webber, a 39-year Southern Company veteran who left retirement
to help knock the kinks out of Southern's first power plant in
China. ``I can walk into any plant in the world. I know the
equipment. And if I know a guy's position in the plant, I basically
know how he thinks. It's basically the way I think. This is all a
very large family, if you will. We all have the same purpose in
life, and that is to produce power.'' At 57, Webber is one of five
Southern Company engineers and technicians assigned to monitor
operations in the new Shajiao C coal-fired power plant in Guangdong
Province, about 50 miles north of Hong Kong. When Southern bought
the controlling share of Hong Kong entrepreneur Gordon Wu's Asian
power venture, it inherited a 32-percent interest in this
1,980-megawatt coal-fired power plant. So far, it is Southern's
only beachhead in China. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Tuesday, June 16 in both the (i) International and
(f) Financial categories for use Sunday, June 21.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRAVEL _ BEIJING _ If you know China, don't bother reading
this. You are already convinced that from megalopolis to
mist-shrouded mountaintop, China is an engaging place. This is
written for the couple of hundred million other Americans who may
love to knock about in bizarre places but haven't yet made it to
the Middle Kingdom. You'll find that China offers spectacular
travel _ riveting vistas, exotic cultures embracing thousands of
years, enticing food on almost every corner of every city. If the
news coverage surrounding President Clinton's trip to China June
25-July 3 intrigues you _ whether it's an aged peasant's creased
smile or the serenity of a Guilin lagoon that sinks the hook in
your wanderlust _ make a plan and go for it. In the three months
we've been living and working in China, we've managed a sampling of
some not-to-miss places. China is more tourist-friendly than ever.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With CHINA-TRAVEL-SIDE _ BEIJING _ This is the city central to
your China trip. From the chaotic alleys called hutongs to the
grace of the Forbidden City built for the emperor and his
entourage, China's capital can keep you happily occupied for five
days. After that, it gets to be work. An aimless stroll or float
across the lake in Beihai Park will put you in the company of
Chinese relaxing away an afternoon. Or try hunting down the Niujie
Mosque, where tranquil gardens date back to the 15th Century, and
the nearby Fayuansi Buddhist temple to see an ancient spiritual
dimension of modern Chinese life. Here are some recommendations
specific to Beijing touring. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Monday, June 15 in both the (i) International and (t)
Travel categories for use Sunday, June 21.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TRIP _ When he visits China later this month, virtually
everything President Clinton does _ every step he takes, every
place he goes, every bite he eats - will have been choreographed
weeks in advance by a horde of advance men and women who will have
scheduled every second of his trip. After spending hours studying
videotapes of the routes Clinton will take, Secret Service agents
will have ensured that manhole covers are sealed and air ducts
blocked to prevent potential assassins from planting bombs. His
armor-plated limousine will have been flown ahead. Hotels will have
been comandeered for the president and his entourage. Detailed
briefing books will have been prepared for him, providing
classified information on the ranking officials with whom he will
meet. Phone banks will have been put in place for the traveling
White House press. Sophisticated electronics gear will have been
installed so the media can beam images back to the United States.
In all, hundreds of advance people will have worked around the
clock and millions of tax dollars will have been spent to make sure
the whole thing goes off without a hitch. Bob recently represented
the print press corps on a trip to China with about 40 White House
advance people responsible for putting the trip together. This
would be a behind-the-scenes look at how a WH trip is staged.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ED: Moving Thursday, June 18, for use Saturday, June 20.
</P>
