   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-WASTE _ WASHINGTON _ Moving dinosaur bones to a
university museum. Building community athletic facilities. Spending
five years and $20 million to construct a 14-mile road on a remote
Alaska island. Meet the modern military at work on ``innovativeness
training.'' First envisioned by Sen. Sam Nunn in 1992, the idea was
to keep the troops busy in the post-Cold War era. But the make-work
operations have survived as an old-fashioned pork-barrel public
works program. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
