   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SIDEEE _ Guangdong Province, China _ ``The people who run power
plants are exactly alike all over the world,'' says Jim Webber, a
39-year Southern Co. veteran who left retirement to help knock the
kinks out of Atlanta-based utility giant's first power plant in
China. ``They think the same, they have the same hobbies, they are
all engineers,'' Webber said. ``China is very much like Turkey.
Turkey was very much like Italy. Italy is very much like the United
States. ``I can walk into any plant in the world. I know the
equipment. And if I know a guy's position in the plant, I basically
know how he thinks. It's basically the way I think. This is all a
very large family, if you will. We all have the same purpose in
life, and that is to produce power.'' At 57, Webber is one of five
Southern Co. engineers and technicians assigned to monitor
operations in the new Shajiao C coal-fired power plant in Guangdong
Province, about 50 miles north of Hong Kong. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox
News Service)
