<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABITAT'S RECIPIENTS, VOLUNTEERS LAUD CARTER BUILDING PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
and LISA M. CHMIOLA 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Harry Russell recalled Thursday how his relatively
simple life got complicated in 1994, when he found out he had
throat cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, his wife, Teresa, was recovering from
open-heart surgery. The bills began mounting, and still are. Harry,
69, has lost his voice and has to scribble what he wants to say on
a notepad.
</P>
<P>
   And this is what he says:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we've been given a second chance at life.''
</P>
<P>
   That chance comes from Habitat for Humanity, which is building
low-cost homes for the Russells and 99 other families this week.
About 6,000 volunteers have been working on the Jimmy Carter Work
Project, which is supposed to wrap things up Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was the fourth day of construction on the sites in
Houston's Second and Fifth Wards, and several volunteers were
excited at the progress being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``This house was a stack of lumber Monday morning,'' said
Charles A. Saunders, a retired partner of Fulbright and Jaworski
law firm, one of three firms building at one Houston site on
Broyles Street.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said each firm has helped the others at some point,
lending tools or manpower when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   However, a bit of competitive spirit carried over into
construction, said Jim Cash, a systems engineer with the Vinson and
Elkins firm. ``There is a great deal of competition. When one law
firm gets ahead of another, they are sure to point it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of these people had a high level of competition in law
school and there's a lot of demand in the office. When we get here
we keep up that level of energy,'' Cash said.
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor heat, however, tends to dampen that energy level.
``About 2 p.m., everyone starts dragging. We could really use a
midafternoon siesta,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Future homeowner Jacqueline Edmonds became overheated Tuesday
and made a 30-minute visit to the first aid trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came on me so fast I was surprised and in shock,'' Edwards
said of the headache and dizziness she experienced.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the intensity of the work took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had sore muscles Tuesday morning. When I got up and
walked down the stairs, I thought I was going to die,'' said Rick
Drosche of Baker and Botts L.L.P. law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Other minor injuries included twisted ankles, cuts and heat
rash, said the Rev. Michael Shirl, executive director of Houston
Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem encountered by volunteers was loss of work time
Monday due to excessive morning heat and evening thunderstorms.
Shirl said approximately four hours per house, or 400 hours, of
work was lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it up by bringing in lights and working until 1 or 2
in the morning (each night),'' Shirl said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russells said they are grateful for all the volunteers' hard
work. ``There is no doubt that God is in Mr. Carter and all the
people who are working hard,'' Teresa Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Russell said he will not end his work with Habitat once
his house is completed. ``I plan to continue working as long as my
health doesn't stop me,'' he wrote. ``It's been such an amazing
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Other volunteers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day you do this you never want to do it again but
after the first week is over you begin planning for the next
time,'' said Hat Gruver, a volunteer who drove from New York. ``No
matter how tough you are, you still cry at the end of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruver, who has volunteered for five years, said he initially
became involved with Habitat because of the deep gratification that
comes from giving to someone else. ``It's so touching to see how
much joy people get out of it and it just makes you want to keep
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   All 100 homes are expected to be completed Friday, after
plumbers and electricians complete their work and volunteers
landscape the lots and finish hanging doors. Starting Saturday and
continuing into next week, volunteers and Habitat staff members
will inspect the houses to make sure all is ready for move-in day,
June 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you build in a `blitz build,' you want to go back and
make sure everything's right,'' Shirl said.
</P>
<P>
   For most of those involved, Friday will be the last day of work
on the project. Houses will be dedicated, and homeowners will get a
peek at what will be their new place to live.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Shirl said, ``We've got another day to go. We just need
to have good weather to wrap it up.''
</P>
<P>
