<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC SHARES CONTINUE TO TUMBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shares in North American Scientific Inc., makers
of radioactive ``seeds'' used to treat prostate cancer, fell 8.5
percent Thursday, bringing the issue's six-day loss to $5, or 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
   North American shares have been led down by profit-takers who
have seen the company's stock rise nearly 700 percent in a year,
according to analyst John Calcagnini at CIBC Oppenheimer in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising to see that after it hit $30 (last week),
people have sold a little,'' Calcagnini said. ``We just look at it
as a hell of a buying opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   North American earlier this week announced that it has increased
its production capacity to make radioactive titanium pellets, or
``seeds,'' used to treat prostate cancer. The seeds, which contain
a form of iodine, are about the size of a grain of rice and are
injected into a diseased prostate to kill its cancerous cells.
</P>
<P>
   Because the treatment, known as brachytherapy, has fewer side
effects than surgery, its use is expected to grow significantly in
the coming decade. In addition to North American, just two other
companies currently make the seeds.
</P>
<P>
   North American Scientific shares fell $2.25 Thursday to close at
$24.25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
