<HEADER>
A6172 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FUND-RAISER-HNS &LR;      06-18 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FUND-RAISER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - An evening with Gov. George W. Bush was the hot
ticket in the nation's capital Thursday as he flew in for a
get-together with his family's longtime political supporters, a
two-event reunion expected to boost his campaign treasury by more
than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although the money was earmarked for his re-election bid, the
response from Washington lobbyists, Republican activists and
officials from his father's White House hampered Bush's efforts to
knock down talk of his being a contender for the presidency in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a governor come to this city and raise this kind of
money, I think is unprecedented,'' said fund-raiser Fred Bush, who
is no relation but says that over the years he has organized about
300 events for Bush family members, including Thursday's
$500-a-person reception and $5,000-a-plate dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Responses to an invitation to dine with the governor over corn
chowder and beef medallions was so great that the $5,000-a-person
event had to be moved to a hotel from the home of Joseph
Gildenhorn, who was ambassador to Switzerland under the governor's
father, former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Originally planned for no more than 80, the dinner list quickly
outgrew the capacity of the Gildenhorn home and early this week
topped out at almost 130 people. ``I saw very quickly that I was
going to have some very angry folks on my hands,'' Fred Bush told
The Washington Post. ``I have never had to move an event of this
price tag because of overwhelming interest.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the guest list for the reception at the swank
Willard Hotel was barely more than 500. By the time the governor
arrived in town, more than 800 were ponying up $500 for cocktails
and hors d'ouvres.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was ``mystified'' by the response, but he
acknowledged he is partly responsible for the presidential
speculation because he has ``refused to close the door'' on a run
for the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the parties, Bush said that for now his focus is on
Austin, not Washington. He declined several interview requests and
his fund-raisers were closed to the media, but he met briefly with
several Texas reporters. ``I want to be re-elected governor of
Texas,'' he said, repeating what has become a mantra for his
frequent forays outside the state in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Before arriving in Washington, Bush was one of the key draws at
a fund-raiser Thursday in Greensboro, N.C., for Sen. Lauch
Faircloth. Bush also has helped raise money for gubernatorial
candidates in California and Ohio, for the Republican National
Committee and the Republican Governors Association. He also
participated in an Arizona fund-raiser for Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to potential donors to Thursday's reception,
Washington consultant Ron Kaufman, who served as President Bush's
political director, stressed the need to ``send an important signal
about the strength of the Bush network.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time formal invitations were printed, 156 people had
signed up as hosts or chairmen of the reception and 52 were helping
to put on the dinner along with Gildenhorn.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early donors were former South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, former Virginia Gov. George Allen, former Transportation
Secretary Bill Brock, former Texas Rangers part-owner Fred Malek,
former White House Counsel C. Boyden Gray, former White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, former U.S. Trade Representative Carla
Hills and the Republican Party's top three officials _ Chairman Jim
Nicholson, Co-chairman Pat Harrison and Finance Chairman Mel
Sembler.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a Who's Who of the Washington influence business,''
said Bill Hogan of the Center for Public Integrity, a non-profit
research group that focuses on ethics and public policy.
``Obviously, many of these people worked in the Bush
administration, but when you put together a roster like this, you
are going to raise money at the stratospheric level.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for every tobacco company were on the list, as were
officials representing dozens of Fortune 500 companies. ``These are
the early bettors on a potential entrant in the presidential
race,'' Hogan said. ``Most big donors like to say we were with you
from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the list of special interest heavy-hitters, Gov.
Bush described them as friends. ``I didn't ask their occupations
before I asked them for money,'' Bush said. ``The point is, these
are friends of mine. They're friends, and I know a lot of them
personally.''
</P>
<P>
   The money Bush raised Thursday is expected to push his campaign
treasury past the $16 million mark, which gives him a huge edge
over Democratic rival Garry Mauro. The latest figures available
indicate Mauro, the state land commissioner, has raised $2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush holds a equally lopsided lead over Mauro among the state's
voters, according to the most recent Texas Poll. Published
Thursday, the poll shows Bush favored by 70 percent of the state's
voters compared to 17 percent for Mauro. Mauro says the poll is
flawed and that a Democratic pollster shows him trailing Bush but
by a narrower margin, 63-28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Early next week, Mauro has scheduled his own fund-raising
excursion to Washington, where he will be joined by President
Clinton at a $1,000-a-person reception and first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton at a $5,000-a-plate dinner. Vice President Al Gore
will attend a fund-raiser for Mauro in El Paso on June 25. All
three events are expected to raise about $400,000. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
