<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sterilization pill distributor under fire
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ In this region with one of America's fastest
growing Hispanic populations, little-known scientist Stephen D.
Mumford offers an unorthodox solution to the immigration problem he
sees brewing.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that developing nations supply women with tiny pills
that prevent pregnancy by scarring their fallopian tubes_pills that
Mumford already supplies. The permanent sterilization would, in
turn, reduce the number of immigrants to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, quinacrine tablets that Mumford and fellow
contraceptive researcher Elton Kessel have distributed to Third
World countries have been used to sterilize more than 100,000
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this method has great promise,'' Mumford said
Thursday. ``We know what the world needs in the way of a
contraceptive method for women who do not want any more children.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Mumford's controversial role in international
contraception was reported in Thursday's editions of The Wall
Street Journal, the phone has been ringing in his brick split-level
house on the outskirts of this university town. Mostly, he said,
news organizations wanted him to elaborate on his views, or appear
on television talk shows where, Mumford concedes, he would likely
be lambasted as inhumane or crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in his living room, decorated in Oriential wall hangings,
drawings and figurines by his Chinese-born wife, Mumford said, ``I
am not anti-immigrant.''
</P>
<P>
   He said much of the U.S. population growth over the next half
century will be driven by immigrants, and he fears they will sap
the nation's resources and drive down the overall standard of
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in America you value is going to be greatly
diminished, including your personal freedom,'' said Mumford. ``If
you want to let this happen, you can live like they do in Mexico or
in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those attacking Mumford's work was Mike Leary, publisher
of the Hispanic newspaper, La Conexion in Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going around and disfiguring people is not the answer. That is
heinous,'' Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a vasectomy, and I'm glad I permanently injured my
body,'' said Mumford, 55, thumbing through a stack of scientific
research. He said it indicates that quinacrine sterilization is
safe, despite other findings that quinacrine causes cells to
mutate, possible circumstantial evidence that it may cause cancer.
The chemical is inserted directly into the uterus at the tip of a
long slender tube.
</P>
<P>
   First used by American soldiers in World War II to prevent
malaria, quinacrine is barred in the United States for
sterilizations. Many health organizations question its
effectiveness considering the possible risks.
</P>
<P>
   Funded over the past decade by $1 million from U.S. backers,
including anti-immigration advocates, Mumford's efforts are
familiar to some in the field of population control. The recent
publicity, however, unleashed fresh criticism that repressive
governments can use quinacrine sterilization against women's will.
</P>
<P>
   In his Third World travels, Mumford said, he discovered many
women who welcomed the contraception rather than risking sickness
or death giving birth in unsanitary conditions. ``The benefit is
you avoid surgery; it is much cheaper; it is vastly easier,'' he
said. In the United States, the method is still unproven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that before it should be used in human beings,
it should go through rigorous safety testing that all contraceptive
methods go through,'' said Jo Ann Lewis, senior vice president for
reproductive health programs at Family Health International, a
nonprofit research organization in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Mumford worked for the organization , but left in the early
1980s in a rift with more traditional researchers. His views on
immigration illustrate the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the point of departure for most of us working in
international family planning,'' Lewis said. ``Our goal is to make
available safe, effective methods to allow families to determine
the number and spacing of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is planning, but it is personal,'' she said. ``It is not
being dictated by a government.''
</P>
<P>
   Mumford said he is fighting ``the very strong anti-family
planning movement in America. The science is on our side, except
this claim that it could cause cancer. What they have is political
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
