<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wreck takes life of Gilbert cousin
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia linebacker Tony Gilbert might miss Saturday's
game after learning Thursday that his 9-year-old cousin, Maggie
Dunning, was killed in a car accident on I-75 in Monroe County.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie was one of four passengers in a van returning to Macon
from a baby's christening in Atlanta earlier this week. According
to police reports, the driver of the vehicle, Sally Lary, fell
asleep at the wheel, veered off the road and struck an abandoned
tractor trailer parked in the emergency lane. Maggie was wearing
her seat belt but was killed instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert did not learn of the accident until Thursday. He was
pulled out of the morning practice to take a telephone call from
his mother. Visibly shaken, Gilbert sat out the rest of the
practice and was consoled by coaches and managers.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert will be a pallbearer at Maggie's funeral at noon
Saturday in Macon. Whether he will return for the 6 p.m. game is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to let Tony do what he feels like he needs to
do,'' Georgia coach Rodney Walker said. ``It's totally up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, a 6-foot-1, 225-pound linebacker from Central Macon
High, is a University of Georgia signee.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales brisk
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Rite Festival officials are hoping for a record crowd
Saturday at the Georgia Dome. Executive director Shelton Stevens
said ticket sales this week are ``ahead of last year'' when 11,200
passed through the turnstiles. He said they're expecting ``a
minimum of 15,000'' for this year's game and are ``hoping for more
than 20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest crowd in the history of the series was 17,652, in
Orlando in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field
</P>
<P>
   The players enjoyed a lighter-than-usual workday Thursday. After
a two-hour practice in shorts and shoulder pads and lunch at Morris
Brown's Hickman Center, the two teams attended the Braves-Marlins
game at Turner Field. They followed that with dinner at the Varsity
and a tour of the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the teams have toured the Falcons complex and been to
Stone Mountain Park and Six Flags. Today, the players will visit
with patients at the Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center in the
morning, practice in the afternoon and attend the official All-Star
banquet at Zoo Atlanta tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Piano man
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Ben Claxton is not your average offensive lineman. The
6-3, 280-pound Ole Miss signee from Dublin is an accomplished
pianist who has earned a ``superior ranking'' in competition. He
said his favorite piece is Mozart's Sonata in D minor.
</P>
<P>
   This and that
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-Florida Game will be the last high school assignment
for longtime Washington-Wilkes coach Butch Brooks. He starts his
new job at Georgia Tech as director of high school relations on
July 1. ... Officials for Saturday's game are all from the college
ranks, four from the Southeastern Conference, three from the
Atlantic Coast Conference and one from the Southern Conference. ...
There probably is more interest in the Alabama-Auburn rivalry than
the Florida-Georgia rivalry in the home of Union County High's
Phillip Weeks. The Florida free safety will play for Alabama this
fall. His brother Adrian is an Auburn linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
