<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XGAMES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Radical dude
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO -- Chad Smith's got a pierced eyebrow, a tongue ring
and furry spotted pants that are available from his
alternative-clothing company, Vinyl Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and he can skate, too, which got him into the ESPN X Games
this weekend. But it's the look that will get him on TV. Air time,
it seems, is an even bigger deal than the $10,000 purse in his
event.
</P>
<P>
   Bogus? Maybe. That's the X Games _ part sport, part made-for-TV
entertainment tailored for the generation it's named for.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's never finished higher than fourth in the downhill
in-line competition, a kamikaze, 40-second bolt down the streets of
San Diego, taking S-turns and corners at 60 mph. But thanks to
reruns of a spectacular spill he took two years ago, Smith is the
self-proclaimed ``X Games Poster Boy.'' He wiped out into some hay
bales, skidded 30 yards and then got back on his skates. The clip
made him the X Games' equivalent to the ``agony of defeat'' skier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I got fifth, and I got more publicity than anyone
else there,'' boasted Smith, 23, of Roswell. ``ESPN will jump on my
clothes company because it's way off the edge and focus on that big
time. It'll be, 'Here's Chad Smith,' with the furry-pants footage.
They'll pump me up. I know that's what they're trying to get, that
aggressive, alternative look.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been called the Dennis Rodman of his sport. ``I know if I
was just like the other in-line skaters, I wouldn't get the
publicity,'' Smith conceded. ``No onegets more write-ups than me,
and I don't even win.''
</P>
<P>
   No one agrees more than Derek Downing of Cumming, who has won
the downhill in-line twice in the three-year X Games history. He's
enjoyed a few perks, like seeing his trophies displayed at the
All-Star Cafe. But in terms of exposure, his friend Smith has him
beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our sport, we've never had the chance to be on TV, and
everyone wants to get on it,'' Downing said. At the X Games, he
says, ``You've got to do what you do to get on TV, either act crazy
_ or win.''
</P>
<P>
   Downing, 24, has a clean-cut look like most professional in-line
skaters. Their corporate backers want to downplay the sport's
danger to parents whose kids are begging for skates. Downing's
spandex Rollerblade uniform hides his pierced nipple because
``sponsors don't want to have someone all freaked-out-looking,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, wildness doesn't get you to the bottom first,''
said Downing.
</P>
<P>
   The prize money, three times larger than what's offered at most
pro skating events, ensures a competitive field _ even though
skaters don't take these kind of risks any other time all year.
Most in-line races are distance events on flatter terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes us go to the extreme and do something we're not
used to,'' said Kim Darnell, 19, of Loganville. ``It's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to see the perceived expression of danger,'' X
Games executive director Jack Weinert said, comparing the X Games
to pro wrestling. ``We are really driven by trying to hold people's
attention. There's not a whole heck of a lot of people who will
stay glued to the set watching someone do a criterium.''
</P>
<P>
   The format, cameras and hype have stamped the X Games as
made-for-TV, a label that makes organizers bristle. Out of the
extreme sports culture, they say, have emerged personalities that
cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing the athletes have figured out is how to get on TV,''
Weinert said. ``We like to exhibit their real personality. If
(downhill skater) Gypsy Tidwell lets out a coyote yell and kisses
the wind, there is no way in the world that's not going to get
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Smith and other X-troverts is staying fresh in
an age in which images are flashed worldwide in seconds. ``Pretty
soon there won't be much that is alternative,'' Smith said,
``because so many people will be doing what we're doing. Then I'll
have to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
