<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-OUTLOOK-ART-N     06-18 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-OUTLOOK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO STOCKS RECOUP AFTER BILL IS EXTINGUISHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TOBACCO-SUITS, CONGRESS-TOBACCO) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on tobacco stocks since March '97 is being sent
to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tobacco stocks rebounded Thursday, the day after the latest
version of a tobacco-settlement bill was stubbed out like, well, a
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Philip Morris Cos., the maker of Marlboro, rose
$1.125, to $39.5625. RJR Nabisco climbed 75 cents, to $25.0625.
Even Brooke Group, the parent of Liggett &AMP; Myers that became
popular recently because of an earlier deal that freed it from tax
penalties proposed in the bill, showed some spark during trading,
though it closed down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Was this a sigh of relief from investors who have been on a
rough ride for the last several years? A momentary uptick in the
sagging fortunes of corporations stuck with products destined for
the ash heap of history? Or was it a long-overdue recognition of
the inherent value of companies like RJR Nabisco and Philip Morris,
regardless of the all-too-visible hand of Congress?
</P>
<P>
   It may be none, or all, of the above. Certainly the biggest
worry for investors _ the threat of interminable litigation and
overwhelming punitive damages from the hundreds of lawsuits that
have been filed against tobacco companies _ remained. Without
restrictions on such lawsuits and awards, many people who might
otherwise buy into tobacco companies were staying away, not wanting
to put their money into companies whose earnings could be siphoned
off by having to make all those payments.
</P>
<P>
   Management itself has not been too encouraging. The 1997 annual
report from Philip Morris stated: ``Management is unable to make a
meaningful estimate of the amount or range of loss that could
result from an unfavorable outcome of pending litigation.'' The
report, though, does suggest that the original tobacco pact _
reached 364 days ago, on June 20, 1997 _ would have resolved ``the
most significant tobacco litigation'' facing the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the litigation is a large issue for the industry to
deal with,'' said Jan Smith, a spokeswoman for R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Co., the cigarette-making branch of RJR Nabisco, based in
Winston-Salem, N.C. ``And the whole youth smoking issue is
something we would like to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other issues that went away, more or less, along with
the bill, which was sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. One was
the spectre of higher prices for cigarettes, which some feared
would create a contraband market for them. Another was spending for
programs to reduce youth smoking, which was also a major element of
the June 20 plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, the failure of the Senate effort takes away
a big potential downside in terms of the big tax increase they were
facing,'' said Marc Cohen, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.,
who predicts that a much narrower tobacco bill will be combined
with an anti-drug measure in the House and could wind up before
President Clinton by early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the impact of the legislative and executive branches
may have been overstated all along. ``These stocks are being priced
as if what's going on in Washington could cripple the companies,''
said Emanuel Goldman, an analyst with Paine Webber in San
Francisco. ``And I think that's very unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at what would happen if Philip Morris, say, broke up
into several small companies and eliminated domestic tobacco sales
from its balance sheet. Right away, the remaining businesses _
international tobacco, Kraft Foods and Miller Brewing Co. _ would
be worth about $66 a share, Goldman estimated. Adding a
conservative valuation for domestic tobacco back in would raise the
price by about $12 a share, he said, bringing the price to $78, or
nearly twice what the stock was selling for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to RJR Nabisco, one could do the same. Goldman said the
company without its domestic tobacco business was worth about $47,
and $58 with the domestic tobacco added in.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, investors have shied away, resulting in most of
the tobacco companies sinking to 52-week lows earlier this month.
``This is a very, very unusual situation,'' Goldman said. ``You
don't usually have this kind of uncertainty due to external
factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Where investors go from here will be interesting to watch. RJR
chief executive Steven Goldstone, who was the first of his peer
group to declare the original tobacco settlement dead back in
April, is scheduled to deliver a speech Friday a meeting of
newspaper publishers in Memphis. Originally, the speech was billed
by the RJR public relations team as being all about the current
tobacco legislation. Instead, Goldstone will be speaking on a
related topic: ``What's been going on in Congress,'' as a
spokeswoman put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry continues to support the position it took last
June, wanting a comprehensive bill that contains caps for annual
payouts on damages and liability relief from class-action
lawsuits,'' said Scott Williams, a spokesman for the tobacco
companies in Washington, who, like Goldman, believes the original
settlement proposal will be revived in Congress before long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just myriad issues out there,'' Ms. Smith of R.J.
Reynolds said. ``In the meantime, we just have to try and run our
business responsibly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2122EDT &QL; 
