<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-VAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CALL UP IMPROVED VAN POPPEL
</HEADLINE>
 POPPEL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Todd Van Poppel returned to the major leagues
yesterday, older than the first time and more prepared to pitch to
big-league hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a better chance of succeeding now than I
did before,'' Van Poppel said. ``It's the first time in my career
I've been able to throw four pitches for a strike at any time in
the count. Before I was just a fastball pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel, the onetime phenom from Martin High School in
Arlington who made it to the majors with the Oakland Athletics as a
19-year-old, joined the Rangers from Triple-A Oklahoma. His
contract will be officially purchased before he starts tomorrow
night against the Angels in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old right-hander takes the spot in the rotation
vacated when Bobby Witt was designated for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd Van Poppel's going to get a chance,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``There's no doubt he has a major-league arm. It gets
down to consistent command of his pitches, but I think he can pitch
in the major leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel likely has two chances to fill the spot on a
long-term basis. His second start will probably be Thursday in
Arizona, and Darren Oliver is due back from a stint on the disabled
list the next day. The Rangers would face a decision on whether Van
Poppel or Matt Perisho, Oliver's replacement, sticks in the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give Todd a chance to start, and then we'll
adjust,'' Oates said. ``I don't think there's competition with each
other for a starting spot. They can both fit on this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers decide Van Poppel isn't the answer in the
rotation, they will consider keeping him in the bullpen, and not
only because he is out of options and can't be sent back to the
minors without clearing waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could throw 70 pitches today and be ready with the same
stuff tomorrow,'' Oates said. ``That's what I saw in spring
training. He'd come out and air it out one day, and be throwing
just as hard the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think Todd is going to be part of this ballclub for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel is simply glad to be back in the major leagues,
whatever the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If being in the bullpen helps this team win, that's fine,'' he
said. ``And if I'm in the rotation, that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel was 5-5 with a 3.72 earned-run average at Oklahoma,
and 3-0 with a 2.57 ERA in his past four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's absolutely been strong,'' said Rick Wrona, the catcher at
Oklahoma before being called up to the Rangers last Friday. ``He's
got four pitches he's throwing for strikes, and that's why he's
been so successful. The last five or six feet that ball really has
a four-seam hop that you just don't see very often. He definitely
still has velocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel was a first-round draft pick of the A's in 1990 after
a stellar career at Martin High. He made it to the majors in
September '91, and struck out five of the first six big-league
batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   But after 3 1/2 years in the majors, including stints with four
organizations and with a 20-33 record and 6.22 ERA, he was released
by the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers signed him to a minor-league deal in June 1997, and
sent him to Class A to start again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what I needed to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers simplified his mechanics, and this year he began to
throw a slider for the first time. He began getting hitters out
consistently, earning another chance in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he can pitch here,'' Oates said. ``It may not be as a
starter, but that's a good starting point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
