<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO CONSIDER 258 AMENDMENTS TO CAMPAIGN BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Conn., Texas, Mass., Colo.)   (bl)  
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Democrats maintaining that the Republican
leadership was once again trying to delay any final vote on
campaign finance, the House voted Thursday to open the debate to a
blizzard of amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure _ rare in a House that is usually controlled
tightly to allow only limited debate and a handful of amendments _
was approved on a near-party-line vote, 221-189. Republican
proponents of overhauling campaign finance law stood with their
party after receiving assurances from the House Majority Leader
Dick Armey that the issue would be brought to a final vote by the
time the House takes its August recess.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats called so long a timetable _ and the 258
amendments approved for consideration _ a farce. Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich., the minority whip, said ``a lot of these amendments don't
even have anything to do with campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're poison pills,'' Bonior declared. ``They're booby
traps. And each of these amendments, if adopted, could open the
floodgates to even more amendments. ''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, pointed out that on Wednesday, the
Republican leadership ``gave us one hour of debate'' before the
House voted to abolish the current federal tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Frost said, ``they've given us seven weeks of debate on
campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   From the other side of the aisle, Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the
majority whip, an opponent of the overhaul effort, mocked the
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the so-called reformers are complaining,'' DeLay said,
``because the debate will be too open for their taste.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just another moment in the odyssey of campaign finance
overhaul, an issue that has unexpectedly refused to die this year
despite the concerted efforts of Republican leaders in both houses
to block any changes that would erode their party's fund-raising
advantage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich tried to dispense with the matter in
March under rules that never allowed the main, bipartisan overhaul
bill to the floor. But the speaker's tactic boomeranged
politically, giving the overhaul effort new momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Next he promised that the issue would come up in May.
Technically it did _ for several hours of debate and with no votes.
Since then, the House has been meandering through a thicket of
campaign finance proposals, usually at night.
</P>
<P>
   But late Thursday afternoon the House opened debate on the main
bill, sponsored by Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., and Martin
Meehan, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, the favorite of most of the groups seeking to
limit the influence of money in politics, would effectively ban
``soft money,'' the unregulated donations to national and state
political parties from corporations, labor unions and wealthy
individuals. It would also put some restrictions on issue
advertising by advocacy groups and would expand disclosure
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   After Bonior, the Democratic whip, had accused Republicans of
seeking to ``keep the spigots of special-interest money flowing,''
Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., said 57 percent of Bonior's campaign
funds came from political action committees, mostly from organized
labor.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rosa DeLauro, D-Conn., attributed the demise of
anti-smoking legislation in the Senate to the tobacco industry's
campaign contributions to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a look at the amount of money the tobacco companies have
provided to the Republican committees in 1996,'' she said, pulling
out a chart. ``Four and a half million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to quote from a Wall Street Journal article about
Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash., who is running for the Senate. In that
article, Ms. Smith, first elected to the House in 1994, said she
had quickly discovered that it was common practice for Republican
leaders to hold up action on bills while seeking more donations
from interested contributors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
