<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko ready to hide after neglecting to slide
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Things had been going so well for the Braves. And
outside of the weather, little was hotter in Atlanta than Ryan
Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't make any difference Thursday at The Ted. Klesko's bat
remains ablaze, but a fourth-inning base-running error, which he
later second-guessed, played a part in the Braves' 3-2 loss to the
Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes baseball so great,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox said. ``It doesn't matter how things are going, you can be beat
by anybody on a given day.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 2-1, the Braves started the fourth inning with three
straight singles, off the bats of Andres Galarraga, Klesko and Javy
Lopez. Lopez's single up the middle scored Galarraga to tie the
score.
</P>
<P>
   On Lopez's hit, Klesko rounded second and, ignoring third base
coach Bobby Dews, charged into third base standing.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko's aggressiveness, however, caused him to stumble over the
base and fall. When he reached back for third, Florida's Todd Zeile
had his glove and the ball there to meet his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down, telling him to slide all the way,'' Dews said. ``I
got down real low. If I had been any closer to the ground, I
would've been under it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Klesko sounded as if he wanted to find a spot
there himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to slide. I kind of got off balance and couldn't
stop in time,'' said Klesko, whose fourth-inning single extended
his career-high hitting streak to 11 games. ``I never should've
changed my mind; I should've just (gone) ahead and slid.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Lopez's single, the third in a row of the inning,
also was the last of the inning. Michael Tucker followed by forcing
Lopez out at second, and Andruw Jones hit a weak grounder to first
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After Klesko's faux pas, only two more Braves got as far as
second base. And the Marlins' pitchers hushed all possibilities of
another score.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko is batting .418 (18-for-43) with four homers and 13 RBIs
during his hot stretch. But the blunder?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things that cost us,'' Klesko said. ``You
would hope we'd get a few more runs, but that happens sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
