<SLUG> BC-BRAVESNOTEBOOK18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest chapter of `Braves vs. police'
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Braves' dispute with Atlanta officials about
re-routing of pre-game traffic escalated Thursday. The driver of
the Florida Marlins team bus was threatened with arrest after the
removal of some traffic cones while trying to deliver the team to
Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police came over yelling and waving their arms,'' said
Tony Perez, the Marlins special assistant to general manager Dave
Dombrowski. ``We were telling them it was important that we get to
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of new traffic restrictions put in place last week, the
club has advised fans to leave 30 to 40 minutes earlier to make the
first pitch. While confused season-tickes holders have been the
ones most affected by the changes _ specifially on the Fulton
Street exit off the connector and on Capitol Avenue _ it was the
first incident involving an official team vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins' bus had been turned away from the usual access and
sent on a 15-minute detour to University Avenue that delivered it
to the same entrance. After some passengers removed some cones
blocking access, the team finally reached the players' entrance,
despite the driver's threatened arrest by Atlanta police.
</P>
<P>
   Big Cat's birthday
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga turned 37 Thursday, the oldest position player
on the club, as well as the most productive player at the plate (26
home runs, 67 RBI). Former first baseman Fred McGriff had 22 homers
and 97 RBI in all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie's jaw
</P>
<P>
   After taking a tipped ball to the point of his jaw Wednesday
night, Eddie Perez is waiting to take a second smash to his head to
get rid of the clicking in the hinges of his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Perez determined that when Todd Dunwoody fouled the ball in the
sixth, the padding across the chin of his mask had been adjusted
too high and the full force of the ball was tranferred directly to
his chin.
</P>
<P>
   His ears began to ring, his jaw went numb, and, for a moment, he
thought his mask must have flown off before the ball hit him.
</P>
<P>
   But he stayed in the game, which, in retrospect, might not have
been the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   The catcher began to forget what pitch he had called for as soon
as he signaled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd signal for a fastball,'' Perez said, ``and then I'd be
waiting for a change-up. That happened twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim's knee
</P>
<P>
   The Braves will be without dugout coach Jim Beauchamp this road
trip, while he recovers from surgery Thursday to repair a torn
tendon in his right knee. The operation, performed by Dr. John
Garrett at St. Joseph's Hospital, will allow Beauchamp to return to
the dugout when the team returns Wednesday, but his field duties
have been doled out until he is mobile again. Third-base coach
Bobby Dews will handle the outfield defensive alignments, Ned Yost
will handle scorecards and first-base coach Pat Corrales will
attend the pre-game exchange of lineups at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
