<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Web News Goes to Print   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
If newspapers and magazines are an endangered species in the
digital age, why are online news services dying to get into print?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at print publications shuddered when Internet-based news
organizations like Cnet, Salon and Motley Fool began to crop up in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom was that the traditional press _ derisively
called ``old media'' by its upstart rivals _ would hemorrhage
readers and advertisers to the fledgling ``new media,'' which can
instantly transmit online stories and ads over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened on the way to the old media's demise.
</P>
<P>
   The new media business isn't as profitable as its proponents had
hoped. That has led many online ventures to peddle their content to
newspapers and magazines in an effort to attract more readers _ and
eventually more advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated online content reaches 10 times more readers in print
than on the Web, even though some publications are hesitant to
carry content from online rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Though syndication fees are nominal _ as little as $50 a week
for a package of news and features _ the potential payoff is
significant for online news operations. Newspaper syndication helps
Web sites build brand-name recognition, reach a broader audience
and pocket some cash in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the information economy, you make money by gathering
information once and then reselling it as often as possible,'' said
Felix Gutierrez, executive director of the Freedom Forum, an
Arlington, Va.-based foundation dedicated to media education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's healthy for any media business to have more than one form
of distribution and revenue,'' said Andrew Ross, managing editor of
Salon in San Francisco. ``To only have one is unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of the old and new media is becoming a downright
blur. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _Motley Fool, an irreverent financial tip sheet on America
Online and the Web, is the king of new-meets-old media syndication.
It is distributed by Universal Press Syndicate in 136 newspapers _
among them the Los Angeles Times, Chicago Sun-Times, Philadelphia
Inquirer and Detroit Free Press. It is also carried on radio and in
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making some money on syndication, but it's not the main
reason we're in papers,'' said Chris Hill, spokesman for the
Alexandria, Va., company. ``It's a way to reach another 13 million
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Motley Fool online, by comparison, reaches about 750,000 people
per month.
</P>
<P>
   _Salon, an online magazine, offers a weekly package of columns
and features through New York syndication giant United Features.
About 30 North American newspapers carry it, including the New York
Daily News, Hartford Courant and Toronto Globe and Mail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Salon reaches millions of people through its newspaper
syndication deals, dwarfing its Web audience of tens of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   _Cnet's News.com, a site devoted to computer news, doubles as a
high-tech wire service for the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to market our brand name and show off our
breaking-news coverage to fresh new eyeballs,'' said a spokeswoman
for San Francisco-based Cnet.
</P>
<P>
   _TheStreet.com provides material to the San Francisco Examiner's
Sunday business section and New York Observer. That explains the
reemergence of Herb Greenberg _ The Chronicle's former business
columnist now at TheStreet.com _ whose syndicated ``Herb on the
Street'' musings in the Examiner first appeared last week.
</P>
<P>
   _Yahoo, which has morphed from Web directory to media company,
provides original news content via King Features Syndicate for 15
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a two-way street. Most newspapers and magazines post
stories on their own Web sites. And media giants like Walt Disney
and NBC are snapping up online ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the breathless hype about the Internet, it hasn't
significantly changed Americans' news-reading habits. Many still
rely heavily on their local paper and TV for news, according to a
recent national study by Pew Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We aren't quite at the point where this medium needs to be
in terms of viewers,'' concedes Jim Cramer, co-chairman of
TheStreet.com, an in-your-face New York-based financial news
service. ``There are still a lot of readers who are not technically
savvy and depend on newspapers and TV to get their news.''
</P>
<P>
   Would online firms go after those readers more directly with a
print publication of their own?
</P>
<P>
   Ross says discussions of a hard-copy Salon magazine are ``on and
off. It's always been in the back of our minds, since (the staff)
comes from print publications,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cramer takes a hard-line approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I do a print version of Street.com? Absolutely not,''
Cramer says, scoffing. ``It's a waste of time and money. Our best
news is immediate and appears on a computer screen. By the time it
goes into print, it's old and useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why syndicate to newspapers? ``I just think we can't afford
to ignore the non-Web reading crowd,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
