 N.Y. REIT Buying S.F. Developer   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A New York-based real estate investment trust is about to acquire
Vylliam Wilson &AMP; Associates, a big private developer based in San
Mateo, in a deal worth $1.8 billion.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The buyer is Cornerstone Properties, a publicly held company
traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The deal _ which probably will involve the issuance of
Cornerstone securities to Wilson's owners _ is expected to be
sealed over the weekend and officially announced early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Cornerstone nor Wilson would comment, informed
sources confirmed the deal yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The lion's share of the proceeds will go to principal owner and
founder Bill Wilson, a Stanford graduate whose real-estate
associates have included the Rockefeller family, Yale University,
pension funds and various private partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Although generally publicity-shy _ ``He's a private guy,'' says
Wilson firm spokeswoman Pam Hittleman _ he serves on the board of
the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   William Wilson &AMP; Associates builds, leases and manages
high-quality office buildings _ known in the trade as ``Class A.''
</P>
<P>
   It owns more than 11 million square feet of office space
throughout California, including substantial holdings in San
Francisco and on the Peninsula. It also has properties in the
Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The firm built the architecturally striking Oracle Corp.
headquarters complex in Redwood Shores and owns a building occupied
by Gap Inc. in San Mateo. It also owns San Mateo's Borel Office
Center, a multitenant, four-building complex.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it bought the Equitable Life Building at 120
Montgomery St. in San Francisco in a deal reportedly worth &QL; 
$70 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and Cornerstone _ which also owns about 11 million square
feet of office space _ combined with Gap Chairman Donald Fisher
this year in an unsuccessful bid for San Francisco's 3.76
million-square-foot Embarcadero Center.
</P>
<P>
   The winning bidder was Massachusetts-based Boston Properties, a
public REIT, which paid $1.22 billion for the property last month.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Cornerstone, which specializes in office properties
in prime metropolitan areas, views Wilson as a more-than-acceptable
consolation prize in its effort to establish a major foothold in
the booming Bay Area office market.
</P>
<P>
   For Bill Wilson, now is the ideal time to sell, says James F.
Wilson (no relation), an analyst with Jefferies &AMP; Co. in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He notes that prices of office properties are soaring and that
private firms ``are finding it tougher to compete with the big
public ones. The big firms have easier access to capital and can
borrow at cheaper rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Rising, president and chief executive of Catellus
Development, a large, publicly held developer based in San
Francisco, said he chatted recently with Bill Wilson about the
Wilson firm's ``options.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising said Bill Wilson was concerned about his ability to
compete in a market increasingly dominated by public REITs. Private
developers ``are all asking themselves whether the trend toward
public ownership of real estate is irreversible,'' Rising remarked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
