<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' MANAGER EJECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates was ejected from
yesterday's game by home-plate umpire Ted Barrett for arguing balls
and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The ejection came in the first inning after Rusty Greer, the
Rangers' third hitter of the afternoon, took a called strike from
Oakland Athletics pitcher Tom Candiotti. Many on the Rangers' bench
thought it was a ball and voiced their opinion. Oates was singled
out and ejected almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time Oates had been ejected this season, and the
second time in his career by Barrett. Barrett ejected Oates in
1996, also on balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Oates declined to comment on the ejection.
Bizarre play
</P>
<P>
   Oates, a former catcher, said he has been involved in a play
similar to the game-winner yesterday when the Rangers scored two
runs on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I was involved in a play where three runs
scored,'' Oates said. ``It was here at the old stadium. I had a
passed ball that allowed one run to score. Then I got the ball at
the backstop, and I tried to make one of those fabulous throws that
I preach against. The ball ended up in center field.''
Starting and lasting
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starters have had their troubles this season, but Aaron
Sele's 6 2/3 innings yesterday marked the 10th time in the past 14
games a starter has pitched at least six innings. That has helped
the Rangers' bullpen, which Oates worries might be getting
overworked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just fine as far as I know,'' reliever Danny Patterson
said. ``I haven't heard anybody complain. Everybody is willing to
take the ball.'' Out of trouble Rangers pitchers worked their way
out of three bases-loaded situations yesterday. Here's the rundown.
</P>
<P>
   First inning _ Sele, with one run home, got Matt Stairs to hit
into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth inning _ Sele kept the Athletics from scoring by getting
Ryan Christenson looking with a curveball for a called third
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh inning _ Xavier Hernandez replaced Scott Bailes and got
Mike Macfarlane to fly out to left, ending the inning.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't have an extra-base hit for the fifth time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   John Wetteland has recorded 20 saves for the seventh consecutive
season, the longest current streak in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin snapped an 0-for-22 slump with a sixth-inning
single.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark is batting .352 with 14 runs batted in during his
past 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 8-9 in one-run games.
Farm report
</P>
<P>
   Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): The Drillers (31-41) defeated
Shreveport, 5-3, Wednesday, scoring all five runs in the fourth
inning. Dan Smith (5-7, 6.88) worked six innings for the victory,
allowing three runs on six hits. Also, the Texas League said
pitcher Corey Lee was selected pitcher of the week for June 8-14.
He was 1-0 in two starts, allowing 13 hits in 14 innings, while
striking out 15.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Charlotte (Florida State League): The Rangers (45-23)
lost to Vero Beach, 3-2, Wednesday. Starter Doug Davis (9-3, 3.10
ERA) allowed just one earned run in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Class-A Pulaski (Appalachian League): The Rangers (1-0) opened
their season with a 7-3 victory Wednesday against Martinsville.
Third baseman Danny Infante, a 20-year-old native of the Dominican
Republic, went 4-for-5 and Douglas Garcia, a 19-year-old native of
the Dominican Republic, hit a three-run homer.
</P>
</TEXT>
