<DOCNO> NYT19980618.0455 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-NYT &LR;      06-18 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GLOBE ASKS COLUMNIST WHO FABRICATED MATERIAL TO RESIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A columnist at the Boston Globe, a Pulitzer Prize finalist,
fabricated people and quotations in four of her columns this year
and the newspaper has asked for her resignation, the Globe
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, she made up nearly an entire column about a woman
dying of cancer, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said the columnist, Patricia Smith, 42, a widely
respected figure in the Boston area, had acknowledged the
transgressions. ``There is no middle ground on something like
this,'' said Matthew Storin, the editor of the newspaper. ``That
was self-evident.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin said he had yet to receive Ms. Smith's letter of
resignation. But he said in Ms. Smith's final column, to be
published in Friday's edition of the Globe, ``she does deal with
the fact that her newspaper career is over.'' He said she is
apologetic.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith did not return messages left on her voice mail at work
and her home telephone was out of service. Her attorney, Ike
Williams of the Boston firm Palmer &AMP; Dodge, also did not return
voice mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time in Ms. Smith's career that her
credibility has come under fire. As an editorial assistant at the
Chicago Sun Times in the late 1980s, she wrote a review of a
concert that she had not attended. The newspaper ran a correction
but she was not dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations about Ms. Smith come just a week after the New
Republic published the results of an investigation into the work of
Stephen Glass, one of its staff writers, whom it said had
fabricated parts or all of 27 of the 41 articles he wrote in two
and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe, which is owned by the New York Times Co., said
Friday's paper would also include a news article about the
incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we confirmed that we had the problem, we wanted to get
the information out as quickly as we could,'' said Benjamin Taylor,
the publisher of the Globe. ``Credibility with our readership is
the single most important asset that we have and I believe the
credibility of the Globe is and remains very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said it discovered Ms. Smith's fabrications two weeks
ago in the normal course of monitoring by senior editors. Under the
monitoring system, which Storin said he established two and a half
years ago, editors occasionally double check columnists' sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had questions raised from time to time over the years
about metro columnists who have such freedom to write about
whatever they want _ street scenes, slices of life, etc.,'' Storin
said. ``It was on my mind when I returned to the Globe in '93 that
at some point we ought to try to come up with a system for vetting
those columns.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin said editors at the Globe discovered the fabrications
earlier this month, while Ms. Smith was on vacation, and waited to
confront her until she returned. ``We detected a few weeks ago that
some quotes seemed too articulate or too polished in certain
circumstances,'' Storin said.
</P>
<P>
   The fabrications appeared in columns published on April 13, 20,
24 and May 11. Storin said further research would be done into Ms.
Smith's work.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fake people quoted in these columns was one named
Janine Byrne, whom Ms. Smith identified as ``a South End
cosmetologist'' in her April 24 article on Stephen Fagan, a man
accused of kidnapping his two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Globe said Ms. Smith created a woman named
Dorothy Gibson in her April 13 column about a little girl's Easter
experience. In the article, Ms. Smith gives this quotation from Ms.
Gibson: ```Seems like that girl's feet grew a size since we bought
those,' said Carolyn's mom Dorothy Gibson. `You know, when they get
a certain age, nothing sits still.'''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gulla, a spokesman for the Globe, said he did not know
whether other people in that article, such as Ms. Gibson's daughter
Carolyn were fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith also acknowledged making up Jim Burke, a worker
erecting barricades at the marathon, in her column of April 20th;
and Claire, for whom Ms. Smith did not give a last name, the
subject of an entire poignant column about a woman with cancer,
published on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claire has been thinking about dying for weeks now,'' Ms.
Smith wrote, ``ever since her doctor said the tragic word, ever
since she found out why she was so woefully tired all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether the New Republic's case influenced the Globe's
handling of the situation, Storin said: ``It reinforced the idea
that we had to get to the bottom of it but we were already on that
track. This process was well under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who began her newspaper career as a typist at the
Chicago Daily News, joined the Globe in 1990. She has been writing
a column for the Metro/Region section since 1994. Earlier this
year, she won an award from the American Society of Newspaper
Editors for a series of her columns published in 1997. She was also
nominated for a Pulitzer Prize for commentary last year. A poet,
she has been widely recognized in the Boston arts community for her
public readings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As to whether the Globe knew about the Sun-Times incident upon
hiring Ms. Smith in 1990, Gulla said, ``I have no knowledge of that
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Moore, the Globe's managing editor, said: ``We've tried
to establish that. We don't really know.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin could not be reached for comment on this.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said Ms. Smith admitted the fabrications after being
questioned by Moore. Storin said the Globe initially had questions
about six columns and that Ms. Smith admitted to fabrications in
four of them.
</P>
<P>
   In a noontime meeting Thursday, Storin and Taylor told the news
staff of their request for Ms. Smith's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy,'' Storin said. ``And I feel that we have
handled it in the only way we could and that itself speaks well for
the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement made at the meeting, Storin said ``anything that
further research reveals will be disclosed in a timely manner.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
