<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPANESE PLEDGE ON BANKS RAISES HOPES FOR OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   Japan's prime minister has again pledged to resolve the more
than $600 billion in bad bank loans that have been hampering that
country's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Although some foreign investors are wary of new promises from
the government because of past letdowns, analysts and economists
say that while uncertainties remain, there are signs that the
government may finally be ready to put a plan into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ARCO CHEMICAL IN $5.6 BILLION DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Lyondell Petrochemical agreed to buy ARCO Chemical from Atlantic
Richfield for $57.75 a share, or $5.6 billion, plus assumption of
$870 million in debt. The deal will triple Lyondell's size and make
it a leading provider of chemicals used in plastics, detergents and
paints. ARCO Chemical shares rose nearly 13 percent on the news.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA TO SEEK MORE IMF FUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government plans to seek $10 billion to $15 billion
in additional assistance from the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   WALT DISNEY BUYING 43 PERCENT OF INFOSEEK
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney became the latest media company to seek a gateway
into cyberspace as it announced it would acquire a 43 percent stake
in Infoseek, a service that helps guide users to what they want on
the World Wide Web, in a deal valued at $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS INSTRUMENTS CUTS 3,500 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Texas Instruments plans to cut 3,500 jobs, or 8 percent of its
work force, and sell its computer memory-chip business to Micron
Technology for about $610 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF TOBACCO COMPANIES RISE
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Murphy of RPM Specialist Corp. mimics the ``Call for
Philip Morris'' slogan as he trades in shares of the conglomerate.
Shares of tobacco companies ignited just one day after the Senate
dropped a measure to raise the price of cigarettes by $1.10 a pack
and discourage teen-agers from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 lawsuits are pending against tobacco companies, a
figure that represents a quadrupling of the number of such cases in
just three years.
</P>
<P>
   TWO FIRMS REPORT STRONG RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Earnings at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter rose 45 percent, to $854
million. Lehman Brothers Holdings said earnings increased 168
percent, to $324 million. The big Wall Street brokerage firms
attributed the second-quarter results to a blistering pace of
mergers and acquisitions, as well as sharp increases in equity and
debt issues and trading.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE STAMINA IN STOCK RALLY
</P>
<P>
   Stocks retreated slightly from Wednesday's rally, reflecting
diminished optimism over new pledges of economic reform by Japan
and a possible turnaround in Asia. While stocks in Asia jumped, the
rally faded in Europe. The Dow Jones industrial average, which fell
207.01 points Monday and surged 164.17 points Wednesday, fell 16.45
points, to 8,813.01. Other indexes were lower.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices edged up. The bond's yield slipped to 5.70
percent, from 5.73 percent Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BIG THREE DIFFER ON LABOR RELATIONS
</P>
<P>
   The three major U.S. automakers have very different approaches
to labor relations. General Motors has consistently lashed out
against the United Automobile Workers and continues to do so as the
strike at two parts factories continues.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA/HCA DISMISSES PAIR
</P>
<P>
   Columbia/HCA Healthcare has dismissed two executives at a
Tennessee hospital after an investigation concluded they probably
altered records on costs in a manner that may have bilked federal
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP BUYS BRITISH HOTEL CHAIN
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of American investors, including Bill Gates, the
Microsoft chairman, has agreed to buy a British luxury hotel chain
for 42.8 million pounds, or $71.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
