<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENBERG, MILLER, NBC ON PAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympic Club, site of the 98th US Open, is one of those
courses that command attention. The roughs are extremely thick and
the greens are small, making it difficult for even top
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   In lesser hands, the course would simply become a pretty
background. Not so with NBC's Dick Enberg and former US Open
champion Johnny Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to keeping track of all of the leaders Thursday,
Enberg and Miller paid homage to the course, giving viewers a real
feel for the precision required to beat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Par is a very good score,'' Enberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Enberg was right. Only three of the first 63 players in the
156-man field to finish the first round broke par: Payne Stewart,
John Daly, and Jesper Parnevik.
</P>
<P>
   NBC used computer-generated animation to show each hole. Viewers
saw the angles, the height of the greens, the sand traps, and the
fairways. NBC also used cameras behind golfers to show us what they
saw as they teed off.
</P>
<P>
   The result was very good television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
