<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Friday, June 19. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOODYKOOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ Time for advice from the one
advice columnist more clueless than the people who offer him
questions: the Pretentious Answer Man. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story
will move in the ``L'' category.
</P>
<P>
   LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (UNDATED) _ This evil is insidious, like all
the worst evils: Vampires, lobbyists, the bubonic plague. Relax for
an eye's blink, and boom. Someone plays KC and the Sunshine Band.
And then someone, some dude in a mood ring and platform shoes,
barks it aloud, that most nightmarish phrase: ``Hey, disco's
back!'' This no right-thinking American can allow. We must stop
disco, for good. I say this because it's back, at least partway.
Which is horrid, in every way. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   SETTLE19 (Phoenix) _ Lori Romeneck made headlines when she
helped police solve the decades-old murder of her mother. Her
testimony got her father convicted and sentenced to life. But there
was another nagging family mystery: the deaths of her two sisters
in a fire that also left her disfigured. Phoenix police and
firefighters blamed the blaze on a faulty dishwasher, but Romaneck
blamed her father and claimed investigators didn't do their jobs.
Now, the city is paying out $5.5 million to settle her lawsuit in
the long and twisted case. By SUSIE STECKNER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTIONS (Phoenix) _ Phoenix officials say they are holding
their own when it comes to attracting conventions to the downtown.
But that could change if the East Valley builds a huge new
convention center. A look at the potential effects of the new
stadium/convention complex on downtown convention business. By
CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   CHEAT19 (Phoenix) _ Larry Dong was eager to help his students
past the test to become naturalized U.S. citizens. But idealism had
nothing to do with it. Dong pleads guilty Thursday to rigging the
test, which culminated classes he taught at the Chinese Chamber of
Commerce, in return for payment. By JERRY KAMMER. Story will move
in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   SNIP (Phoenix) _ Randy Hinkle of Mesa won a free Vase ctomy this
morning. He blazed through an obstacle course on a 15
</P>
<P>
   horsepower riding mower in record time to take the checkered fl
ag. And an all-expenses paid trip to the urologist! By JUSTIN
SCHMID. Story will run in the ``A'' category.
</P>
