<SLUG> BC-BKO-LABOR-STRIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR STRIFE AFFECTS WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world championships have become the latest battleground in
the labor strife between the players and the owners. After the
players voted unanimously to boycott the event last week in the
event of a lockout, USA Basketball announced Tuesday it would send
an alternate team to Athens, one probably composed of players not
in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player in the NBA, it's a big contradiction for us to go
over there when there is an NBA lockout, if that's what's going to
happen,'' said the Knicks' Allan Houston, who had been selected.
</P>
<P>
   With no deal in sight, the owners are expected to lock out the
players on July 1 _ the day after the collective bargaining
agreement expires.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Commissioner David Stern accused the boycotting
players of ``trashing their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston replied: ``We know what he was saying was just a tactic.
I can tell you by no means are we trying to trash our country.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
