<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JUNE 19
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-DARTMOUTH-PRESIDENT-NYT (moved on Sunday, June 14)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, June 14,
about the retirement of James O. Freedman as president of Dartmouth
College referred incorrectly to the James Joyce book he received as
a gift. It is ``Finnegans Wake''; Joyce omitted the apostrophe for
the sake of a wordplay, ``Wake'' serving as both noun and verb.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-PC-ANATOMY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 16,
about technical advances in personal computers, misstated the price
of the Microsoft Natural Keyboard Elite. It is $64, not $46.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-WRISTWATCH-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 16,
about digital watches misstated the name of the company that
manufactures Beepwear and misidentified one of the partners in the
company. The company is Beepwear Paging Products; MTX is its former
name. Along with Motorola, the partner is Timex, not Swatch.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-POETRY-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
16, about the Electromagnetic Poetry Kit misstated the Web site
address for the product. It is www.magpoe.com.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-MARKETS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, June 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, June 16,
about Draeger's, a supermarket in San Mateo, Calif., incorrectly
translated the name of its restaurant. Viognier is a French grape
variety; it does not mean ``great variety'' in French.
</P>
</TEXT>
