<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART HEATS UP THE FIRST ROUND OF THE US OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The clouds rolled in over the Bay area and the
temperatures plummeted, but Payne Stewart was red hot Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By the shores of Lake Merced, the veteran from steamy Orlando,
Fla., birdied the final three holes as he came in early with a
stunning 4-under-par 66 in the first round of the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   Then The Olympic Club's US Open tradition took over. This was
the course were Jack Fleck beat Ben Hogan, where Billy Casper beat
Arnold Palmer, and where Scott Simpson dashed Tom Watson's hopes
for a second national crown.
</P>
<P>
   So enter the long shots, though none could eclipse leader
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Carnevale, who has made only four cuts in 14 PGA Tour
events this year, checked in with a bogey-free round of 67. Joe
Durant, who once was so discouraged that he quit the game and has
made just six cuts in 12 tournaments, walked at Carnevale's side
and posted a 69. That was later matched by Tom Lehman, who has led
this championship the last three years entering the final round but
has come up short every time.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who won the 1991 US Open at Hazeltine in a playoff with
Simpson, took the past two weeks off and went to Aruba to film a
made-for-TV match with Nick Price, then settled by the pool at his
home in Florida. He was totally relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have been out there and walked part of the golf course,
you know that you have got to play from the fairway and be very
patient,'' he said. ``I was in the rough 50 percent of the time off
the tee, but mostly in the short rough.''
</P>
<P>
   After making the turn in 34 and registering six straight pars,
Stewart birdied the 16th (9-iron, 8 inches), 17th (rough, 2-iron,
15 feet), and 18th (2-iron, rough, 8-iron, 12 feet above hole). The
par-4 17th, which stretches for 469 yards, was the key to Stewart's
round. ``I said to my caddie, `Let's just try to chase a 2-iron up
to the gap. If it gets there, fine. If it doesn't, we will try to
get it up and down,''' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `This is a par 5, anyway. In my mind, I am approaching
this golf course as if it is a par 71. I really feel that's a par-5
hole. I hit a great drive Thursday in the practice and had a 3-wood
shot to the green. So I made eagle today. I chased this 2-iron and
made a 45-foot putt. In my mind, eagle. On the scorecard, birdie.
Then I get up there and hit the worst shot I hit all day and
shanked it into the rough. I caught a lie. I hit the 8-iron 12 feet
above the hole and bled it down there. Voila _ 66.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnevale, whose father, Ben, led North Carolina to its first
NCAA basketball championship in 1945 and was head coach at Navy for
many years, quit the game to become an insurance broker in the
1980s. He returned to win the Chattanooga Classic in 1992, but his
best finish this year was joint 41st in Phoenix. ``It was a lot of
fun,'' he said of Thursday's round. ``It's only Thursday, but this
is what you struggled all your life to get to. You finally realize,
`Hey, I'm here.'''
</P>
<P>
   His round warmed up on the seventh hole when, from a terrible
lie in the rough, he hit into the fronting bunker and got it up and
down to save par. Then it heated up when he rolled in a downhill
putt from 40 feet on the eighth and made a 15-foot birdie putt on
the ninth to turn in 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I got a little nervous,'' said Carnevale. ``I
think I just realized what was going on and I was a little shaky.''
</P>
<P>
   He settled down, made birdie on the treacherous 17th, and who
knows what's ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Durant stirred things up when he birdied four of the first five
holes and, after a three-putt bogey on the sixth, hit a 9-iron into
the par-3 eighth and made a birdie to turn in 31. When he hit a
wedge into the 12th to within a foot, he was 5 under. Joe Durant?
</P>
<P>
   He returned to earth with a three-putt double bogey on the 14th
but sank a 40-foot birdie putt on the 15th. Bogeys at 16 and 17
clouded his moment in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day long, I was struggling with my driver,'' said Durant,
who grew up and lives in the Pensacola, Fla., area and played on
the Nike Tour the past five years. ``Usually, that's my
bread-and-butter. You just realize that if you keep making pars,
pars aren't going to hurt you. This is my first US Open. It was a
Tale of Two Cities. I played the front nine really solid. I made
some not-so-good swings on the back side. To win? I can't even
think that far ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
