the former U.N. ambassador. Holbrooke, who negotiated the Bosnia
peace agreement in 1995, was effusively praised by the president at
the ceremony. ``His remarkable diplomacy in Bosnia helped to stop
the bloodshed, restored hope and saved lives,'' said Clinton. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BEIJING -- June 18, 1998 -- CHINA-MIDDLECLASS, 6-18 --
Zhang Can, left, and Yan Junjie, computer entrepreneurs, own a home
in Dynasty Gardens, a development for Beijing's upper middle class.
Ms. Yan and Zhang live a life unthinkable a decade ago in China,
with many luxury items including a house in Freemont, Calif., where
their company, The Dyne Group, has its American office. ``We formed
our company in 1990, when China was starting to transform from a
planned to a market economy and was full of opportunity,'' says
Yan. (Elisabeth Rosenthal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- June 18, 1998 -- NELLY-PROFILE, 6-18 -- Nelly
Toll, who somehow created happy paintings amid the horrors of World
War II. Ms. Toll, who along with her mother spent much of the war
hiding from the Nazis in an apartment of a gentile couple in
Poland, painted 64 watercolors in the 13 months she and her mother
were in hiding. ``There is a duality to my approach to life, you
might say,'' Ms. Toll says. ``In my art I was able to separate. It
was my escape to a better world.'' Six of Ms. Toll's paintings will
be auctioned at Sotheby's next Friday. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 18, 1998 -- BRAIN-THEATER-REVIEW, 6-18
-- Malcolm Gets, foreground, as a composer named Gordon Michael
Schwinn, and others in ``A New Brain,'' at the Mitzi Newhouse
Theater at Lincoln Center. In ``A New Brain,'' William Finn, the
composer of wonderful ``Falsetto'' musicals, translates his
life-threatening experiences on the operating table into an evening
of song and dance. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MOSCOW -- June 18, 1998 -- RUSSIA-BRIDES-COX, 6-18 --
``These meetings are terribly unpleasant,'' explains Elena
Vishnitsev, 31, while standing under umbrella in Moscow recently.
Ms. Vishnitsev has been searching for a husband for three years
through an Internet-based service which catalogs hundreds of young
women looking for husbands. She says that introductions via the
service, while safer, also can be degrading. ``You feel like you
are for sale at a slave market.'' (Charles W. Holmes/Cox News
Service) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- June 18, 1998 --
MURDER-SCHIZOPHRENIC-2, 6-18 -- A portrait of Michael Laudor taken
on the campus of Yale University in Nov. 1995. Laudor, 35, a
schizophrenic who went on to graduate with honors from Yale and
become a lawyer, surrendered late Wednesday night to police in
Ithaca, N.Y. Police announced they wanted to question him about the
murder of his pregnant girlfriend who was found stabbed to death in
their apartment. (Jim Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MOUNT KISCO, N.Y. -- June 18, 1998 -- GLF-BLIND-GOLFERS,
6-17 -- Bob Andrews, president of the U.S. Blind Golf Association,
lines up a shot with the help of his wife, Tina, in her capacity as
his coach. Andrews lost his sight in Vietnam when a booby-trapped
grenade blew up in in his face. For players on the U.S. Blind Golf
Association circuit, coaches are all-important. ``We still play the
same game, with the same USGA rules, as sighted players do,'' says
Andrews. ``It's all very competitive.'' (Bernie Nunez/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- June 18, 1998 --
MURDER-SCHIZOPHRENIC-1, 6-18 -- Michael Laudor leans against the
wall inside an arch at Yale University in Nov. 1995. Laudor, 35, a
schizophrenic who overcame his disability to graduate with honors
from Yale University and become a lawyer surrendered after his
pregnant girlfriend was found to stabbed to death. She was found
dead in their apartment in Hastings-on-Husdson, a New York City
suburb late Wednesday afternoon. (Jim Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
SACRED-MUSIC-B&AMP;W, 6-17 -- Said Guissi's Aissawa band praises Allah
and the Sufi masters, piling syncopation on syncopation with the
aide of giant tamborines and horns. ``The music takes you over
completely,'' says a dancer emerging from a trance. ``It is a
healing thing.'' This is a ceremony, from the Aissawa Sufi
brotherhood that dates back to the 17th century.(Jon Pareles/New
York Times PHOTO) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRINCETON, N.J. -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21
-- ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY, 6-18 -- This artist's rendering shows how
the bleacher seats of Rafael Vinoly's Princeton University Stadium
evoke classical ruins. The seating is arranged on two tiers, the
lower, more conventional one in the form of a squared-off bowl, the
upper divided into three flat trapezoidal slabs that are
vertiginous to look at and exhilarating to sit in. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
SIDE-MAN-THEATER, 6-17 -- Michael Mayer, left, the director of
``Side Man,'' with its author, Warren Leight. The play, opening
Thursday at Stage Right at the Roundabout Theater Company, is a
memory play about jazz performers. ``For the last 20 years I've
been a writer-for-hire, basically,'' says Leight. In jazz, sideman
refers to a musician who works for hire on band jobs, knows the
standards by heart and solos but also blends in with an orchestra's
sound. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
CANBY-THEATER-1, 6-18 -- Howard McGillin, left, Kevin Chamberlin
and Judy Kuhn in ``As Thousands Cheer.'' This play, the 1933 Irving
Berlin-Moss Hart topical revue, is directed as a series of
collegial, go-for-broke turns by Christopher Ashley, whose credits
include ``Jeffrey'' and the recent Encores production of ``Li'l
Abner.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILL RIVER, Mass. -- June 18, 1998 -- HUMOR-BLOUNT-BOS,
6-17 -- Humorist Roy Blount Jr., 56, ponders outside his home in
the southern Berkshires. Blount's new memoir is titled ``Be Sweet:
A Conditional Love Story.'' That book is part of a Blount boomlet
that includes the recently published ``If Only You Knew How Much I
Smell You'' (his text accompanies Valerie Shaff's dog photos), and
the reissue of his 1980 book, ``Crackers.'' (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- June 18, 1998 -- WOM-ANDERSON-BOS, 6-17 --
Bentley College volleyball standout Heidi Anderson in front of her
college's scoreboard. This weekend Anderson will be honered in
Marco Island, Fla., as the winner of the Honda Inspiration Award,
presented each year to a collegiate woman athlete who has overcome
great physical adversity. A leukemia survivor, Anderson is two and
a half years out from the bone marrow transplant she received from
her sister. (Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
