<SLUG> BC-GLF-USOPEN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALY SHOWS MATURITY BY NOT USING HIS DRIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Before John Daly teed off Thursday, he made an
important decision. He left his driver in his bag.
</P>
<P>
   For Daly, parting with his driver is like Sampson cutting off
his hair, like Popeye giving up spinach. However, conservative golf
is the best golf at the U.S. Open, even for Daly, perhaps the
game's longest hitter. And by replacing his driver with a 3-wood,
Daly showed a newfound maturity and shot himself into contention.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting an opening-round 69, Daly was three strokes off the
lead, threatening to win the third major of his career. It was the
first time he had played a round at a major without his driver
since the 1993 PGA Championship at Inverness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, but it's challenging,'' Daly said. ``Whenever
I can't use my driver for 18 holes, it's not good for the fans. But
it's the only way to play this course, and I believe it's the only
way I have a chance to play really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, who won the PGA Championship (1991) and the British Open
(1995), has come a long way since last year, when he withdrew from
the U.S. Open after nine holes with the shakes, just a month after
a stay in the Betty Ford clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking off at nine was not the smartest thing I could've
done,'' Daly said. ``It was a very difficult time. I'm proud I
didn't get mad or do something stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went in the Betty Ford, it was my second time in
rehab,'' he said. ``The first time, I didn't listen to anybody. I
didn't want to be there. This time, I'm allowing myself to go to
meetings and talk about it. The only way I'm going to stay sober is
to surround myself with those people.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Daly was steady, and while his drives were not
spectacular, he played precision golf instead of power golf,
keeping the bogeys and double bogeys off his card.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Daly teed off, there were omens that he might play
well. One of the main roads to the Olympic Club is named John Daly
Boulevard, and Daly City is the name of a town nearby. Daly has not
won this year, but he has two top 10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Woods Eight Back
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods shot a four-over-par 74, including one four-putt and
two three-putts. He was two under par after eight holes, but he
double-bogeyed the par-4 ninth with a four-putt, including a miss
from about three and a half feet. Woods also bogeyed Nos. 12, 13,
16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left a lot of shots out there,'' said Woods, who only used
his driver three times. ``I hit the ball pretty well, but I didn't
make enough putts. I'm just trying to stay patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
