   (NYT7) NEW HAVEN, Conn. -- June 18, 1998 --
MURDER-SCHIZOPHRENIC-1, 6-18 -- Michael Laudor leans against the
wall inside an arch at Yale University in Nov. 1995. Laudor, 35, a
schizophrenic who overcame his disability to graduate with honors
from Yale University and become a lawyer surrendered after his
pregnant girlfriend was found to stabbed to death. She was found
dead in their apartment in Hastings-on-Husdson, a New York City
suburb late Wednesday afternoon. (Jim Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
SACRED-MUSIC-B&AMP;W, 6-17 -- Said Guissi's Aissawa band praises Allah
and the Sufi masters, piling syncopation on syncopation with the
aide of giant tamborines and horns. ``The music takes you over
completely,'' says a dancer emerging from a trance. ``It is a
healing thing.'' This is a ceremony, from the Aissawa Sufi
brotherhood that dates back to the 17th century.(Jon Pareles/New
York Times PHOTO) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRINCETON, N.J. -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21
-- ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY, 6-18 -- This artist's rendering shows how
the bleacher seats of Rafael Vinoly's Princeton University Stadium
evoke classical ruins. The seating is arranged on two tiers, the
lower, more conventional one in the form of a squared-off bowl, the
upper divided into three flat trapezoidal slabs that are
vertiginous to look at and exhilarating to sit in. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
SIDE-MAN-THEATER, 6-17 -- Michael Mayer, left, the director of
``Side Man,'' with its author, Warren Leight. The play, opening
Thursday at Stage Right at the Roundabout Theater Company, is a
memory play about jazz performers. ``For the last 20 years I've
been a writer-for-hire, basically,'' says Leight. In jazz, sideman
refers to a musician who works for hire on band jobs, knows the
standards by heart and solos but also blends in with an orchestra's
sound. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 18,1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 21 --
CANBY-THEATER-1, 6-18 -- Howard McGillin, left, Kevin Chamberlin
and Judy Kuhn in ``As Thousands Cheer.'' This play, the 1933 Irving
Berlin-Moss Hart topical revue, is directed as a series of
collegial, go-for-broke turns by Christopher Ashley, whose credits
include ``Jeffrey'' and the recent Encores production of ``Li'l
Abner.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILL RIVER, Mass. -- June 18, 1998 -- HUMOR-BLOUNT-BOS,
6-17 -- Humorist Roy Blount Jr., 56, ponders outside his home in
the southern Berkshires. Blount's new memoir is titled ``Be Sweet:
A Conditional Love Story.'' That book is part of a Blount boomlet
that includes the recently published ``If Only You Knew How Much I
Smell You'' (his text accompanies Valerie Shaff's dog photos), and
the reissue of his 1980 book, ``Crackers.'' (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BOSTON -- June 18, 1998 -- WOM-ANDERSON-BOS, 6-17 --
Bentley College volleyball standout Heidi Anderson in front of her
college's scoreboard. This weekend Anderson will be honered in
Marco Island, Fla., as the winner of the Honda Inspiration Award,
presented each year to a collegiate woman athlete who has overcome
great physical adversity. A leukemia survivor, Anderson is two and
a half years out from the bone marrow transplant she received from
her sister. (Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
