<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-18 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6318 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-18 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCO'S BACK, SO LET'S KILL IT QUICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This evil is insidious, like all the worst evils: vampires,
lobbyists, the bubonic plague. It moves with utmost stealth,
thrives on lack of vigilance. Relax for an eye's blink, and boom.
</P>
<P>
   Someone plays KC and the Sunshine Band.
</P>
<P>
   And then someone, some dude in a mood ring and platform shoes,
barks it aloud, that most nightmarish phrase: ``Hey, disco's
back!''
</P>
<P>
   No right-thinking American can allow this. We must stop disco
here, and we must stop disco now. For good. Forever.
</P>
<P>
   I say this because disco and the 1970s are in fact back, at
least partway. Which is horrid, in every way. Not as horrid as,
say, Denny Terrio, the ``Dance Fever'' guy, getting a new TV show,
but far more horrid than reruns of ``Charlie's Angels.'' &QL; 
THE DARKER DAYS OF DISCO &QL; 
Disco terror hit me early this week. First, I saw a movie with a
promising title _ ``the Last Days of Disco'' _ which I assumed
would be the inspirational tale of a serial killer stalking
bell-bottomed cokeheads at Studio 54.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck.
</P>
<P>
   And then, 12 hours later, I opened this very newspaper to a
feature story headlined ``Disco Relapse.''
</P>
<P>
   Good metaphor: disease. Bad message: ``The halcyon days of disco
_ with all their attendant terrors _ are back.''
</P>
<P>
   The article named the usual culprits in the recycling of
cultural abominations: films, TV, music, fashion. It also had the
obligatory ``those were the days'' quote, supplied by director Mark
Christopher, whose upcoming ``54'' will chronicle that fabled disco
Sodom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an era of anything goes, and I think people today want
to see what it was like,'' he said. ``There was a sense of liberty,
of being able to really let go and get crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Or get a social disease. Or get divorced. Or get addicted.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, niceties like that, the real fallout from the 1970s,
get skipped by those rejoicing over hiphuggers, tube tops and Kool
and the Gang. We also don't hear much about that other legacy of
the Disco Age.
</P>
<P>
   The death of public trust.
</P>
<P>
   I am speaking of Richard Nixon and Watergate, of 1974 and his
plane out of D.C. Three Mile Island, the Bee Gees, polyester _
mercifully, those afflictions came and went. But nothing has
stitched the tear between politicians and people.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970s brought us all that. Thus, the decade begs for
execution. Instead, its corpse keeps jumping up for one more chance
to do The Hustle. &QL; 
A MERCY KILLING
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic,'' 1987: ``Meanwhile, the hippest of the
twenty-something generation revel in a 1970s pop-culture revival.''
</P>
<P>
   1991, the ``New York Times'': ``Sick of '60s nostalgia? . . .
Perhaps then you will appreciate the next, and most improbable,
pop-culture comeback: The '70s, the disco decade.''
</P>
<P>
   1995, ``The Indianapolis Star'': ``Just when you thought they
were forever banished to the annals of bad taste, the '70s are back
in all their glitzy glory.''
</P>
<P>
   1996, the ``Cleveland Plain Dealer'': ``Disco, Bell-Bottoms,
Bradys Back As '70s Pop Culture Enjoys Revival.''
</P>
<P>
   1997, the ``Times'' again, where the editors still wear
puka-shell necklaces: ``Now disco is back, and so are the Village
People.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, this decade has been on the way back for so long, I can't
wait until it finally gets here. So we can jab a stake through its
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Or drown it in Billy Beer. Or coat it in Jovan Musk Oil for Men.
Whatever it takes to kill the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   It would be euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
   Face the facts. The only thing right in the '70s was the
catchphrase: Disco sucks.
</P>
<P>
   Did then, does now. Just like pointy collars, shag haircuts,
``Barnaby Jones,'' Atari, oil embargoes, Kiss singing ``I Was Made
For Lovin' You'' and pet rocks.
</P>
<P>
   KC, Your Boogie Man, must've tripped on his Boogie Shoes and
smacked his head while (Shake, Shake, Shake) Shaking His Booty
because he was so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way, nuh-uh, nuh-uh, I like it. Nuh-uh, nuh-uh. &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at 444-8515, or at
david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. Watch Channel 12 (KPNX) for his
commentary Monday and Wednesday at 4:35 p.m. on ``12 News First at
Four.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
