<HEADLINE>
LAWN-MOWER JOCKEY TRIUMPHS IN RACE _ WINS VASECTOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUSTIN SCHMID  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Randy Hinkle won the contest Thursday, but it's the
doctor who will make the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle's victory in the Father's Day lawmower-riding contest
will ensure he will never be a father again.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize was a vasectomy.
</P>
<P>
   The losers were fit to be tied. The winner will be.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle was a virile competitor, nearly tipping his 15-horsepower
John Deere mower as he rounded the final turn, sputtering towards
the finish line at the course set up at Los Arcos Mall in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Michelle, 22, and 17-day-old daughter Emma cheered him
from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Other men watching the festivities would have raced to avoid a
vasectomy. But Hinkle, 42, was eager to claim the prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to spoil this one,'' he said, gazing at his
newborn.
</P>
<P>
   Hinkle bested two opponents, Jesse Mason and Chris Carlile, to
win his date with the doctor. The losers got KSLX-FM T-shirts as
consolation prizes.
</P>
<P>
   The classic-rock radio station, is springing for five
vasectomies this week. It's an idea hatched by morning radio
personality Joey ``T'' Teehan.
</P>
<P>
   Each day this week, the station is hosting a lawn mower contest,
buying the winner a vasectomy in honor of Father's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Other men wanted to race the riding mowers. But they turned pale
and slinked back into the crowd after hearing the V-word.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Guttierrez of Gilbert turned down a shot at the grand
prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it the way it is,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justin Schmid can be reached at 444-7474 or at
justin.schmid(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
