<SLUG> BC-NY-MCCALL-LILCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCALL FORMS COALITION TO FIGHT LILCO PAYOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ State Comptroller H. Carl McCall has
organized a coalition of major stockholders in Marketspan Corp.
seeking to remove its chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos, because of
the growing controversy over his compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketspan's future success will depend on strong
leadership,'' McCall wrote to the company's board of directors on
Wednesday. ``Dr. Catacosinos has lost the confidence of
shareholders, customers and regulators, and I do not believe he can
provide the leadership Marketspan needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Marketspan spokesman, Joseph McDonnell, said that
Catacosinos still has the confidence of other investors
representing far more shares than the coalition does.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's move opens a new front in the battle over the $67
million in special compensation that Catacosinos and 25 other top
executives of Long Island Lighting Co. took before it disbanded in
a complex deal on May 28. The state's Long Island Power Authority
took over LILCO's electricity service. The rest of LILCO merged
with the Brooklyn Union Gas holding company to form Marketspan,
which the authority hired to run the electric system.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Gov. George Pataki disclosed the payments, which
he said violated the takeover deal. He accused Catacosinos, who got
$42 million, of ``secret acts of greed'' and called for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   McCall is the sole trustee of the state's Common Retirement
Fund, which owns 440,000 shares of Marketspan. He acted in concert
with the New York State Teachers' Retirement System, which holds
170,000 shares, and New York City's comptroller, Alan Hevesi, the
adviser and a trustee for five city pension funds that have 800,000
shares. McCall said he was also ``reaching out'' to other
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that the recent controversy over executive
compensation packages has had a deleterious impact on the value of
our investment,'' McCall wrote to Marketspan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
