r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGSCREEN-JUMP-LADN     06-18 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGSCREEN-JUMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FILES' MAKERS HOPE THEY HAVE `X' FACTOR FOR BIG-SCREEN SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: ``Today'' in story refers to Friday, June 19.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
files.) 
BY MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES _ Their foray into the realm of motion pictures could
be the biggest expedition into alien territory yet for Scully and
Mulder, the two sullen heroes of Fox Television's eerie action
drama, ``The X-Files.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet in their silver-screen debut _ a $70 million, two-hour
action-packed adventure that opens today _ Scully and Mulder are
not traveling to a land where no man has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Not entirely.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The X-Files'' movie is just the latest in a very long
list of television shows turned motion pictures _ including the
long-running ``Star Trek'' series _ it is different from its
predecessors in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' is still in its first run on prime-time
television. ``The X-Files'' movie features the same actors and
actresses 20 million to 30 million viewers tune to Fox each Sunday
night to see. The movie is not a remake from the '50s, '60s or
'70s. And it's not animated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's most unusual, especially in current times,'' said Tom
Borys, chief operating officer of ACNielsen EDI, a market research
firm that does overnight box-office tracking for the motion-picture
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very interesting. A lot of people will be looking
at this. I think it will be imitated a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That interest is in large part based on the profitability of
adapting popular television shows into feature films, according to
Borys.
</P>
<P>
   According to ACNielsen EDI research, the average gross for
movies made from television shows this decade is $60.6 million. The
average for all other films in wide release is $35.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speaks to why they do it. They already have the built-in
identification and a track record,'' Borys said. ``But that is by
no means a guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Batman'' grossed $251.2 million at the box office. ``Batman
Forever,'' ``The Fugitive,'' and ``Mission: Impossible'' all
grossed in excess of $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Batman Returns,'' ``Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,'' ``The
Flintstones,'' ``Wayne's World,'' ``Addams Family Values,'' ``Star
Trek IV,'' ``George of the Jungle,'' ``Dick Tracy,'' ``Maverick,''
and ``Casper'' each also brought in more than $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Davis, who directed ``The Fugitive,'' which shot to No. 1
on the box office list upon its release in August 1993, said the
story sold more tickets to his movie than fan allegiance to the
1960s TV series. But he did not see anything wrong with dipping
into the TV well for movie ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's worthwhile material, it doesn't bother me,'' he said
when his movie debuted.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``The X-Files'' series attracts 20 million to 30 million
viewers each week, ``X-Files'' creator and now film producer and
screenwriter Chris Carter is hopeful ``The X-Files'' movie can do
at least that well.
</P>
<P>
   He admits there's no guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite ``X'' fans beseeching each other on Internet chat
sessions to give the movie a boost and spur sequels by seeing the
movie again and again, Carter said making the film was a scary
proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were risks inherent in taking it to the big screen,''
Carter said. ``But (Fox) saw the beauty of making the movie. They
were a little afraid the movie would be the end of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to convince them it wasn't going to be. That it would be
a really good way to invigorate the series and to make a great
movie, too,'' Carter said. ``I didn't want this to be seen as an
exploitation. I wanted it to be seen as a celebration of the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   If the celebration turns out to be profitable, the possibilities
for television producers who want to make movies is nearly endless,
Borys said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a trend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter agreed. ``Anybody could do it. `ER' could do it. `NYPD
Blue' could do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that we did, and we had good reason to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Borys doesn't think just anyone can do it. Sitcoms couldn't
make the translation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do need to have the right kind of show to translate to the
big screen. ``X-Files is a good one that does translate. The
concept stands on its own as a film kind of idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt we're going to see `Friends: The Movie.' But `ER'
could probably do it. That makes perfect sense to me and I'm not
even a producer,'' Borys said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Borys, there are already other conversions in the
works, including a ``South Park'' movie and a new ``Beavis and
Butt-head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's still a lot of other old TV shows out there to be
mined.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-98 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
