<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING NOTES: MAGAZINES REVISE THEIR MASTHEADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several magazines have made top executive changes.
</P>
<P>
   Reader's Digest Association Inc. named Bernadette Harrison
Haley, 44, vice president and publisher of the U.S edition of The
Reader's Digest. Ms. Haley, who will be based in New York, succeeds
Dick Porter, 40, who left to become publisher of TV Guide, which
News Corporation is selling to United Video Satellite Guide Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Haley had been associate publisher at Good Housekeeping
magazine in New York, part of the Hearst Magazines unit of Hearst
Corp. She will be succeeded there by Sean Sullivan, 39, who had
been marketing director and will become associate
publisher/marketing.
</P>
<P>
   At Teen People magazine in New York, which is part of the Time
Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc., Anne Zehren, 36, was named
publisher, assuming duties from Nora McAniff, 39, who continues as
publisher of People. Ms. Zehren had been associate publisher at
Glamour magazine in New York, part of the Conde Nast Publications
unit of Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   At Glamour, Vanessa Reed was named to succeed Ms. Zehren as
associate publisher for marketing. Ms. Reed, 44, had been an
associate publisher at People magazine for almost six years.
</P>
<P>
   At The Advocate magazine in Los Angeles, owned by Liberation
Publications Inc., Joe Landry, 34, associate publisher, was
promoted to publisher, succeeding Sam Watters, 45, who continues as
president at Liberation Publications.
</P>
<P>
   And at Money magazine in New York, also part of Time Inc.,
Geoffrey Dodge, 37, publisher, is adding the additional
responsibilities of overseeing the magazine's business operations,
including consumer marketing and new-business development.
</P>
<P>
   He assumes those duties from Michael Pepe, 44, who continues a
president of the Business Information Group at Time Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Creative Director at Bates Worldwide
</P>
<P>
   Bates Worldwide in New York, part of Cordiant Communications
Group PLC, has named its first worldwide creative director since
Bill Backer retired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   John Fawcett, who served for the last two years as chairman and
chief executive at George Patterson Bates in Sydney, Australia,
will relocate to New York on Aug. 1 to oversee the agency's
worldwide creative output. Fawcett, 48, who continues as chairman
of the Bates Worldwide Creative Board, will report to Michael
Bungey, chairman and chief executive at Bates.
</P>
<P>
   At Patterson Bates, Ian Elliot, 44, managing director, was named
to succeed Fawcett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
