<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR JOCKEYS GET OLDER AND BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ When the lights come up tonight at Lone
Star Park at Grand Prairie, there is the inevitable presumption
that some of the participants are old enough to be put to stud.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. Jerry Bailey, Hall of Fame jockey, still
wants to work.
</P>
<P>
   At the NTRA All-Star Jockey Championship, they'll be checking
birth certificates only on the horses, thank you. Bailey, born in
Dallas and raised in El Paso, will turn 41 this summer and has
saddled more than 4,300 winners.
</P>
<P>
   Laffit Pincay, another of the seven Hall of Fame jockeys who
will ride tonight, is a nimble 51. Cajun-born Eddie Delahoussaye is
46. Canadian Sandy Hawley is 49.
</P>
<P>
   They may be getting older. They may also be getting faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the few athletic endeavors, I guess, where you
don't lose your edge or your physical ability just because you get
older,'' Bailey said on the eve of the second annual event.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's record, like Pincay's and Delahoussaye's and all of the
40-something set's, more than substantiates that. They don't ride
on the seniors circuit and their winners don't pay off in Depends
coupons.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, instead, offers this thought: ``The more horses you
ride, the wiser you become.''
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, a betting man might have wagered that not all
jockeys would live into their 40s, let alone win in them. Bailey
has heard the old stories, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard, fast life,'' he said. ``And I think the owners
and trainers wanted them to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners and trainers felt that a guy was more of a
risk-taker out on the track if he was a risk-taker in every other
endeavor of his life. So the wilder the jockeys were at night, they
figured the wilder they would be on the race track for them. I've
heard stories about some of the great riders of the past showing up
in the morning wearing tuxedoes _ from the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey paused and smiled. ``I don't think that's the mentality
anymore,'' he assured.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone with the Damon Runyon novels. The stakes
today are too high. One slip _ even one vacation _ and there's
somebody else in the saddle.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey rides six horses a day, five days a week, about 48 weeks
a year. He has been averaging 1,100 to 1,200 rides each calendar
year.
</P>
<P>
   He rides in New York, because all the great ones, sooner or
later, tend to gravitate to the New York, Kentucky or California
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't Texas. But Bailey has earned enough _ his mounts'
winning purses last year totaled nearly $16 million _ that he has
been able to buy himself some Texas-sized elbow room on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 3 acres,'' Bailey said, ``and I can't see the next
house.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was born in Dallas, Bailey moved to El Paso with his
family before he had turned 3. His father, a dentist, bought a pony
for the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   When his dad bought more horses, Jerry learned that pitching hay
and combing colts was far more intriguing than throwing newspapers
and bagging groceries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, growing up in Texas, I wanted to be a football
player,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   But his bio lists him _ generously _ at 5-foot-5 and 112 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too little,'' he said. ``I wanted to be a basketball player,
but I was too short. I tried out for all the teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be a professional athlete. I ended up coming full
circle back to racing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 17, he began riding professionally at Sunland Park in New
Mexico. His first winner was named Fetch. But his greatest winner
was the legendary Cigar.
</P>
<P>
   From October 1994 until August 1996, Cigar won 16 races without
losing. The streak equaled Citation's as the longest by any North
American-based horse in the 20th century. Bailey was aboard Cigar
for 15 of those 16 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had great personality to him,'' Bailey said of his former
partner. ``Two or three days before a race, he'd bite your hand
off. He knew what was coming. Yet the day after the race, my
4-year-old son could go pet him on the nose and he'd be as gentle
as a kitten.''
</P>
<P>
   Cigar's resoluteness carried itself onto the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had nerves of steel, and he'd pass it on to the horses he
was running with,'' Bailey said. ``That air of invincibility. He'd
beat horses mentally as well as physically.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jerry Bailey aboard, Cigar was once called ``Nureyev in
horseshoes.'' Racing lore tells the story of the stakes race he won
in Illinois where $200,000 in winning tickets went uncashed. Fans
wanted, instead, to keep them as mementos.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar retired in 1996. But his old saddle mate, Bailey, as a
spry 40-year-old, rides on.
</P>
<P>
   As you may observe tonight, age matters only on the horses.
They're all stars, and they never looked brighter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
