<HEADER>
A6565 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-1STLD     06-18 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON GLOBE ASKS COLUMNIST WHO FABRICATED MATERIAL TO RESIGN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to expand, with Smith column excerpts, additional Storin
quote, etc.)  (EDS. NOTE: The Boston Globe is planning to move a spot news story
on the columnist and the last column by Patricia Smith for use by
New York Times News Service clients. For questions, call Frank
Perrotta at the Globe: (617) 929-2597.)  
 (ps)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A columnist at The Boston Globe, a Pulitzer Prize finalist,
fabricated people and quotations in four of her columns this year,
and the newspaper has asked for her resignation, The Globe
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, she made up nearly an entire column about a woman
dying of cancer, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said the columnist, Patricia Smith, 42, a widely
respected figure in the Boston area, had acknowledged the
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy,'' said Matthew Storin, The Globe's editor.
``And I feel that we have handled it in the only way we could, and
that itself speaks well for the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin added, ``There is no middle ground on something like
this. That was self-evident.''
</P>
<P>
   Storin said he had yet to receive Ms. Smith's letter of
resignation. But in Ms. Smith's final column, published in Friday's
issue of The Globe, which is owned by The New York Times Co., she
acknowledges her misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``From time to time in my metro column, to create the desired
impact or slam home a salient point, I attributed quotes to people
who didn't exist,'' she said. She also apologized ``to the grocery
clerks and bartenders and single mothers, to the politicians, PR
flacks, spokespersons and secretaries, to my dear husband and
family and friends, I am sorry for betraying your trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith did not respond to messages left on her voice mail at
work, and her home telephone was out of service. Her lawyer, John
Williams of the Boston firm Palmer &AMP; Dodge, also did not respond to
voice-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second time in Ms. Smith's career that her
credibility had come under fire. As an editorial assistant at The
Chicago Sun-Times in the late 1980s, she wrote a review of a
concert that she had not attended, a former colleague recalled. The
newspaper ran a correction, but she was not dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations about Ms. Smith come just a week after The New
Republic published the results of an investigation into the work of
Stephen Glass, a staff writer, who it said had fabricated parts or
all of 27 of the 41 articles he wrote for the magazine in two and a
half years.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said Friday's paper would also include a news article
about Ms. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we confirmed that we had the problem, we wanted to get
the information out as quickly as we could,'' said publisher
Benjamin Taylor. ``Credibility with our readership is the single
most important asset that we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said it discovered Ms. Smith's fabrications two weeks
ago during normal monitoring by senior editors. Under the system,
which Storin said he established two and a half years ago, editors
occasionally double check columnists' sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had questions raised from time to time over the years
about metro columnists who have such freedom to write about
whatever they want _ street scenes, slices of life, etc.,'' Storin
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said editors discovered the fabrications earlier this month,
while Ms. Smith was on vacation, and confronted her when she
returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We detected a few weeks ago that some quotes seemed too
articulate or too polished in certain circumstances,'' Storin said.
</P>
<P>
   The fabrications appeared in columns on April 13, 20, 24 and May
11. Storin said further research would be done into Ms. Smith's
work.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fake people quoted in these columns was Janine Byrne,
whom Ms. Smith identified as ``a South End cosmetologist'' in her
April 24 article on Stephen Fagan, who is accused of kidnapping his
two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, The Globe said Ms. Smith created a woman named
Dorothy Gibson in her April 13 column about a little girl's Easter
experience. In the article, Ms. Smith gives this quotation from Ms.
Gibson: `` `Seems like that girl's feet grew a size since we bought
those,' said Carolyn's mom Dorothy Gibson. `You know, when they get
a certain age, nothing sits still.'''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for The Globe, Richard Gulla, said he did not know
whether other people in that article, including Carolyn, were
fabricated.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said Ms. Smith also acknowledged inventing Jim Burke,
a worker erecting barricades at the Boston Marathon, in her April
20 column; and Claire, for whom Ms. Smith did not give a last name,
the subject of a poignant column about a woman with cancer,
published on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claire has been thinking about dying for weeks now,'' Ms.
Smith wrote, ``ever since her doctor said the tragic word, ever
since she found out why she was so woefully tired all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   As to whether The New Republic's case influenced The Globe's
handling of the situation, Storin said: ``It reinforced the idea
that we had to get to the bottom of it but we were already on that
track. This process was well under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who began her newspaper career as a typist at The
Chicago Daily News, joined The Globe in 1990. She has been writing
a column for the Metro/Region section since 1994. This year, she
won an award from the American Society of Newspaper Editors for a
series of columns published in 1997. She was also nominated for a
Pulitzer Prize for commentary last year. A poet, she has been
widely recognized in the Boston arts community for her public
readings.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether The Globe knew about The Sun-Times incident,
Gregory Moore, The Globe's managing editor, said: ``We've tried to
establish that. We don't really know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Globe said Ms. Smith admitted the fabrications after being
questioned by Moore. Storin said that The Globe initially had
questions about six columns and that Ms. Smith admitted to
fabrications in four of them.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting Thursday, Storin and Taylor told the news staff of
their request for Ms. Smith's resignation. ``There is no middle
ground on something like this,'' Storin said. ``That was
self-evident.''
</P>
<P>
   In her column Friday, Ms. Smith said she would ``survive this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will write as long as I breathe, despite the dire
predictions that this indiscretion spells the end of my career,''
she wrote.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
