<SLUG> BC-GLF_USOPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART ON TOP AFTER UNEVENT FUL FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Most every player in this week's 98th U.S. Open
knows the eerie history of this tournament at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   They know why this notorious tract was dubbed ``the John Wilkes
Booth of golf courses'' after an unknown named Jack Fleck upset Ben
Hogan here in the 1955 national championship, and Billy Casper did
the same to Arnold Palmer in the '66 version.
</P>
<P>
   They also are well aware that the ominous San Andreas Fault lies
underneath the course's most scary stretch (Nos. 2-5), called
``Quake Corner.'' Escaping it without a bogey is almost unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why Payne Stewart was so giddy after a 4-under
66 in Thursday's opening round, which was contested under very mild
conditions, at least in these parts. Yep, no wind, no fog and _
thank goodness _ no you-know-what.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Thursday) was a day that you could get a good round of golf
in around here,'' noted Stewart, who held a 1-stroke lead over
unheralded Mark Carnevale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows? The wind could be howling by tomorrow, and we could
have an earthquake running down the 18th fairway. So I'm going to
just sit back and relish this.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Stewart dared to utter the ``e'' word. Perhaps he had
earned the right, considering the 1991 Open champ was one of the
few who held his game together, chiefly by closing with three
straight birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tournament favorites were much more shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods absorbed two 3-putt bogeys, and a disasterous 4-putt
double bogey at the ninth hole, on his way to a 74.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually played very well, I just couldn't make the putts,''
said Woods, who would have been much worse if not for three birdies
on the front side, when he was briefly among the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champ Ernie Els also had his putting problems on
greens that, for the most part, were fairly moist and slow by
Olympic standards. His chances for a third national championship in
the past five years looked bleak after a 75.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, America's hottest player? He kept slipping and
sliding as he also could do no better than 75.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Casey Martin, making Open history when he became
the first player to ride these always-tight fairways with the aid
of a cart. Professional golf's ``Lone Rider,'' who needs the cart
because of a circulatory condition in his right leg, made the turn
at even par before a few bumps down the homestretch left him at 74.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a player who had it on cruise control, it was
Carnevale. He never made a bogey while carding a 67.
</P>
<P>
   The group at 68 also was plenty strong with the exception of
journeyman Joe Durant. They included Scottsdale's Tom Lehman, Bob
Tway and Spain's Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   At 70 were Masters champ Mark O'Meara; last year's Open
runner-up, Colin Montgomerie; Paradise Valley's Andrew Magee; and
U.S. Amateur champ Matt Kuchar, who also played well at The
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   British Open champ Justin Leonard and Paradise Valley's Phil
Mickelson were lurking in a pack at 71.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, only nine players in the field of 156 managed
to break par.
</P>
<P>
   Even Stewart made several references to his first 18 holes being
``lucky.'' That would be an accurate assessment, considering three
of his birdies came from the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never drove it off line huge, where I had to chip out of the
deep rough except for the 18th,'' Stewart said. ``That was a
horrible 2-iron (off the tee) there.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievably, he caught a good lie and managed to smack an
8-iron to 12 feet for his fifth and final birdie of the day against
one bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave myself a lot of chances, and I was very patient, which
is what you have to be at a United States Open,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, who has finished third, second and third in the past
three Opens, was cautiously optimistic about his 68, which included
three birdies on his last four holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to put the ball in the fairway,'' said Lehman, who
had rallied back from a double bogey at No. 10. ``I know the fans
are rooting for me after all the near-misses, but I'm going to
forget about winning it until the 72nd hole on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how fickle the Olympic Club can be, there seems no other
way to approach it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
