<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-MCELROY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS CLOSE BOOK ON FAILED PICK MCELROY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leeland McElroy, a second-round draft pick by the Cardinals in
1996, was released Thursday after several attempts to trade him
failed.
</P>
<P>
   McElroy, from Texas A&AMP;M, struggled during his two seasons. He
became expendable with the off-season additions of running backs
Adrian Murrell, Mario Bates and draftee Michael Pittman, plus kick
returner/wide receiver Terry Metcalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made significant moves at the running back position in
the off-season,'' Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said. ``Leeland
became a victim of the numbers game. It was in the best interest of
Leeland and the team to take action now instead of later.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, McElroy gained 424 yards on 135 carries for an
average of 3.1 yards a carry. He scored two touchdowns and started
eight games for a team that was the NFL's worst rushing team.
</P>
<P>
   McElroy's release will cost the Cardinals only $100,000 for
salary-cap purposes.
</P>
<P>
   They have signed all but their top two 1998 draft picks, Andre
Wadsworth and Corey Chavous, after Thursday's signing of former
Arizona State player Pat Tillman, a seventh-round draft pick. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
