<HEADLINE>
GORE WANTED MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jason Gore's opening drive at his first U.S.
Open got rid of his jitters. And his third shot gave everyone in
his gallery shivers.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Gore's second shot that set the tone for his round
Thursday at the Olympic Club's Lake Course.
</P>
<P>
   It was a doozy, a 4-iron that landed in a spot that might as
well have been Alcatraz. His lie in a tangle of bushes and
Monterrey pine branches was unplayable, so Gore took a one-stroke
penalty and got a free drop in return. Some handout it turned out
to be; his golf ball landed in lethal _ but legal _ rough 65 yards
from the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's next shot was arguably the best one anybody had Thursday.
The graduate of Hart High in Newhall, a Los Angeles suburb, chipped
onto the green with his wedge and the ball rolled 50 feet and
disappeared in the cup. It was the first of two birdies Gore had en
route to a 7-over-par 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most exciting thing I've ever seen,'' said Gore's
mother Kathy, who was easy to pick out of the crowd in her ``Gore's
Gallery'' shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a first-year pro on the Nike Tour, hit eight of 14
fairways, so he reasoned his score should have been lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really disappointed with the way I played,'' he said. ``I
was not capitalizing on the opportunities I had.''
</P>
<P>
   He missed the green with his tee shot on the par-3 third hole
and wound up with a triple bogey. His tee shot on the par-5 16th
landed in the fairway and he walked away with a double bogey, which
in his mind might as well have been a triple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have made a birdie from the middle of the fairway,''
Gore, 24, said.
</P>
<P>
   His approach shots posed problems all day. Club selection was a
real guessing game because of the adrenaline coarsing through his
body.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was so nervous when he stepped to the first tee box, he
barely could breathe. He looked heavenward and instantly felt, at
once, better and sadder.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's father Sheldon died of a heart attack last September,
shortly after Gore emerged victorious in the California State Open
and the California State Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about him all the time,'' said the former Pepperdine
standout. ``I know he's watching me, but I kind of wish he was here
physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Gore would have been proud of how his only son handled
himself. There were no angry outbursts, no emphatic club tosses,
just one ear-to-ear grin that, like the marine layer overhead,
stayed put throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks happy to be here,'' one fan told Gore's mother as the
golfer walked from the eighth green to the ninth tee.
</P>
<P>
   Replied Kathy with a grin that matched her son's, ``He is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daly Show: Before John Daly teed off, he made an important
decision. He left his driver in his bag.
</P>
<P>
   For Daly, parting with his driver is like Sampson cutting off
his hair, like Popeye giving up spinach. However, conservative golf
is the best golf at the U.S. Open, even for Daly, perhaps the
game's longest hitter. And by replacing his driver with a 3-wood,
Daly showed a newfound maturity and shot himself into contention.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting an opening-round 69, Daly was three strokes off the
lead, threatening to win the third major of his career. It was the
first time he had played a round at a major without his driver
since the 1993 PGA Championship at Inverness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, but it's challenging,'' Daly said. ``Whenever
I can't use my driver for 18 holes, it's not good for the fans. But
it's the only way to play this course, and I believe it's the only
way I have a chance to play really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods eight back: Tiger Woods shot a four-over-par 74, including
one four-putt and two three-putts. He was two-under par after eight
holes, but he double-bogeyed the par-4 ninth with a four-putt,
including a miss from about 3{ feet. Woods also bogeyed Nos. 12,
13, 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left a lot of shots out there,'' said Woods, who used his
driver only three times. ``I hit the ball pretty well, but I didn't
make enough putts. I'm just trying to stay patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
