<HEADLINE>
EAST VALLEY GIVES `WAKE-UP CALL' TO PHOENIX CIVIC PLAZA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Cohn issued the warning more than a year ago: ``Phoenix
is no longer a first-tier convention city, and a strong argument
can be made that it is no longer a second-tier convention city
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cohn, managing director of the Crowne Plaza Hotel in
downtown Phoenix, stands by those words and says the city's
convention center could be headed for even tougher times.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes the plans being unveiled Friday for a major
East Valley convention center and football stadium are ``a wake-up
call'' to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Phoenix already have opened their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Said one city official, envisioning competition from a sparkling
new East Valley convention center and stadium nestled amid open
space, maybe near a town lake, ``I'm not so confident we'd win the
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Civic Plaza has about 330,000 square feet of exhibit
space, trailing smaller cities such as Anaheim and Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Trade Show and Convention Guide'' for
1997-98, the size of the Civic Plaza ranks 29th &UR; nationally. But
exclude the outdoor Symphony Hall terrace &UR; and the Civic Plaza would
not crack the nation's top 30.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Councilman Sal DiCiccio said the Civic Plaza is
vulnerable, not only to the East Valley's plans but to those in
other cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The City of Phoenix is slowly but surely moving out of the
competitive position,'' DiCiccio said. ``The city missed the chance
two years ago to build a bigger convention center to make us more
competitive in the national scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn points to an exhibit hall list that placed Phoenix at No.
13 in 1990, ranking the size of the country's convention centers.
By 1993, Phoenix slipped to 34 and reportedly has fallen even
lower.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a new convention center that competes with and
takes some business from the Civic Plaza is something Phoenix
officials are watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn noted that the problem for Phoenix officials is not just
what is happening down the road in the East Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to be concerned on a national level. They compete
nationally for national conventions,'' he said. ``Phoenix does not
have a competitive facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogwash, said David Krietor, director of Phoenix's Community and
Economic Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If the East Valley convention center opened its doors, ``We
would be concerned. The Civic Plaza is essential to the viability
of downtown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if a new convention center does sprout, Phoenix will do what
it can to keep its hold on the Valley convention business. He said
competing against the Phoenix Civic Plaza ``will be like trying to
climb Mount Everest with your fingernails.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the size of the Civic Plaza doesn't compare to other
centers in the larger cities, but a look at the whole package shows
downtown amenities from sports arenas to museums within walking
distance _ and a recent $32-million face lift. Two planned downtown
hotels should help, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Given the size of the facility and the number of hotel
rooms downtown, we're certainly not in the top tier'' of convention
cities, said Kevin Hill, marketing director for the Civic Plaza.
``Even with the new hotel rooms planned, we're at best a
second-tier city. That's the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like Krietor, he said there are other factors to make up
for that disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   Local convention figures show 50 conventions booked into the
Civic Plaza in fiscal 1997-98, which ends June 30. That would
compare with 43, 49 and 62 in the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at convention business Valley-wide _ including, but not
limited to, Civic Plaza _ total conventions booked, convention
attendees and convention ``room nights'' are all up considerably
from last year, according to local figures.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``The size of the Civic Plaza is an issue,'' Krietor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Mayor Skip Rimsza said Thursday, ``We've had a lot of
discussions internally'' about how to expand the facility.
</P>
<P>
   The city already purchased more than eight acres at the old
Phoenix Union High School campus. One of the reasons: to possibly
use it for expansion of the Civic Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   If 200,000 or 300,000 square feet of meeting and exhibit space
were built at the old campus at Seventh Street and Van Buren,
Krietor said the plaza could double-book, hosting some events at
the plaza and some at the nearby campus.
</P>
<P>
   If the East Valley plan becomes reality, Hill said, the Phoenix
Civic Plaza will survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it take some business away? Absolutely,'' Hill said. ``Is
it competition? Anything is competition. Is it going to empty out
our place? No.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Fiscus can be reached at 444-8697, or at chris.fiscus &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
